<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ROYALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS STRUGGLES AGAINST ROYALS BUT MANAGES TO GET VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By JACK CURRY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Roger Clemens keeps teasing the Yankees, pitching the
way they expect in some spurts and disappointing them in some
others. They want to believe that Clemens can dominate, and
sometimes he does. But there are other puzzling starts when Clemens
is ordinary, and the Yankees get exasperated. Friday night Clemens
was a little bit of everything.
</P>
<P>
   Helped by a botched pop fly that scored two runs, the Yankees
defeated the Kansas City Royals, 7-5, as Clemens lasted six innings
to earn the victory. The Yankees can point to how Clemens battled
on a chilly night when his fastball was inconsistent and when he
needed to rebound after slogging through two innings. The Yankees
will focus on the positive with Clemens because they can get away
with doing that in April.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, though, it was another ugly game for the Yankees,
another game in which they did not play crisply but still won. The
Royals rumbled into Yankee Stadium as the most dramatic team in the
major leagues after winning four straight games, all in their last
at-bat. The streak died Friday night when Mariano Rivera bagged the
final four outs without the Royals' hitting the ball past the
mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was long and ugly,'' the Yankees manager, Joe Torre, said.
``It's just nice to be able to get away with games like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre had expressed a desire for a starter beside Orlando
Hernandez to record a victory, which Clemens finally did. But it
was not an artistic effort, as Clemens surrendered five earned runs
and seven hits in six innings, walking four, hitting one and
throwing a wild pitch. What were the positives? Well, he never lost
a lead and managed to win despite uncorking a whopping 114 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   On a windy evening with temperatures in the 40's, Clemens never
seemed comfortable. He went to a full count on five of the first 10
batters and took 36 pitches to muddle through the second inning. He
began the inning by drilling Mike Sweeney in the right forearm with
a fastball, causing Sweeney to tumble to the dirt and shout in
pain. One out later, Clemens walked Mark Quinn. A groundout pushed
runners to second and third with two out.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens fired two quick strikes past the No. 9 batter, Rey
Sanchez, setting up an enviable situation where he could pump a
fastball past Sanchez or get him to bite on a split-finger
fastball. Clemens threw a split-finger fastball that stayed up in
the strike zone and Sanchez lashed it to center for a two-run
single.
</P>
<P>
   Torre has often questioned why Clemens does not throw a crisper
fastball more to simply overpower hitters, which he might have been
able to do against a batter who had never opposed him. Clemens
roared back in the third by inducing two groundouts and a strikeout
on nine pitches. It was the Clemens the Yankees wish they could see
more often.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is I'm getting myself into poor counts,''
Clemens said. ``I've just got to work through it. It's simple math,
and I've got to get around it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Posada belted a two-run homer into the right-field upper
deck off Jay Witasick to even the score at 2-2 in the second. Ricky
Ledee's two-out, run-scoring double in the third made the score
3-2.
</P>
<P>
   But Clemens and the Yankees were fortunate in two game-turning
situations in the fourth. With Chuck Knoblauch on first and two
out, Derek Jeter tapped a ball between first and second base.
Sweeney strayed too far from first, so second baseman Carlos Febles
fielded the ball and threw to Witasick for what should have been
the third out. But Umpire Mark Wagner called Jeter safe. Replays
appeared to show Jeter was out.
</P>
<P>
   After Witasick walked Paul O'Neill to load the bases, Witasick
seemed to sneak through a dicey spot by getting Bernie Williams to
hit a pop fly to shallow left. The ball hung in the air for an
agonizingly long time, long enough for Williams to ponder having
stranded three Yankees and for the Royals to exhale. Maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Randa drifted back on the ball behind third, started to
settle under it about five feet from the foul line and suddenly
veered away as if Sanchez, the shortstop, had called for the ball.
The 200-foot pop dropped to the grass and the glaring mistake
allowed two runs to score, giving the Yankees a 5-2 bulge.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens bounced a split-finger fastball for a wild pitch to
produce the Royals' third run. After Jeter's two-run single made
the score 7-3, Clemens gave up Gregg Zaun's two-run homer to keep
the Royals close. Two batters later, Clemens trudged to the dugout
after finishing the sixth and finishing his night.
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen assured a victory for Clemens. He just left some
unanswered questions about his pitching.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
