</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PIRATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS' OLD RELIABLES PRODUCE A RARE VICTORY FOR FRANCO 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Manager Bobby Valentine's critical comments about
the Mets had general manager Steve Phillips flying here Friday on a
damage-control mission. But when Valentine spoke to students at the
Wharton School of Business in Philadelphia on Wednesday, he did say
some positive things about his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of them have surfaced,'' Valentine said before Friday
night's game against the Pittsburgh Pirates. ``About the way we
fought last year, and Mike, and Robin.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be Mike Piazza and Robin Ventura, and it would be
hard to be critical of those Mets. Along with Edgardo Alfonzo,
Piazza and Ventura provide the thump in the middle of the Mets'
lineup, and their offensive production drives this team.
</P>
<P>
   It was that way again Friday night, and the Pirates could not
control the damage. With all the pregame focus on Valentine and the
players he had apparently slighted, the Mets' old reliables led
them to an 8-5 victory in 12 innings. The Mets had 20 hits.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza had five hits, the most he has ever had in a game,
including two homers. Ventura hit his first homer of the year, and
Alfonzo tripled and knocked in a run. Melvin Mora drove in the
go-ahead runs on a two-run broken-bat single off Jose Silva (2-1)
in the four-run 12th.
</P>
<P>
   The winning pitcher was John Franco, who worked two scoreless
innings and ended a streak of 112 games pitched without a victory.
Franco's last victory came on Sept. 13, 1997; he lost all 10 of his
decisions in between.
</P>
<P>
   Protecting a 4-3 lead in the ninth inning, the Mets' closer,
Armando Benitez, had two outs and a 2-2 count on Pat Meares. But
Meares smoked a triple to right field, scoring Jason Kendall to tie
the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets came right back in the 10th, when Derek Bell singled
through the middle with two out and Rey Ordonez, who was on second,
raced for home. But Kendall, the Pirates' catcher, received Adrian
Brown's throw with his thigh blocking Ordonez's path to the plate,
and Kendall tagged Ordonez out to keep the score tied.
</P>
<P>
   The game had been tied at 2-2 in the top of the seventh inning.
With one out, Piazza got a curveball from the right-hander Jason
Schmidt and drove it over the fence in right field, putting the
Mets ahead, 3-2. It was Piazza's second home run of the year and
the fifth of his career off Schmidt, who has surrendered more
homers to Piazza than to any other active hitter.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets increased their lead to 4-2 on the next pitch when
Ventura also took Schmidt over the right-field wall for a homer.
Ventura, who hit 32 home runs last year, was batting .139 before
connecting Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo had a hand in the Mets' other runs. His sacrifice fly
scored Rickey Henderson to give the Mets their first run in the
third inning. In the fifth, Alfonzo hit a one-out triple and scored
on an opposite-field double by Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   That appeared to be enough to support the left-hander Al Leiter,
who was starting for the first time in 11 days. He had strained his
groin in the Shea Stadium opener, in which he pitched eight strong
innings. He was sharp again Friday night, pitching seven and
two-thirds innings, allowing two earned runs on homers by Wil
Cordero and Kevin Young.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
