</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-RAPTORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS HAVE NO ANSWER FOR CARTER, OR RAPTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ All night long, Vince Carter would take off from the
floor with the unpredictability of a bottle rocket and leave behind
a vapor trail. In his wake, he left fear.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks tried to disguise their trepidation Friday night with
fits of visible anger. Afterward, they tried to smooth over their
anxieties with some reassuring words. But after another night when
they were baffled by Carter's moves and confused by their inability
to compete with the brazen Raptors, there is an unusual nervousness
beneath the Knicks' usual swagger.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a team that is not haunted by the Knicks. Here is a team
that does not tremble at their lore. Here is the team they may face
in the first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   What if they face this team in the first round? What if they
can't stop Carter again? On Friday, he unraveled their mental state
one more time as he scored 34 points and led the Raptors to a third
straight double-digit victory against the Knicks. This one was the
worst of all, an 86-71 victory for the Raptors that began with a
28-11 lead after the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Carter had only scored 2 points by then. The Knicks seemed
psyched out by his presence and let it filter down to their
horrible defense, slow transition offense and sloppy ball-handling
(19 turnovers). It was enough to let coach Jeff Van Gundy engage in
the kind of self-flogging that has become familiar when the Knicks
look as though they are flirting with danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't made it crystal clear what we need to do against
these guys,'' said Van Gundy, whose team dropped the season series,
3-1, to the Raptors and allowed Carter to average 33 points a game.
``He knows that we know we don't want to play him. We didn't want
to compete against him. I'm frustrated with myself. I haven't come
up with the right plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy tried Larry Johnson, then Latrell Sprewell, then
Marcus Camby, and not one of them could get close enough to put his
body on Carter. Meanwhile, the rest of the team was falling apart
on the side. Allan Houston (10 points) couldn't guard Dell Curry
(10 points) in the first quarter. Sprewell (3 for 13) couldn't get
off a focused shot, and Patrick Ewing (16 points) was too slow to
react to Antonio Davis (17 points) on the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we meet them in the playoffs, we have to find a way,''
Sprewell said. ``We have to figure out how to get it done. This
game will be fresh in our minds. I know that.''
</P>
<P>
   The third-seeded Knicks and sixth-seeded Raptors have just three
games left in the regular season. If the Knicks hadn't fallen
apart, they could have put the pressure on second-seeded Miami,
which lost to Indiana Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been like a highlight reel for them,'' Van Gundy said
before the game. ``Vince Carter has crushed us. Tracy McGrady has
had his way with us, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy sounded as if he was at his wits' end before tipoff.
In three games, Carter had averaged 32 points by weaving and
whirling past Sprewell. So Van Gundy tinkered with that strategy
and saddled Johnson with the task of keeping up with Carter.
</P>
<P>
   It was impossible. Some teams have had luck putting a body on
Carter and making him feel an arm in his ribs as he has taken shot.
Johnson couldn't get that close. Before he knew it, Carter would
step away from him, leap as he launched and snapped off
back-to-back jumpers in front of Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   He just looked over at Van Gundy in disgust after Carter rose up
for a third straight jumper to put the Raptors ahead, 35-16, with
seven minutes left in the second quarter. It would get worse. Van
Gundy pulled Johnson and put Sprewell back on Carter, but that
didn't work, either. In 45 seconds, Carter did a scissors kick as
he hit a fallaway 3-pointer at the shot-clock buzzer, and then lost
Sprewell on a screen for another 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks hit bottom at that point, down by 41-20 with 4:45
left in the half. No amount of pleading Van Gundy did in the
huddles registered. They let Carter destroy their confidence, ruin
their concentration and trickle down into every other part of their
game.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks finished the first half behind by 47-27, and were
shooting 32.4 percent. They had 12 turnovers, including 4 by Camby,
and had only one star to count on, Ewing. But he was in foul
trouble, and could deliver just 10 points in 14 minutes of the
first half.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Carter had 15 points (6 for 8), while Curry picked
apart Houston's defense for 10 points and Davis slipped outside of
Ewing's reach for another 10.
</P>
<P>
   These were the same Raptors who lost eight of nine games late
last month. The Raptors left people wondering if their young stars
would fold under the crush of the regular-season finish, and then
under the pressure of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take talent over experience anytime,'' Van Gundy said.
``I don't buy into it. This Toronto team can go to the finals out
of the East. They're that good.''
</P>
<P>
   They kept on validating that theory in the third quarter. With
Davis making a mockery out of Ewing's defense outside the paint, he
scored 6 points in two minutes to give the Raptors a 59-33 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Carter kept right on scoring, no matter who Van Gundy put on
him. The third Knick to try his luck with Carter was Camby. With
Camby's wingspan in his way, Carter simply dribbled forward,
stepped back and launched some more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
