<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS HOME OPENER A REAL GALA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They were weary from two months on the road and
five hours of sleep, maximum, thanks to the scheduling genius of
baseball, which made it all the more a wonderful time for the home
opener.
</P>
<P>
   The sleepy-eyed Los Angeles Dodgers were guzzling coffee like
harried college students readying for exams. Some had no idea where
they live, or how to get home from Dodger Stadium. They needed a
boost, and the soldout crowd was there to provide the stimulant.
</P>
<P>
   Once the yawning stopped, the Dodgers continued their strong
play as Gary Sheffield, Shawn Green and Eric Karros each drove in
two runs, and Orel Hershiser, who received a standing ovation
before throwing a pitch, battled through six innings as the Dodgers
beat the Cincinnati Reds 8-1 Friday in front of 53,223.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just an outstanding opening day,'' Dodgers manager
Davey Johnson said. ``We've been through the toughest time you
could imagine with this schedule. None of us got much sleep
(Thursday) night; to come in and wing the bats and play like we did
was outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, a team that thought completing a grueling season-
opening road trip to Canada, New York and San Francisco at .500
would be fantastic, has won five straight and is 7-3. The Dodgers
have not won six in a row since July 25-Aug. 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of day, opening day or not, guys can come and
try to get through the game, but we were battling,'' Green said.
``That's the thing right now that I'm really excited about. All
these little signs are pointing in the right direction for this
team. You look at Cincinnati last year and they were doing the
things we are doing early. You see the tendencies of a team early
on, and I think the tone of the year gets set early on.''
</P>
<P>
   The optimism is brought with tempered enthusiasm, but it lives.
On a day when expectations were limitless and the chance for
disaster great, Hershiser fought out of jams to record his first
win with the Dodgers since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But it certainly wasn't smooth. His only perfect inning was his
last. Twice, double plays bailed him out of trouble and the Reds
had runners at third three times but failed to get them in. The
only run was an Aaron Boone homer in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the starting rotation that brought question marks when
Kevin Brown was injured is 3-0 with a 3.13 ERA in his absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as what's going on in my life and what I have to look
forward to, this is a huge day,'' Hershiser said. ``It's hard to
describe. To be 41-years-old, to do something this special, to have
this kind of special day and have it turn out positive, it's an
awesome feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really like a playoff game. Opening day, a sellout, Mr.
(Bob) Daly's first game (as an owner). It was amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, once the Dodgers woke up.
</P>
<P>
   Through five innings they had two hits, including a Sheffield
solo homer. Meanwhile, the Reds looked poised to break it open in
every inning. And no time was better than te seventh. With the Reds
trailing 2-1, and reliever Terry Adams pitching, Ken Griffey Jr.
was up with the bases loaded and two out. Griffey, who hit into a
double play in the first inning, struck out on a high fastball.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the inning the Dodgers broke the game open with
six runs.
</P>
<P>
   With a run already in, Sheffield (3 for 3, HR) was intentionally
walked to load the bases only to have Green drive in a pair to
break the game open with a two-run double. Karros followed with his
own two-run double.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was it right there, with Griffey and Adams,'' Sheffield
said. ``I feel this team, we could win a one-run game or explode.
That's what championship teams need to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
