<HEADLINE>
FISHER FINALLY YIELDS TO INJURED LIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The seemingly indestructable Derek Fisher, who has
playedthrough every bruise and strain the last four seasons, was
finally felled by injury Friday, when the Lakers placed him on the
injured list for the first time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, who never talks about his injuries, has quietly carried
on for the last two weeks despite a bone spur in his right ankle.
Coach Phil Jackson hopes to have his hustling guard back for the
playoffs, which begin next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't moving right out there on the court the last couple
games,'' Jackson said. ``We felt if anything, some rest might help
him get back in the fray a little bit, so to speak.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers activated rookie guard John Celestand to take
Fisher's place on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   Counting Friday night's game against Sacramento, Fisher will
miss the last four games of the regular season. Normally, a player
on the injured list must skip five games, but Fisher's status for
the postseason will not be affected.
</P>
<P>
   Playoff rosters must be set by Thursday at noon, so the Lakers
have until then to determine if Fisher can play. Rosters cannot be
changed once the playoffs begin, except in extreme cases in which a
team has several injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you want to go in with players that are 100 percent or
close,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he'll force it if he can,'' Jackson said of Fisher.
``He's had this problem before. This is not new to him. But we hope
to get rid of that. We need someone that can take care of some
details out there.''
</P>
<P>
   As for gambling on Fisher's continued health, or on Celestand's
inexperience in the playoffs, Jackson said: ``I'm not thinking in
those type of terms yet. . . . I think Derek's going to get healed
and he'll be fine, and we'll go from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher had played in all 78 games and was averaging 6.3 points
and 2.8 assists in 23.1 minutes. He also started the first month of
the season, in place of the injured Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   __ His turn: Celestand was supposed to get his opportunity to
play last week, but the Lakers spiked a plan to put Ron Harper on
the injured list. Now the 6-2 guard from Villanova gets four games
to make an impression.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives me a good time at the end of the year to get some
playing time hopefully, and get a little bit of experience,'' said
Celestand, who appeared in 12 games in November and December but
hadn't played since. ``I've been anxious for a long time. It was
hard, because I thought I was going to play earlier, and it was
kind of disappointing, but we've got a good team and I've just got
to wait my turn.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Silenced: Lawrence Tanter, the Lakers' longtime
public-address announcer who has rarely missed a game, was out ill
Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
