<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S STILL BITE IN OL' BULLDOG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Orel Hershiser isn't superstitious or anything.
All the same, he'd really rather we didn't make a big fuss over how
well he and the other Los Angeles Dodgers starting pitchers are
faring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day you start saying the starting pitching is awesome,''
Hershiser cautioned, ``is the day the starters start to struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, so we won't make a big deal of the fact the Dodgers are 3-0
with a 3.13 ERA since their staff ace, Kevin Brown, broke his
pinkie.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser was the latest pitcher to star in a starting role. He
turned back Cincinnati and the clock Friday, pitching six gritty
innings in the Dodgers's 8-1 win in front of a Dodger Stadium
sellout of 53,223.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for someone brought in mostly for insurance and
inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers signed Hershiser in December, presumably to buttress
the relieving corps. The Bulldog had other ideas, though. He wasn't
ready to be put out to the pasture that is the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   He pushed left-hander Carlos Perez in spring training and drove
Eric Gagne, a pitcher 17 years Hershiser's junior, down to Triple-A
(if only temporarily) by usurping a spot in the starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Let the cynics say there's something wrong with a starting
rotation that can find room for a 41-year-old arm. But to look at
Hershiser as a pitcher whose best years are behind him is to see
the hourglass as nearly empty when the flip side is he's full of
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser brought 3,110 innings of hard-earned knowledge to the
mound for the Dodgers' home opener and proceeded to collect chits
for all that combat duty. Like Perez and Chan Ho Park before him,
Hershiser proved that where their starters have the will, the
Dodgers are finding ways to win.
</P>
<P>
   Despite battling untold distractions and a potent Cincinnati
lineup, Hershiser stuck around for 18 outs, thereby saving the bulk
of the bullpen for another day. It was the fifth time in 10 games a
Dodgers starter has stuck around through the sixth, no small factor
in their 7-3 start.
</P>
<P>
   When the starting rotation has staying power, it has a domino
effect on the whole team.
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen is better for it, gaining a decided advantage when
it's able to field a fresh arm every night. Batters are harder-
pressed to groove in on a reliever they aren't facing night in and
night out.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Dodgers reliever Mike Fetters, who was with Baltimore
last year. The first few weeks of the Orioles' 1999 season, Fetters
said, ``We couldn't get our starters out of the third and it took a
toll on the bullpen. Guys had to throw out of their comfort
zones.''
</P>
<P>
   The hitters also benefit from the doggedness of their starters
inasmuch as tenacity tends to be contagious. If a pitcher is
digging deep to get the job done, his teammates will take it upon
themselves to make his counterpart dig even deeper.
</P>
<P>
   So it was Friday when, fortified by Hershiser's will, the
Dodgers batters kept fighting, finally breaking open a one-run game
with a six-run seventh inning. It marked the sixth time the Dodgers
have scored more runs in the last three innings of a game than in
the opening or middle three innings, which suggests the starting
pitchers aren't the only ones hanging tough.
</P>
<P>
   Stalwart starters can benefit their managers most of all. As the
Dodgers' Davey Johnson quipped, ``When they go six, I become
smarter. When they go seven, I get to be a real genius.''
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser has stuck around for 18 major-league seasons because
he pitches with both his head and his heart. What he did for 98
pitches Friday was practice what he has been preaching to the
pitching staff since the start of spring training: Control one's
emotions for optimal control of one's pitches; block out
distractions and never, ever give up.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, a less-focused pitcher might have come unraveled a
little bit when he stood front and center in the Dodgers's first
home game of the season in the team's refurbished, re-energized
crib.
</P>
<P>
   A less-wily pitcher might have come undone in the third inning,
after giving up a leadoff home run to Aaron Boone and practically
capitulating to his rookie counterpart, Rob Bell, allowing him to
work the count to 3-2 before striking him out.
</P>
<P>
   The next batter, Pokey Reese, sent Hershiser's fourth pitch into
left for a double. After Barry Larkin grounded out, Hershiser
frittered away a 1-2 count on Ken Griffey Jr., walking him on seven
pitches before bearing down to get Dante Bichette to pop up to
first for the final out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I was walking a tightrope,'' Hershiser said,
summing up the inning.
</P>
<P>
   His high-wire act so inspired his teammates, they bound together
like protective netting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the whole team rallies around a performance like
that,'' said reliever Terry Adams, who succeeded Hershiser in the
seventh and struck out Griffey swinging with the bases loaded to
wiggle out of the inning unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Herges then mopped up. But make no mistake; on this day it
was Hershiser who provided the polish.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
