u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-3RDLD-WRITE     04-15 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-3RDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO MOVES TO REGAIN POWER TO TRANSFER CUBAN BOY 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to insert new 5th graf and to move last two grafs up as 6th
and 7th grafs, with some rewriting; see also CUBAN-BOY-LEGAL)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT14 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Justice Department Friday asked an appeals
court in Atlanta to lift an emergency injunction and give federal
law-enforcement officials the power to reunite Elian Gonzalez with
his father.
</P>
<P>
   If the federal court cancels an order issued on Thursday that
blocked the child's transfer, the government will be free take him
from his Miami relatives and allow the father, Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, to return home to Cuba with him.
</P>
<P>
   The swirl of legal maneuvering took place as hope for a
settlement dwindled.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Elian's Miami relatives showed no sign that they
would soften their determination to keep the boy even as
immigration officials wrote to Lazaro Gonzalez, the child's
great-uncle, reminding him that his legal authority over the child
ended on Thursday at 2 p.m. when he was ordered to take Elian to
authorities at an airport north of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, in a brief filed with the 11th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals, in Atlanta, the Miami relatives said that they had been
denied an opportunity to show in court why Elian should remain in
the United States. They said they had evidence that ``Elian
confronts serious psychological injury if he is removed from his
home with Marisleysis and taken to Cuba.'' Marisleysis is Lazaro
Gonzalez's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the relatives made public an uncorroborated
affidavit from Orlando Rodriguez, a neighbor of Elian's father in
Cuba, which said that the father mistreated his former wife, who
drowned in the attempt to flee Cuba with Elian last November. It
said that Rodriguez had ``personal knowledge'' of Juan Miguel's
mistreating his former wife, Elian's late mother, Elizabet Brotons.
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit said Rodriguez saw the father hit Brotons ``to the
point she went to the hospital'' and that similar acts were
inflicted on his son. The relatives said two other witnesses could
submit sealed affidavits about such behavior by Elian's father.
</P>
<P>
   At the Justice Department, a mood of grim resolve replaced the
disappointment over Attorney General Janet Reno's fruitless trip to
Miami on Wednesday to try to talk the relatives into giving up the
boy. Officials said that Reno was at last resigned to taking the
step she had hoped to avoid: a tactical law-enforcement operation
to remove the child from Miami forcibly.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said that Reno had quietly met law-enforcement
officials in Washington and Miami to discuss the operation.
</P>
<P>
   They said she alone would choose the timing and nature of the
action, adding that it was likely to be carried out using a minimum
of force at a time of the day when demonstrators were not likely to
be massed in the streets of the Little Havana neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Other officials said it was possible that Reno would delay a
tactical operation until next week, when there would be fewer
people available to take part in protests than on Saturday or
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as it is clear that there is no injunction, the
government will move to implement its enforcement action to enforce
our order,'' an immigration official said Friday. ``It seems clear
that the relatives have no intention of working with us on a
cooperative agreement to turn over the little boy.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, downpours reduced the number of demonstrators outside
the Gonzalez house from the thousands who marched in the streets on
Thursday to about 150 people, some of whom sang songs about Elian
during their soggy vigil.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department filed its brief with the 11th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals, in Atlanta. A judge on the panel had
issued a temporary order on Thursday, which prevented the
government from transferring Elian to his father and blocked the
boy's return with his father to Cuba. Gonzalez is now waiting in
Washington for a reunion with his son.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department brief said, ``It is very important to
Elian's long-term well-being that Elian be transferred to his
father's care as as soon as possible, that the transfer be
unambiguous, that his care-givers since his arrival in the United
States prepare him for and participate in the transfer in a
supportive manner and that the transfer occur at a neutral
location.''
</P>
<P>
   The brief said that that Reno and the immigration commissioner,
Doris Miessner, ``have gone to extraordinary lengths'' to obtain
the cooperation of Elian's Miami relatives in the last week. But,
the legal paper argued, the relatives had refused to obey lawful
government directives, like the order to hand Elian over to
authorities at the Opa-Locka airport north of Miami by the Thursday
afternoon deadline.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department's filing said that if the relatives
surrendered the child the government would use its authority to
keep Elian in the United States while the appellate court
considered the relatives' appeal of a decision by a federal
district judge in Miami who ruled that the government could allow
the child to return to Cuba with his father.
</P>
<P>
   The brief said that Gonzalez had agreed, in a letter sent on
Thursday to the Justice Department, to remain in the United States
for the appeal _ so long as he is given custody of his son.
</P>
</TEXT>
