<SLUG> BC-ELIANDECONCI-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECONCINI VISITS WITH ELIAN'S DAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY JEFF BARKER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   told a former Arizona senator that he's ``very upset'' that
Miami relatives released a home video of Elian instead of allowing
the boy to deliver his wrenching message directly to his dad.
</P>
<P>
   In the tape, Elian sits on a bed and tells his father in
Spanish, ``I don't want to go to Cuba . . . I want to stay here.''
</P>
<P>
   Juan Miguel Gonzalez, who is fighting the relatives for custody,
``was very upset about the tape they did,'' former Sen. Dennis
DeConcini, D-Ariz., said in an interview Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Gee, that's most unfortunate that they wouldn't have
the boy call you,' and he said, `Exactly!' '' DeConcini said.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez's response to the video was, ``If he wants to tell me
something, I'm his father, and we used to talk a lot,'' DeConcini
said. Questions have been raised about whether Elian's message was
coached.
</P>
<P>
   DeConcini, who retired from the Senate in 1994, visited
Gonzalez, his wife and baby as a representative of a business and
political group seeking to re-establish U.S. trade relations with
Cuba. The meeting Thursday night took place in a highly secured,
split-level home in a modest subdivision outside Washington that is
home to the chief of the Cuban Interests Section.
</P>
<P>
   According to DeConcini, Gonzalez said he declined an offer to
remain in the United States that was conveyed by Lazaro Gonzalez,
Elian's great-uncle in Miami. Juan Miguel told DeConcini the deal
would have included $2 million, a job, a car and a home with a
swimming pool, all from influential Cuban-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having been to Cuba and knowing how repressive it is, I was a
little surprised that he might not want to stay (in America). But
his answer was pretty fatherly, I thought,'' DeConcini said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no price for my kid's reunion with me, and we have a
home and a life in Cuba,'' Juan Miguel Gonzalez said through an
interpreter, according to DeConcini.
</P>
<P>
   An anti-Castro foundation in Washington said Friday that
Gonzalez probably would receive aid from the Cuban-American
community if he remained, just like any other Cuban refugee. But a
foundation official called the $2 million ``nonsense'' and charged
that DeConcini was being used by the Cuban government.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just stupefied that a man like Dennis DeConcini could go
into that house and think it is just a normal environment where
three people are free to express their opinions and make their
allegations and that we all should accept them at face value,''
said Jose Cardenas, director of the Cuban American National
Foundation, which has offices in Washington and Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas said that the father is ``under total control of the
Cuban government, he is a victim'' and that DeConcini is a pawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``This idea about $2 million is just absolute nonsense. Of
course, somebody would probably provide him a job, but he'd have to
show up and work. The bottom line is, America itself is the
incentive for people to free tyranny. They can't be bought with
cars and cash.''
</P>
<P>
   DeConcini, highly critical of Castro while in the Senate, says
that Cuba no longer poses a threat and that the continued embargo
is inconsistent with U.S. economic interests. But DeConcini, who
led a fact-finding trip to Cuba last year, said he is not naive
about the pressures on Cuban citizens to conform to the interests
of the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him a ton (of questions), being a former (Pima County)
prosecutor. Why don't you defect? Did they offer you anything here?
Did Castro or anybody in the Cuban government put pressure on
you?'' DeConcini said.
</P>
<P>
   ``His answers were pretty typical of what you think a father
would say. He acknowledges that life is good in the United States,
and he says that. And he doesn't admit that communism is terrible,
but he says, `It's my home, my family is there,' and he shows me a
picture of his family _ father, grandmother, mother and brother and
cousin.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian's mother drowned off Florida last Thanksgiving during a
raft trip from Cuba, and he has been in the care of Miami relatives
during the custody battle.
</P>
<P>
   DeConcini said he believes the Justice Department has purposely
dragged out the saga to be sure the father doesn't want to defect
to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had plenty of time to do it. He's been out taking coffee
to the police out there. He could have gotten in the car and left.
He doesn't want to,'' DeConcini said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Gonzalez ``had some tears in his eyes as he talked about
his son, because I asked him, `How much communication do you have
with your son? Are you allowed to talk with him?' '' DeConcini
said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
