<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7670 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODSIDE-LADN-(SLA     04-15 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODSIDE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _  &UR;  &LR; He came to Los Angeles Dodgers spring camp
claiming to be in the best shape of his life, and people nodded.
Heard that one before.
</P>
<P>
   Got off to a nice little start the first week and proclaimed,
``You ain't seen nothing yet.'' And they figured, right, how
original.
</P>
<P>
   Only now, it is clearly becoming time to pay attention to Gary
Sheffield. To what he says, maybe. To what he does, certainly.
</P>
<P>
   Opposing pitchers are, for all the good it's doing them. It
remains two very early weeks into the 2000 season, but Sheffield is
looking like a hitter who is out to prove something.
</P>
<P>
   Which it turns out, he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel like the Dodgers haven't seen the best of me,''
Sheffield said. ``I just want to go out, do the best I can, and the
more games I play, the more you'll all see.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are seeing plenty so far. Friday afternoon in their
home opener against the Reds, it was Sheffield opening the scoring
with his third home run. When the Reds tied the game, it was
Sheffield's hit that put the Dodgers back on top for good in the
third.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield has hit in each of the Dodgers' first 10 games,
batting .429. Actually, he ended last season with a six-game
hitting streak, giving him a carryover streak of 16 games (.414).
</P>
<P>
   ``He is locked in,'' Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone said.
``He's had nothing but good at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every at-bat, there is a chance to see something happen. He's
fun to watch right now.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not like success is new to the outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   He won a batting crown with the Padres at age 24. He had 42 home
runs and 120 RBI for the Marlins in 1996. The next year, he helped
lead the Marlins to their World Series title. Just last season, he
became the first Los Angeles Dodger to hit at least .300, with 30
home runs, 100 RBI, 100 walks and 100 runs.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Sheffield believes there is more to come, more to him than
the Dodgers have had chance to witness. That at age 31, the last
remaining Dodger acquired in the Mike Piazza trade can take his
game up another level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like on the field, anything I put my mind to, I can
do,'' said Sheffield, who at one time briefly considered retiring.
``I have that enthusiasm back.''
</P>
<P>
   He also has left-handed Shawn Green hitting behind him, though
the Reds _ in the ultimate respect of the hot hitter _
intentionally walked him in the seventh to get to Green (who
doubled, to score two). Sheffield has been in the midst of his
recent tear, despite badly spraining his ankle Saturday in New
York. Briefly he was on crutches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was concerned,'' Malone said. ``That was like Black Sunday.
(Kevin) Brown fractures his pinkie, (Gregg) Olson irritates a nerve
in his elbow, (Eric) comes up with a sore back.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Davey Johnson wanted to give him a day off, but
Sheffield wasn't going to let something like a swollen right ankle
slow him down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to rest him a game, but he wouldn't come out,''
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   With seven stints on the disabled list during his career,
Sheffield knows he has a reputation for being injury prone, and
it's one he wants to shake.
</P>
<P>
   Quietly, at least verbally, in his third season with the
Dodgers, Sheffield is emerging as a force at the plate and in the
dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's becoming a leader just by his performance,''
Malone said. ``He's stepped it up a notch. He sort of leads by
example.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Sheffield: ``I can't say it's my team. I feel like I have a
role as a leader and I feel like guys respond to me. But I just go
out and play baseball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
