<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO MO HITS IN LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Anaheim Angels starting pitcher Ken Hill had to leave
Friday night's game against the Chicago White Sox because of the
stomach flu, but after the Angels' 9-4 loss, it was Mo Vaughn who
was feeling sick.
</P>
<P>
   Physically, Vaughn is fine. It was his 0-for-5 performance which
gave him that queasy feeling. Vaughn's batting average dipped to
.216, and he has only four RBI in 10 games this season. He had
opportunities Friday but left runners on base in his first four
at-bats in front of a home-opening crowd of 38,912 at Comiskey
Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gotta get hot,'' Vaughn said. ``We gotta get consistent
production from 3-4-5. The opportunities are there.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Nos. 4 and 5 in the order weren't so bad Friday. Tim
Salmon had two doubles in the cleanup spot and Garret Anderson, who
signed a four-year contract extension, hit a two-run homer in the
No. 5 spot.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn came up with nobody out and runners on first and third in
the first inning and popped out. With a runner on first and none
out in the third, he flied out. With a runner on first and one out
in the fifth, he hit into a double play. With a runner on third and
two out in the seventh, he struck out. His flyout in the ninth
ended the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm slowing down the chain,'' he said. ``I'm not doing the
things I'm capable of doing, things that should be done. I'm not
clicking right now. We could have been up, 1-0, 2-0, 3-0. I'm not
casting in, but I'll get it together and get hot. I gotta get it
together, and I will.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Angels left the bases loaded in the top of the first,
the White Sox took the lead on Frank Thomas' solo homer with two
out in the bottom of the inning. In the second inning, Ray Durham
drove in a run with a sacrifice fly and Greg Norton scored two more
with a double for a 4-0 White Sox lead.
</P>
<P>
   Hill (1-2) worked a 1-2-3 third inning but gave up a run in the
fourth and didn't make it out of the inning. In 3 innings, Hill
gave up five runs and five hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew Ken was under the weather a little bit, but there
never was a point where scratching him was an option,'' Angels
manager Mike Scioscia said. ``He threw a lot of pitches and it
caught up with him. His command wasn't quite what it was in his
previous starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ken's arm is live, it feels good. His mechanics were sound,
but his stamina wasn't there. Even between innings, the innings got
long and he got tired.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill was back in his hotel room before the game was over, but
Angels catcher Bengie Molina said the weather added to Hill's
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball was moving everywhere, in and out, he's never had
that much movement on his ball,'' Molina said. ``His ball is
straight. The way it was moving tonight, it was the wind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
