<SLUG> BC-BBC-UCCSUN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS FINALLY GET VICTORY OVER NORTHRIDGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They are headed in opposite directions. The Cal
State Northridge and UCLA baseball teams have different goals,
though.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins want to be in the College World Series this year.
Northridge wants to be in the mix for the College World Series as
well, though maybe two seasons from now.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Friday night's game between UCLA and Northridge
seemed so, well, blah.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins used a three-run fifth to break open a close game and
won 10-5 at Jackie Robinson Stadium. But there were hardly any
nervous moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost a scout-league game atmosphere,'' said Northridge
coach Mike Batesole, alluding to exhibition games played against
each other by college teams each fall. ``Our goal is to keep
throwing the young guys out there. (UCLA) is a top-five team. It's
good for us to look at what we want to be someday.''
</P>
<P>
   True, 15th-ranked UCLA (24-13) went into this three-game
nonconference series against Northridge leading the Pac-10 at 6-2.
The Bruins are better than the Matadors (13-24) across the board.
</P>
<P>
   So it is satisfying for Batesole to see CSUN trailing 3-2 after
three innings and 6-3 going into the bottom of the seventh. But
there were painful visions.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN hit into two double plays, had two hits against Bruins
starter Ryan Karp (5-1) and had a runner picked off second base in
the fifth _ after a successful sacrifice bunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time next year, this better not be happening,'' Batesole
said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the staid appearance of the game, the Bruins did have
motivation _ they hadn't beaten the Matadors since 1995 and CSUN
was 4-0-1 in the teams' last five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no clue it was five years. Wow,'' said UCLA left fielder
Bill Scott, who was 4 for 5 with a double and two RBI. ``We haven't
forgotten what's happened. Last year, they took it to us (CSUN won
10-4 in Northridge). It was a pride thing; we've had some bad
performances against them.''
</P>
<P>
   Karp, a sophomore right-hander, had his second consecutive
quality start. He allowed two unearned runs, both in the third, and
struck out six. Left-hander Ryan Carter gave up four hits and two
runs in 2 innings of relief for UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Karp and Carter are two of the best 20 pitchers in the country
right now,'' Batesole said.
</P>
<P>
   A bright spot for Northridge was right fielder Tim Coltey, who
had three hits and scored twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always doing good things,'' said Coltey, a freshman from
Long Beach, ``but they're not enough to get the (win). We came in
here pumped up. We're always thinking positive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
