<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 01:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7698 &Cx1f; ttc-z
u a BC-DA-BELMONT-2Takes-LAD     04-15 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DA-BELMONT-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO CRIMES FOUND AT BELMONT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG GITTRICH 
 &HT;    and DAVID R. BAKER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Infuriating Los Angeles Unified's inspector
general, local, county and state prosecutors on Friday said
insufficient evidence exists to prove environmental crimes were
committed during the development of the ill-fated, $175 &UR;  &LR; million
Belmont Learning Center.
</P>
<P>
   The state Attorney General's, Los Angeles County District
Attorney's and City Attorney's offices reported separately that
none of the suspected felonies or misdemeanors can be proved beyond
a reasonable doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Bill Lockyer found that no state agency failed
to perform its oversight duties as required by law during the
planning or construction of the nation's costliest high school,
which was abandoned before completion because of environmental and
financial concerns.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Gil Garcetti's lead environmental prosecutor
contended that the environmental conditions at Belmont are not
unique and ``appear to be very limited,'' adding to an already
fierce debate over the safety of the 35-acre site.
</P>
<P>
   And City Attorney James Hahn's office said insufficient evidence
existed to prove any misdemeanors and noted that even if there were
proof, the statute of limitations for prosecution already had
expired.
</P>
<P>
   The enforcement agencies based their conclusions primarily upon
a six-month review of the evidence compiled by LAUSD Inspector
General Don Mullinax. City and county prosecutors said they also
conducted independent reviews of the project and consulted with
state and local regulatory agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly angry, Mullinax categorized the response as a
``brush-off'' that would set a dangerous precedent of companies not
being punished for breaking environmental laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad day for the children and the taxpayers of Los
Angeles,'' Mullinax said. ``(These decisions) show that children
can be put at potential risk and taxpayers' dollars wasted, but no
one is held accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   Mullinax added that developers across the state should joyously
proclaim: ``This is a great day. ... We can build where we want,
skirt the law and no one will hold us accountable!.''
</P>
<P>
   One of his lead investigators was more direct. ``This is clearly
a prosecutorial whitewash of Belmont,'' the investigator said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the school board voted in January to kill the project, a
debate over the safety of the campus has intensified and become
increasingly politicized. Along with the school's unprecedented
price tag, the main disagreement centers around whether toxic
hydrogen sulfide and explosive methane rising from an oil field
below the site make it unsafe and if so, there is vast disagreement
about whether a fail-safe technical fix can be designed and
installed to protect students and teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives from the attorney general's, district
attorney's, and city attorney's offices rejected Mullinax's
criticism and allegations of a cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very disappointed with the internal auditor's response,
which attempts to deflect attention away from the fact that (the)
report simply does not support the allegations of criminal
wrongdoing,'' Garcetti said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a violation of the public trust for any
prosecutorial agency to file criminal charges when there is
insufficient evidence to support the allegations.''
</P>
<P>
   Deputy City Attorney Vincent B. Sato, supervisor of the
environmental protection section, added: ``This is not a whitewash.
Very experienced and seasoned environmental prosecutors worked on
this for quite some time. There just wasn't anything there.''
</P>
<P>
   Head Deputy District Attorney John Paul Bernardi, who heads up
the environmental crimes division, said Mullinax was off base.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our primary jurisdiction in the case was felonies. They didn't
show us any felonies,'' Bernardi said.
</P>
<P>
   He then added, ``I am not convinced that they have demonstrated
the methane problem that was described.''
</P>
<P>
   In a confidential referral sent last September to the three
agencies, as well as the U.S. Attorney's Office, Mullinax said his
million-dollar audit found ``reasonable cause to believe'' that the
developer, former school boards, state agencies and several
environmental consultants violated environmental, hazardous waste,
and education laws and statutes.
</P>
<P>
   Mullinax singled out Temple Beaudry Partners _ a consortium led
by Kajima Urban Development _ and environmental consultants El
Capitan, CalEx, Intera, Law/Crandall and Remedial Management Corp.
None of the firms responded to requests on Friday for comment.
</P>
<P>
   While Mullinax has a ``reasonable cause to believe'' crimes were
committed, prosecutors said, the same evidence failed to provide
proof beyond a reasonable doubt, which must be met in a criminal
prosecution.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL 2ND TAKE FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   During the past six months, representatives from each agency
have met repeatedly to reach a consensus on their handling of the
Belmont fiasco.
</P>
<P>
   The agencies did not address findings contained in Mullinax's
second audit of Belmont, which documented a long list of alleged
financial crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Reports from the prosecutorial agencies on the suspected
financial crimes are expected this summer. One official involved in
the review of Mullinax's second audit described the financial
allegations as ``more promising than the environmental stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   School board member Mike Lansing, who supports abandoning
Belmont, said he now hopes to push for completion of a final
battery of environmental tests by the state Department of Toxic
Substances Control.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles County Supervisor Gloria Molina, one of the
project's most vocal supporters, and state Assemblyman Antonio
Villaraigosa, a mayoral candidate, have offered to find the
$1million needed to complete the tests.
</P>
<P>
   School board members Valerie Fields and Caprice Young, who both
voted with a five-person majority to abandon Belmont, said they
accept the prosecutorial decisions, but showed no sign of changing
their stance on the school's fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have, in a criminal finding, a very high level of
proof, and that's very hard to get,'' Fields said. ``It may be
unethical, but it may not rise to that level.''
</P>
<P>
   While nearly identical in their conclusions, the state, county
and city presented their evaluation of Mullinax's allegations to
the public in very different forms.
</P>
<P>
   The Attorney General's Office issued a brief statement from
Lockyer but would not release its report. A spokeswoman said the
report was confidential.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Daily News obtained a copy of an 18-page report
written by Richard M. Frank, chief assistant attorney general. It
focuses almost entirely on the responsibility of state agencies,
including the Department of Conservation, Department of Toxic
Substances Control, Department of Education, Division of Oil and
Gas, and the Governor's Office of Planning and Research.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the affected state agencies performed well and
faithfully executed their responsibilities under California Law,''
Frank wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The City Attorney's Office released a 25-page packet that
addressed each of the allegations in Mullinax's referral letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although we are concerned that the on-site methane
accumulation at the Belmont Learning Complex poses a threat to
public safety, as prosecutors we are ethically bound to consider
only legally admissible evidence in making a charging
determination,'' the City Attorney's report concluded.
</P>
<P>
   The District Attorney's Office released a 57-page report,
supported by more than 400 pages of exhibits, including aerial
photos and detailed maps.
</P>
<P>
   Since construction was temporarily halted at Belmont in February
1999, Garcetti has faced mounting criticism over his handling of
the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of the described conduct would support a felony
prosecution,'' the report said, suggesting administrative or civil
remedies.
</P>
<P>
   In a two-page, written critique of Garcetti's report, Mullinax
refused to back down from his belief that key players involved in
Belmont broke the law.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly troubling, Mullinax insisted, was Garcetti's lack
of interest in the failure of Belmont's developer and a contractor
to alert the city's fire department that they had found significant
amounts of explosive methane gas in areas they previously said were
clean. The companies delayed giving fire officials the updated
information for six months, Mullinax said, while buildings were
under construction on the site.
</P>
<P>
   If the city had received that information in time, Mullinax
said, proper protections against methane buildup could have been
designed and installed. Other Los Angeles buildings in the vicinity
have included such protections, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did it the right way,'' Mullinax said. ``They didn't put
up a building first and then say, whoops.''
</P>
<P>
   City and county prosecutors said that no basis exists for
criminal prosecution of the developer for its handling of the
site's methane conditions or its dealings with the fire department.
</P>
<P>
   Temple Beaudry Partners, which was fired by the district last
November, has denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-15-00 0146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000415.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 01:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7702 &Cx1f; ttc-z
u a BC-WAYSTATION-WAR-LADN     04-15 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAYSTATION-WAR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANCTUARY DISPUTES ALLEGATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By  JENNIFER HAMM  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Wildlife Waystation officials vowed Friday to
fight allegations that the facility is unsafe even as state
officials released details of problems that caused them to halt
tours and other operations.
</P>
<P>
   The state agency said it found hundreds of Fish and Game Code
violations when a team of 20 inspected the exotic animal sanctuary
last month. The most serious include allegations of allowing
wastewater to flow into a stream and caging that does not meet
state codes.
</P>
<P>
   Wildlife Waystation founder and director Martine Colette, who
said she feels betrayed and unjustly accused, assembled her own
team of researchers and other supporters and even actress Dyan
Cannon at a news conference at the facility Friday to help counter
the state's allegations.
</P>
<P>
   The supporters said the 1,200 lions, tigers, monkeys and other
animals receive top-shelf care at the nation's largest rescue
sanctuary for exotic animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way station performs an incredible duty for animals in
need,'' said James Mahoney, a research professor from New York
University's School of Medicine, who flew in to Los Angeles to
speak on the way station's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney gave about 50 chimpanzees to the way station in 1995
when the university research laboratory he worked in was being
turned over to a private researcher. Mahoney said he searched the
United States for a place to house the chimps and chose the way
station.
</P>
<P>
   He visits the animals regularly and said they receive
``exemplary care.''
</P>
<P>
   A concern that any of the chimps are HIV positive or have
hepatitis B is unfounded, Mahoney said. That conclusion, he
believes, may have been drawn because the animals were involved
with research for finding vaccines for both diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The health of the chimps remains a concern, however, for Fish
and Game officials, who said they have still not received health
records requested weeks ago. State officials have expressed concern
that a quarantined chimp has not been properly isolated .
</P>
<P>
   The chimps' health was not, however, among the concerns outlined
in a five-page letter sent to the way station on Friday. The letter
details 10 specific alleged violations found during the three-day
inspection. Most refer to water problems such as trash and other
possible dangerous items found within 150 feet of a stream.
</P>
<P>
   Colette said the entire 160 acres of the way station is near or
part of a stream.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot get 150 feet away from the water,'' she said. ``The
garbage in my office can't be 150 feet away.''
</P>
<P>
   Fish and Game officials maintain they saw workers spraying feces
into a stream. They declined to release tapes they have said
support their allegations, saying the tapes are part of the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin Blevins, watermaster for the San Fernando Valley, said
that in more than 20 years of inspecting the area, he has not found
the way station to be responsible for water contamination.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing going on here that is adverse to the water
quality in the San Fernando Valley,'' Blevins said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 cages were inspected last month and state
officials said two-thirds are out of compliance. Half of those have
``minor deficiencies, but the remainder have substantial problems
that may be difficult to bring into conformance,'' according to the
letter sent by Michael R. Valentine, an attorney for the California
Department of Fish and Game.
</P>
<P>
   Fish and Game spokesman Steve Martarano said the next step is to
set up a meeting with way station officials to work out the
problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-15-00 0150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
