<HEADLINE>
HOME FOUND FOR ANDERSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Garret Anderson found a home in center field after the
trade of Jim Edmonds last month, and Friday the Angels signed him
to a contract extension that will keep him at home through 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who is making $3.25 million this year in the final
year of his current contract, is believed to be getting a deal
worth between $19-21 million over four years beginning with the
2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson made it clear in recent weeks he wanted to stay in
Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the direction the team is going,'' said Anderson, 27.
``The coaches, the direction of the front office and some of the
moves they made. And the people who I work with every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The feeling was mutual, especially after Anderson had his best
season in 1999 _ 157 games, .303 average, 21 homers, 80 RBI, 188
hits _ and was the club's MVP.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're full of surprises,'' general manager Bill Stoneman
joked. ``We started to work on it in spring training, but it took a
little bit of time. It was something neither of us wanted to carry
into the season, but it seemed like it made tons of sense to keep
it going because it was something both sides wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who was reared in Granada Hills and lives in Sand
Canyon, said staying close to home was important.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was definitely something I wanted to do, but I didn't know
how possible it was going to be,'' he said. ``I had to be ready for
the reality it might not happen.''
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!What a rookie:!off! The Angels have had only one American
League rookie of the year in club history _ Tim Salmon in 1993 _
but have two who could contend for the award this season.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Ortiz (1-0, 3.60 ERA) won his first start of the season,
but even more impressive so far has been sec- ond baseman Adam
Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, acquired from the Cardinals in the trade for Edmonds,
had three hits Friday and is now hitting .357 with a team-high five
stolen bases. But Rookie of the Year?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so early, so far off,'' the former Cal State Northridge
standout said. ``It's not what anybody in here wants to hear about,
as far as what your mindset should be. Something like that comes
with the team's success.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
