<HEADLINE>
LAKERS HOLD OFF KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ At some later date, perhaps in another week or
so, the wisdom of the Los Angeles Lakers' strategy Friday night may
be called into question. For now, it will go down as just another
satisfying, if meaningless, victory on the way to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Lakers meet the Sacramento Kings when those playoffs
begin,they'll have only themselves to blame for orchestrating the
matchup with their toughest possible first-round opponent.
</P>
<P>
   By beating Sacramento, 121-114, at Staples Center, the Lakers
prevented the seventh-seeded Kings from gaining a game on the
eighth-seeded Seattle SuperSonics. If the Kings, just a game up on
Seattle, slip to the No. 8 slot, it means a first-round meeting
with the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   And few teams have, in the words of coach Phil Jackson, been as
befuddling to the Lakers as the Kings _ whose point total Friday
was the most scored against the Lakers this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers won the season series, 3-1, including both games at
Staples. But this game was typical of the way things have gone _
with the Kings pushing the Lakers to the brink at every turn.
</P>
<P>
   It took a monstrous, 41-point night from Shaquille O'Neal to
hold off the scrappy Kings. O'Neal, playing his first game in more
than a week after resting a sprained left ankle, made 16 of 29
field goals and 9 of 15 free throws to go with 16 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant added 31 points and Glen Rice scored 24, making 8 of
13 field goals. Ron Harper had 10 assists.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento took a 15-point lead in the first half, watched the
the Lakers wipe it out and build a double-digit lead in the second
half, then clawed back in the final minutes to make things
interesting again.
</P>
<P>
   After trailing by as many as 13 points in the fourth, the Kings
pulledwithin three points, 111-108, with just over three minutes
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   But Bryant hit a pair of free throws and a fadeaway jumper that
bounced up and in as the Lakers pulled away again. Rice and Bryant
combined for six free throws down the stretch to put it away as the
Lakers _ who already have clinched the league's best record _
improved to 65-13, with three games left to play.[ep They survived
a 36-point, 10-rebound night from Chris Webber, who has given them
fits in every meeting this season.
</P>
<P>
   Having weathered Bryant's one-game suspension, Harper's one-game
rest and O'Neal's two-game respite, the Lakers trotted out their
regular starting five for the first time in five games. But they
looked more like third-stringers in the first half, as the Lakers
fell to a 65-57 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings came out with their usual rapid-fire offense, and
almost everything seemed to find the net as they made 58.7 percent
of their shots,led by a 21-point, 9-for-12 effort from Chris
Webber.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of the worst defensive halves of the season for the
Lakers,who lead the league in opponents' field-goal percentage
(.414). The 65 points scored by the Kings was one point shy of the
most allowed by the Lakers in a half this season. And Sacramento's
39-point first quarter was the most scored by a Laker opponent in
any quarter this season.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Anderson made 5 of 7 shots for 14 points as the Kings built
as much as a 15-point lead in the half.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers stayed in the game on the strength of O'Neal's 19
points, Bryant's 12 points and a 7-point effort off the bench from
Robert Horry.
</P>
<P>
   As promised, O'Neal showed little rust after a one-week layoff
to heal a sprained left ankle. He missed 4 of his first 5
field-goal attempts, but quickly settled into a groove.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson figured O'Neal would have no trouble reacclimating after
his only injury absence of the season. Asked before the game what
he anticipated, Jackson quipped, ``I expect 50 points, 20 rebounds,
10 blocks, five assists.''
</P>
</TEXT>
