<P>
   &UR; For SATURDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, April 15.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 9 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-HOLOCAUST (Jerusalem) _ In a basement meeting room in the
Israeli Parliament, a committee of legislators is trying to unravel
a tangled and troubling legacy of the Holocaust that has gone
unexplored for decades. The committee, led by Colette Avital, a
lawmaker from the governing One Israel Party and former Israeli
consul-general in New York, is investigating what happened to bank
accounts, plots of land and other assets that were held in Israel
by Jews who died in the Holocaust. Begun in February at Avital's
initiative, the parliamentary inquiry reflects a growing sense here
that Israel should practice what it has preached. By Joel
Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT 33 has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   GAMBIA-WWII-VETS (Farafenni, Gambia) _ Around Farafenni, a
border town in the interior of this tiny West African nation,
Bakary Dibba is known as the last survivor among the 10 local men
who fought in the British army against the Japanese in Burma. World
War II changed Africa forever, in great part because the European
colonial powers drafted hundreds of thousands of young men like
Dibba from the remotest corners of their African colonies and sent
them to places they never knew existed. A clear moral imperative
may have guided U.S. and British soldiers as they fought in Europe
and Asia, but for many African soldiers _ fighting as they did for
their colonial masters, the same men who talked of battling the
racist regimes of Nazi Germany and Japan _ there was deep
ambivalence. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   (Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   L.A.-SCHOOLS-CORTINES (Los Angeles) _ Ramon C. Cortines does not
put much stock in the trappings of power. His spotless desk at the
Los Angeles Unified School District headquarters is not in the
spacious superintendent's suite, but in a small ascetic office just
down the hall. But in just over three months as interim
superintendent of the nation's second-largest public school system,
Cortines has shown himself to be quite comfortable with the
exercise of power. He was brought in to shake up a system in
crisis, and he has. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT 27 has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIAN-SAMOVAR (New York) _ Much of New York's Russian-American
population has funneled in and out of the Russian Samovar
restaurant for more than a decade. The restaurant has become much
more than a place to eat: The Samovar is an unwieldy and thoroughly
singular social club. By Kathleen O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ Jews preparing for Passover and
Christians intent on the coming Holy Week cannot be expected to pay
much heed to the fact that April is National Poetry Month. But
perhaps they should. By Peter Steinfels.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NADER-POLITICS (Minneapolis) _ Forget six years of booming
economic growth and skyrocketing stock markets. Globe-trotting
corporations are sucking the life out of small business owners and
family farmers. Pollution is poisoning our rivers, lakes and air.
Inner city schools and health clinics are crumbling. And while the
nation burns, the rich are buying and selling politicians like
cheap baseball cards. ``Big business is on a collision course with
American democracy, and American democracy has been losing.'' Those
are the words of Ralph Nader, who is mounting another radical
campaign for the presidency. But this time things are a little
different. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT 4 has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOTCOM-LOSSES (Mountain View, Calif.) _ In a market climate that
can alter a company's prospects in the course of a trading day for
no easily discernible reason, employees and executives in the
high-technology industry have found creative ways to cope with _
and tune out _ what they cannot control. Executives must manage
expectations of investors, partners and acquisition candidates,
sometimes uncertain of the company's value from one day to the
next. They must calm employees unsure whether they will have enough
for the down payment on a house and who are besieged by job offers
from competitors. A look inside HearMe, an Internet company,
illustrates how one Silicon Valley company, and its rank-and-file
employees, cope financially and emotionally with being caught up in
the market's volatility. By Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   (Graphic is being sent to New York Times graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-DEBT (Sao Paulo, Brazil) _ A look at a long-running
financial scandal surrounding the mayor of Sao Paulo, which has
left the city mired in billions of dollars in debt and risking
insolvency. By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE AND ENTERTAINMENT (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BARZUN-CULTURAL-HISTORY (Undated) _ Jacques Barzun, one of the
founders of ``cultural history,'' taught history at Columbia
University for nearly 50 years and led legendary seminars with
Lionel Trilling. He has written over 30 books, translated nearly a
dozen more, and now, at 92, has finished an epic chronicle of his
historical forays, a survey of 500 years of Western cultural life.
By Edward Rothstein.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT 3 has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   BACH-FUGUES (Undated) _ The fugue is a drama not about the
individual voice at large in a society of sound, but a drama about
a society of sound created by related individual voices. It is an
astonishing structure, constructed with intense concentration. Bach
was so renowned for his fugues that after King Frederick II of
Prussia challenged him to improvise a fugue based upon a
mischievously slithering theme, Bach countered with a masterpiece
of inventive play, ``The Musical Offering.'' By Edward Rothstein.
</P>
<P>
   NSYNC (Undated) _ Until last month 'N Sync was the second-banana
boy band, seen almost universally as a Backstreet Boys knockoff.
Then 'N Sync's third album, ``No Strings Attached'' (Jive), sold
1.1 million copies in the United States the day it was released,
March 21. Within a week it had sold 1.3 million more, and it has
now passed 3.8 million. The group's entire national tour, which
reaches Madison Square Garden on July 25, is already sold out. By
Jon Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-COLUMN (Boston) _ Anthony Lewis writes about Lori
Berenson, a 30-year-old American being held in an isolation cell in
Peru _ a cell without light, heat or running water.
</P>
