<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 02:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7708 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-NADER-POLITICS-2NDLD-     04-15 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NADER-POLITICS-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RALPH NADER'S PRESIDENTIAL CAMPAIGN IS MAKING UNEXPECTED HEADWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS to change globe-trotting to global in 2nd graf.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ The students with purple hair, the graying
academics with Jerry Garcia beards and the union organizers with
their anti-WTO buttons had crowded into the college auditorium to
hear some red-meat _ make that green-vegetable _ radicalism. And
Ralph Nader, America's foremost consumer curmudgeon, did not
disappoint:
</P>
<P>
   Global corporations are sucking the life out of small businesses
and family farms. Pollution is poisoning our rivers and air.
Inner-city schools and health clinics are crumbling. And while the
nation corrodes, the rich are buying and selling politicians like
baseball cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big business is on a collision course with American democracy,
and American democracy has been losing,'' said Nader, who in his
dark suit was the most conventional-looking person in the room.
</P>
<P>
   The man who became famous by killing off a sporty but unstable
little car called the Corvair some 35 years ago is at it again,
running for president on the Green Party line.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike his previous presidential effort in 1996, when he
refused to raise money, spent less than $5,000 and attracted barely
1 percent of the vote, this time he is serious, Nader insists. And
that could spell trouble for Vice President Al Gore, from whose
Democratic column Nader is likely to draw most of his votes,
political analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I specifically said I wasn't going to campaign in '96,'' said
Nader. ``This is a campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader is cranking up that campaign just in time to step onto the
world stage this weekend, when tens of thousands of protesters
descend on Washington to demonstrate against the International
Monetary Fund and the World Bank. Green Party affiliates from
around the world are playing a major role in the protests, and
Nader himself will address demonstrators near the White House on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is not to win, of course, but to get more than 5
percent of the vote, the number that would qualify Nader for
millions in federal campaign matching funds that he says he would
use to build the Green Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Green Party breaks 5 percent, the Democratic Party
won't be the same again,'' said Nader, still irrepressibly dour and
hauntingly hungry-looking at 66, reflecting on the prospect of
undercutting the influence of the centrist Democratic Leadership
Council and its president, Al From. ``If you think Al From and the
Democratic Leadership Council has a grip on the Democratic Party,
wait and see what a significant and growing progressive third party
can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Vice President Al Gore, the apparent Democratic
nominee, say they are not losing sleep over a Nader challenge.
Nader is not the most skillful of campaigners, and even many
liberal allies question his ability to move voters. Further, the
Green Party is better known for its internal squabbling than its
ability to run campaigns or raise money. Nader's aides say they
have raised thousands of dollars so far, but will not file their
first campaign finance report until next month.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's yielding even a few percentage points to Nader could
be damaging to the vice president if the election is tight.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a recent poll by the Zogby Group showed Nader receiving
more support than Pat Buchanan, the likely Reform Party candidate,
5 percent to 3 percent. The poll indicated that the vast majority
of Nader's support came from Democrats and that he was doing
particularly well in California, considered a vital state for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   All of this suggests that an aggressive Nader campaign could
eliminate any advantages Gore might have gained from Buchanan, who
is expected to siphon votes from the likely Republican candidate,
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Nader intends to remain a thorn in Gore's side by promoting
issues that many liberals _ a large number of whom defected to Bill
Bradley in the Democratic primaries _ say the Clinton
administration has neglected: universal health care, urban poverty,
the environment and campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike Bradley, Nader _ like Buchanan _ is a fierce opponent
of the North American Free Trade Agreement and the World Trade
Organization, endearing him to traditionally Democratic union
members who feel the Clinton administration's free-trade policies
have hurt American workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have very little loyalty to either party,'' Nader
asserted.
</P>
<P>
   Nader contends that he expects to draw almost equally from both
major parties. But Republicans are a rare species in his crowds.
More common are disaffected Democrats like Stanley Campbell, 49,
who voted for the Clinton-Gore ticket in 1996 but feels Gore has
become Bush's look-alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Bore versus Gush,'' said Campbell, the director a church
social service agency who watched Nader speak in Dekalb, Ill.,
recently. ``I just don't know if there would be much difference
between the two.''
</P>
<P>
   As evidence that this year will be different from 1996, Nader
says he has hired 15 full-time campaign workers in Washington and
will soon dispatch 10 more _ possibly including former Bradley
campaign organizers _ to get him on the ballot in every state. (The
Green Party is already on the ballot in 13 states, including New
York and California.)
</P>
<P>
   He has also vowed to raise $5 million, and he says he may get
some help from celebrities like Paul Newman, Warren Beatty and
Susan Sarandon, and musicians like Bonnie Raitt, Jackson Browne and
the Indigo Girls.
</P>
<P>
   But to get anywhere near 5 percent, Nader will have to overcome
some big obstacles, not the least of which is the Green Party
itself. The party is notoriously disorganized and fractious, with
some groups opposing any involvement in electoral politics and
others supporting another candidate, Jello Biafra, the former lead
singer for the rock group the Dead Kennedys.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is Nader. Gawky, shy and prone to long speeches,
he is the first to acknowledge that he is not the world's best
campaigner. He is, for one thing, painfully uncomfortable with
asking people for their votes. Last week, for instance, a Delta
Airlines workers stopped him in the Minneapolis airport to say,
``I'm a big fan.'' All Nader could say in return was, ``Thanks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Campaigning takes a level of political ego I just don't have
yet,'' he said after the man had sped off.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   He is also notoriously private, refusing to tell even co-workers
where he lives. (It is in an apartment he rents in the Dupont
Circle section of Washington.) And the only crumbs of biographical
information he salts into his hour-long speeches are passing
references to his Connecticut hometown of Winsted. Rarely does he
mention that he is the son of Lebanese immigrants, that his father
owned a restaurant, that he studied Chinese at Princeton and law at
Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   His secretiveness has spawned a host of dark theories among his
critics. Some contend that despite his seemingly penurious
lifestyle, he is actually quite wealthy. Some contend that he lives
in a million-dollar town house here, not in the ill-furnished
apartment of Nader lore. (Nader says the town house he has been
spotted entering is his sister's.) They say that despite his
seemingly penurious way of living, he is actually quite wealthy,
that he purposely spent almost nothing on his 1996 campaign to
skirt federal election laws, which require candidates who spend
more than $5,000 to file reports disclosing their assets.
</P>
<P>
   Nader says he will file a financial disclosure report next
month. It will show, he said, that despite his attacks on genetic
engineering firms and Microsoft, he owns technology stocks. It will
also disclose, he said, that he earned about $200,000 last year in
speaking fees but gave half of it to charities. Most of his
remaining earnings went toward ``projects.'' He lives on about
$25,000 a year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how such a private man could run for such a public job,
Nader, who has never been married, replied, ``When you work all the
time you don't have a problem in terms of private time. There is no
private time.''
</P>
<P>
   Even among many leftists, Nader is not considered the dream
candidate. In a recent essay in The Nation, Katha Pollitt
complained that Nader was a less than scintillating standard-bearer
and that his 1996 campaign had focused too much on trade issues to
the exclusion of other issues dear to the left, such as race
relations, health care, and gay and abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of progressives cranking up an organization, raising
funds, fomenting energy and enthusiasm on behalf of this doomed
project,'' Pollitt wrote, ``well, it's just too depressing. If
working on Nader's campaign is the best way progressives can spend
the next eight months, it's time to hire a hearse and lie down in
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader, who says he is running partly at the behest of Green
Party leaders, replied, ``I think she ran out of material that
week.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, his platform seems to reflect some of the criticisms of
progressives like Pollitt. At the top is universal health care
followed by an anti-poverty program built heavily on
consumer-protection ideas, including loan discrimination by banks,
high auto insurance rates and landlord abuses.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Corporate welfare,'' one of his favorite issues, will also
play front-and-center in his campaign as he rages against
government tax-breaks and subsidies which allow big companies ``to
privatize profits and socialize risk.''
</P>
<P>
   And in an effort to win support from social conservatives, he
plans to attack big media corporations for exploiting children with
their racy programming and aggressive marketing practices.
</P>
<P>
   While he is counting on anti-trade protests this week to raise
his national profile, Nader says his best hope for gaining
attention will be to squeeze between Gore and Bush in televised
debates.
</P>
<P>
   The private commission that will determine presidential debate
participants has said candidates must be receiving 15 percent in
national polls to be included. Nader contends the threshold is
ridiculously high and plans to recruit Buchanan to protest the
process. And he said that if he prevails he hopes to raise the kind
of questions that will spark interest in his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Candidates are asked, What is your position on welfare, what
is your position on crime?' '' Nader said. That's not the right
question. It needs an adjective. What is your position on corporate
welfare? What is your position on corporate crime? We're going to
open this up. We're going to provide adjectives to these issues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
