<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-SPOON-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME AT LAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG SPOON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Well, they did it.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers got their home opener in before the All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   Forced by the schedule makers to wait nearly two weeks into the
season to play a home game, the Dodgers tried to make up for lost
time here Friday afternoon. And although dark clouds and a couple
light showers threatened the festivities, there was just no way
they were going to rain out the Dodgers' parade.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers paraded 16-year-old drummers in the outfield. They
paraded 41-year-old Orel Hershiser to the mound. The drummers
drummed, the Bulldog growled and the Dodgers beat big, bad Ken
Griffey Jr. and the Cincinnati Reds, 8-1.
</P>
<P>
   All is well in the ``new and improved`` Dodger Stadium, where
the foul territory is shrinking as fast as the Krispy Kreme
doughnut stands are moving in.
</P>
<P>
   The stadium, soon to become the fourth oldest ballpark in the
major leagues, is a mere shadow of its former self. Fox has gone
corporate on the Dodgers, cluttering up the club level with 33 new
luxury boxes. Not only that, they took out the landmark sunken
``dugout`` boxes behind home plate and replaced them with nine new
rows of seats in a little neighborhood they call the Dugout Club.
</P>
<P>
   Fans there were even closer to the plate Friday than was
Hershiser, who played out a 1988 highlight reel for six innings
before retiring to the real dugout with a 2-1 lead and eventually
the win. Presumably, he is not after Dave Johnson's job for at
least another five days.
</P>
<P>
   The more things change, the more they stay the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt like Dodger Stadium, it felt like L.A., but it
definitely felt like a different ballpark,'' said Hershiser, who
returned to the Dodgers this spring after a five-year absence. ``It
felt different to look in to the catcher and see people right
there. Before, there was always an optical ilusion that the catcher
was out there all alone for you to focus on.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't stop the distractions from coming in. The yellow
seats, which have always stood out in the background here. The
(outfield) wall with all that stuff (murals) on it when you look
out there. You have to keep control of every thought when you're
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially when you're 41 and your Bulldog status admittedly is
now more like that of a cocker spaniel with attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Hershiser allowed only six hits in six innings, including
a home run to Aaron Boone leading off the third. Yes, he got
Griffey to ground into a double play in the first inning and
retired him on an inning-ending grounder with a man on third in the
fifth.
</P>
<P>
   But he also threw 98 pitches, worked out of a stretch about half
the time and failed to argue with Johnson when the manager
suggested perhaps that was enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was sort of a mutual agreement,'' Hershiser said with a
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Who cares? No harm done. The man knows his limits, the fans got
their thrill and the Dodgers won anyway, jumping on Reds relievers
for six runs in the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   So Hershiser uses his changeup a little more these days because
his fastball lost some of its fast and his sinker lost some of its
sink. So what? As long as he keeps games close and the fans
continue to fall for a guy with a baby face who tries real hard to
scowl, Orel will be around a while longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get up some days and I feel like a kid, and other days I get
up feeling like I'm 41,'' Hershiser said. ``You hope the days you
pitch, you feel like a kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was one of those days. This was not a hard one to get up
for.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course not. The man lives a charmed life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
