<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 10:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7762 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-LAWSTUDENTS-ETHICS-RE     04-15 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAWSTUDENTS-ETHICS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING FOR A FEW HONEST LAWYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By ALEX BERENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   To cynics, the news last month that three Georgetown University
law students had settled Securities and Exchange Commission charges
of running an Internet stock manipulation scheme that netted almost
$350,000 probably came as no surprise. After all, lawyers have had
an image problem at least since Shakespeare, and it hasn't improved
in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   But even people who think the phrase legal ethics is an oxymoron
may have been startled by Georgetown's announcement that it would
take no action against the students, Douglas Colt, Kenneth Terrell
and Jason Wyckoff, who did not admit or deny wrongdoing in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   That decision created considerable public controversy, and the
school, which initially said the students had suffered enough,
quickly reversed itself and opened an investigation into their
actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have the full picture of what the SEC's response
was,'' said Karen Siebert, a school spokeswoman. ``Whether or not
they will graduate is not certain.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgetown is also the school that in 1998 quietly allowed
Stephen Glass, who fabricated all or parts of dozens of stories he
wrote at The New Republic magazine, to become a full-time law
student. He is now only two months from earning his degree.
</P>
<P>
   Siebert said Georgetown had decided that Glass deserved a second
chance. ``A system of justice should provide more than just
punishment,'' she said. ``He had paid a very high price for his
misdeeds, and we were not in a position to ban him forever from
society.'' Siebert noted that was the business of bar admissions
committees to decide who is fit to practice law.
</P>
<P>
   Georgetown's behavior may have raised some eyebrows, but is
hardly outside the norm for U.S. law schools. ``That's the result I
would recommend,'' said Stephen Gillers, vice dean at New York
University Law School.
</P>
<P>
   ``In admitting an applicant, Gillers said, ``what we are doing
is not making a decision about the person's character for
practicing law, but making a decision about the person's
intellectual capacity to practice law.''
</P>
<P>
   But other legal experts see the Colt and Glass cases as signals
of a breakdown in the way law schools deal with unethical and
immoral conduct, an abrogation of their responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make a mistake if we think that everything that isn't
illegal isn't shameful,'' said Jeffrey Rosen, a George Washington
University law professor who worked with Glass at The New Republic.
The fact that Glass' actions weren't illegal ``should only begin
the discussion of what social and professional consequences he
should suffer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   James Cox, a Duke University law professor, said law schools
should hold to themselves and their students to a standard.
``Institutions have to announce what they're about, and what law
schools ought to be about is preparing people for a life of
responsibility,'' Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   But Peter Rubin, a professor of constitutional law at
Georgetown, notes that moral standards were often used by elites to
punish vulnerable members of society. ``We have replaced a system
of community control over people's behavior with one associated
with more formal procedures for ethical or legal lapses,'' Rubin
said. ``This has been an enormous step forward for society.''
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Rhode, a law professor at Stanford University, partly
agrees. ``There has been a very unbecoming history of the moral
character standard being used to keep the riffraff out _ read Jews
and immigrants,'' she said. Still, Rhode, the author of a Yale Law
Journal article on the way law schools and bar committees deal with
unethical behavior, said law schools should take student misconduct
seriously wherever it occurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to create an impression among future applicants to
the bar that serious misconduct is a matter of concern,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-15-00 1059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
