<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7769 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-WWII-ART-THEFTS-REVIE     04-15 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WWII-ART-THEFTS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETURNING THE SPOILS OF WAR, WITH IMMUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the closing days of World War II in Germany, Cameron
Anderson, a young U.S. Army private, casually pocketed a valuable
14th-century manuscript from the castle of Grossgrundlach on the
outskirts of Nuremberg. It troubled him for years.
</P>
<P>
   When Anderson, now a retired president of Kinney Shoe Co.,
informed the German authorities of his desire to repatriate the
manuscript, they arranged to have him fly to Germany on an
all-expenses-paid, red-carpet trip to personally present the
8-by-12-inch document to Baron Helmut Haller von Hallerstein, whose
family had owned the castle of Grossgrundlach for generations.
</P>
<P>
   Not every light-fingered U.S. veteran has been so penitent. Maj.
Gen. Lemuel C. Shepherd Jr., who commanded the 6th Marine Division
on Okinawa in World War II, would not hear of returning the
15th-century Buddhist temple bell _ a Japanese national treasure _
presented to him in Okinawa by his troops, which he in turn donated
to the Virginia Military Institute, his alma mater.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until after Shepherd's death in 1990 that the Defense
Department dared to arrange the return of the bell.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to stimulate more cases like Anderson's, art
institutions and private and governmental agencies around the world
are publishing catalogs on the Internet describing artworks in
their holdings that might have been confiscated or looted by
members of the armed forces during World War II and, if so proved,
should be returned to their rightful owners.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of this research and publication _ the latest such
disclosure was announced April 12 by the Metropolitan Museum of Art
_ is to uncover ownership histories of the artworks tainted by Nazi
occupation authorities or by Red Army ``trophy squads.''
</P>
<P>
   What is belatedly coming to light, however, is that while U.S.
soldiers in World War II were expressly forbidden from stealing by
Article 93 of the Articles of War, a surprising number of U.S.
servicemen and women _ like Anderson _ stole artworks and other
valuables.
</P>
<P>
   All this raises questions _ and fears _ in the minds of veterans
and their heirs. Might a U.S. veteran who came home with a medieval
painting taken from a bombed-out French church run afoul of the law
when attempting to return it? Is it possible to profit legitimately
from such acquisitions?
</P>
<P>
   As to the second question, someone possessing stolen property
does not have clear title to it, and therefore cannot make a lawful
sale because he cannot pass along clear title.
</P>
<P>
   The only possibly lawful way to profit from war booty would be
to sell it to its owner (who presumably already has title). The
catch is that the prospective buyer may instead accuse the seller
of extortion, or file a civil suit to recover the property without
paying ransom. Furthermore, the U.S. Customs Service does not take
kindly to someone offering illegally imported or smuggled artworks
for sale.
</P>
<P>
   A thief cannot hide behind the statute of limitations, said
William H. Kenety, a Washington lawyer who has advised clients on
art matters, because, ``as a general rule, the statute does not
begin to run until the victim knows the location of the stolen
artwork, and that conceivably could take forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, what about the Napoleonic ``spoils of war'' theory, in
which soldiers who have made great sacrifices in order to achieve
victory are said to be entitled to trophies?
</P>
<P>
   ``The `spoils of war' practice is no longer sanctioned by
civilized nations,'' said Constance Lowenthal, director of the
Commission for Art Recovery at the World Jewish Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Quedlinburg case, which concerns the theft of medieval
church treasures from Germany by an American officer in World War
II, has set an important precedent,'' Lowenthal said. ``Even though
in that case the thief's heirs escaped trial on a technicality, it
has been a powerful deterrent because it showed that if you indulge
in careless or shady acquisitions, let alone outright theft, you
not only run the risk of a possible civil action, but also may face
criminal prosecution.''
</P>
<P>
   The best way to return looted art is to follow Anderson's
practice: give it back to the owner or a responsible official at
the locality from which it was taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one ever got in trouble for trying to arrange the voluntary
return of a looted artwork,'' said Thomas C. Kline, a Washington
lawyer who specializes in the recovery of lost cultural property.
``Unless, that is, he was asking an extortionate price.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-15-00 1109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
