<HEADER>
A7770 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-CEO-PAY-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      04-15 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CEO-PAY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXECUTIVE PAY DROPS OFF THE POLITICAL RADAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1992, Bill Clinton denounced the soaring salaries of
America's chief executives and vowed to do something about them if
he won the presidency. Sure enough, in his first year in office he
pushed through a law that slapped a new tax on some companies
paying their top executives more than $1 million. At the time, the
typical chief executive officer of a large company was making about
$3 million a year in salary, bonus and stock awards.
</P>
<P>
   In the eight years since, CEOs' average pay has more than
tripled to $11.9 million, according to Pearl Meyer &AMP; Partners, a
pay consulting firm in New York. The average corporate chieftain
now makes more in a single day than the typical American worker
makes in a year.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, executive pay has managed to disappear as a
political issue.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush and Al Gore do not mention it. Even as they
battle over the next seven months to position themselves as
reformers, executive salaries seem unlikely to enter the debate.
</P>
<P>
   Their vanquished rivals paid it scant attention, too. Bill
Bradley said the rich have a right to get richer but should feel a
moral obligation to spread the wealth. And John McCain even
disavowed a bill he had co-sponsored in 1997 that would have made
it more difficult for companies to pay their executives with stock
options.
</P>
<P>
   These days, however, the populist issue has paled. The media's
annual lists of the fattest corporate cats, which have been
appearing in recent weeks at the same time many stocks have turned
south, have caused little protest. The political paradox is
fascinating: A candidate makes hay out of a perceived problem and
wins an election; the problem worsens but the issue vanishes.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the explanation is simple. The U.S. economy has been the
envy of the world in recent years as it has enjoyed the longest
expansion in its history. Executives, be they savvy bosses like
General Electric's John F. Welch or Internet wunderkinds, are
getting much of the credit. In the last two years, European
companies have begun to pay their bosses more like American
executives in an effort to produce similar results.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the current volatile stock market, where many stocks are
worth less today than they were a year ago, executives have
persuaded corporate boards and shareholders to fork over bigger and
bigger awards _ some of which do not depend on share prices. Still,
outrage is minimal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who wants to criticize a nine-year boom?'' said Ira T. Kay, an
executive compensation consultant at Watson Wyatt Associates in New
York and a prominent defender of current CEO pay levels. ``You want
to hold your breath until it continues to a 10th or 11th year.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of sky-high salaries say they cannot argue. ``As long
as the economy stays good and most people are very hopeful about
their personal economic future, no one's terribly concerned about
excessive CEO pay,'' said Robert B. Reich, who served as Clinton's
secretary of labor.
</P>
<P>
   It helps, too, that the new mega-millionaires have donated
liberally to both Bush and Gore. If there is one issue on which
Silicon Valley executives will brook little dissent, it is the
generous accounting rules for stock options. The laws on options
``have become the new third rail of American politics,'' said
Patrick S. McGurn, a vice president at Institutional Shareholder
Services of Rockville, Md., which advises large investors.
</P>
<P>
   But the speed with which the political winds have shifted
suggests that more than economic indicators and political gifts are
at work. Early in 1996, after a series of layoffs at big companies
around the country, Newsweek ran a cover article titled ``Corporate
Killers,'' which pilloried businessmen who had fired workers but
still earned millions of dollars. A few days later, Pat Buchanan
won the New Hampshire Republican presidential primary while
blasting American business and credited his victory to ``peasants
with pitchforks'' storming the Republican establishment. The next
year, McCain made his proposal on stock options.
</P>
<P>
   On its face, the political situation seems similar today. Big
layoffs, like those announced at Coca-Cola and Xerox earlier this
year, continue to accompany the economic expansion. And the average
pay for a CEO has more than doubled since 1996, according to Pearl
Meyer. But there is nary an article on the new Corporate Killer nor
have pitchfork-wielding peasants appeared.
</P>
<P>
   The changing attitude of Americans toward money may be
responsible. Since the 1996 election, hundreds of recent college
graduates and mid-level workers have become millionaires, thanks
mostly to the Internet boom.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, an $11.9 million pay package looks less unusual. The
attitude has spread to popular culture. To paraphrase the
television hit, most Americans want to  &UR; be &LR;  millionaires, not
criticize them.
</P>
<P>
   Over the long term, however, such feelings could set the stage
for a new political firestorm over executive pay. When the economy
eventually slows _ and the plunge of technology stocks last week
suggests that the time may not be far off _ struggling workers are
more likely to reconsider their views on big pay packages. ``We're
in a rare moment of history in which there seems to be a gulf
between money and effort,'' said Reich, a professor at Brandeis
University.
</P>
<P>
   If that gulf seemed like an inviting political target in 1992
when the typical chief executive made 100 times what the typical
employee did, it could be irresistible when the multiple is closer
to 400. At that point, CEOs could face a choice between accepting a
large pay cut or waging an unpopular political fight. They might
then look back at the early months of 2000 as that unusual period
when they could enjoy both record paychecks and the presidential
campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-15-00 1112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000415.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 11:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3019 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-CEO-PAY-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      04-15 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CEO-PAY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXECUTIVE PAY DROPS OFF THE POLITICAL RADAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
