Silicon Valley executives will brook little dissent, it is the
generous accounting rules for stock options. The laws on options
``have become the new third rail of American politics,'' said
Patrick S. McGurn, a vice president at Institutional Shareholder
Services of Rockville, Md., which advises large investors.
</P>
<P>
   But the speed with which the political winds have shifted
suggests that more than economic indicators and political gifts are
at work. Early in 1996, after a series of layoffs at big companies
around the country, Newsweek ran a cover article titled ``Corporate
Killers,'' which pilloried businessmen who had fired workers but
still earned millions of dollars. A few days later, Pat Buchanan
won the New Hampshire Republican presidential primary while
blasting American business and credited his victory to ``peasants
with pitchforks'' storming the Republican establishment. The next
year, McCain made his proposal on stock options.
</P>
<P>
   On its face, the political situation seems similar today. Big
layoffs, like those announced at Coca-Cola and Xerox earlier this
year, continue to accompany the economic expansion. And the average
pay for a CEO has more than doubled since 1996, according to Pearl
Meyer. But there is nary an article on the new Corporate Killer nor
have pitchfork-wielding peasants appeared.
</P>
<P>
   The changing attitude of Americans toward money may be
responsible. Since the 1996 election, hundreds of recent college
graduates and mid-level workers have become millionaires, thanks
mostly to the Internet boom.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, an $11.9 million pay package looks less unusual. The
attitude has spread to popular culture. To paraphrase the
television hit, most Americans want to  &UR; be &LR;  millionaires, not
criticize them.
</P>
<P>
   Over the long term, however, such feelings could set the stage
for a new political firestorm over executive pay. When the economy
eventually slows _ and the plunge of technology stocks last week
suggests that the time may not be far off _ struggling workers are
more likely to reconsider their views on big pay packages. ``We're
in a rare moment of history in which there seems to be a gulf
between money and effort,'' said Reich, a professor at Brandeis
University.
</P>
<P>
   If that gulf seemed like an inviting political target in 1992
when the typical chief executive made 100 times what the typical
employee did, it could be irresistible when the multiple is closer
to 400. At that point, CEOs could face a choice between accepting a
large pay cut or waging an unpopular political fight. They might
then look back at the early months of 2000 as that unusual period
when they could enjoy both record paychecks and the presidential
campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-15-00 1113EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
