<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 11:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7778 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      04-15 1413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, April 16:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-SHAH (Undated) _ A secret history of the 1953 coup in Iran
that returned the shah to power has surfaced, revealing the inner
workings of a plot that set the stage for the Islamic revolution in
1979. A special report. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic and sidebars.
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-INSTITUTIONS (Washington) _ Commissions are examining
whether the World Bank lends too much to middle-income nations and
not enough to the world's poorest. The IMF is embroiled in battles
over whether it did more harm than good when it placed strict
budget-balancing and interest rate requirements on nations hit by
the Asian contagion. And the World Trade Organization, which is not
meeting in Washington this week, is a target nonetheless. ``I think
one of the common complaints is that many of these organizations
don't listen as well as they say they do,'' said Andrea Durbin of
Friends of the Earth, who frequently interacts with the
institutions at the center of the protests. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-PROTEST-VOICES (Washington) _ Voices of some of the
protesters in Washington. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   GAMBIA-BORDER (Farafenni, Gambia) _ African borders remain the
absurd legacy of European colonialists who carved up the continent
more than a century ago without consulting any Africans. But
colonial map drawing reached an absurd extreme here: Gambia, an
enclave inside Senegal, is about 300 miles long, though only about
15 miles wide. The maps, though, were never that precise. By
Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-RECONSTRUCT (Macuto, Venezuela) _ Armed with shovels
and pickaxes, Jose Estevez and half a dozen neighbors stood at the
door of what used to be his home here and contemplated the dried
mud and debris that filled the building to the ceiling. With a
shrug, he called out, ``Let's go, folks,'' and began to dig. Four
months ago, a 25-mile strip of Caribbean coast just north of
Caracas was inundated by floods and mud slides. But after an
initial burst of activity, government relief has been been slow in
arriving. People like Estevez have decided to begin helping
themselves. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-DIPLOMACY (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ Despite the indictment
of President Slobodan Milosevic on war crimes charges and the
efforts of Washington to isolate his regime, the Western diplomatic
quarantine of Yugoslavia has broken down, with every major European
country represented here by senior diplomats. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Perm, Russia) _ The Russian authorities have
yet to disclose the results of their inquiry into the ambush on
March 29, which led to the death of as many as 36 policemen from
the Perm region, reverberated through the news media and shook the
nation's confidence in its generals. But a handful of survivors who
have returned to this Ural mountains region have given their
accounts. And it is a tale of high-level incompetence, poor
training and terror on the battlefield. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KAZAKHSTAN-U.S. (Astana, Kazakhstan) _ At the start of a
five-day visti to Central Asia, Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright renewed U.S. criticism of Kazakhstan over its sale of some
40 MiG fighter jets to North Korea. And President Nursultan
Nazarbayev, reproached Albright for, in essence, not minding her
own business. By Steve Levine.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TAX-AUDITS (Undated) _ Last year, for the first time, the poor
were more likely than the rich to have their tax returns audited,
new Internal Revenue Service data compiled by Syracuse University
researchers show. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-REACT (New York) _ Mutual fund managers have long
exhorted investors to live by a very simple mantra when the stock
market falls: Buy on the dips. For a decade, investors have largely
followed that advice, driving U.S. stocks ever higher. Until
Friday. By Alex Berenson and Patrick McGeehan.
</P>
<P>
   SC-GOP-DEFECTORS (Columbia, S.C.) _ A few hours after two
representatives startled the Southern political world this month as
the first Republicans in the state to become Democrats since the
end of Reconstruction, they were stripped of their positions on two
prestigious committees and moved to the Military, Medical,
Municipal and Public Affairs Committee, which has so few
responsibilities that not a single Republican serves on it. By
David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-MOB (Youngstown, Ohio) _ Reality is a tired saga here. It
already includes a prosecutor who was gunned down after being
deemed unbribable; the racketeering and murder-conspiracy
conviction of Lenine ``Lenny'' Strollo, the local godfather; the
conviction of Rep. James A. Traficant Jr.'s late district manager
as an admitted bagman for the mob; plus assorted county
commissioners and patronage appointees gone bad. By Francis X.
Clines.
</P>
<P>
   L.A.-WRITERS-TAXES (Los Angeles) _ After years of heated
conflict, the union that represents screenwriters and the city of
Los Angeles have reached a truce over imposing local taxes on
writers, artists and other self-employed people who work at home.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Dateline TK) _ Developments in the Elian Gonzalez
case.
</P>
<P>
   WELLESLEY-GIFT (Undated) _ In the largest donation ever to a
women's college, a New York couple has given $25 million to
Wellesley College. By Kate Zernike.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-DILEMMA (Houston) _ Bush's dilemma is that he must hold on
to right-wing conservatives but keep enough of a public distance
from them to court the political middle. By Jim Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-REFORM (Washington) _ When Vice President Al Gore declared
late last month that he would devote himself to remaking the system
of political finance, he conceded that he was an ``imperfect
messenger'' for campaign finance reform. But supporters and critics
of Gore agree that he has been, since first elected to Congress in
1976, a steady if largely invisible supporter of measures to change
the political finance system. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-CUBAN-BOY (Los Angeles) _ On March 30, prompted by no one,
Al Gore thrust himself into one of the most emotionally and
politically charged cases in the country. After months of saying
that the fate of the 6-year-old Cuban boy should be decided in the
courts, Gore said that Elian Gonzalez should be granted permanent
residency status. There was a fierce backlash. By Katharine Q.
Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-CULTURE-WARS (Washington) _ For anyone wanting a
front-row seat at the next battle in the culture wars, the place to
be is the Supreme Court later this month when the justices hear the
case of Boy Scouts of America vs. James Dale, a former assistant
scoutmaster whom the Scouts expelled after learning from a
newspaper article that he was gay. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ The real thing. By Maureen Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   KRUGMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ The good times aren't over. By Paul
Krugman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AM-SPORTS-BUDGET _ A rundown of sports stories will move by 1
p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   AM-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ A description of the front page layout of the
first edition of The New York Times will move at 12 noon.
</P>
