<HEADLINE>
RULES? THE XFL SPITS IN YOUR FACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (duplication notice: also sent with `s' code)  
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In February, Vince McMahon turned his attention from the raunch
of his staged World Wrestling Federation events to create the XFL,
a high-octane, ``smash mouth'' football league. Last month, NBC
Sports became his 50 percent partner and will carry XFL games
Saturday nights starting next year.
</P>
<P>
   McMahon vows legitimate football _ even though the rules will be
tweaked to create more offense, WWF stars like Val Venis, Triple H
and the Rock won't be sacking and tossing quarterbacks into the
cheap seats. McMahon has not revealed how he will merge real
National Football League-style football, which produces plenty of
smashed mouths and serious injuries, with the debauchery that makes
the WWF's television shows and exhibitions must-see attractions for
young males.
</P>
<P>
   But for the real strategy behind Vince McMahon's secret plan to
turn himself into Vince Lombardi with bulging pectorals, let's turn
to his unauthorized manifesto, ``The XFL: An Accident Waiting to
Happen'':
</P>
<P>
   The Field: 100 yards long, enclosed by a steel cage.
</P>
<P>
   Equipment: Players will wear old-style leather helmets, shoulder
pads filled with goose down and spandex singlets to expose bruises
and broken bones. (For pantywaist football, see the NFL.)
</P>
<P>
   The Game: Each of the four ``acts'' will last 15 minutes _ or
until the quarterback is pinned for a count of three. There will be
no timeouts, not even for injury. Just because the quarterback
can't get up doesn't mean he can't be trampled.
</P>
<P>
   Teams: Eight teams of 40 feral players each, with names that
evoke terror, immorality and enormous royalties: the Miami Vile,
Los Angeles Pestilence, San Francisco Sin, Philadelphia Turpitude,
Chicago Carnage. And so on.
</P>
<P>
   Names: Players will be renamed for weapons, poisonous animals or
defeated presidential candidates, i.e., Rat Casket, Boa Dukakis.
</P>
<P>
   Scoring: Touchdowns will be called smackdowns. Each smackdown
will be worth 6 to 12 points, depending on the length of the
scoring play and the creativity of the humiliation heaped on the
defense. For field goals, defenses must count three Mississippis
before trying to rush the place kicker.
</P>
<P>
   Fomenting rivalries: A system of ``tag teams'' will be created,
so that if the Pestilence is being routed mercilessly by the
Carnage, for example, the Sinners can rush to the Pestilence's aid
from a cell inside the stadium. If the Sin subdues the Carnage and
the Pestilence wins, the Sin will receive three points.
</P>
<P>
   Pregame entrances: Armed cheerleaders in bikinis, trained by the
Godfather's working-girl wannabes, will precede players onto the
field.
</P>
<P>
   Cheerleading: Each team's cheerleading squad will be captained
by wrestlers ranging from the evil Kane to the septuagenarian
exhibitionist Mae Young. All cheers will conclude with squad
members whacking fans with metal chairs.
</P>
<P>
   Scripts: Scripted dialogue and action will not be tolerated, as
they are in the WWF. But general outlines will provide a compass.
Quarterbacks can review outlines on teleprompters built into their
helmets. All games are subject to rewrite by the XFL executive
council depending on team standings.
</P>
<P>
   End zone celebrations: Hugging, dancing, finger-pointing,
taunting and trash-talking will be mandatory and sharpened during
two weeks of pre-season education at the Stone Cold Steve Austin
Institute of Shame.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback protection: No such thing. No ``in the grasp'' calls
to limit sacking, no safe zones. QB's are carrion. Miniature heart
monitors implanted inside quarterbacks' chests will let XFL.com
surfers witness real-time terror.
</P>
<P>
   Incentives: Penalties are now ``incentives'' _ bonus yardage for
showing egregious aggression. Perfect mandible claws, full nelsons
and body slams will allow offending teams to move 10 yards
downfield. A 15-yard incentive will be awarded for an open field
tackle launched from atop the steel cage.
</P>
<P>
   Penalties: Actions that purposely slow a game will receive 10-
and 15-yard penalties, i.e., a quarterback using a confusing
cadence to draw the defense offside or a running back moving side
to side, rather than forward.
</P>
<P>
   Concealed weapons: Optional and recommended. Rolls of dimes,
shivs and brass knuckles are unlikely to be spotted by each game's
one-man officiating crew, despite the scantiness of the singlets.
Those who can't hide them effectively will suffer a temporary loss
of their NRA benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Fan involvement: Young fans who win regional age-group
competitions in Punt, Pass &AMP; Bludgeon contests will be eligible to
stand beside emergency medical personnel at the Tylenol Trauma
Bowl, the league's championship game.
</P>
