<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 11:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7780 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-CONFESSIONS-REVIEW-2T     04-15 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONFESSIONS-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRIME, PUNISHMENT AND THE PASSIONS OF MIRANDA 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the Supreme Court prepares to revisit the
Miranda decision, in a case to be argued Wednesday, there is
something oddly appropriate about the timing.
</P>
<P>
   Miranda, of course, was a case about confessions, and 34 years
after the court raised the bar for obtaining confessions from
criminal suspects, not only do people who receive the famous
warnings still bare their souls, but the country is awash in
confessions of all kinds.
</P>
<P>
   Confession _ by almost anyone to almost anything _ appears to be
a national obsession. There are memoirs on the best-seller list,
revelations of appalling intimacy on television. Political leaders,
or would-be leaders, are expected to admit to all manner of
personal transgressions: Barely two years ago, the country was
mesmerized by President Clinton's grudging path toward confessing
to what, by the end, everyone already knew.
</P>
<P>
   So it should be no surprise that after all these years, long
after other landmarks of the Warren Court's criminal procedure
revolution were comfortably absorbed by the criminal justice
system, Miranda vs. Arizona still stirs passions, as the foot-high
stack of briefs filed in the pending Supreme Court case attests.
True, 80 to 90 percent of suspects waive their Miranda rights and
talk anyway, and many police departments have long since made peace
with Miranda. But the decision still casts a long symbolic shadow.
</P>
<P>
   As Miranda's reappearance before the Supreme Court demonstrates,
the passions unleashed in 1966 never really went away; they just
kept flowing underground, kept alive by the political right largely
out of sight of the liberal establishment that had considered the
question closed long ago.
</P>
<P>
   The new case is the result of a tenacious search for a vehicle
that might push the Supreme Court to resolve the question of
whether a long-ignored 1968 law supplanted Miranda. The argument is
being made by an otherwise obscure University of Utah law
professor, Paul Cassell, who was only 6 years old when Miranda was
decided but who has since built a career as its mostly widely
published critic, along with the Washington Legal Foundation.
Cassell says Miranda has unduly handicapped the police in pursuing
criminals, although social scientists on the other side have raised
serious questions about the validity of the statistics he offers to
back up his argument.
</P>
<P>
   Congress intended the 1968 law, known as Section 3501, to
replace the Miranda warnings, in federal cases, with an inquiry by
the trial judge into whether a confession was voluntary in light of
``all the circumstances.'' This is essentially the case-by-case
test the Supreme Court found unworkable two years earlier when it
decided Miranda. Section 3501 and Miranda are mutually exclusive;
by the time the court decides Dickerson vs. U.S. early this summer,
only one of them will be left standing. (While a decision in favor
of Section 3501 would apply only to federal cases, it would free
states to adopt their own statutory substitutes.)
</P>
<P>
   That the battle over Miranda still rages is evidence of ``the
whole cultural unease, the ambivalence, about confession and what
we expect and want from it,'' said Peter Brooks, the Chester D.
Tripp Professor of Humanities at Yale University, who has written
an illuminating book on the role of confession in western thought.
``Troubling Confessions: Speaking Guilt in Law and Literature,''
which is to be published next month by the University of Chicago
Press, examines confession's deep roots in religious, literary,
legal and cultural tradition. Confession is ``one of the most
complex and obscure forms of human speech and behavior,'' Brooks
writes, in part because it serves a dual role, leading
simultaneously to punishment and absolution, discipline and
redemption. Confession is supposed to serve the interests of the
state even as it meets the needs of the soul.
</P>
<P>
   The book examines confession in the context of the church, the
analyst's couch and the novelist's pen, as well as in judicial
opinions, which Brooks reads as literary texts and places in the
company of Dante, Rousseau, Dostoevsky and James Joyce. He quotes
Joyce's depiction of Stephen Dedalus, in ``Portrait of the Artist
as a Young Man,'' returning home after confession, ``conscious of
an invisible grace pervading and making light his limbs.''
</P>
<P>
   That urge to feel the cleansing power of confession, Brooks
says, ``must make us suspicious of its use for other purposes:
purposes that seek punishment rather than absolution, or, even,
that claim that absolution and purification pass through
punishment, rather than penance.''
</P>
<P>
   The urge is so strong that false confessions have long troubled
the criminal justice system, as the court noted in the Miranda
decision. Aside from the constitutional and human rights arguments
against coerced confessions, there are substantial questions about
whether such confessions are reliable; a lawyer's presence offers
protection not only against compelled self-incrimination but also
against false confession.
</P>
<P>
   The majority and dissenting opinions in the Miranda case
themselves reflect the justices' encounter with confession in its
various aspects. Focusing on confession as the route to punishment,
Chief Justice Earl Warren's majority opinion emphasized the need to
protect people from the ``inherently compelling pressures'' of
custodial interrogation, which ``work to undermine the individual's
will to resist and to compel him to speak where he would not
otherwise do so freely.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-15-00 1139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000415.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 11:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3029 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-CONFESSIONS-REVIEW-2T     04-15 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONFESSIONS-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRIME, PUNISHMENT AND THE PASSIONS OF MIRANDA 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the Supreme Court prepares to revisit the
Miranda decision, in a case to be argued Wednesday, there is
something oddly appropriate about the timing.
</P>
<P>
   Miranda, of course, was a case about confessions, and 34 years
after the court raised the bar for obtaining confessions from
criminal suspects, not only do people who receive the famous
warnings still bare their souls, but the country is awash in
confessions of all kinds.
</P>
<P>
   Confession _ by almost anyone to almost anything _ appears to be
a national obsession. There are memoirs on the best-seller list,
revelations of appalling intimacy on television. Political leaders,
or would-be leaders, are expected to admit to all manner of
personal transgressions: Barely two years ago, the country was
mesmerized by President Clinton's grudging path toward confessing
to what, by the end, everyone already knew.
</P>
<P>
   So it should be no surprise that after all these years, long
after other landmarks of the Warren Court's criminal procedure
revolution were comfortably absorbed by the criminal justice
system, Miranda vs. Arizona still stirs passions, as the foot-high
stack of briefs filed in the pending Supreme Court case attests.
True, 80 to 90 percent of suspects waive their Miranda rights and
talk anyway, and many police departments have long since made peace
with Miranda. But the decision still casts a long symbolic shadow.
</P>
<P>
   As Miranda's reappearance before the Supreme Court demonstrates,
the passions unleashed in 1966 never really went away; they just
kept flowing underground, kept alive by the political right largely
out of sight of the liberal establishment that had considered the
question closed long ago.
</P>
<P>
   The new case is the result of a tenacious search for a vehicle
that might push the Supreme Court to resolve the question of
whether a long-ignored 1968 law supplanted Miranda. The argument is
being made by an otherwise obscure University of Utah law
professor, Paul Cassell, who was only 6 years old when Miranda was
decided but who has since built a career as its mostly widely
published critic, along with the Washington Legal Foundation.
Cassell says Miranda has unduly handicapped the police in pursuing
criminals, although social scientists on the other side have raised
serious questions about the validity of the statistics he offers to
back up his argument.
</P>
<P>
   Congress intended the 1968 law, known as Section 3501, to
replace the Miranda warnings, in federal cases, with an inquiry by
the trial judge into whether a confession was voluntary in light of
``all the circumstances.'' This is essentially the case-by-case
test the Supreme Court found unworkable two years earlier when it
decided Miranda. Section 3501 and Miranda are mutually exclusive;
by the time the court decides Dickerson vs. U.S. early this summer,
only one of them will be left standing. (While a decision in favor
of Section 3501 would apply only to federal cases, it would free
states to adopt their own statutory substitutes.)
</P>
<P>
   That the battle over Miranda still rages is evidence of ``the
whole cultural unease, the ambivalence, about confession and what
we expect and want from it,'' said Peter Brooks, the Chester D.
Tripp Professor of Humanities at Yale University, who has written
an illuminating book on the role of confession in western thought.
``Troubling Confessions: Speaking Guilt in Law and Literature,''
which is to be published next month by the University of Chicago
Press, examines confession's deep roots in religious, literary,
legal and cultural tradition. Confession is ``one of the most
complex and obscure forms of human speech and behavior,'' Brooks
writes, in part because it serves a dual role, leading
simultaneously to punishment and absolution, discipline and
redemption. Confession is supposed to serve the interests of the
state even as it meets the needs of the soul.
</P>
<P>
   The book examines confession in the context of the church, the
analyst's couch and the novelist's pen, as well as in judicial
opinions, which Brooks reads as literary texts and places in the
company of Dante, Rousseau, Dostoevsky and James Joyce. He quotes
Joyce's depiction of Stephen Dedalus, in ``Portrait of the Artist
as a Young Man,'' returning home after confession, ``conscious of
an invisible grace pervading and making light his limbs.''
</P>
<P>
   That urge to feel the cleansing power of confession, Brooks
says, ``must make us suspicious of its use for other purposes:
purposes that seek punishment rather than absolution, or, even,
that claim that absolution and purification pass through
punishment, rather than penance.''
</P>
<P>
   The urge is so strong that false confessions have long troubled
the criminal justice system, as the court noted in the Miranda
decision. Aside from the constitutional and human rights arguments
against coerced confessions, there are substantial questions about
whether such confessions are reliable; a lawyer's presence offers
protection not only against compelled self-incrimination but also
against false confession.
</P>
<P>
   The majority and dissenting opinions in the Miranda case
themselves reflect the justices' encounter with confession in its
various aspects. Focusing on confession as the route to punishment,
Chief Justice Earl Warren's majority opinion emphasized the need to
protect people from the ``inherently compelling pressures'' of
custodial interrogation, which ``work to undermine the individual's
will to resist and to compel him to speak where he would not
otherwise do so freely.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Justice Byron R. White, one of the four dissenters, had a
different focus. Granting, he said, that confessions should not be
coerced, neither should they be discouraged, because they can be a
positive good for the person confessing. ``Has it so unquestionably
been resolved that in each and every case it would be better for
him not to confess and to return to his environment with no attempt
whatsoever to help him?'' White asked. ``I think not. It may well
be that in many cases it will be no less than a callous disregard
for his own welfare as well as for the interests of his next
victim.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond this debate, the Miranda decision raises, at least
implicitly, a separate issue that remains all the more compelling
for never having been satisfactorily resolved: the question of free
will. The majority's premise was that, properly advised of his
rights, a suspect could make a free and rational decision about
whether to talk, and any confession would then be voluntarily given
_ or at least, the law could so presume.
</P>
<P>
   But this concept of a freely chosen and ``knowing waiver'' of
one's rights contains a paradox: If the court was correct that the
atmosphere of the interrogation room is inherently coercive, then
how can the choice to waive those rights in that very setting ever
really be free? ``How do you ever know what's voluntary?'' Brooks
asked in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, Brooks said, the court bought into a comfortable
fiction _ that of the rational person who, once freed of undue
pressure, can make a rational choice. ``The law has to insist on
the Enlightenment notion of people as actors exercising free will,
but actors in the criminal justice system rarely fit that,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Silence in the situation requires a radical effort of the
will: Everything in the culture presses toward speech,'' he writes,
referring to questions in the interrogation room. Rarely the
product of free and rational choice, confessions ``arise in
situations of constraint, whether physical or psychological,'' he
says, ``motivated by inextricable layers of shame, guilt, disgrace,
contempt, self-loathing, propitiation and expiation.''
</P>
<P>
   By offering the ritualized formula of the Miranda warnings, it
could be argued, the court has shielded society from the need to
confront that disconcerting truth.
</P>
<P>
   From that perspective, the four Miranda warnings _ ``You have
the right to remain silent. Anything you say can be used against
you in a court of law. You have the right to a lawyer and to have
the lawyer present during questioning. If you cannot afford a
lawyer, one will be appointed for you.'' _ look like fragile reeds
on a sea of turmoil and human vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
   Confronting the deeper meanings of Miranda in its full cultural
context is neither comfortable nor reassuring. That Miranda
continues to roil the waters after 34 years tells us something
about law, something about politics, but perhaps most of all, in
our confession-saturated society, something about ourselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-15-00 1140EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000415.0064 </DOCNO>
