</P>
<P>
   By offering the ritualized formula of the Miranda warnings, it
could be argued, the court has shielded society from the need to
confront that disconcerting truth.
</P>
<P>
   From that perspective, the four Miranda warnings _ ``You have
the right to remain silent. Anything you say can be used against
you in a court of law. You have the right to a lawyer and to have
the lawyer present during questioning. If you cannot afford a
lawyer, one will be appointed for you.'' _ look like fragile reeds
on a sea of turmoil and human vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
   Confronting the deeper meanings of Miranda in its full cultural
context is neither comfortable nor reassuring. That Miranda
continues to roil the waters after 34 years tells us something
about law, something about politics, but perhaps most of all, in
our confession-saturated society, something about ourselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-15-00 1140EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000415.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 11:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7787 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-EURO-WOMEN-POLS-REVIE     04-15 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EURO-WOMEN-POLS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPE'S MEN OF POWER HOLD OPEN A DOOR FOR WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ESSEN, Germany _ She blushed bright red and managed an
embarrassed smile. Her arms dangled awkwardly, until, overwhelmed
by the ovation from the congress of her Christian Democratic party,
Angela Merkel managed a wave so rigid it suggested an East German
leader from the Soviet days.
</P>
<P>
   In an age of pollsters, dubious campaign financing and image
manipulation, Germany has abruptly produced an anti-heroine as the
new leader of its main conservative political force.
</P>
<P>
   Merkel, 45, East German by birth and a physicist by training, is
being put forward by her scandal-mired party as an antidote to
politics as usual. But she is also representative of a broader
trend: the political breakthrough by women in Germany and France,
the dominant countries of continental Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Former Chancellor Helmut Kohl, who led the Christian Democrats
for 25 years and his country for 16, believed firmly in the the
three K's: Kinder (children), Kueche (kitchen), and Kirche (church)
as defining a woman's proper role. A fourth K, for Kanzlerin, or
female chancellor, was simply out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the conservative culture of our party, a female leader was
unthinkable until very recently,'' said Kurt Biedenkopf, the
Christian Democrat premier of Saxony.
</P>
<P>
   Rita Sussmuth labored long and hard under the Kohl system,
rising to become the Christian Democratic speaker of the Bundestag.
But even she felt she could go only so far. ``In a male-dominated
political culture, I was allowed into the forecourt of power,'' she
said. ``But the forecourt was the limit set by Kohl, and he made
that abundantly clear. The difference today is that Merkel can
reach the very center of power.''
</P>
<P>
   How long Merkel's political honeymoon will last, and whether she
can revive her battered party, remain to be seen. Her message,
beyond the straightforward image that has allowed her to emerge as
the party's potential savior from financial misdealings, remains
vague. But the zeitgeist is on her side.
</P>
<P>
   Awareness has grown that the female vote cannot be taken for
granted, and that, as in the United States, it wins elections. For
example, Roman Catholic women over 45 long constituted an essential
pillar of the German Christian Democrats. But religion is now less
important, working women have different priorities, and party
allegiance has become more fickle. The 7 percent drop in the female
vote for the Christian Democrats in 1998, and the 5 percent surge
in the female vote for the Social Democrats, gave a decisive nudge
to Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder in his quest for power.
</P>
<P>
   Women appeared to be drawn to women candidates, and the Social
Democrats, unlike the Christian Democrats, had imposed a quota,
saying a minimum of 40 percent of their candidates must be female.
</P>
<P>
   In France, too, the female vote has migrated from its
concentration on the Gaullist right toward the center and left.
Political swings now tend to involve both sexes equally, although
women vote rather more for ecologically minded parties and rather
less for the extreme-right National Front than men.
</P>
<P>
   The French Gaullist party, like the Christian Democrats long a
bastion of European conservatism, recently opted for a woman,
Michelle Alliot-Marie, as its new leader. Francoise de Panafieu, a
straight-talking former custodian of the Paris parks, has emerged
as a potential mayor of the French capital. And Martine Aubry, the
Socialist labor minister, is widely seen as a serious future
contender to become France's first Madame la Presidente de la
Republique.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing more chic today than being a woman in
politics,'' said Elisabeth Badinter, an author and philosopher.
</P>
<P>
   Behind this shift lies several factors. The push for equality of
opportunity that started with the feminist movements of the 1970s
has produced a generation eager to eliminate the last barriers to
women in politics and the upper echelons of business. In German top
management, women account for only 6 percent of posts; the same low
ratio applies to the presence of women in the French Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Prodded by his feminist wife, Sylviane Agacinskci, French Prime
Minister Lionel Jospin has made women's issues a central plank of
his policies. Even the constitution was recently revised to favor
of women as candidates: parties are now obliged by law to present
lists that are at least 50 percent female for some elections.
</P>
<P>
   German women, propelled by a particularly strong feminist
movement, made faster headway in politics: almost one-third of the
parliament is female today, compared with 11 percent of the French
lower house. But it took unification, a decade ago, to challenge
deeply held patriarchal attitudes. East Germany was a place where
women worked _ 80 percent of them had a job. Even today, the
percentage of women who work in the eastern part of the country _
73 percent _ is far higher than the 56 percent in the west. ``In
one area at least, communism taught us something positive,'' said
Christel Hanewinckel, a Social Democratic parliamentarian.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Merkel to shake up the last loden-coated male bastions of
German conservatism. She has come up with a slogan ``Markt und
Menschlichkeit'' _ ``The Market and Humanity'' _ that captures the
difficulty of her task. There is no shortage of men, particularly
in Bavaria, who would be happy to see her fail in her attempt to
juggle national identity and globalization, the Internet revolution
and social welfare, immigration and the Volk. But the initial
evidence is that Merkel will gain support from East Germans and
from women, which may shield her from sniping.
</P>
<P>
   If she can pull it off, and if she can galvanize her party,
Germany may be treated to an extraordinary sight: that of a woman
entering the still-unfinished Berlin Chancellery, a vast Kohlian
monument to male fantasies of power, and taking office as the first
Kanzlerin in a house built for a Kanzler.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-15-00 1143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000415.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 11:43 </DATE_TIME>
