<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBAL-POVERTY-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING ROOM FOR THE POOR IN A GLOBAL ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ On all sides of the debate about globalization,
in rich and poor nations alike, there lurks a disturbing, shared
sense that even as industry expands around the Third World,
something is going tragically wrong in the poorest economies and
most disadvantaged societies.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute is about how and why this is happening, and what can
be done about it _ and these questions threaten to divide world
opinion as nothing has since the collapse of communism.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, leaders of the Third World meeting in Havana and
protesters marching in Washington both denounced the global economy
and its symbols: the World Bank, the International Monetary Fund
and the World Trade Organization. But slogans and oratory do little
to illuminate the profound complexity of human development in the
new economic order.
</P>
<P>
   From a village-eye view where life is harshest, some development
experts say, nothing could be more irrelevant than global theories
or rants against multinational companies. To the poorest people who
live without teachers, doctors, roads, electricity and sometimes
even food and water, the culprit is a lot closer to home: the
local, state or national government. When the people of Calcutta
march to denounce power cuts or uncollected garbage, they fault the
government of West Bengal, not the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   Among development experts working at the grass roots, in fact,
there is no dearth of ideas about how to bring the benefits of
globalization to the poor. Computer technology, for example, can be
brought to poor regions at a relatively low cost with the use of
satellite telephones, making available all kinds of information in
health, education, agriculture and consumer advice.
</P>
<P>
   International companies, for another example, could be persuaded
to conduct hands-on projects in their factories that could help
workers improve their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts say national debt relief should be tied to
requirements that the poor reap the benefit. Some say that
well-meaning outsiders might rethink such activities as labor-union
boycotts of low-wage imports because this only denies poor people
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In most theories, one theme increasingly stands out: If the
world wants development of poverty-stricken nations, it must
improve the way the world governs itself, at all levels. Big
international institutions need to assure that their policies work
for all levels of society. National governments need to make
programs like health and education reach more than an urban elite.
Aid already goes into building courts, political organizations,
economic regulatory bodies and police forces, but the experts say
more is needed.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. secretary-general, Kofi Annan, speaking at the
University of Havana last week, suggested that both the
anti-internationalists and the critics of their own rulers deserve
to be listened to. ``The issue,'' he said, ``is primarily one of
governance _ how the international community of sovereign states
and multilateral organizations copes with global challenges, and
how individual nations manage their own affairs so as to play their
part, pull their weight and serve their peoples.''
</P>
<P>
   Annan is not alone in his focus on governance at every level.
Virtually no intergovernmental organization or independent
mainstream development group argues any longer that international
organizations or national governments are so worthy of aid that it
can be given without guarantees that it not be diverted, stolen, or
used to bolster a nondemocratic regime.
</P>
<P>
   Debt relief _ a demand made by Third World leaders in Havana _
is an example. Oxfam, which no one could accuse of insensitivity to
the poorest nations, now argues that governments seeking debt
forgiveness should be expected to demonstrate that the money saved
will go into programs to reduce poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Proposals like these align international organizations
advocating for the poor more with the citizens of poor countries
than with their governments, and that gives globalization a new
twist: The familiar critique has been that globalization empowers
multinational corporations and organizations like the World Bank
and World Trade Organization to act as if they had more power than
states. Now, nongovernmental organizations are responding in kind _
building links with intergovernmental organizations or
multinational corporations that have direct aid programs, thus
circumventing national governments.
</P>
<P>
   The very institutions that have been most criticized by
protesters in Seattle or Washington have begun moving to act
differently too. Bengt Save-Soderbergh, secretary-general of the
International Institute for Democracy and Electoral Assistance in
Stockholm, which is supported by 19 democratic governments, says he
has seen the World Bank move dramatically into social programs in
recent years _ ironically, just as protesters operating on outdated
images single it out for attack.
</P>
<P>
   At the University of Michigan Business School, Dr. Linda Y.C.
Lim, a professor of international business, says the International
Monetary Fund has also moved well beyond its charter as a purely
fiscal rescue squad into the once-forbidden territory of human
rights. Last year in Indonesia, it withheld desperately needed
financial support because of army-inspired violence in East Timor.
``A lot of people have become unhappy with the IMF attaching
conditions like democracy and human rights, which are not in its
charter,'' she said in an interview. But she said that in Asia
these days, ``a lot of reformers like having the IMF there'' _
because it gives local leaders political cover to initiate reforms
that are needed if the economy is to be made rational.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-15-00 1151EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
