<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Taking a Little Time Out for Making Amends &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush met with a dozen gay Republicans and
pronounced himself psychically refreshed. ``I'm a better person for
the meeting,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Reed, a senior consultant to the Bush campaign,
acknowledged that his consulting firm had been lobbying Bush on
behalf of the Microsoft Corp. and pronounced it a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   And Sen. John McCain, in agreeing to meet with Bush in
Pittsburgh next month _ their first face-to-face encounter since
Bush knocked him from the presidential race _ said he was a step
closer to endorsing his fellow Republican. ``If not then, certainly
over time,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a week, it seemed, for making amends. Throughout the
primary season, when his ability to appeal to Christian
conservatives was especially crucial to his candidacy, Bush
repeatedly rebuffed the requests by the gay Log Cabin Republicans
for a sit-down. Now, moving ever more closely to the middle, the
governor was displaying a more embracing side, even if the meeting
was greeted warily by some gay leaders as well as bysome
Republicans on the far right.
</P>
<P>
   On health care, too, the Bush campaign seemed intent on
extending its reach, as the governor proposed a $2,000 tax credit
to help low- and moderate-income working families buy health
insurance. It was part of a package Bush called ``a new prosperity
initiative'' designed to make poverty a ``stage, not a fate.''
</P>
<P>
   His presumed Democratic opponent, Vice President Al Gore,
meanwhile, was tiptoeing gingerly around a different sort of
national concern. In the midst of last week's volatile tug-of-war
over Elian Gonzalez, Gore canceled a news conference to avoid
weighing in again on the issue at a potentially explosive moment,
his campaign said. (Two weeks ago he said he supported legislation
to grant the boy and his father permanent residency status.)
</P>
<P>
   On another day, Gore took up residency in the home of a
Charlotte, N.C., language arts teacher. He spent the night in the
home of Laurel Wingfield, talking about education over midnight
snacks. This was Gore's own outreach program to the Republican
Party. That's the side Wingfield said she voted with most of the
time.
</P>
<P>
   _ By PETER MARKS
</P>
<P>
   The Case of the Dozing Diplomats &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now the world knows how Alain Dejammet, France's just-departed
ambassador to the United Nations, was amusing himself during those
long Security Council consultations. He was thinking about naps.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Paris after four years in New York, Dejammet went public
with his guide to sleeping at the United Nations _ ``Dormir aux
Nations Unies.'' The little booklet, no more than a computer
printout with a black cat on the cover page, has kept photocopiers
busy ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Dejammet, who says he had the help of a couple of other French
diplomats in compiling his survey, ranked 12 mostly cozy,
preferably dark, corners where the chairs were perfect for catching
a snooze. The only perfect score of 20 went to a place off limits
to everyone except the French _ their private office near the
Security Council. A possibly better-quipped and certainly more
accessible siesta center that rated high is the periodicals
library, with enveloping sofas and, the guide says, the calm of
``an abandoned monastery.''
</P>
<P>
   Definitely out: the off-campus Meditation Room across First
Avenue, where blue-tinted windows create a gloom worthy of ``a
Draculesque crypt'' and there is the annoying squeak of tourists'
sneakers and many Scandinavian visitors.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BARBARA CROSSETTE
</P>
<P>
   Shorn of Its Horns, The Nasdaq Stumbles
</P>
<P>
   The bull market in Nasdaq stocks is no more.
</P>
<P>
   As shares in the fledgling technology companies that dominate
the Nasdaq composite and investors' hearts plummeted, the index
fell deep into bear market territory. Although the more established
companies in the Dow Jones industrial average held up a bit better,
inflation fears were re-ignited by the government's announcement
Friday that consumer prices rose at the fastest pace in five years.
This drove the Dow down 5.6 percent alone. All the major stock
indexes are now showing significant declines for the year.
</P>
<P>
   _ By GRETCHEN MORGENSON
</P>
<P>
   Runoff in Peru  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   President Alberto K. Fujimori, the longest-serving Latin
American leader after Fidel Castro, fell just short of winning an
outright first-round victory for a third five-year term in an
election tainted by accusations of fraud from international
monitors. When a runoff for June was announced, crowds of tens of
thousands of protesters dispersed and international observers
expressed relief.
</P>
<P>
   _ By CLIFFORD KRAUSS
</P>
<P>
   With a Friend Like This  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain tried to back away from the compliment almost
immediately after he offered it. But there was no mistaking his
words: First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, if elected to the Senate,
``would be a star of the quality that has not been seen since Bobby
Kennedy was elected senator from the state of New York.''
</P>
<P>
   The former Republican presidential candidate is known for his
candor. But his remarks were a bit surprising, given that McCain
has campaigned for Clinton's Republican opponent, New York City
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ERIC LIPTON
</P>
<P>
   Waiting With Elian
</P>
<P>
   The government asked a federal appeals court to order Elian
Gonzalez's Miami relatives to return the boy to his father, who
agreed to stay in this country until it rules. The relatives,
turning to another court for help, invoked the U.N. human-rights
charter in asking that the child be allowed to stay.
</P>
<P>
   After daring the government to take him by force Thursday, by
the end of the week Elian's Miami relatives vowed to keep waiting,
holding the child, until federal agents come to them _ something
that won't happen until a last-minute injunction is resolved in the
11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID JOHNSTON
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-15-00 1155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000415.0074 </DOCNO>
