   As shares in the fledgling technology companies that dominate
the Nasdaq composite and investors' hearts plummeted, the index
fell deep into bear market territory. Although the more established
companies in the Dow Jones industrial average held up a bit better,
inflation fears were re-ignited by the government's announcement
Friday that consumer prices rose at the fastest pace in five years.
This drove the Dow down 5.6 percent alone. All the major stock
indexes are now showing significant declines for the year.
</P>
<P>
   _ By GRETCHEN MORGENSON
</P>
<P>
   Runoff in Peru  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   President Alberto K. Fujimori, the longest-serving Latin
American leader after Fidel Castro, fell just short of winning an
outright first-round victory for a third five-year term in an
election tainted by accusations of fraud from international
monitors. When a runoff for June was announced, crowds of tens of
thousands of protesters dispersed and international observers
expressed relief.
</P>
<P>
   _ By CLIFFORD KRAUSS
</P>
<P>
   With a Friend Like This  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain tried to back away from the compliment almost
immediately after he offered it. But there was no mistaking his
words: First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, if elected to the Senate,
``would be a star of the quality that has not been seen since Bobby
Kennedy was elected senator from the state of New York.''
</P>
<P>
   The former Republican presidential candidate is known for his
candor. But his remarks were a bit surprising, given that McCain
has campaigned for Clinton's Republican opponent, New York City
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ERIC LIPTON
</P>
<P>
   Waiting With Elian
</P>
<P>
   The government asked a federal appeals court to order Elian
Gonzalez's Miami relatives to return the boy to his father, who
agreed to stay in this country until it rules. The relatives,
turning to another court for help, invoked the U.N. human-rights
charter in asking that the child be allowed to stay.
</P>
<P>
   After daring the government to take him by force Thursday, by
the end of the week Elian's Miami relatives vowed to keep waiting,
holding the child, until federal agents come to them _ something
that won't happen until a last-minute injunction is resolved in the
11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID JOHNSTON
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Raising the Bar on Seizures  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Congress completed legislation that will make it harder for
prosecutors to confiscate homes and other property before they
bring charges in narcotics and other cases.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, the product of an unusual coalition of
conservative and liberal lawmakers and organizations, is the first
time in 30 years since the government declared a war on drugs and
terrorism that Congress has curtailed the broad powers of law
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   _ By STEPHEN LABATON
</P>
<P>
   A Ceiling for Drugs Prices  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Maine legislature is the first in the country to just say no
to drug prices. It overwhelmingly passed a bill requiring that
medications sold in the state cost no more than those in Canada.
The bill is expected to face legal challenges, and the
pharmaceutical industry argues that it could hinder Maine patients'
access to drugs and chill research efforts.
</P>
<P>
   _ By CAREY GOLDBERG
</P>
<P>
   Losing a Libel Case  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   David Irving, a historian who has written more than 30 books on
World War II, lost a libel case in Britain, his reputation in
shreds after the judge ruled that he was a Holocaust denier and
anti-Semite who manipulates history to serve his own pro-Nazi
ideology. Irving had sued Penguin Books and Deborah Lipstadt, an
American historian, over passages in a 1993 book that described him
as a dangerous spokesman for a growing movement devoted to the
argument that there was no large-scale Nazi program to exterminate
Europe's Jews. He is now obligated to pay Lipstadt's and Penguin's
legal fees, estimated at about $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SARAH LYALL
</P>
<P>
   Occupational Radiation  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Big, unregulated and dirty, the nationwide complex of factories
that built nuclear weapons for more than five decades employed
about 600,000 people, and, the government now admits, made some of
them sick. The Clinton administration announced a plan to offer
compensation for medical expenses and lost wages, and anticipates
that about 3,000 cases will be filed, half claiming exposure to
radiation and half claiming other hazards. In many cases,
reimbursement, if it comes, would be posthumous.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MATTHEW L. WALD
</P>
<P>
   A Downside to Drugs  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A new impotence drug got a lift when a panel of advisers
recommended that the Food and Drug Administration approve it
despite some troubling side-effects. The drug, a pill called
Uprima, helps some men who are not helped by Viagra, the only
impotence drug now on the market. Although one in 30 men who used
Uprima in a study fainted or had a serious drop in blood pressure,
the FDA advisory panel voted 9-3 to approve it, along with strong
warnings to patients and doctors.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JANE FRITSCH
</P>
<P>
   Vitamins' Plat Du Jour  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Megadoses of vitamins C and E, though popular, do not prevent
disease and may be harmful, according to scientists convened by the
government. They concluded that most Americans do not need
supplements because fruits and vegetables provide enough nutrition.
Because of toxicity, upper limits were recommended: people should
take no more than 2,000 milligrams of vitamin C a day, 400
micrograms of selenium and 1,500 International Units of vitamin E
as d-alpha-tocopherol.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DENISE GRADY
</P>
<P>
   Putin Wins START-2
</P>
<P>
   President Vladimir Putin of Russia won ratification of the
START-2 treaty, which calls for halving U.S. and Russian nuclear
arsenals. The parliament had blocked the treaty for seven years.
The passage, Putin's first legislative initiative since his
election, was viewed as a sign that he seeks not only a
constructive relationship with the West but also intends to fight
hard to block U.S. efforts to revise or abandon earlier
arms-control treaties. The treaty must still be approved by the
upper house, and the U.S. Senate has yet to approve several
features.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MICHAEL R. GORDON
</P>
<P>
   Low May It Wave  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The seemingly endless effort to remove the Confederate flag from
South Carolina statehouse may have begun in earnest when the state
Senate voted to move the flag to a Confederate monument in front of
the Capitol. Although many black legislators, along with the NAACP,
complained, a nearly unanimous group of black senators said the
compromise would pass the House when lawmakers realized that it was
the only way to get the flag off the dome and out of the nation's
glare.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID FIRESTONE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-15-00 1156EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
