<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-RECONSTRUCT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTHS LATER, MUD VICTIMS IN VENEZUELA STILL LACK AID
</HEADLINE>
  By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MACUTO, Venezuela _ Armed with shovels and pickaxes, Jose
Estevez and half a dozen neighbors and volunteers stood at the door
of what used to be his home here and contemplated the dried mud and
debris that filled the building to the ceiling. With a shrug, he
called out, ``Let's go, folks,'' and began to dig.
</P>
<P>
   Four months ago, in the worst natural disaster in modern
Venezuelan history, a 25-mile strip of Caribbean coast just north
of Caracas was inundated by floods and mudslides. But after an
initial burst of activity, government relief has been been slow in
arriving, for reasons ranging from political squabbling to lack of
organization. People like Estevez, tired of the waiting, have
decided to begin helping themselves.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, official reconstruction efforts appear to have
been slowed by a dispute between the state and federal governments.
The governor of Vargas State, Alfredo Laya, belongs to a left-wing
party that originally was part of President Hugo Chavez's coalition
but has now broken with the president and is running its own
candidates in national elections scheduled for May 28.
</P>
<P>
   The Chavez coalition, Patriotic Pole, is running a rival slate,
meaning the president has little interest in doing anything that
would enhance Laya's popularity, though the federal government
denies that the rivalry has anything to do with why money for
relief and reconstruction efforts has slowed to a trickle.
</P>
<P>
   The national government says it wants to move many of the
150,000 people who were displaced by the floods and mudslides to
the interior and rebuild the disaster zone's tourist facilities.
Money for such a large relocation program is scarce, however, and
opposition is vehement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This land and this house are mine, and I'm not going to accept
some 20-year government bond for what belongs to me just so that
they can build some big development for tourists,'' said Estevez,
who is 60. ``How can I go to the interior with no support when my
business is here and I need to eat now?''
</P>
<P>
   For several days in April, local people protesting the
relocation plan have blocked the main coastal highway west of here.
Some carried placards proclaiming, ``No real estate deals, no
displacements'' and ``We are going to die of hunger.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents also criticize Chavez for rejecting help from the
American military. Though his government accepted aid from many
other nations, a contingent of American military engineers had to
turn back when Chavez said he would find their presence
objectionable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big mistake to say no to them and their equipment,''
said one resident, Gladys Cedeno Zamora, ``but our president is a
pigheaded man, and now we are the ones paying the price for that.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, human rights groups are investigating accusations
of abuses by government security forces in the chaotic days after
the mudslides. At the time, residents complained of summary
executions of suspected looters, as well as arbitrary arrests and
searches, mistreatment of people taken into custody, and forced
disappearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clandestine activities were undertaken, and they were
generalized, not isolated,'' said Liliana Ortega Mendoza, director
of the Committee of Families of Victims, which has filed complaints
with international courts. ``The government's investigations into
what happened has not been what I would call free, open and
transparent, and no officials have been disciplined or called to
account.''
</P>
<P>
   An accurate death toll from the disaster has still to be
determined. The Chavez government first minimized the number of
casualties and then suggested that 30,000 to 50,000 people might
have died, figures that are now considered exaggerated. According
to recent Venezuelan press reports, fewer than 1,000 bodies have
actually been recovered, and about 5,000 people are still missing,
with the vast majority presumed dead.
</P>
<P>
   The toll, said Antonio Jaime, the International Red Cross
delegate here, ``could be 10,000, or it could be two or three
thousand, but honestly, the chaos and confusion were such that it
is going to be difficult for anyone ever to be able to give you a
certifiable figure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
