<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 12:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7830 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-N     04-15 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-LEVEL FUMBLING LED TO CHECHEN ROUT OF RUSSIAN UNIT, SURVIVORS
SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PERM, Russia _ Chechen rebels were raking a column of Russian
militiamen with machine-gun fire and mortars when the militia made
a desperate effort to save what was left of its men.
</P>
<P>
   Barking into a radio, the Russians, special police from the Ural
mountains region, promised to be more lenient toward the Chechens
in Vedeno, a mountain town in southern Chechnya. In return, they
wanted the rebels to let them take their wounded and retreat. The
militants responded by pressing the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `Allah will decide all,''' recalled Vladimir
Kurakin, one of the few survivors.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian authorities have yet to disclose the results of
their inquiry into the ambush on March 29, which led to the death
of as many as 36 policemen from the Perm region, reverberated
through the news media and shook the nation's confidence in its
generals.
</P>
<P>
   But a handful of survivors who have returned to this region have
given their accounts. And it is a tale of high-level incompetence,
poor training and terror on the battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, the whole thing could have been avoided,'' said Sergei
Ostapchuk, one of those who was caught in the firefight, his head
swathed in bandages.
</P>
<P>
   It was also a tale of bureaucratic fumbling.
</P>
<P>
   Although Russian politicians have portrayed the Perm militia as
heroes, there was no military plane to take Ostapchuk home. He
returned to Perm in economy class on a regular commercial airliner
after making a connecting flight in Moscow. So did Aleksandr
Prokopov, a 29-year-old noncommissioned militia officer who lay on
a stretcher balanced across the airline seats and whose leg was
amputated in Perm soon after his return.
</P>
<P>
   Money worries were also on the soldiers' minds. Before shipping
out to Chechnya, the militia members were given a three-month
salary advance of about 20,000 rubles, or $700. But because their
tour was cut short by the ambush, some of the survivors feared that
they might have to pay most of that money back.
</P>
<P>
   In long, detailed interviews, they told of the ordeal that began
in Vedeno, the hometown of Shamil Basayev, the most notorious of
the Chechen warlords. After the Russian military seized Vedeno with
great fanfare in February, Basayev's palatial red brick house
became the headquarters for the Russian military commandant there.
</P>
<P>
   Soon afterward, however, the generals declared the military
phase of the operation over and withdrew virtually all of the
Russian troops from the area. The special police unit from Perm was
sent to keep the peace in Vedeno, where about 7,000 Chechen
civilians remain. The Russian Army's high command seemed so relaxed
that the policemen were worried that they would not qualify for
combat pay, despite a number of disturbing incidents in Vedeno.
</P>
<P>
   March 28 was a quiet day. The militia drove around Vedeno with
Yuri P. Trutnev, Perm's mayor, who was visiting the town along with
the chief of the Perm region's militia to show their support for
their hometown boys and deliver toys to needy children. These were
good photo opportunities for the news media back home, about 1,400
miles northeast.
</P>
<P>
   That evening the policemen received what turned out to be the
fateful order, instructing them to send a few dozen men to a nearby
settlement. Gennadi V. Igumnov, the governor of the Perm region,
said in an interview this month that the purpose was to pick up
nine prisoners in nearby Zhani-Vedeno and take them and their
confiscated weapons to a more secure location.
</P>
<P>
   There is an old Russian saying that the biggest problems in the
country are roads and fools, and in Vedeno the two came together.
The Russian authorities have still not said who ordered the convoy
to leave Vedeno. The militia insists it came from a high-ranking
commander, and the local Perm newspaper Permskiye Novosti said it
had come from Maj. Gen. Sergei Makarov, the commander of the
eastern group of Russian forces in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The militia's mission was based on a gross misreading of the
rebels' tactics. After being chased into the mountains, the
militants split into small groups and began to carry out guerrilla
attacks. There was no longer a clear front line in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   That put a premium on proper reconnaissance and close
coordination with the more heavily armed army forces. Neither
existed. Anatoly Kulikov, a former interior minister and commander
of the Russian troops in Chechnya during the previous war there,
noted that the militia was not trained to call in airstrikes or
artillery barrages. Nor are its radios compatible with those used
by the Russian military.
</P>
<P>
   Those deficiencies could have been remedied if a contingent of
Russian soldiers had escorted the militia column. Vladimir
Rushailo, the interior minister, had ordered that militia convoys
be properly protected after an earlier ambush, and it is not clear
why that order was not carried out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main task of any commander is not just to prepare an
order, but to ensure that it is carried out,'' Kulikov said
caustically.
</P>
<P>
   At 7:30 a.m., a 49-man column left Vedeno along with several
trucks and a lone armored personnel carrier. Most of the policemen
were from Berezniki, 100 miles north of Perm.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we approached the last of our checkpoints, the Interior
Ministry troops who manned it said the road we were to go on was
under Chechen control,'' recalled Kurakin, a 35-year-old platoon
commander. ``But we had our orders.''
</P>
<P>
   The column had gotten all of 4 miles when one of its trucks
broke down. So the commander, Valentin D. Simonov, walked up to a
nearby house. Suddenly, there was a burst of gunfire, and Simonov
was mowed down. The policemen jumped out of their vehicles and
dispersed, and the armored personnel carrier made a quick U-turn so
that it could join the fight, the survivors recalled.
</P>
<P>
   There were no leaves on the trees, but the rebels were on the
high ground and were well hidden.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were very well prepared,'' said Prokopov. ``They knew all
the distances to the targets and had picked the lines of fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Kurakin added: ``They had small arms, large-caliber rifles,
machine guns, grenade launchers. They had everything. Just name
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon, the trucks and the armored personnel carrier were hit. As
the fighting continued, the militia had several frantic
conversations with the militants on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-15-00 1247EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000415.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 12:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7831 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-2     04-15 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 PERM, Russia: the radio. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At first, they tried to negotiate their way out, offering to
ease their patrols in Vedeno in return for safe passage out. Then
they threatened to level the town if they were not permitted to
retreat. But nothing worked. As the firefight continued, a rescue
party was sent from Vedeno. These men, too, were mostly militia,
although there were also several ``kontraktniki,'' essentially
mercenaries who sign six-month or one-year contracts to fight in
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   As the rescue column rumbled through the forest, its members
could hear the shooting ahead. Suddenly, some of them were felled,
said Ostapchuk, who was in the rescue party. Anticipating the
rescue attempt, the rebels had set up a second ambush closer to
Vedeno, which the first column had passed without even noticing,
and now were shooting with sniper rifles, which were equipped with
silencers.
</P>
<P>
   ``First it was snipers, then machine guns,'' said Ostapchuk.
``It was hard to figure out where the rebels were because the shots
were echoing through the mountains.''
</P>
<P>
   The rescue column tried to fight its way forward, but as it
approached a narrow pass in the road, the rebels blasted the
armored personnel carrier at the head of the convoy, blocking the
road.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned later that we were just 800 meters from the first
ambush,'' Ostapchuk said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the rescuers were trying desperately to save their own
lives. They piled some of the wounded into one of the surviving
armored personnel carriers and beat a retreat. Nobody in the rescue
party was killed, but 17 were wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Russian spokesmen later said fog prevented the military from
defending the original column, but the survivors say the weather
was clear much of the time. And they add that the militia could
have used flares to identify its position and those of the rebels
when patches of fog emerged _ if only helicopters had been there
when they were needed.
</P>
<P>
   Kulikov is a member of the Russian Parliament's Security
Committee. After the attack, the panel demanded that Rushailo, the
interior minister, and the military prosecutor report on why the
debacle occurred. Instead, they sent an aide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The aide read a paper from which nothing could be understood,
neither the causes, not the names of those who are guilty,''
Kulikov said in an interview. ``And, most important, he did not say
what measures were taken in order to prevent such tragic incidents
from happening in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The authorities have not asked Ostapchuk for his views, but he
has taken away a few lessons from the ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to change our military structure radically, establish
cooperation between our different types of forces and improve our
reconnaissance,'' he said. ``If some of our guys had just flown
over the area beforehand, they could have seen what the rebels had
in store for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked who was to blame, he raised his hand and pointed up in the
air.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's them,'' he said, referring to Russia's top commanders.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
