<DOCNO> NYT20000415.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 12:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7835 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-TRADE-INSTITUTIONS-AR     04-15 1235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADE-INSTITUTIONS-ART-1180(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLOBAL LOAN AGENCIES BUCKLE UP FOR TURBULENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT1,2 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the police built barricades and wrapped razor
wire over the gleaming glass front of the World Bank headquarters,
James D. Wolfensohn, the bank's Australian-born president, gathered
his staff last week and told them to ``remember to stand tall,
because we are way ahead of the protesters.''
</P>
<P>
   In the battle over who is to blame for the widening economic
inequities that thousands of people are arriving in Washington to
rail against, it was a telling moment of defiance.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I find demoralizing is that there is no organization on
earth that is doing more for the poor than we do,'' Wolfensohn said
last week. ``Globalization is not something the World Bank can turn
back. It's not something the International Monetary Fund can stop.
We can only help people and countries adjust to it, to try to close
the gaps.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfensohn paused and then, referring to the head of the World
Trade Organization, the initial target of the protesters' ire in
Seattle late last year, he added, ``You know, Mike Moore said today
that blaming us for civil strife and poverty is like blaming the
Red Cross for war.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps so, but second-guessing generals and doctors is hardly
new, even in economic war.
</P>
<P>
   And if the protesters on the streets sound extreme in demanding
that the bank and the monetary fund be shut, they are hardly the
only ones taking aim at the half-century-old institutions designed
for a simpler economic era.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly a week goes by in Washington these days without an
environmental group criticizing the World Bank's 650-mile-long
oil-pipeline project in Chad and Cameroon, or a development project
on the fringes of Tibet that has been caught up in the politically
sensitive question of whether the bank is helping China dilute the
proportion of Tibetan people in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Commissions galore are re-examining whether the bank still lends
too much to middle-income nations and not enough to the world's
poorest. The IMF is still embroiled in battles over whether it did
more harm than good when it placed strict budget-balancing and
interest-rate requirements on nations hit by the Asian contagion.
And then there is the World Trade Organization, which is not
meeting in Washington but is a target nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe and Asia, the WTO is seen as a tool of Washington,
forcing countries to ingest hormone-treated beef or allow in U.S.
manufacturers. In Washington it is seen by many on Capitol Hill,
particularly conservatives, as a rogue bureaucracy intent on
setting labor, environmental and trade rules that override national
laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the common complaints is that many of these
organizations don't listen as well as they say they do,'' said
Andrea Durbin, director of international programs for Friends of
the Earth, who frequently interacts with the institutions at the
center of the protests. ``The Indonesians have a new saying for
dealing with the World Bank _ they invite us, they inform us, and
then they ignore what we have to say.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is also clear that the criticism is having some effect.
The IMF now publishes far more data about the economic condition of
its member countries than ever before. The idea was to flush out
nations that routinely hid bad news, but recently, to the fund's
delight, it set off howls in London when it questioned the wisdom
of Britain's economic strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfensohn came to Saturday's meetings brandishing charts
showing that big power projects, once 25 percent of the World
Bank's lending, now account for just 2 percent, and that spending
on nutrition, education and ``microloans'' to small businesses,
many run by women in the Third World, has skyrocketed.
</P>
<P>
   He talks about new partnerships with the World Wildlife Fund in
Brazil. For the first time, the top agenda item for the Development
Committee, the bank's main policy-setting body, is a review of
programs to fight AIDS, taking the bank into areas previously
handled by the United Nations and the World Health Organization.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also clear that many of these changes do not strike at
the core of the bank's operations and that the pressure for better
focus and far bigger changes is growing. Twice in the last few
months Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers has given speeches
outlining the Clinton administration's agenda, calling for ``a new
division of labor between the IMF and the World Bank.''
</P>
<P>
   While Summers hedged his comments carefully to avoid fueling
more extreme critics, he clearly is worried that the bank lent far
too little money for humanitarian purposes during the Asian crisis,
and should get out of some lending that could clearly be handled by
the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of legitimate questions about what proportion
of the bank's projects work, and how well they get executed,'' a
senior American official said. ``And there are questions about
whether the bank's rhetoric matches its realities.''
</P>
<P>
   While many of the proposals to reform the bank and the fund
appear to be at cross-purposes, there is rough agreement that both
have strayed from their main missions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants the bank and the IMF to return to their core
competencies,'' said Nancy Birdsall, a senior associate at the
Carnegie Endowment for International Peace, who participated in a
study with the Overseas Development Council. ``The question is how
to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The IMF should lend to poor countries, she said, but ``not for
too long, because they get sucked into other issues, from reforming
education to bank supervision to designing the medical-care
system.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's put poverty reduction in the World Bank, and managing
crises back in the IMF,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But another major study, commissioned by Congress and headed by
Alan Meltzer, a Carnegie Mellon professor who until recently called
for the elimination of the fund, concluded that the IMF should lend
money to countries in distress for no more than 120 days, with
perhaps one renewal. Fund officials say that is ridiculous; they
would have been pulling money out of Thailand, Indonesia and South
Korea before their recoveries had gathered any steam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these ideas don't make any sense,'' said Stanley
Fischer, the fund's No. 2 official. ``It's fine to say that
countries shouldn't rely on the IMF, just the way it would be nice
if people didn't need to rely on psychiatrists. But sometimes you
need some outside help, and it's usually when all the private money
is pulling out.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the fund's track record has been mixed at best _ not
surprising, since countries come to the fund only when they are in
dire financial straits _ it has been a ripe target.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, there is little question that some of its policies in
recent years made bad situations worse. It encouraged the free flow
of foreign capital in and out of countries around the world before
many had the supervisory systems to handle it. And it had to back
down from early requirements that Indonesia stop subsidizing fuel
and other critical staples.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the fund is at a politically vulnerable moment. Its
longtime chief, Michel Camdessus, has just retired, and a bruising
battle over the selection of his successor is dividing its board.
</P>
<P>
   As the new chief, Horst Kohler of Germany, arrived in Washington
last week for the meetings, he was greeted with a vituperative
blast by Joseph E. Stiglitz, who was formerly the head of President
Clinton's council of economic advisers and, later, chief economist
at the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters on the street, Stiglitz wrote in the magazine New
Republic, would ``say the IMF's economic `remedies' often make
things worse _ turning slowdowns into recessions and recessions
into depressions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And they'll have a point,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stiglitz went on to describe a culture of arrogance and inertia
within the fund, fueled by a staff of ``third-rank students from
first-rate universities'' and older men who ``act as if they are
shouldering Rudyard Kipling's white man's burden.''
</P>
<P>
   Echoing the street protesters, he said the fund ``undermines the
democratic process by imposing policies'' in return for its
emergency cash. But his main complaint appeared to be that the fund
was not willing to adopt his approach to handling the Asian crisis
when he was at the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Stiglitz published his blistering account, the IMF
and economists have been shooting back in equally nasty language.
Rudiger Dornbusch, a prominent professor at Massachusetts Institute
of Technology and an occasional critic of the fund, immediately
circulated a response arguing that Stiglitz's argument was ``as
contrarian as it is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When countries arrive at the IMF, on a stretcher, this is not
the time for cute ideas,'' he wrote. ``Drastic politics are
necessary to avoid hemorrhage, currency collapse and irreparable
meltdown.''
</P>
<P>
   The austerity imposed by the fund, Dornbusch and others argue,
is nothing compared with the austerity that would be imposed if the
country in trouble simply ran out of cash, at the very moment when
private investors are fleeing.
</P>
<P>
   And in the end, Dornbusch said, austerity was as successful as
it was unpopular. ``The chief lesson for the IMF is that next time
they should apply exactly the same remedies and enjoy as
spectacular success,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
