<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7843 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-15 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE REAL THING 
</HEADLINE>
   By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bill Clinton has been musing about his presidential
afterlife.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't want a pardon. He doesn't want to be just another
Senate spouse. He doesn't want to give up the job he loves.
</P>
<P>
   I've been fretting over his future, too. And I think I've come
up with a novel way for him to still play a starring role in the
nation's life.
</P>
<P>
   Remember when Bill stumbled with Monica and Hollywood big shots
groused that Clinton critics in Washington were unrealistic? A
president, they said, should be allowed to have grays, and not be
viewed in black and white.
</P>
<P>
   As Sean Daniel, a producer, told The New York Times' Bernard
Weinraub: ``There's an understanding here that you can have a
messed-up private life and still do good work.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Herskovitz, who produced ``thirtysomething,'' said we
should accept ``the possibility of complexity and ambivalence'' in
marriage. ``In Hollywood,'' he said, ``marriage is often not seen
as a monolithic simple entity.''
</P>
<P>
   So, you'd think when Hollywood had the chance to influence the
culture by limning its own chief executives, it would paint with
those intriguing shades of gray.
</P>
<P>
   Nah. Hollywood is sticking with that old Henry Fonda formula.
They may love Clinton out there, but they are not ready to give us
a fictional president who is morally flawed.
</P>
<P>
   We get dream presidents like Harrison Ford in ``Air Force One,''
Morgan Freeman in ``Deep Impact'' and Bill Pullman in
``Independence Day.''
</P>
<P>
   The comedy ``Dave,'' with Kevin Kline, started out with a
duplicitous, libidinous president. But he was quickly consigned to
a coma and replaced with a true-blue twin.
</P>
<P>
   In NBC's ``West Wing,'' we get President Josiah Bartlett, a
Nobel Prize-winning economist who is a faithful husband, fabulous
dad and forgiving boss. The guy is so preternaturally inspiring
that even President Clinton is smitten. ``West Wing'' was created
by Aaron Sorkin, who sired a similarly idealized leader in ``The
American President.''
</P>
<P>
   The show's success has spurred a lot of interest in Washington
dramas packed with extremely attractive young men and women who do
good by day and get down by night.
</P>
<P>
   In ``D.C.,'' a Senate staffer, a lobbyist, a TV producer and a
Supreme Court clerk, all roommates, opine: ``Sometimes it's not
about blind ambition. It's about doing the right thing.'' And,
``You know who makes this place really hum? It's us, the people
behind them. We're the only ones with enough energy to write the
laws, run the committees, party 'til 3 and then do it all again the
next day.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Washington shows are in the hopper. This will be Clinton's
true legacy. Along with George Stephanopoulos, he showed Hollywood
that politics could be sexy, that Pennsylvania Avenue could be
Melrose Place.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to newspaper editors in Washington last week, the
president was asked if he was going to have an impeachment wing in
his presidential library. ``Yeah,'' he said, ``we'll deal with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmmmm. Impeachment Wing. It had a nice ring, like ``West Wing''
but less goody-goody. If the saint in that show can get big
ratings, what could a sinner in a new show called ``Impeachment
Wing'' get?
</P>
<P>
   Since Bill Clinton is casting around for something to do, why
not cast himself in his own Oval hour? It would give the
Entertainer in Chief the third term he really wants. It could be
MTV's ``Real World'' meets ABC's ``World News Tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's sitcom pals, the Thomasons, could write it, capping
their efforts to fuse show biz and politics. The TV President
Clinton could do good by day and get down by night. Or vice versa.
There could be an eerily familiar cast of supporting players: the
steely but vulnerable senator-wife; the knowing but unknowing
secretary-gatekeeper; the frisky but delusional mistress-intern;
and the bungling but tall attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood should take a lesson from the phenomenal success of
``The Sopranos.'' Audiences are willing to embrace an ethically
compromised, dysfunctional patriarch with big appetites, a
complicated marriage and an edgy relationship with his college-age
daughter. A mama's boy who fears his life will amount to a Big
Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Look for ``Impeachment Wing'' in the 2001 May sweeps. On cable,
of course.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-15-00 1313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
