<DOCNO> NYT20000415.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7888 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GIULIANI-DONORS-ART-7     04-15 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIULIANI-DONORS-ART-775(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI DONORS LOATHE FIRST LADY FROM AFAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT4 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They may never have set foot in New York, may have
little use for big-city notions and may harbor only a vague idea of
which vowel goes where in the last name of the Republican who wants
to be the state's next U.S. senator.
</P>
<P>
   But for many of the people who have been showering Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's campaign with donations from far-flung ZIP codes, just
one fact matters: His opponent is Hillary Rodham Clinton. And she
must _ must! _ be stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is a brash, pushy woman,'' said Jocelyn Wallace of
Scottsdale, Ariz., one of thousands of out-of-state Republicans who
seem to have seethed their way through the long years of the
Clinton administration and are now looking for some payback. She
gave $250 to the Giuliani campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In shattering the fund-raising record for a Senate candidate,
Giuliani appears to have tapped a vein of deep loathing for Hillary
Clinton, often more than for her husband, among people outside the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Several retirees in Florida, a construction executive in North
Carolina who is a regular visitor to the HillaryNo.com Web site, a
woman in Maine still bothered by the first lady's role in the
administration's failed health care plan _ all were lured into New
York politics by the prospect of a Senator Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, who said she doubted that she would have contributed
had Giuliani run against a home-grown Democrat, was among more than
20 out-of-state Giuliani donors selected at random from the
campaign's disclosure records and interviewed by telephone last
week. Her criticisms of Clinton were actually tamer than most.
</P>
<P>
   A more typical response came from William Orthwein of St. Louis,
who said Clinton was ``out-of-this-world power hungry.'' What did
he think of the mayor? ``Not much,'' snapped Orthwein, a retired
McDonnell Douglas executive who donated $250 three times to the
campaign. ``I hope he beats her. It's that simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the $19 million that Giuliani has already collected with
seven months to go before the election, roughly half of it is from
out of state. By contrast, when another nonincumbent, Charles
Schumer, then a Brooklyn congressman, defeated Sen. Alfonse D'Amato
of New York in 1998, Schumer raised a total of $17 million for the
entire campaign, only 25 percent of which originated out of state.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, with $12 million so far, has also done well with
out-of-state donors. But the mayor's startling success has prompted
her to assert that he is filling his coffers by embracing the far
right.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the archconservative senator from North Carolina,
Clinton said earlier this year that Giuliani ``learned from people
like Jesse Helms that you run some of these campaigns, these
negative campaigns, out of state so that you can go around saying
you're not doing it in-state and hope that nobody will catch you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That seems to be the pattern,'' she said, ``and it's been a
pretty tried-and-true technique of the right-wing Republicans for a
long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has responded by ridiculing Clinton, saying that she
attributes everything to a ``right-wing conspiracy.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interviews, some donors certainly voiced views more
conservative than those of the mayor, who supports abortion rights
and gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't aware of that,'' said one, Hiram Groover, a retiree
from Mesa, Ariz., when informed of Giuliani's stance on social
issues. ``But what do you think about Hillary Clinton? What do you
think she stands for? She sure isn't pro-life. She'd probably do
anything to get a vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of these people would probably have sent money to the
Giuliani campaign without being asked. But the campaign, aided by a
prominent conservative Washington-based fund-raiser, Richard
Viguerie, has barraged the mailboxes of Republicans across the
nation with solicitations. The letters often describe Clinton as
the ``leader of the ultra left-wing Democrats,'' contending that if
she wins the Senate race, she will then run for president.
</P>
<P>
   The pitches work. Groover's only donation to any candidate on
the federal level since 1980 was the $250 he sent to the Giuliani
campaign, according to campaign records.
</P>
<P>
   Still, several donors characterized themselves as centrist
Republicans who favored abortion rights, though their moderation
did not extend to their feelings toward Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really do believe that I have a greater dislike for her''
than for President Clinton, said Fenton Hord, who said he backed
abortion rights. ``When I hear her speak, it's almost as if I hear
her speaking down to me _ as if she clearly has in her own mind the
answers to everything.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Hord, an executive of a building-materials company in Raleigh,
N.C., displays a banner on his computer screen _ ``Eight Years Is
Enough'' _ that he got from the HillaryNo.com site, which is run by
the Giuliani campaign. Hord has given two $250 donations to the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to explain what exactly about Clinton is so troubling,
some donors cited her role in Whitewater and other inquiries during
the Clinton administration. Others said she was haughty, and
presumptuous in moving to New York to run for office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that New York would be better served by someone from
New York,'' said Julia Moss of Yarmouth, Maine, who donated $2,000.
Moss later added that she was ``turned off by the fact that she was
going to be in a policy-making situation with health care, because
we didn't elect her.''
</P>
<P>
   A sizable percentage of the donors from out of state are
retirees, the Giuliani campaign says.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is a carpetbagger, pure and simple,'' said one retiree,
Grant Bakewell of Palm Desert, Calif., who donated $500. ``She is a
devious, self-promoting, selfish woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Others referred to her in almost apocalyptic terms. ``I will
tell you that she has been a very miserable kind of person,'' said
another retiree who gave $500, John Daly of Vero Beach, Fla.
``Everything that she has ever put her hand in has been a failure.
She was a communist and also a member of the KGB, or close to it.
She is a person who is very, very dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giuliani campaign has amassed a list of more than 200,000
donors, which bodes well for its future fund raising because past
donors tend to give again. The campaign is receiving about 75
percent of its donations from direct mail _ an achievement,
considering that most candidates find they must personally solicit
most of their money, either on the phone or through fund-raising
events.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, there is less pressure on Giuliani to attend
fund-raisers, which may be fortunate for the mayor, who sometimes
appears reluctant to leave the city to campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's national reputation has obviously also helped her fund
raising, and she has collected roughly 55 percent of her $12
million from people outside New York. But while Giuliani tends to
arouse strong passions in New York City, he is not nearly as well
known nationally, so he cannot be turned into the same kind of
direct-mail fund-raising vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   That said, some of the Giuliani donors did praise his record in
New York, saying that they had visited the city and had been
impressed with the changes during his tenure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like what Giuliani has done in New York,'' said Cary
Maguire, an oil-company executive in Dallas who donated $1,000 at a
fund-raising event there which was attended by Giuliani. ``I'm not
going to say anything negative about her. I just thought he was the
better candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Hord, the North Carolina executive, said he admired Giuliani's
``straightforwardness and tenacity.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added that he had never before contributed to a New York
candidate. So why did he really donate? ``I just don't want any
more of my dinners being ruined by listening to her or her
husband,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-15-00 1413EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000415.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7890 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-CHICKENSOUP-MAIN16-CO     04-15 2273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICKENSOUP-MAIN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A relentless serving of Chicken Soup for the masses
 &HT;    By Rachel Sauer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ Admit you got a little sloppy over the
story with the puppy. Admit it.
</P>
<P>
   Admit you drove home through Los Angeles-style traffic after a
hideous Monday, watched mass graves and hurricanes on the news,
heard Allen Greenspan intone doom, picked the kids up from soccer,
skipped aerobics and PTA, swigged some Pepto-Bismol and locked
yourself in the bathroom with the book your mom gave you for
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Admit you saw that limping puppy with no hip socket and the
little boy with the leg brace pulling $2.37 out of his pocket, and
you got a little misty. You can admit you laughed at yourself, but
you also wanted to shout, ``That puppy is just as good as everyone
else! So is the little boy!'' You wanted to hug them both and
scribble out a check to pay the pet store owner the balance.
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead, admit it.
</P>
<P>
   You won't be the only one, you know, and that's OK. That's good.
That's what we call chicken soup.
</P>
<P>
   Used to be chicken soup was presented in a ceramic bowl, laced
with noodles and vitamins, to the kid home sick from school.
Comfort food, we called it, easy to swallow, like Ben and Jerry's
except healthier.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's a phenomenon, therapy in 101 stories to open the heart
and rekindle the spirit. It's ``Chicken Soup for the Soul'' and
readers of 50 million books in print in 33 languages are lapping it
up.
</P>
<P>
   Readers have spoken: Feed us.
</P>
<P>
   Give us what Oprah doesn't. Give us a commercial break, stories
where the plot doesn't hinge on infidelity or addiction or neglect
or kidnapped children. Don't make us slog through 300 pages before
we get to a possibly unsatisfying resolution. Make us feel good.
</P>
<P>
   Make us feel good now, while the microwave is zapping the Jiffy
Pop, when we have 10 spare minutes before setting the alarm for
5:30 a.m. and turning off the light.
</P>
<P>
   Feed us something lite _ like lite ice cream, Milky Way Lite.
Something that won't eventually make us feel guilty and stand
tip-toe staring over our shoulder into the bathroom mirror,
grimacing at the reflection of our butt.
</P>
<P>
   Give us a catalyst to cry and purge the pollution of life in
2000, and give it to us in eight pages or less. Give us Muzak in
true short stories. Not the kind that makes us shriek at the
customer service representative after we've been on hold for 11
minutes. Nice Muzak. Our favorite Enya song after a nap Muzak. We
want stories about goodness and surviving and triumph. And puppies.
We want puppies.
</P>
<P>
   Feed us chicken soup.
</P>
<P>
   These books are popular in Iowa. They sell very, very well in
Iowa. And Wyoming. Perpetual best-sellers up there. And our very
own Colorado, and Arkansas, and Idaho, and Utah. They sell very
well in what coastal types condescendingly call the fly-over zone.
</P>
<P>
   Where they don't sell well is New York City and Los Angeles and
Miami. Places where black isn't so much a clothing color as a
lifestyle decision, where the espressos are double, the waiters are
really actors, the answering of cell phones a life-or-death
quick-draw.
</P>
<P>
   It's all about sophistication and cosmopolitanism in those
places, where everything's a statement and an accessory, including
books. In those places, books had better include frustrated
artists, suburban malaise, existential angst and questions about
sexual identity, and possibly a mime. If there's chicken soup
involved anywhere, it had better be free-range chicken and it
better be served at some dumpy little cafe that nobody knows about,
where all the patrons are 27 and working on their novels and are
there for some esoteric irony trip.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, stories about a limping puppy? A dying boy who wants
to be a fireman? How jejune. How provincial. Oh, you know, darling,
how common. We'll discuss it over creme brulee.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Canfield, during a telephone interview, on people who
criticize the ``Chicken Soup'' books: ``We're not great literature.
We do as much editing as we can, but I don't claim to be a great
writer. I do claim to recognize a good story, and I do think we've
been able to see how to tell a good story. We're not out there
trying to deal with the forces of evil in a teleological,
theological level. We're saying, 'Look, here's this person who went
through this.' Just so people can be reminded that life is good,
it's a good feeling to be a human being.''
</P>
<P>
   He's the one who started all this, way back in the late 1960s
when he taught at an inner-city Chicago high school where most of
his students were black. He said he noticed the kids weren't
applying themselves. For a guy who grew up in white suburbia with
all kinds of straight-A, sports hero, editor of the yearbook and
onward to college expectations, that was a new _ and bad _ concept.
</P>
<P>
   So he started clipping stories out of Parade, Reader's Digest,
Guidepost, People, stories about black history, members of the
black community who were overcoming obstacles and achieving goals.
That was the beginning of it. Other teachers asked him to teach
them how to inspire their kids like he was inspiring his. His
secret for success was: stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I began to realize stories really are the vehicle for the
highest teachings,'' he said. ``Christ taught in parables, Buddha
told stories. What do we do every night? We watch TV. And what's on
TV? Stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon he was doing teacher inservices to tell them stories about
telling stories. Then he was teaching seminars and doing public
speaking. During his presentations he told some of the stories he'd
clipped and collected for years. Often people approached him
afterward and asked him in what books they could find certain
stories he'd shared.
</P>
<P>
   Blink went the light bulb over his head. This was the early
1990s, remember, and books of short stories just didn't sell well,
especially nonfiction stories. But with his friend Mark Victor
Hansen, Canfield began compiling the uplifting stories they both
had collected for more than 20 years into one book of 101 stories
``to open the heart and rekindle the spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   As Canfield explains it on his Web site, the title came about
like this: ``When we were almost finished with the book, we still
didn't have a title. Mark and I decided to meditate and pray for an
answer. I use a receptive meditation process in which I ask God to
give me an answer to my question, and then I sit in silence and
wait to see an answer on a blank screen in my mind or to hear the
answer. I did that every day for a week. On the third day, I saw
the words Chicken Soup written on the screen. ... I began to
reflect on its meaning, I remembered that when I was a child my
mother always made chicken soup when we were sick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I began to think that although our bodies weren't that sick,
America's spirit was sick. There was so much hopelessness,
resignation, cynicism and despair in America. So, I figured, we
needed chicken soup for our spirits. By the end of the week it had
evolved into 'Chicken Soup for the Soul.' Everyone we told the
title to got goose bumps.''
</P>
<P>
   The publishers in New York City didn't get goose bumps. They got
the glassy-eyed and vaguely bored look that precedes a rejection.
Canfield and Hansen got it 33 times, ``this doesn't meet our needs
at this time'' or ``this is great, but ...'' or just plain ``no.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Canfield and Hansen went to the American Booksellers
Association convention in Anaheim, Calif., and tried peddling their
101 stories to booksellers who smirked bemusedly at the nice
stories. At least the people from Health Communications Inc.,
agreed to take the book back to Florida and read it. The company
mainly publishes self-help and inspirational books, and had their
first big seller in 1983 with ``Adult Children of Alcoholics.'' A
week later the small company's owner called Canfield and said he
loved the book and wanted to publish it.
</P>
<P>
   To say that readers like these books is to say, ``John Grisham.
Is he the one who writes those nice stories about lawyers?'' People
love these books. They LOVE them.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Chicken Soup'' tsunami started with word-of-mouth
advertising when the original ``Chicken Soup for the Soul'' was
published in 1993, said Larry Getlin, public relations specialist
for Health Communications Inc. Things didn't pick up until two
years later, when word-of-mouth had mushroomed into an
international bellow. The stories struck a collective cord,
Canfield said, a need for simple reassurances of goodness in a
world where 6-year-olds have guns.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty soon there was ``A Second Helping of Chicken Soup for the
Soul,'' then a third serving, a fourth course, a fifth portion, a
sixth bowl. Each time it was 101 stories to open the heart and
rekindle the spirit. People wrote to Canfield and Hansen asking for
certain sorts of stories, stories about coping with the loss of a
loved one, stories about living well with physical handicaps,
stories about being a good mother when life goes crazy.
</P>
<P>
   The books began specializing, branching out. Now there is
chicken soup for women, teen-agers, pet lovers, mothers, golfers,
couples, Christians, Christian families, survivors, little souls,
golden souls, country souls. When the third volume of ``Chicken
Soup for the Teenage Soul'' is published April 25, there will be 30
``Chicken Soup'' books in print, more than 50 million copies in 33
languages _ ``Sopa de Pollo para el Alma.''
</P>
<P>
   In the works are chicken soup for so many kinds of souls:
laughing, golfing, Jewish, single, man, college, divorced,
grieving, writer, parent, global, unstoppable, entrepreneur,
doctor, emergency worker, nurse, Canadian, prisoner, expectant
mother, rock `n' roll, sports fan, adopted, traveler, Celt and
physically challenged. There will be low-fat chicken soup with
stories about weight loss. There will be chicken soup for the
Greek, Pakistani, Indian, South African soul.
</P>
<P>
   There are ``Chicken Soup'' calendars, ``Chicken Soup'' CDs with
uplifting songs, ``Chicken Soup'' magnets and mugs and games.
Companies that make products that relate to the spirit of ``Chicken
Soup'' approach the company that handles ``Chicken Soup'' marketing
and ask to be associated with the phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is simple: Make a difference in the world, possibly do
something toward world peace and sell a billion books by 2020.
That's all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We picked a goal that seemingly was impossible, that would
force us to think in a way that we wouldn't think if we were just
writing books and sending them to publishers and going on book
tours,'' Canfield said. ``To reach a billion people you're reaching
one-sixth of the world's population.''
</P>
<P>
   They're having to think outside the bowl, as it were. Right now
about 80 percent to 85 percent of ``Chicken Soup'' readers are
women, so they're reaching out to men through just plain stories
that men can relate to, and through specialty books dealing with
professions.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of professions, did you know the woman who wrote
``Romancing the Stone'' flunked her first creative writing class?
That story will be in ``Chicken Soup for the Writer's Soul.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Chicken Soup'' people are thinking globally, with stories
for people from different countries, stories about the tolerant
soul (about a person's transformation from being bigoted to being
tolerant), the global soul.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's forced us to get out of our American mentality,'' he
said. ``Stories for the global soul will show that a mother in
Pakistan is no different than a mother in Texas. They all want the
same things for their children. It'll show the universal human
desires to have our relationships work, to be respected, to
overcome obstacles. That transcends any cultural differences that
we seemingly go to war over.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicken Soup for the Prisoner's Soul'' will not be sold in
bookstores, but will be given free to 1.3 million of America's
prisoners. And a portion of the proceeds from every book is donated
to different charities. Like Canfield said, it's about making the
world a better place.
</P>
<P>
   Give peace a chance. Have some chicken soup.
</P>
<P>
   Each new ``Chicken Soup'' that's released spikes up the New York
Times nonfiction best-seller list and literary purists cringe.
Critics sniff that the books pander to the very lowest in appetites
for the printed word. They might as well be comic books, critics
huff. They're too easy (though Canfield points out the stories
never preach at the end or moralize, so readers can draw personal
meaning from the stories). They're maudlin. They're sugary enough
to induce diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   True, all of it true. In these books there's always some little
boy named Tommy or Billy or Timmy who gets a disease and dies or
gets lost in the grocery store. There are injured athletes who give
it the old college try and throw the winning pass with a broken
arm. There are wise old next door neighbors who Teach Us Something
About Life.
</P>
<P>
   There are easy-to-swallow vignettes that make us feel good, as
opposed to Oprah's pick most months in which a child drowns in a
swimming pool and everybody falls apart. ``Chicken Soup'' stories,
even the ones on death and dying, ultimately are about redemption.
Who says life's literary lessons have to be shrouded in symbolism
and metaphor? Why can't they be short and sweet?
</P>
<P>
   The ``Chicken Soup'' message is: They can.
</P>
<P>
   The other ``Chicken Soup'' message is: Just because a puppy is
born without a hip socket doesn't mean it's not as good as the rest
of the litter.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
