</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICKENSOUP-SPOOF16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chicken Soup for the Chicken Soul
 &HT;    By ``Chicken Little''
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ It was a beautiful summer day, one I'll
never forget. The sun was round and gold like a big bowl of creamed
corn. The sky was blue like Clean &AMP; Clear astringent face wash for
sensitive skin. Fluffy puffs of clouds that looked like Farmer
Brown's white hair where it sticks out the back of his baseball cap
floated along like they had nowhere to go. Come to think of it,
they probably didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Timmy and I were playing in the yard. Timmy was my best friend.
I'd known him my whole life: Our moms laid us on the same day, we
hatched the same day. When we were still yellow and fuzzy we
cheeped and scampered and frolicked together. Timmy couldn't frolic
as well as the rest of the chicks because he wore Coke bottle
glasses for far-sightedness, he lisped, he stuttered, he laughed
like this: ``henk-henk-henk.'' He was a conspiracy theorist and one
of his legs was an inch shorter than the other so he mainly went in
circles. But he was my best friend. We got our pinfeathers
together, we ``borrowed'' Farmer Brown's copies of ``American
Poultry Monthly'' and giggled over it out behind the henhouse, we
talked about our hopes and dreams.
</P>
<P>
   On this beautiful summer day, Timmy and I were sitting on a
grassy knoll in the farmyard, talking about our hopes and dreams.
Timmy told me he wanted to be a fireman and then president. I told
him I wanted to be an astronaut or a pilot because that's the only
way I'd fly with these dumb chicken wings. We smiled happily.
That's when it happened: The sky fell. It wasn't the whole sky,
just a piece of it, and it landed on Timmy's head.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't know what to do. I ran screaming into the chicken yard.
``The sky is falling! The sky is falling!'' The older chickens
ignored me _ I saw them huddled in tight circles muttering
something about Chick-Fil-A _ and the younger ones laughed.
``You're crazy, Chicken Little, go cluck somewhere else.'' I ran
back to Timmy, cradling his head in my wings. ``Rosebud,'' he
gasped, his eyes fluttering closed. ``What? Timmy!'' I cried.
``Don't leave me!'' He smiled weakly and whispered, ``Chicken
Little, someday we'll fly together.''
</P>
<P>
   And then he drew a deep, shaky breath and heaved himself up,
gingerly rubbing the goose egg on his head. Getting beaned by the
falling sky had cured his far-sightedness, stutter and lisp. After
that he got all the chicks and ended up going to MIT and designing
airplanes. He took me flying one time when he was home visiting his
mother. And I spend most of my time outside, staring up and hoping
the sky will fall on me, too. I have never forgotten that summer
day.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-15-00 1413EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000415.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7892 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-COLUMBINE-HEALING16-C     04-15 1626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMBINE-HEALING16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Communities work through emotional wounds
 &HT;    By Rachel Sauer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ They're called ``trigger events'' _
sounds, sights or smells that can trip a wire in the memory and
take a person back to a certain time or event.
</P>
<P>
   Theresa Miller and her advanced chemistry students experienced
one several weeks ago when drama students practicing a skit in the
hallway outside her classroom screamed. Almost in unison the
chemistry students gasped and blanched, she said, ``and there are
other things, too. I think all of us shiver when we hear
helicopters.''
</P>
<P>
   It may always be that way at Columbine High School. The faces of
students will change, the students who were there April 20, 1999,
will graduate and leave, the teachers who were there will retire,
but it's impossible to forget.
</P>
<P>
   Because for all the pop-psychology talk of closure, it's
doubtful such a concept is real. When Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold
blasted through Columbine High School at about 11:30 a.m. April 20,
1999, killing 12 students, one teacher and themselves, the tragedy
became a part of the school's fabric, an elemental part of
Littleton's consciousness, a fundamental event in the memories of
the people of Colorado and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   And as for the grief that follows death and tragedy, ``I don't
think you really have closure,'' said Kerri Mosinski, a grief
counselor for Grand Valley Hospice and Palliative Care in Grand
Junction. ``A lot of people think about grief as there's a start
and there's a stop. But most people will tell you, if they've
really gone through it, that grief doesn't ever really stop. When
you have the grief experience, your life goes on but that
experience forever changes your life, it's with you until you
die.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of other American communities that have experienced
tragedy can attest to that fact. In Oklahoma City _ where on April
19, 1995, Terry Nichols and Timothy McVeigh blew up the Alfred P.
Murrah Federal Building, killing 168 individuals _ people still
mourn, still grieve, said Lauri Hanna, community relations
coordinator for the Oklahoma City American Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   She said five years later the Red Cross still has 37 open cases
stemming from the bombing, including helping people with medical
bills from dozens of surgeries and referring people to counselors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen divorces, attempted suicides, a lot of depression
and drug and alcohol abuse, just post-traumatic stress disorder,''
she said. ``Some of the cases we have now are people we've had
since right after it happened. But we have people who are brand
new, who felt like they could deal with it on their own.''
</P>
<P>
   Tragedies that happen in America's cities and towns have become
national tragedies _ the bombing in Oklahoma City, and school
shootings in Pearl, Miss., Jonesboro, Ark., Paducah, Ky.,
Springfield, Ore., and Littleton. People talk and talk and talk
about them.
</P>
<P>
   Pundits 2,000 miles away tell the people in a city where tragedy
occurred what they should have done to prevent it. The media crush
becomes suffocating. Emotional wounds are re-opened daily, the
grief made fresh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been difficult,'' said Andy Lowry, a Columbine High
School physical education teacher, during a media forum April 5.
``What's made it really hard is the media, irresponsible journalism
and not finding facts. I turn on the radio, turn on the news, and
there are all these experts on Columbine who've never even been
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey White, a Columbine senior who was at lunch when the
shootings occurred, said it's been hard enough going to school
there every day knowing what happened and trying to persevere
through the daily memories, ``but then you get a tour bus full of
people pulling into the parking lot, people standing across the
street staring at us. That's really hard.''
</P>
<P>
   After a while, said Pearl (Miss.) Police Chief Bill Slade,
people make an effort to get life back to normal _ not to forget,
because the grief is still so much a part of the town, but to just
live life.
</P>
<P>
   Last month the police department closed the last case relating
to the Oct. 1, 1997, high school shooting _ a case in which one
person charged as an accessory in the shooting made a plea
agreement and now is in state prison _ and that has helped. Life in
Pearl is what might be described as normal, if there is such a
thing, but the town has changed in little ways, Slade said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are more alert,'' he said. ``If they hear anything,
they call us. I don't just attribute that to what happened here, I
attribute that a lot to Columbine _ the terribleness of their
tragedy has made people say, 'Hey, enough is enough.' The kids or
whoever, they don't want to be an innocent party, they are saying,
'Hey, if I hear it I'm going to say something because I don't want
something like that to happen.'''
</P>
<P>
   Slade said since 1997 rumors have flown rampant through Pearl,
which hurt more than helped people. For the first two months of the
investigation, he said, four investigators worked the case 16 hours
a day while two more investigators spent as much time tracking down
rumors ``because we don't have the luxury of saying, 'Well, this is
nonsense.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But I would say overall that we are doing pretty good. Our
kids have gotten back in the groove, and I think at the end of that
year they were back in the groove at school,'' Slade said. ``There
still are a lot of memories and every time something else would
happen somewhere else the media would call, visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the kids are dealing with it better than some adults. With
adults there's a lot of wondering, a lot of guilt. I know I look at
it from my viewpoint, 'OK, what could I have done?' I tend to take
it personal because of my job, still wonder and second-guess about
different things. The kids say, 'OK, this happened, this is what's
been done.' Adults still think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   In Littleton, guilt has compounded the grief for some. Rich
Long, a Columbine technology teacher, said, ``I had a college
professor say to me, 'You're in the place of a parent for those
eight hours.' I struggle with this because it happened on our
watch. I just hurt when I think about how one of (the parents')
sons or daughters lost their lives. And these lives lost, they were
not insignificant. We lost a colleague who was a tremendous person,
who had a lot more life to live.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Rodney Reeves, pastor of Central Baptist Church in
Jonesboro, Ark., said the town as a whole is dealing well with
grief resulting from the March 24, 1998, tragedy at Westside Middle
School where two adolescent boys killed four students and one
teacher, but the tragedy at Columbine High School renewed much of
the grief for some because it happened so close to the Jonesboro
first anniversary, ``and because you really hope that somehow
society or the world you share with others would learn from your
tragedy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're hoping evil can somehow be spent in a sacrificial way
so it doesn't happen again, so the deaths of these children in
Jonesboro, these beloved members of our community, their lives
wouldn't have been sacrifices. But even though the Littleton
tragedy was something so disappointing for us because we were
hoping our tragedy would be the end of it _ and I'm not in any way
discounting what happened in Oregon and other places, but there's
something about the timing of Littleton and how it re-opened wounds
for us _ at the same time it gave us a reason to seek healing more
permanently, more significantly. I think we're doing better as a
community.''
</P>
<P>
   That is part of the grief journey, Mosinski said. She cited a
mother who lost a child several years ago and told her that at
first she thought about the loss every minute of every day, then
every hour, then many times every day, ``then you wake up and
realize you have gone a day without thinking about it. But it's
never gone. You don't ever get over it, but your life changes, you
have growth experiences because of that loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowry said attitudes at Columbine and in Littleton have changed
in subtle ways: ``Tomorrow is not guaranteed to any of us,'' he
said, ``so let's take care of today.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said in Jonesboro, a deeply religious community, people
have found comfort in the concept of God's providence, ``how God
seems to invest in us everything we need to get through tragedy,''
he said. ``A lot of people think a desire for a healthy community
of faith will operate as preventative maintenance for tragedy, but
that's not altogether true. What God does is he resources us
knowing what we will face, so we're able to work through things and
be healthier for it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the April 5 media forum, Columbine students said the same
thing. They noted how family, friends and the Littleton community
have surrounded and embraced them, and helped them return to school
and succeed, and have been there when they needed to talk about
their grief.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at each other in a different light now,'' said Jamie
Conwell, a Columbine sophomore. ``It's been really hard knowing I
got out and my friends had to go through so much pain, see so much.
But your friends and family help you get through the bad times and
we all have those. But the support we get is what helps us through
this. Every day I get asked by teachers, 'How is your day going?'
We're a lot more aware of each other.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to focus on each day when you wake up,'' said
Columbine student body president Mike Sheehan, a senior.
``Something happened to our school and it's hard to move on, but
we've been given a second chance to live.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
