<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7893 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-COLUMBINE-MAIN16-COX     04-15 2819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMBINE-MAIN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pain of Columbine still lives
 &HT;    By Gary Harmon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ The jolt of gunfire that shattered the
halls of Columbine High School still splits the air over Colorado's
amber plains, roars over purple mountains, drowns the cacophony of
its crystal rivers and clatters down red canyons.
</P>
<P>
   The echoes of 55 shots from a TEC-DC9 semi-automatic handgun,
bought illegally for $500, and blasts from a sawed-off shotgun
fired a year ago ricochet wildly through the memories of those who
were horrified from afar.
</P>
<P>
   They remember watching young men and women streaming in fear
from school. They remember witnessing a teen's foot drag a bloody
trail down the library wall as he was tugged to safety. They
remember as the body count heaved, trembled and, finally, stilled
at 12 students, a teacher and two killers.
</P>
<P>
   The killers were, by most accounts, outcasts whose rampage was
motivated by revenge against their tormentors. Their victims,
however, came from every caste of high school society.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, the report of gunfire from April 20, 1999, shakes the
halls of Congress and the Colorado Legislature. It sends presidents
and would-be presidents scuttling for political cover.
</P>
<P>
   But the echo of Columbine booms most loudly in the tiniest
places, in the consciences of those who watched, who lived and who
fear it all could happen again. For them, the word ``columbine''
will forever be more than just the name of the state flower.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last April 20, as the news of the tragedy began to come over
the news media, I remember thinking that as terrible as it was, I
was not directly affected by it,'' wrote Ron Taylor of Grand
Junction, who soon learned the bullets struck more closely than he
first realized.
</P>
<P>
   ``That very evening, my sister Lila called to tell us that my
nephew Philip was safe and unharmed,'' Taylor went on, responding
to a request by The Daily Sentinel that readers write their
impressions, recollections and prescriptions for the Columbine
killings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went from complacency to concern in a heartbeat,'' he wrote.
``Suddenly, a far-off, Front Range tragedy involved my youngest
sister's eldest son and was as close as my immediate family.''
</P>
<P>
   The bullets flew closer to Layne Newton, a Columbine graduate
now attending Mesa State College.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard noises and gunshots and screams,'' Newton said in an
interview with The Daily Sentinel. ``I ran out the front doors. The
glass in the doors shattered as my friend Charlie was running past
them. I thought he'd been shot but the bullets only shattered the
glass.''
</P>
<P>
   Students in Carolyn Burger's combined fourth- and fifth-grade
class at Lincoln-Orchard Mesa Elementary School felt the terror
just almost as palpably as did Newton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am really scared because someone could come kill me some
day,'' wrote Kristie Herrera, who, like many of her classmates,
said she would feel more comfortable in a school with video
cameras, metal detectors and armed guards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't understand how people have the heart to do
that,'' wrote Danielle Edwards, a sixth-grader at Bookcliff Middle
School. ``I don't feel very safe.''
</P>
<P>
   The Columbine killings touched deep nerves from sea to shining
sea.
</P>
<P>
   The Pew Research Center for the People and the Press
(www.people-press.org) listed the Columbine killings as the
sixth-most followed story of the decade, with 68 percent of
respondents saying they followed the story very closely. The
killings in suburban Littleton garnered more interest than the
return of veterans after the end of the Persian Gulf War, yet were
a percentage point short of the interest in a little girl who fell
into a well in Texas in October 1987.
</P>
<P>
   The deaths in 1999 of John F. Kennedy Jr., his wife and
sister-in-law, as well as the death in 1997 of Princess Diana, were
followed closely by 54 percent of respondents.
</P>
<P>
   Each of those cases involved people known to millions. Columbine
involved teens previously known only to their friends and families.
</P>
<P>
   Not every family was touched by the Columbine killings, but for
many, family was the overarching theme that both explained what
happened and offered a shield against more Columbine gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem goes back to what our society has become,'' wrote
Lynn Vrany of Grand Junction. ``Mothers no longer raise children;
day care does. Kids have very few boundaries or consequences and
law has taken power away from parents and schools and given it to
the children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids need continual love, care, guidance and consequences as
well as rewards for behavior. If they have self-respect and like
who they are and feel secure and part of something they will not
feel as bitter or violent.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Bambino runs Youth Alternatives (www.youthalternatives.com)
next to his to Dare to Car-e mechanic's shop. Prominently displayed
in each building are photographs of each Columbine victim and a
paragraph summing each too-short life.
</P>
<P>
   For Bambino, Columbine was the logical reflection of a society
that has forgotten its familial connections and interdependence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millions of Americans made sure that I had a pretty good
America to grow up in,'' he said. ``I think we owe kids today the
same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adult dedication to kids they do not know has got to rise.''
</P>
<P>
   Bambino said he hopes the trauma of Columbine will take a
positive turn for his hope of building youth centers throughout the
Grand Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Implicit in all the debate of the Columbine killings has been
the question of whether such an outburst was predictable and
whether repeats are preventable.
</P>
<P>
   Not hardly, said Dr. Bob Sammons, a Grand Junction psychiatrist.
</P>
<P>
   It's much easier to predict the outcomes of people whose lives
are on a trail of chronic violence and lawlessness. The Columbine
killers had criminal records, but their lawbreaking wasn't of the
frequency or extremity that would suggest the destruction they
actually caused, Sammons said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Single acts of violence are extremely hard to do something
about,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mental-health professionals are no closer to identifying killers
such as those who terrorized Columbine before they kill than before
the rampage, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not that psychologists, psychiatrists, counselors and therapists
haven't been trying.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Rakiecki, head psychologist for School District 51, said in
the past year, the district investigated more deeply threats,
gestures and comments made by schoolchildren to determine whether
they were made lightly or seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that we are assessing more kids more vigorously
than ever before,'' Rakiecki said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the horror of Columbine, children are still safer in
school than they are in the car driving home or on the ski slopes,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The district's watchful approach is appropriate, said a private
psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think School District 51 is closing its eyes,'' said
John Sorrick, a Grand Junction psychologist. ''I have not found
School District 51 to be overreacting.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Traylor, a Grand Junction lawyery sige on Mount Caramel
</P>
<P>
   By Mark England
</P>
<P>
   c. 2000 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ People from all over the world have come here for
the last seven years and made the 10-mile trip east to Mount Carmel
even though there wasn't much to see: slabs of concrete sticking
out of the earth like toppled tombstones, the rusted carcass of a
motorcycle owned by the late David Koresh.
</P>
<P>
   Destroy it and they will come.
</P>
<P>
   That seems to be the mantra emanating from the 1993 debacle that
saw 82 Davidians and four ATF agents die during a months-long siege
and ignited a backlash against the federal government that's still
not ebbed.
</P>
<P>
   The seventh anniversary of the fire that destroyed Mount Carmel
is Wednesday. Meanwhile, surviving Branch Davidians are preparing
for the June 19 start of the trial of their lawsuit against the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant English Professor Robert Darden of Baylor University
has led numerous unofficial tours of Mount Carmel, largely because
he and journalist Brad Bailey wrote a book on Koresh, ``Mad Man in
Waco,'' the title based on a song penned by Koresh about onetime
rival George Roden.
</P>
<P>
   Darden recently took a group in town for an academic freedom
conference on a tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some, it's like people who slow down at a car crash,''
Darden said. ``They just want to see where it happened. For most,
it's an historic site. They get their picture taken on Koresh's
motorcycle. They look on the ground for expended shells or broken
glass. Others get real quiet and are careful where they step. The
Bible talks about the ground crying out, and some people seem to
actually feel that. They feel a real sense of depression because of
the loss of life there.''
</P>
<P>
   `IT'S NOT A PLACE OF REST'
</P>
<P>
   Darden said he's never felt comfortable at Mount Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love going to cemeteries,'' Darden said. ``They're very
peaceful to me. I don't feel that at Mount Carmel. It's not a place
of rest. I'm not a mystic, just an old East Texas boy. But I don't
feel a sense of peace there.''
</P>
<P>
   Echoes of rumbling tanks and gunshots and screams are fading,
though, helped by a new church visible through a field of 76 young
crape myrtles _ planted to commemorate the Davidians who died on
the final day of the siege _ that speaks more about hope than death
and destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's somewhat of a statement on the part of those who
volunteered to build it,'' said Davidian Clive Doyle, who lost his
daughter, Shari, in the Mount Carmel fire he survived. ``It is
somewhat of a statement on our part, too, that we're still around.
We are still an entity. It is not just an abandoned piece of
property.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Argo of Austin last week began painting the inside of the
church, which won't be finished by its dedication on Wednesday. He
was decked out in white from his overalls to his hair and beard.
Argo volunteered his services after hearing about the
church-raising from Alex Jones, the libertarian radio host in
Austin who has spearheaded the project since last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Argo looked shocked when asked why he had come.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is it Wilford Brimley says? 'Because it was the right
thing to do,''' Argo said. ``Maybe I'm weird. There are so many
people willing to donate their time and money to build the church
that I don't believe we're all eccentric. There was an injustice
done here. This is our way of undoing some of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeing Mount Carmel for the first time didn't initially produce
any emotional reaction, Argo said, adding that he's seen too many
``battlefields'' in America where authorities clashed with
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just another place,'' Argo said. ``It just happens to
be the most recent place.''
</P>
<P>
   His first night camping out at Mount Carmel was eerie, however,
Argo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sleeping in a tent by the pond,'' Argo said. ``The
coyotes were doing their coyote thing. I was listening to them,
looking out over the pond when, I swear, the coyotes sounded like
children crying. That got to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Argo and an Oklahoma City man, who would identify himself only
as Glen, were the only people at Mount Carmel on a wet and windy
April morning. Two more men later joined them. All of them, thrown
together, affably worked out details of a supply run to Lowe's,
where an account has been set up to buy materials and supplies for
the church.
</P>
<P>
   Glen said he was going to stay for a week before returning home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really know anything about these people, but what the
government did to them was wrong,'' he said. ``There was a better
way to bring them out. The government initiated all this.''
</P>
<P>
   He's found the atmosphere pleasant at Mount Carmel, despite its
troubled history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just had a good feeling about this place,'' Glen said.
``Maybe it's the people I met. They're good people, the type you'd
want as neighbors. If someone needs help, they're there.''
</P>
<P>
   VISITORS BY THE BUSLOAD
</P>
<P>
   Clive Doyle and his mother, Edna, are back at Mount Carmel. They
live in a mobile home near the entrance. There has been talk of
rebuilding Mount Carmel to resemble the huge, four-story structure
thents might be tempted to scold them and take the toy away.
Parents who instead reach into the problem-solving toolboxes to
accomplish their long-term goal of teaching their kids conflict
resolution, might acknowledge the children's feelings, state the
rule about property rights, put the ball in their court and see
what happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we intervene, we want to teach these skills, so we can
eventually get to the point of saying, `Gee, I bet if you two put
your heads together you can come up with a plan that is respectful
and fair to both of you,' and they will,'' she says in the book.
</P>
<P>
   But that's easier said than done, Corley said. She said she is
often tempted to react emotionally when her children fight. But she
usually lets them work it out themselves first, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``With five children, when they fuss and fight, very often
there's no way we can be there and know the exact situation,'' she
said. ``More times than not, it's not one person's fault. When the
problem escalates to the point that they need mom or dad, usually
both of them are in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilder said she agrees with Pawel that balance and consistency
are important to effective parenting. But, Wilder said, going with
gut reactions probably won't have any long-term consequences to
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most of us as parents have to make fast decisions,''
Wilder said. ``We all will sometimes respond out of our gut
reaction. What we don't want is to respond in a childlike way.
Respond the way you'd handle it with another adult.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilder said she thinks most parents have long-term goals in
mind, such as helping their children be self-disciplined, motivated
and with good self-esteem. She advises parents to think of such
long-term goals when they rear their children, as long as they
don't get weighted down with the stress of achieving those goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``My experience is that every parent has those in mind from the
minute they know they're gonna be parents,'' she said. ``Then they
start worrying when they're young that the child is not going to
reach those goals because they don't have a history of watching
children grow up and seeing how children change. I see parents
carry this burden, and some become burdened by the responsibility
they feel for preparing the children for life, so they worry a lot
and don't trust themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Alicia Shamblin of Hewitt says she and her husband, Kirk, have
received so much advice since their daughter Isabel was born 16
weeks ago, that they are refusing to listen to any more for fear
they will start to think of parenting as a burden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten advice as far as when to feed the baby, when to
introduce solids, if I should breast feed; we've been told not to
pick her up when she cries, not to buy any newborn-to-3-month
clothes,'' Alicia Shamblin said. ``I really haven't taken much of
that advice mostly because we're going on our own instincts. I
guess I have what I feel like are maternal instincts, and the
15-and-a-half weeks I've had, I feel like I've done a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she wouldn't want to follow a universal blueprint for
parenting because she wants to develop her own parenting style.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you have a good balance of love, discipline and
values, you need to have a mixture there. I think we'll do OK,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Wilder said no amount of parental instruction compares to
parents' instincts about their own children. She, too, is a mother.
Her oldest son was born the same month she graduated with a degree
in child development 26 years ago. She said none of her instruction
prepared her enough for being a mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think parents know much more about their child than anyone
else,'' she said. ``As professionals, we must respect the parent's
understanding of their child.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Pawel says her program is easily adaptable to all
families.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a universal plan, but it can be applied in an
individual way,'' she said. ``I can only go so far in print. It's
only a formula because it's easier to learn that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Johnston, executive director of the Plano-based
instruction course Practical Parent Education, encourages parents
to explore different parenting advice but ultimately to come up
with a plan of their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my experience working with families, I find that most of
them want the same thing for their children, but they will take
different road maps to get there,'' she said. ``We might all want
to go to New York, but there are different ways to get to New York.
It's the same with children. If you have the same goals, there are
different ways to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
