<HEADER>
A7894 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-SWIMSUIT16-COX     04-15 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWIMSUIT16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Get ready for the summer games: Swimsuit shopping
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In this Olympic year, we need suits that
go the distance. Gold, silver, bronze. Red, white and blue. Neons,
florals, racing stripes ...
</P>
<P>
   Olympic swimmers, divers, water polo players and synchronized
swimmers don't have much say about
</P>
<P>
   what they wear to the pool. Their primary considerations are
patriotic and athletic, but those aren't taken lightly. (Among
sprinters and distance swimmers, there's currently a controversy
brewing over the use of neck-to-ankle suits _ a look that is no
doubt as hard to tug on as it is to pull off.)
</P>
<P>
   We non-Olympians, free from all governing bodies but our own,
can choose from a spectrum of colors and a whole closetful of cuts
this summer. Lime greens and hot pinks hang from store racks, but
so do slimming black and fun tropical prints. Some suits are sliced
up to there, but just as many hit mid-thigh.
</P>
<P>
   And if you're really looking for coverage, tie on a filmy sarong
_ a flattering alternative to wrapping yourself in the flag.
(Particularly since our flag has horizontal stripes.)
</P>
<P>
   TAKE A BREATHER
</P>
<P>
   Diving requires concentration of Olympic proportions. Just ask
Greg Louganis. The legendary diver blamed jet lag after he thwacked
his head on a diving platform in a 1979 contest. Nine years later
at the Seoul Games, Louganis' head met springboard during the
prelims. His scalp was patched together with temporary sutures,
enabling him to qualify. After a good night's sleep, he medaled
easily, becoming only the second athlete to win double diving golds
in two Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   STRETCH!
</P>
<P>
   Remember what your mother told you: Wait half an hour after
eating before jumping back in the pool. And if you're swimming
laps, by all means stretch. Alfred Hajos almost certainly did. The
19-year-old Hungarian won the 1200-meter freestyle at the first
modern Olympic Games in Athens in 1896. The contest began with a
boat dropping the competitors into the chilly waters of the
Mediterranean. Hajos was the first swimmer to reach shore. Said he:
``My will to live completely overcame my desire to win.''
</P>
<P>
   PLAY WELL WITH OTHERS
</P>
<P>
   Along with the requisite nose clip, synchronized swimmers rely
on waterproof hair gel, themed swimsuits and underwater speakers to
practice their sport, which made its Olympic debut in 1984. The
nose clip prevents a nasal cavity full of water during upside-down
movements, and some synchro swimmers even tuck a spare clip into
their suits. The gel creates a unified look regardless of team
members' hair cuts and colors and, frankly, it just looks a whole
lot better than matching swim caps or hair nets.
</P>
<P>
   PERFECT YOUR TIMING
</P>
<P>
   In case you can't get enough of athletes performing in unison
during the synchronized swimming competitions,
</P>
<P>
   set your VCR for another event, new to
</P>
<P>
   the Olympics this summer: Synchronized diving. That's right _
two men or two women diving in unison from either the 10-meter
platform or 3-meter springboard. Judges will score teams according
to individual dives as well as the amount of synchronization.
Olympians have plenty of maneuvers to choose from: 345 dive
variations exist between springboard and platform.
</P>
<P>
   PROTECT YOURSELF FROM THE ELEMENTS
</P>
<P>
   Water polo is no day at the beach. The aquatic equivalent of
rugby, water polo attracts the hardiest of Olympians. Over
</P>
<P>
   four quarters of seven minutes each, players cannot touch the
bottom or the sides of the pool. And physical contact is the rule,
not the exception. Fouls that result in a player being temporarily
sidelined include kicking and striking; deliberate face-splashing;
and holding, sinking or pulling back an opponent not holding the
ball. No wonder most players opt for swim caps fitted with ear
protectors.
</P>
<P>
   SIZE UP YOUR COMPETITION
</P>
<P>
   Who looks good to gold in Sydney? It depends on who you ask, of
course, but here are some of the favorites ... Just last week, the
Russian team floated to the top in the synchronized swimming
trials. The Europeans have always dominated men's water polo, and
six teams will compete for the first women's gold. The United
States has typically placed well in swimming and in diving. Since
diving became an Olympic sport, the Americans have captured 46 out
of 75 golds, and 125 of 225 total medals. Get ready to hear ``The
Star-Spangled Banner.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
