<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7895 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-DAVIDIANS-MEMORIAL16-     04-15 0407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVIDIANS-MEMORIAL16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Service to mark new church, honor 76 Davidians who died
 &HT;    By Mark England and Tommy Witherspoon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The church that volunteers are building for
surviving Branch Davidians will be dedicated Wednesday during a
memorial service on the anniversary of the fire that destroyed
Mount Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   It will mark the seventh year that a service has been held to
honor the 76 Davidians, including their leader, David Koresh, who
died on April 19, 1993, at the end of a 51-day siege.
</P>
<P>
   Names of the victims will be read and a bell sounded afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The list of speakers is still up in the air, according to
Davidian Clive Doyle. It will include Ramsey Clark, the former U.S.
attorney general helping represent the plaintiffs in the upcoming
wrongful-death lawsuit filed against the government by surviving
Davidians. Alex Jones, the Austin radio host who launched the
volunteer effort to build the church at Mount Carmel, also will
speak.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle said more than 200 people are expected to attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the volunteers want to see it, and the people who
have put (money) into it,'' Doyle said. ``But you have to consider
that it's on a weekday, and a lot of people will be at work.''
</P>
<P>
   Doyle said the Davidians still in prison on manslaughter and
weapons convictions will be foremost in his thoughts at the
service. The U.S. Supreme Court will hear their appeal April 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``An ongoing sore point with all of us are those guys in
prison,'' Doyle said. ``It is just not about us. It's not just
about building a building. We are trying to get the truth out about
what happened and what is still happening. The fact that we built
the church is an optical reminder that we still exist. They didn't
get rid of us all. Perhaps they wished they had.''
</P>
<P>
   Workers began painting the inside of the new church last week.
It probably won't be completed in time for its dedication, with
plumbing and electrical work remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The keys to the building, however, will be given to the
Davidians on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A supporter also will give church members a flag she's made
bearing the image of a winged serpent, Doyle said. A lingering
image for many is a similar Davidian flag, seared by the fire
devouring Mount Carmel, flying about madly and then diving into the
flames.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
