<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7898 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-CULTURE-WARS-2     04-15 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-CULTURE-WARS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE LOOMS WHEN SUPREME COURT HEARS PLEA OF BOY SCOUTS TO BAR
GAYS  
 BY LINDA GREENHOUSE  
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For anyone wanting a front-row seat at the next
battle in the culture wars, the place to be is the Supreme Court
later this month when the justices hear the case of Boy Scouts of
America vs. James Dale.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the Boy Scouts nor Dale, an Eagle scout and former
assistant scoutmaster whom the Scouts expelled after learning from
a newspaper article that he was gay, come into court alone.
</P>
<P>
   The case has galvanized the religious right, on the Boy Scouts'
side, and organizations like the American Bar Association and the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People on
Dale's. Religions have been split by the case: Orthodox Jewish
groups for the Scouts, Reform Judaism for Dale; the United
Methodist Church for Dale, a dissident group of Methodists for the
Boy Scouts.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of organizations, including medical and education
professionals, bar groups and state and local officials, have filed
briefs. The dispute _ for the weight of its competing arguments,
the doctrinal challenge it presents for the court and its overall
cultural resonance _ is plausibly the most compelling case on a
docket already weighty with potential landmark rulings.
</P>
<P>
   The Boy Scouts are appealing a decision last August by the New
Jersey Supreme Court that Dale's expulsion from the troop he had
served with distinction for half his life violated New Jersey's
anti-discrimination law. The 5 million-member organization argues
that what is at stake is the freedom of a private, voluntary
organization to ``create and interpret its own moral code'' _ in
this instance, by excluding avowed homosexuals _ and that without
such freedom, ``American society would be fundamentally
transformed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A society in which each and every organization must be equally
diverse is a society which has destroyed diversity,'' the Boy
Scouts assert in their brief, warning that the logical result of
the New Jersey court's ruling would be for a Croatian cultural
society to have to admit Serbs or for a gay rights group to be
unable to exclude a biblical fundamentalist. The argument is based
on the First Amendment right to freedom of association and its
corollary, the freedom to not associate.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court has agreed with the kind of arguments the Boy
Scouts are making _ sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   Dale and his lawyers at the Lambda Legal Defense and Education
Fund are arguing that freedom of association has never been
regarded as an absolute free-floating right, but rather as a right
to associate for a purpose, to advance a cause or belief. Even
assuming that people have a right to come together for the purpose
of opposing homosexuality, his brief says, that is not a
description of the Boy Scouts.
</P>
<P>
   The common interests that bring its millions of members together
``are not about homosexuality or sexual orientation,'' Dale says.
Consequently, he argues, New Jersey's ``vital government
interests'' in prohibiting discrimination outweigh any incidental
burden on the expressive interests of a major civic organization
that is chartered by Congress and stitched tightly to government at
all levels.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court has agreed with the kind of argument Dale is
making _ sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an undeniable, inevitable tension between the right
of a private group to define who it wants as members, and the right
of the state to prevent invidious discrimination,'' David D. Cole,
a professor at Georgetown University Law Center, who filed a brief
on Dale's behalf, said in an interview the other day. ``There is no
easy answer.''
</P>
<P>
   With no clear way to resolve the tension, Cole said, the Supreme
Court has dealt with it by establishing two categories of cases: On
the one hand, the court has rejected efforts by government to limit
what a private group can say, or to force a private group to yield
control over its message. This category was exemplified by a 1995
decision holding that the organizers of the Boston St. Patrick's
Day parade, the South Boston Allied War Veterans Council, could not
be required, despite a state anti-discrimination law, to accept the
participation of a group whose members wanted to march under a
banner of gay pride.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Cole said, the court has held that exclusion
from an organization based simply on someone's group status or
identity, is not constitutionally protected. In a trilogy of cases
in the mid-1980s, the court rejected claims by all-male
organizations, including the Jaycees and the Rotary Club, to a
First Amendment right to continue excluding women.
</P>
<P>
   In all these cases, the St. Patrick's Day parade case as well as
the all-male club trilogy, the justices were unanimous, in outcome
although not necessarily in their reasoning. Unanimity on such
touchy issues is ``remarkable,'' Cole said, reflecting the court's
success in placing the cases in one analytical box or the other and
thereby avoiding the struggle of reconciling the tensions inherent
in each case.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, the court found that the clubs existed for a
commercial purpose and that the exclusion of women was not part of
their self-described mission.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, each side in the current case, Boy Scouts vs.
Dale, No. 99-699, to be argued on April 26, invokes the precedent
that supports its desired outcome. The Boy Scouts assert that the
case is controlled by the St. Patrick's Day parade case, Hurley vs.
Gay, Lesbian &AMP; Bisexual Group of Boston (GLIB). ``By donning the
uniform of an adult leader in scouting,'' the Boy Scouts' brief
says, Dale would ``celebrate his identity as an openly gay scout
leader in precisely the same way that the GLIB marchers wished to
conscript the parade to celebrate their identity'' and to claim
social acceptance within the Irish community.
</P>
<P>
   Dale asserts that the trio of all-male club cases, beginning
with Roberts vs. U.S. Jaycees in 1984, governs his case; just as
the clubs could not keep out women simply for being female, without
regard to any views they might hold on the clubs' mission, they
cannot exclude him simply upon learning his identity as a gay man.
The New Jersey Supreme Court found that under the state's Law
Against Discrimination the Boy Scouts were a ``public
accommodation'' to which the law could properly be applied.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure of Dale's sexuality was not connected to his Boy
Scout activities, but rather came in a newspaper article about a
gay students' group in which he was active at Rutgers University,
where he was an undergraduate. Within days after the article, with
his picture, appeared in The Star-Ledger of Newark, the Monmouth
Council of the Boy Scouts revoked his membership in Troop 73,
telling him that it was Boy Scout policy to ``specifically forbid
membership to homosexuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the dueling precedents, the fate of the case may well turn
on whether the court sees a statement of gay identity as an
inherently expressive act, one that conveys a message beyond a
simple self-description. The Boy Scouts, looking to place Dale in
the position of the would-be St. Patrick's Day parade's marchers,
assert that being openly gay conveys not only an identity but a
built-in message of disaffection with the ``scouting values'' that
a troop leader is supposed to transmit.
</P>
<P>
   Dale, on the other hand, asserts that ``learning that someone is
gay tells you nothing about his or her political party, religious
beliefs, lifestyle, or moral code'' and that consequently his
exclusion amounted to the same discrimination based on status that
the court rejected in the all-male club cases. If reinstated, his
brief says, ``Dale is prepared to be bound by the same directives
and limitations placed on all scoutmasters.''
</P>
<P>
   Underneath the legal arguments is the fact that the case
concerns not just any mass-membership organization, not a
businessmen's dinner club, but the Boy Scouts _ described by Lord
Robert Baden-Powell, who founded the organization in England in
1907 as a ``character-factory.'' What impact will that have on the
justices?
</P>
<P>
   Both sides strive for the high ground. ``In an age when we laugh
and mock what we used to honor and venerate,'' the Family Research
Council, a conservative Christian organization, says in its brief,
``the Boy Scouts of America stands against a cultural tide'' and
should not be ``sacrificed on the altar of a civil right that
belies its name.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the American Public Health Association tells
the court that Boy Scouts' ``central role in so many communities''
makes it all the more important to make sure the organization does
not rely on ``discredited myths and stereotypes to justify
excluding gay scouts simply because of their status.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-15-00 1422EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000415.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 14:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7900 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TRADE-PROTEST-ART-NYT     04-15 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADE-PROTEST-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE SHUT DOWN HEADQUARTERS OF TRADE PROTESTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Skedded earlier as TRADE-PROTEST-VOICES) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT6 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As thousands of protesters determined to stop the
World Bank meeting poured into Washington on Saturday morning, the
police shut down the demonstration's headquarters in a sudden
pre-emptive strike.
</P>
<P>
   Contending that the ramshackle warren of warehouse space known
as the ``convergence center'' was a fire hazard, the police evicted
more than 200 protesters shortly before 9 a.m. and sealed it off
indefinitely. The space was the nerve center for demonstrations
planned for Sunday and Monday as a repeat of the chaotic Seattle
protests against the World Trade Organization in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fire marshals were concerned about the safety and
well-being of the people who are staying at that location,'' a
straight-faced Chief Charles H. Ramsey of the Metropolitan Police
Department told reporters at his post by the barricades around the
World Bank. ``It's a safety issue. We're concerned about the safety
of all people who come to D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   Under an umbrella organization called Mobilization for Global
Justice, adherents of a number of causes plan two days of
demonstrations here against the annual spring meeting of the World
Bank and International Monetary Fund, beginning on Sunday. The
protesters contend that globalization and the financial
institutions' development policies are destroying the environment
and hurting poor people in the third world.
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected shutdown of their headquarters threw their plans
in doubt, although many of the demonstrators were expecting to act
on their own in small groups.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the protesters have vowed to block finance ministers and
other delegates from around the world from attending the meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Striking in small, close-knit bands of five to 20 people called
``affinity groups,'' the protesters _ some of whom have been
training for months _ hope to close down the streets around the
global economic power's headquarters. A solid block along H Street
is already lined with television satellite broadcasting trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The finance ministers and international bureaucrats who shape
the world economy to make the rich richer and the poor poorer need
to know that Seattle was not just a bump on their road to global
domination,'' the mobilization declared on its Web site, one of the
demonstrators' primary organizing tools.
</P>
<P>
   But the protesters will be facing an armada of at least 1,500
police officers from a half dozen city and federal agencies
determined to prevent any repeat of Seattle's chaos.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Park Police, which patrols much of the federal land
here, has carried out training drills with its mounted units and
SWAT teams, said Sgt. Rob MacLean, who added, ``If a situation
occurs like the one in Seattle, we'll be prepared.'' Two fire
marshals, accompanied by two Metropolitan Police officers who said
they were with the Nuisance Abatement Task Force, appeared shortly
after 8:30 a.m. at the headquarters, where protesters had been
holding workshops in nonviolent tactics and making other
preparations. The officials said they were checking for possible
fire hazards.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, the area was sealed off by the officers of the
elite police Emergency Response Team. Shouting demonstrators
clutching their sleeping bags and backpacks were being escorted to
the streets, and ranking officers appeared to brief the media.
</P>
<P>
   Executive Assistant Chief Terrance W. Gainer told reporters that
the fire marshals had found ``numerous'' violations, including
clogged stairwells, propane cooking stoves and jury-rigged
electrical wiring.
</P>
<P>
   He denied that the shutdown was a tactical maneuver, saying,
``No, the real purpose was that these kids don't burn themselves up
in a fire.''
</P>
<P>
   The protesters, clustered outside the police lines, differed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This just indicates how the police are in league with corrupt
governments, the IMF and the World Bank,'' said Han Shan, a member
of the mobilization, calling the talk of possible conflagration
``spurious.''
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of mostly youthful demonstrators wandered the city's
streets this morning, many of them having organized protest groups
at their colleges in recent weeks. Gretchen Holzheimer, 20, a
junior at Hobart and Willam Smith Colleges in Geneva, N.Y., came
with three cars full of friends on Friday night. ``We're all in
agreement that there are definitely issues that have to be dealt
with about the WTO, but we're not all in agreement on just what
those issues are,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At the IMF, police cars with lights and sirens escorted shuttle
buses full of perplexed-looking bankers through the barricades that
had been erected along Pennsylvania Avenue. Even the man delivering
a hand-truck full of pink Financial Times' had to clear security
before he was allowed past the barricades.
</P>
<P>
   The headquarters for the protesters was a set of old warehouses
down an alley in the Columbia Heights neighborhood. In one corner
of the alley on Friday, young mechanics worked on donated bicycles
to be used by couriers during the demonstrations. Early arrivals
diligently painted banners, while another group practiced with
giant puppets dressed in bankers' suits, representing their
targets. To the beat of drums and muffled giggles, the
banker-puppets high-fived one another.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other puppets being assembled was a ``structural
adjustment mechanism,'' a reference to the strict budgetary
limitations the World Bank imposes to bail out troubled third world
economies. Reflecting the protesters' point of view, the
contraption has giant jaws that chew up forests.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere was earnest _ lectures on a ``doomsday economy''
abounded _ and so determinedly democratic that protesters insisted
that no one was in charge. Decisions were reached by consensus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we are organizing is creating the world we want to
live in,'' Patrick Reinsborough, one of the activists, said.
``There are no leaders, no hierarchy.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an eclectic gathering. There was Russ Davis, a
43-year-old unemployed electrical worker, who said he was laid off
in August when General Electric cut its work force in Lynn, Mass.,
to 2,000 from 9,000 and moved many of the jobs to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   There was a guerrilla gardener clutching a sprig of rosemary,
who gave his name as Sasha Scatter and who grew up in Manhattan and
was among the squatters in Tompkins Square Park in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The police have been no less diligent in their preparations.
Earlier in the week, the police intelligence unit and other
officers arrested seven people a few blocks from the convergence
center and charged them with conspiracy and ``possessing implements
of crime.''
</P>
<P>
   The material seized by the police included 256 PVC pipes, 45
smaller pipes, two rolls of chicken wire, 50 rolls of duct tape,
gas masks, bolt cutters, heavy chains, an electrical saw and
locking devices used to link people together.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are instruments that are commonly used by demonstrators
to connect themselves to different objects, to hook themselves to
one another, to block traffic, to cause other kinds of disruptions,
and we were able to intercept a lot of the material,'' Ramsey told
reporters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-15-00 1430EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000415.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7901 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-CUBAN-BOY-530&AMP;AD     04-15 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CUBAN-BOY-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE'S PUZZLING MOVE TO TAKE BOY'S UNEXTENDED HAND 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Everything was humming along fine for Vice
President Al Gore, until little Elian Gonzalez strayed into the
picture.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president was making a seamless transition from a
successful primary season. He had vanquished former Sen. Bill
Bradley and begun a highly competitive general election campaign by
catching and even surpassing Gov. George W. Bush, the presumptive
Republican nominee, in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   But on March 30, prompted by no one, Gore thrust himself into
one of the most emotionally and politically charged cases in the
country. After months of saying that the fate of 6-year-old Elian
should be decided in the courts, Gore said the boy should be
granted permanent residency status.
</P>
<P>
   There was a fierce backlash, not because Gore seemed to
contradict himself _ he had spoken earlier in such code that it was
hard to discern what he believed. The concern was rather that he
had chosen a highly volatile moment in the case to break openly
with the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   And a number of Democrats simply disagreed with his position. He
appeared to be saying that because of Fidel Castro's dictatorship
in Cuba, the Cuban boy should not be returned to his father.
</P>
<P>
   Because his statement seemed so unnecessary, a number of people
in his own party denounced Gore as pandering to Miami's politically
potent Cuban-Americans in an overt play for Florida's 25 electoral
votes. To black lawmakers, it looked like favoritism over
foreigners who sought to enter the United States from poor
countries such as Haiti and the Dominican Republic but did not have
the power to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's involvement in the Elian case quickly ballooned into a
political crisis. Whether it will change votes in November is
probably unknowable; Gore advisers insist it will be a wash.
``There has been no erosion in the polls because of Elian,'' a top
Gore official said.
</P>
<P>
   Most Gore backers insist that the Elian case is just a bump in
the road to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is going to be voting on Elian in November,'' said
Edward G. Rendell, chairman of the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's move seemed damaging in a fundamental way. It
reinforced his biggest weakness _ the perception that he is a
calculating opportunist, not a man of principle.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Hart, a Democratic pollster not connected to the campaign,
gives Gore credit for achieving some milestones _ recharging his
campaign last fall and emerging from the primaries with his party
intact. But, Hart said, the Elian case provided an unfortunate
reminder that Gore is ``always trying to pounce on the issue of the
hour.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People see a pattern of pragmatism rather than a pattern of
conviction,'' Hart said.
</P>
<P>
   The Elian case highlighted another potential weakness in the
Gore candidacy. Rather than rally members of his party behind his
view, the vice president alienated them. The Elian statement came
on the heels of another declaration, on campaign-finance reform,
that was swiftly faulted as unworkable and that failed to stir a
following within his party. Together, the two statements raised
questions among some on Capitol Hill about Gore's ability to lead.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Elian case also showed the Gore campaign suddenly losing its
footing. It was exactly the kind of situation that Gore, through
strict discipline and message control, had meticulously avoided, at
least since January, when he suggested and then retreated from the
idea that he would ensure that his appointees to the Joint Chiefs
of Staff would favor allowing gays to serve openly in the military.
</P>
<P>
   In an instant, the vice president, by his moves in the Elian
case, seemed to undo much of the progress that he had made since
the fall.
</P>
<P>
   His subsequent backing and filling only made the situation
worse, and Gore appeared weakened in at least one opinion poll.
Some of his top staff, including Tony Coelho, his campaign
chairman, and Monica Dixon, his deputy chief of staff, have been
trying to mend fences with angry Democrats, particularly blacks,
who had been among Gore's staunchest supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Some advisers said they had not been widely consulted, and the
spin that emerged was this: Gore was just being consistent, true to
his passions (a word they like because it conveys something that
voters think he lacks) and to his somewhat hawkish views on foreign
policy, which are generally to the right of the center of his
party.
</P>
<P>
   All of this culminated in the vice president's decision to forgo
a news conference planned for Thursday, as a human chain circled
Elian's house in Miami and the Justice Department negotiated with
his relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's last news conference was on Feb. 19. His advisers said
that the risks of being pressed about Elian now and further
stirring the pot outweighed the advantages of capitulating to the
news media. ``Things were moving too fast,'' one said of the
negotiations. ``We couldn't assure him of any stability.''
</P>
<P>
   But the lingering problem is this: The Elian case underscored
the central challenge that the campaign had already pinpointed,
that Gore needs to counter the perception that he is more
preoccupied with tactics than with principle.
</P>
<P>
   Gore backers do not deny a connection between Gore's
vulnerabilities and the campaign's long-term task _ to rid Gore of
his calculating air.
</P>
<P>
   The real worry in the campaign is that episodes like this cannot
be predicted, only managed after the fact. ``Both campaigns are
going into this with set pieces,'' said one Democratic strategist.
``It's these other wild cards, these pop quizzes, that always get
you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
