<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7902 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-ELIAN-CUBA-2TAKES-HNS     04-15 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-CUBA-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF ELIAN RETURNS TO HIS HOMETOWN, HE'LL FIND LIFE LARGELY UNCHANGED
FROM WHEN HE LEFT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Optional ending included) 
 
By DUDLEY ALTHAUS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARDENAS, Cuba _ If and when Elian Gonzalez returns with his
father from Miami, he likely will come home to this tattered city,
a place straining with unrealized potential and struggling toward
wherever Cuban society may be headed.
</P>
<P>
   Elian, 6, would come back to a country still ruled by a
communist regime that is reviled by Cuban exiles and revered by
many Cubans still on the island.
</P>
<P>
   He would grow up in a society untouched by most of the changes
that have swept the globe in recent decades, in a threadbare
socialist economy still struggling for a return in a free-market
world.
</P>
<P>
   But most important, many here say, Elian would come home to his
own family. He would come back to where he belongs.
</P>
<P>
   ``His life will be much the same as it was before,'' says Fidel
Ramirez, 32, a co-worker and childhood friend of Elian's father,
Juan Miguel Gonzalez, whose own children sometimes play with Elian.
``And Elian lived very well here.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Cardenas is among Cuba's better communities, the city
could also be ranked among its most dissatisfied. Many of the
Cubans leaving the island in small boats to Florida depart from the
mangrove swamps near here. The Gulf Stream sweeps past the island
just a few miles offshore, washing everything in it north toward
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, Elian, his mother and 12 other people from
Cardenas boarded a patch-wood boat with a bad motor in a bid for
the U.S. coast. The boat sank off South Florida. Only Elian and two
others survived.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Cuban demands for his return and the U.S. government's
efforts to comply, Elian remains in Miami, where he is staying with
his great-uncle and his family.
</P>
<P>
   Once Elian returns home, some here say, he will come back a
newly minted hero of Fidel Castro's revolution, which has ruled the
island since 1959.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to be privileged in this country,'' says Raimundo
Garcia, a Protestant minister who heads a foreign-funded foundation
in Cardenas that teaches democracy and economic development. ``If
he needs a house, he's going to get a house. If he needs food,
he'll get food. If he needs psychiatric care, he'll have it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The family (of Elian) here is going to have all sorts of
support.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, few in Cardenas, a city of 100,000 people about 90 miles
east of Havana, doubt that Elian would enjoy more material comforts
in Miami. Television images from there and years of visits and cash
gifts from relatives now living in the United States have left
little doubt here that Miami means money.
</P>
<P>
   But many people here argue that wealth isn't everything. And
their views seem guided as much by common sense as communist
sensibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``A child needs to have discipline,'' says Ramirez, the Gonzalez
family friend who is a staunch member of the Communist Party. ``It
is not good to give children everything they want, to teach
children they can have anything.''
</P>
<P>
   While most Cubans are poor, the country offers its children many
advantages. The government makes certain that every child has
enough to eat. Education is free, and university study is
encouraged. Sports are pervasive. Health care is universal.
</P>
<P>
   And, people will tell you, unlike those in Haiti, Mexico or
other Latin American countries, no Cuban child sleeps in the
streets.
</P>
<P>
   People say they know this because they see no children in the
streets. They also know it because the government reminds them of
it.
</P>
<P>
   While no one may be starving in Cuba, few are doing better than
getting by. A revolutionary society that once boasted that it was
showing poor countries the way to a better world now brags about
simply holding its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``The children who are not Elian, what are we going to do for
them?'' asks Garcia, the minister.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a few late-model cars navigating the streets and the
young men and women strolling the sidewalks in Lycra and shirts
emblazoned with U.S. sports teams logos, Cardenas seems caught in a
time warp.
</P>
<P>
   As across Cuba, many of the city's buildings have been in slow
decay since the 1959 revolution, most apparently unpainted for
decades. With buses few and regular taxis expensive, most people
get around either by bicycle or in horse-drawn wagons, creating
silent traffic jams in the streets.
</P>
<P>
   The house where Elian's paternal grandparents live, where by all
accounts the boy has spent much of his young life, sits on a quiet
street a few blocks from a rusting factory that produces syrup, rum
and other sugar products.
</P>
<P>
   Thick, black smoke spews from the factory's high chimney,
drifting over the neighborhood. An odor of burnt sugar hangs in the
air.
</P>
<P>
   Like most everywhere else in Castro's Cuba, the Gonzalezes'
street is racially integrated, with white, black and mixed-race
families living easily next to one other. Neighbors walk into each
other's houses unannounced, share chores, lend a hand when people
are sick.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL; 
$$$
</P>
<P>
   The houses are mostly small, some tiny, with large families
often sharing just a few rooms. But there is running water and
sewers, and every house seems to have a television.
</P>
<P>
   Trash clogs the vacant lot a few doors down from Elian's
grandparents' house, but their street is paved. Those a few blocks
away are not. Even a brief spring downpour floods a few of the
neighborhood streets.
</P>
<P>
   Young children are everywhere, playing stick ball or soccer in
the streets and riding bikes.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the men who live in the Gonzalezes' neighborhood work at
the sugar plant or at the city's docks, also a few blocks away.
Others labor at a nearby oil refinery or at a factory in the city
that makes building supplies.
</P>
<P>
   But the luckiest _ perhaps as many as 7,000 people in Cardenas _
have landed jobs in the hotels, restaurants and tourist traps of
Varadero, the nearby beach resort where the currency is the U.S.
dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's mother, Elizabet Broton, worked as maid in a Varadero
hotel. His father mans a gate and works at a snack bar at a
tree-shaded theme park, a place where tourists eat in ethnic
restaurants, drink rum concoctions and watch ducks and geese frolic
in man-made ponds.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez and other park employees earn $60 a month or more in
tips, the workers say. Some Varadero jobs, such as waiter or
bartender in a big hotel, can bring tips of $300 or more a month, a
fortune in a country where the top official wage, earned by
physicians and other professionals, stands at just $30.
</P>
<P>
   The tourism jobs go to Communist Party members such as Gonzalez
or those with family connections. For everyone else, there are
regular jobs at Cuban pay. And many Cubans increasingly want no
part of those.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of idle young men fill the streets of Cardenas at
midmorning each weekday, standing on corners or sitting listlessly
in doorways and on curbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who live here don't want to work in anything that isn't
attached to tourism,'' says Garcia, the Protestant minister.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many people have started their own small businesses,
making and selling shoes, clothing and other items or operating
small mechanic's shops.
</P>
<P>
   That initiative, and the many millions of dollars sent back to
Cubans by relatives in the United States, is changing the mentality
here. Castro and his government might still talk of revolutionary
socialism, but many people have left it behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagine that in the future the government is going to have
to make some changes,'' Garcia says, ``because the economy is
changing, and the society is changing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't have to be capitalism,'' he says. ``But it has to
be another type of socialism, more attached to Cuba's reality but
also to the changing world.''
</P>
<P>
   But Elian would still be returning to a communist-run country.
And while the situation perhaps is not as dire here as Miami's
Cuban exiles paints it, this is a society that can still seem
stultifying to the outsider.
</P>
<P>
   Castro and the other heroes of the 1959 revolution still hold a
favored place in popular culture. Billboards and graffiti across
the island extol the sayings of Fidel or thank the late Argentine
revolutionary Ernesto ``Che'' Guevara, an early Castro disciple,
for his ``teachings.''
</P>
<P>
   Defiant slogans are everywhere, tying most everything to the
revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Construction is revolution!'' assure large signs at building
sites. ``We believe in Fidel, the revolution and socialism,''
proclaim others.
</P>
<P>
   While many Cubans, especially the young, have grown increasingly
bored with the struggle, millions more have not.
</P>
<P>
   ``There continues to be a close relationship between the people
and the (Communist) party, of people and the government,'' explains
Garcia, the minister, who says he took part in Castro's rebellion
when he was a teen-ager but broke with the revolution after it
veered to Marxism. ``Despite all the errors and the economic
crisis, the revolution fulfilled a lot of expectations, and people
still feel it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to destroy what we have now,'' Garcia says of
himself and others seeking reforms, ``but to improve on what we
have.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Elian, should he return, like the country's
other schoolchildren, will be drilled in reading, writing and
revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Child, where do you want to live?'' Amelia Cruell, 49, who
lives down the block from the Gonzalezes, asks the 9-year-old
grandson she is raising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cuba!'' responds the boy, Rodolfo Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why, child?'' asks the grandmother. ``This is my fatherland!''
the boy says.
</P>
<P>
   ``And who is Fidel?'' the woman asks, a pleased smile sweeping
her face. ``He is my `comandante!''' Rodolfo answers as if by rote,
his eyes fixed on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see,'' Cruell says, turning to a visitor. ``Who says Cuban
children want to leave?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We know Elian is going to return,'' Cruell says, as her
grandson crawls up on her lap. ``Because I trust the law, and I
trust my `comandante.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
