<HEADER>
A7904 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OHIO-MOB-ART-2TAKES(1     04-15 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-MOB-ART-2TAKES(1100)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHTING TO HELP AN OHIO CITY SHED ITS IMAGE AS `CRIMETOWN USA' 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT3 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 BY FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   YOUNGSTOWN, Ohio _ For all the pop culture amusement in ``The
Sopranos,'' ``The Godfather'' and their welter of bang-bang, ha-ha
imitators, James B. Callen is decidedly not amused as he lives here
through the reality as opposed to the entertainment of it all.
</P>
<P>
   Callen, a 54-year-old lawyer, is rounding out two decades of
trying to rouse outrage against this city's endemic bedevilment by
organized crime. But he finds a benumbed citizenry all too casually
expecting another indictment, No. 79 in a series, this time of its
pugnacious and popular congressman, James A. Traficant Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell people it's not a question of personalities; it's a
question of a community, its value structure, its culture,'' said
Callen, the director of Ohio Legal Services. He noted that
Traficant campaigned quite successfully against Democratic primary
challengers last month by positively predicting his own indictment
and portraying himself as the victim of a Justice Department
vendetta against this city and its people.
</P>
<P>
   Traficant's success, in Callen's view, personifies the sorry
tale of Youngstown, where another judge was indicted last week.
</P>
<P>
   Reality is a tired saga here that already includes a prosecutor
gunned down after being deemed unbribable; the racketeering and
murder-conspiracy conviction of Lenine ``Lenny'' Strollo, the local
godfather worthy of central casting; the conviction of Traficant's
late district manager as an admitted bagman for the mob; plus
assorted county commissioners and patronage appointees gone bad,
including a popular mob-busting prosecutor who was indicted on
suspicion of being a secret agent of the mob.
</P>
<P>
   And, most famously, there is the 1983 indictment of Traficant,
who was then county sheriff, after he was recorded accepting
$163,000 in bribes from organized-crime figures. A nonlawyer but a
potent orator, Traficant defended himself in court and was
acquitted as a folk hero who argued that he was secretly running a
sting to target organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   The specter of corrupted officials perennially vowing to root
out corruption in this Mahoning Valley city prompted a bleak
warning in 1997 from Thomas Moyer, the chief justice of the state
Supreme Court: ``The citizens of Mahoning County have reason to
question whether the legal system is working for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The record shows that those who fight corruption put life and
career at risk. Two county building inspectors were turned in two
years ago by their superior, Stephen Berry, and he was soon
targeted in a counterinvestigation. It proved fruitless, but he
lost his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't play ball with these guys and look what happened to
me,'' said Berry, who is suing for civil damages, presenting the
ultimate Youngstown argument that government here amounts to a
criminal enterprise. ``My kids are going to grow up here,'' he
said, articulating the outrage that Callen says is too often
missing in this city's scandal story.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can put a thousand people in jail, but unless we change
the culture in the community, the way we do business, it doesn't
matter,'' said Callen, who began grass-roots organizing 19 years
ago when he found the corruption of local government so pervasive
that it was barely commented on by a passive citizenry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless the community culture changes, this place will be like
`Groundhog Day,' endlessly repeating itself,'' Callen predicted.
The Citizens' League of Greater Youngstown, of which he is a
founder, is a tenacious group that continues to believe that this
dilapidated shell of a once-vital steel-mill city can someday shed
its notoriety as ``Crimetown USA.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been numbed by it all,'' said Bruce J. Beard, a business
executive and a proud native of Youngstown. Like other area
leaders, Beard now grieves for his city from the prosperous ring of
nearby suburbia. But he works to help by bolstering the troubled
Youngstown school system and volunteering through some resilient
church groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember Youngstown as a vibrant city, with an orange crust
in the air from the open-hearth mills,'' Beard said of his youth 40
years ago. ``But it was on the wane even then, and now we have
written it off,'' he said of the city's failure to escape the mob
image and, judging by the evidence of the continuing indictments,
the mob itself.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Callen and other members of the Citizens' League fairly ache at
the gruesome cliche of this city's life imitating gangster
melodrama, down to the spates of car bombings and the car-bombing
jokes that signal the public's impotence. The fact that the only
obvious growth industry is in special federal task force
indictments underlines Youngstown's failure to share in the
suburban economic boom, which leaves it encircled like some
ossified European city-state caught in a time warp.
</P>
<P>
   That Old World image is at the heart of the blunt alarm to the
city that has been delivered lately by Callen and his Citizens'
League colleague Mark T. Shutes, an associate professor of
anthropology at Youngstown State University.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``We support the ones who support our values,'' said Shutes, a
specialist in the cultural ways of anachronistic hamlets in
Ireland, Greece and Italy where the values of organized corruption
in behalf of the powerless evolved as the antidote to despotic
government. He noted that those values were seeded here across a
century of immigration and blue-collar insularity, and when the
steel mills failed and no new opportunity arrived, the old ideas
stayed entrenched as a lucrative monopoly for organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``People here don't trust politicians who don't want to be
brokers for them,'' Shutes said of the waves of reformers who come
and go in this Democratic Party bastion. Some of them are
incrementally successful, he noted, but others are finally
corrupted in a pattern that reinforces the cynicism of the people.
``They expect their politicians to do their dirty work and take
their share in the bargain,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There is no lack of calls for reform in the political arena.
Traficant's chief primary challenger, state Sen. Robert F. Hagan,
made government corruption his main issue and went down fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of dealing with this corruption,'' Hagan told
voters. ``I'm tired of people putting us down. I'm tired of the
media showing up every time there's an indictment, and I think
everyone here should be tired of it too.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Traficant maintains that the Justice Department, smarting from
his earlier acquittal, is on a vindictive ``fishing expedition''
against him. He notes that task force investigators have been
subpoenaing 15 years of his office records with a persistence that
he predicts will find him indicted again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nothing to hide,'' he said during the primary, scrappy
as ever as he contended it was he, not the Justice Department, who
was Youngstown's anti-corruption champion. ``I have done nothing
wrong,'' he declared, complaining that newspaper leaks about the
investigation were efforts to influence the primary, which he won
with 50 percent of the vote in a four-way race.
</P>
<P>
   His critics find that relatively small percentage encouraging.
But Traficant's Republican challenger, Paul Alberty, a computer
consultant, ran against him on the corruption issue in 1998 and
says he learned his lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim Traficant is a daunting figure in Youngstown politics,''
Alberty said. ``This time out I'm emphasizing how the city has not
been a part of the economic recovery going on all around us in
Akron and other booming cities.''
</P>
<P>
   Youngstown has never seemed more jaded, in the view of Ray
Butler, a 50-year-old native who is working for a long-shot victory
by Alberty. ``This city can be humorous, laughable,'' he said.
``But after a while it's got to be seen as pathetic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-15-00 1440EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000415.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7906 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE-TEXAS0416-COX     04-15 1428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-TEXAS0416-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore tries to put Texas on trial
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Fifth-worst poverty rate. Second-worst hunger
problem. Second in the number of children without health insurance.
Forty-fifth in homeownership.
</P>
<P>
   These are the Texas statistics that Vice President Al Gore
trotted out last week when Gov. George W. Bush unveiled health-care
and housing proposals designed to cement his image as a
``compassionate conservative.'' Though not all of Gore's numbers
withstand scrutiny, Texas almost always fares poorly when it is
compared to other states on social services.
</P>
<P>
   ``He keeps saying he's a reformer with results,'' Gore said last
week in a speech to the American Society of Newspaper Editors.
``Where are the results? They're not in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   It's fair to challenge Bush on what he's done to improve health
and housing since he's been governor _ particularly since the state
has enjoyed budget surpluses during his tenure. But taxes,
demographics and even the Lone Star State's frontier past all play
a part in Texas' low rankings. Those factors predate Bush, and
they're likely to persist long after he's gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes from a bootstrap mentality: Unless you're the poorest
of the poor or the sickest of the sick, help is not forthcoming,''
said state Rep. Garnet Coleman, D-Houston, who's been at the
forefront of legislative battles for more social services money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe people should take care of themselves, or the
community should.''
</P>
<P>
   SELF-RELIANCE AND RUGGED INDIVIDUALISM
</P>
<P>
   The other women at the welfare office nod in recognition when
Lisa Anderson lifts up her sleeve to reveal scars from dozens of
blood donations.
</P>
<P>
   Each pin prick was worth $15, a critical supplement to the $168
monthly welfare check Anderson got from the state when her husband
left her and their two children for another woman _ taking the car
and the contents of their bank account with him.
</P>
<P>
   The welfare check, combined with the blood-donation money,
enabled Anderson to cover the camping fees she had to pay for
pitching a tent in a public park. For six months, that tent was
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go to Dollar General, you buy everything on clearance and
you just go without,'' Anderson said of life on the Texas dole.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has increased its monthly welfare benefit since Anderson
relied on it several years ago. But it's still about half the
national average. That fact says a lot about Texas' social services
philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you after answering 12 years of mail that the
people of Texas want people to be self-sufficient if they are at
all capable of doing so,'' said state Sen. Bill Ratliff, R-Mount
Pleasant. As chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, Ratliff
holds the purse strings in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the public looks to us to only provide help to those
who truly can't help themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Many say Texas' approach to social services is connected to its
frontier past, when self-reliance and rugged individualism were
paramount virtues. In his book ``Lone Star,'' regarded as the
definitive history of Texas, T.R. Fehrenbach wrote that the state
carried its frontier ethos into the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texans were decent, Protestant people, but the concept of
public welfare beyond the starvation level violated every ancient
Protestant ethic they possessed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``God helped them who helped themselves. Those who could not
cope deserved second class, or worse, status.''
</P>
<P>
   Unable to subsist solely on state help, Anderson was forced to
find work. She did day labor _ unloading trucks, laying sheetrock,
cleaning work areas, she says _ and trained to become a dental
assistant. She no longer gets a monthly check, although her
children are enrolled in Medicaid and she receives food stamps.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kharfen, a spokesman for the U.S. Department of Health
and Human Services, said ``there are basic questions of
subsistence'' when welfare benefits are as low as they are in
Texas. On the other hand, a low benefit level fulfills a social
purpose, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Work will then pay much more than welfare, and that's a good
thing,'' Kharfen said.
</P>
<P>
   FEWER TAXES, LESS SPENDING
</P>
<P>
   But Texas' low social services spending has as much to do with
fiscal philosophy as it does social philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   State health Commissioner Reyn Archer, a Bush appointee,
admitted as much last week when he was asked why 600,000 Texas
children are eligible for Medicaid but not enrolled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that the Legislature knows that if we are
successful, and we got all those kids registered, they would not
balance their budgets any more,'' Archer told The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Texas is an anti-tax, anti-government spending state _ and it
always has been. It is one of six states without a state income
tax, and its constitution includes a balanced budget requirement, a
specific limit on welfare spending and a cap on the growth rate of
spending from certain taxes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the most recent year for which numbers are available,
Texas ranked 40th in state and local taxes, according to the U.S.
Census Bureau. It ranked 44th when the state's aggregate wealth was
factored in.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Texas ranked last among states in per capita state
spending, according to the Census Bureau. It was among the bottom
five in spending on public health, highways, police protection and
parks. With local spending included in the mix, Texas ranked 44th _
below all of the other states without an income tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have a history of low services, and there's a certain
inertia,'' said Dick Lavine, the tax expert at the Center for
Public Policy Priorities, an Austin-based think thank that supports
more spending on social services. ``Other states have prospered
with higher taxes and higher levels of services.''
</P>
<P>
   When extra money is available _ as it was during the most recent
legislative session _ Texas lawmakers are more apt to return it to
the taxpayers or spend it on education than funnel it to health and
housing programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The legislative pressure was to do a tax cut,'' said Coleman.
``Many times we make the budget fit through health and human
services.''
</P>
<P>
   GORE'S STATISTICS IN QUESTION
</P>
<P>
   So will Gore's rankings hurt Bush politically?
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, being governor of Texas is not the same as being
governor of New Hampshire. Texas faces challenges that most other
states don't. It is diverse, with a rapidly growing population that
includes a large number of immigrants. It must deal with abject
poverty in its border region, and it has vast rural areas that are
difficult and expensive to serve.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Glen Maxey, D-Austin, says attempts to boost social
services money usually meet political resistance because ``it's
always a big number.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even a minor change is a big number when you talk about a
state this big with this much poverty,'' Maxey said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Scott McClellan says Gore is ``attacking and
distorting the governor's record in Texas.'' Many Bush supporters
question the numbers themselves _ particularly because some of the
statistics come from groups with a liberal political agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in public life long enough to know that when someone
quotes statistics such as Texas ranks very low as far as its hunger
rate, I quickly in my own mind think, 'Who the heck determined
that? How does anyone go out and count hungry people?''' Ratliff
said.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say it is possible to measure hunger. But some of the
rankings touted by Gore do seem to be open to manipulation. For
example, he has cited a study that named Texas the ``third-worst
place to raise a child'' _ but what factors should be part of that
ranking?
</P>
<P>
   Some of the numbers, particularly the health-care numbers, are
more difficult to dismiss. As Bush rolls out his presidential
health-care proposals, Gore will continue to accuse the governor of
doing little to improve health care in his own state. In five
years, Bush has given two speeches on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   But as Gore attempts to drag down Bush by touting statistics
that portray Texas as some kind of third-world backwater, he'd be
wise to remember 1992, the last time a governor ran for president.
</P>
<P>
   Because if there's one state that does worse than Texas is the
rankings game, it's Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
