</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-RUNOFF-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUISING RIDE AWAITS TOLEDO IN RUNOFF AGAINST FUJIMORI 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN OTIS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ A glance at Lima's pro-government tabloids last
week offered a glimpse of the bruising free-for-all that awaits
Alejandro Toledo when he tries to unseat President Alberto Fujimori
in a runoff election in a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   One newspaper ran a cartoon depicting Toledo, a former World
Bank economist, covered with snakes. Bold black headlines in
another proclaimed, ``Toledo the Liar.'' And still another claimed
that the former World Bank economist ``wants to send us all to
hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Although several opinion polls indicated that Toledo is running
neck and neck with Fujimori, who is seeking a third straight
five-year term, analysts say that Toledo must brace himself for a
high-octane, dirty-tricks campaign from the man who has built a
political dynasty in Peru.
</P>
<P>
   The challenger, independent election monitors, foreign diplomats
and Peruvian political analysts are all demanding a level playing
field for the runoff.
</P>
<P>
   They are calling on the incumbent to agree to an overhaul of the
nation's election process. But there's not much time. The vote will
be held in late May or early June.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just firing some electoral officials won't be enough,'' said
Eduardo Stein, who heads a team of Organization of American States
electoral observers. ``This requires reconstructive surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, government ombudsman Jorge Santistevan offered a list
of suggestions, ranging from equal TV time for both candidates to a
housecleaning at the much criticized National Electoral Office, the
government agency that oversees the voting and ballot counting.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did it take the election office four days to tabulate
last Sunday's results, critics point out, but several of its
members were implicated in a scheme to falsify more than 1 million
signatures allegedly used to get Fujimori's name on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The electoral office is in ruins,'' said one observer,
sociologist Julio Cotler.
</P>
<P>
   According to ombudsman Santistevan, the runoff ``has to be the
total opposite of what happened during the first round.''
</P>
<P>
   Prior to last Sunday's ballot, opponents and monitors say, the
Fujimori government engineered a partial TV blackout of opposition
candidates, unleashed a smear campaign in the tabloids and
mobilized vast state resources on behalf of the president.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, critics say, it ignored reports by the OAS and
other monitoring groups that a deeply flawed election was being
mounted.
</P>
<P>
   During the past decade, Fujimori, 61, has been called Latin
America's most successful president _ and one of its most
authoritarian.
</P>
<P>
   First elected in 1990, he was credited with defeating the
Shining Path guerrilla movement and engineering an economic
turnaround. Re-elected by a landslide in 1995, he spent much of his
second term concentrating powers in his own hands.
</P>
<P>
   With the approval of the Congress, a rubber-stamp body for the
president, and the courts, Fujimori managed to skirt a
constitutional ban on sitting presidents running for three
consecutive terms.
</P>
<P>
   But in last Sunday's first round, Fujimori failed to win a
majority of the vote. He received 49.84 percent, according to the
official count, compared with Toledo's 40.31 percent. Seven others
divided the rest of the votes.
</P>
<P>
   But Fujimori's people say that while their man did not go over
the top, he remains a formidable candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fantastic and incredible that after 10 years in power,
Fujimori beats the entire opposition with almost 50 percent,'' said
Ricardo Marcenaro, the vice president of the Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo, though, represents the biggest political threat that
Fujimori has ever faced.
</P>
<P>
   The challenger was born into a working-class family 54 years
ago. As a child, he worked as a shoeshine boy to help his family
make ends meet. He did well as a student and eventually won
scholarships to a prestigious high school in Peru, then to Stanford
University in Palo Alto, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   With his indigenous background, he appealed to millions of
down-and-out Peruvians, many of whom are Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toledo's support has grown spectacularly,'' said political
scientist Joanna Drzewieniecki. ``Many people _ half the population
_ will stand behind him.''
</P>
<P>
   Such support, she said, puts the challenger in a much stronger
position to demand quick reforms in the electoral process.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori, on the other hand, finds himself in a vulnerable
position, Drzewieniecki said.
</P>
<P>
   She added that Fujimori and his followers ``are all trying to
pretend that nothing happened but a great deal has happened.''
</P>
<P>
   A State Department official said that, in the short term, it
will be difficult to reform the election office and other electoral
bodies.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that some changes can be made, such as opening up
the airways to opposition candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leveling the playing field means giving the opposition every
opportunity to take their case to the voters,'' he said. ``We think
there is plenty of time to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Toledo appears only sporadically on broadcast TV
stations, several of which are vulnerable to pressure from
Fujimori's government because of their outstanding tax debts.
</P>
<P>
   Only one small cable channel has provided extensive coverage of
Toledo's press conferences and rallies.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pastor, a political science professor at Emory University
in Atlanta, said Fujimori seems to have been caught by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 2000, the issue is change and Fujimori hasn't yet woken up
to that,'' Pastor said.
</P>
<P>
   For Peruvians, he added, the issue ``is no longer can we elect
someone who can take on terrorists and fix the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is whether they will retain democracy or descend
into a new form of authoritarianism.''
</P>
<P>
