u p BC-BUSHPOLLS0416-COX     04-15 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSHPOLLS0416-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush and Gore camps dispute polling dataBy Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Last week, while Al Gore was touting numbers he
believes show that George W. Bush is an under-achieving governor
who never should be president, the Bush campaign was shopping
numbers they believe indicate Gore never will be president.
</P>
<P>
   In a crowded meeting room at Bush's downtown headquarters, top
campaign advisers endeavored to make their case by projecting their
survey of recent surveys onto a wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very problematic for Al Gore,'' said a Bush staffer who,
under the ground rules of the event, can be identified only as a
``senior Bush adviser.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers behind the rhetoric _ which forms the basis for the
Bush campaign strategy _ were compiled from the 27 polls published
since March 8, the Super Tuesday when Bush and Gore effectively
clinched the nominations.
</P>
<P>
   The point of the ``pen and pad briefing'' was to counter
conventional wisdom that says Bush emerged battered and scarred
from his primary battle with Arizona Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   That feeling was fueled by a Pew Research Center poll in
mid-March that declared Bush a primary season winner who lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore was clearly helped, and George W. Bush was just as
clearly hurt,'' the Pew Research Center said in its conclusions,
adding ``many people have come to dislike Bush personally,
especially former supporters of John McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   Au contraire, said the Bush advisers armed with data from the
post-Super Tuesday polls. Though the results of many are within the
margin of error, the Bush officials are eager to note that Gore led
in only five of the polls.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush team is even more eager to note that Gore led in only
two of the 18 polls taken since March 14, the day both candidates
mathematically clinched nomination.
</P>
<P>
   And even more importantly, the Bush folks like what they see in
the trend. In the nine polls from March 8-13, Bush's average lead
was 1.4 percentage points. In the seven polls in April, the lead
had grown to 5.7 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we indicating the race is over? No,'' said a senior Bush
adviser. ``But there are a couple of things. There is a durability
that is pretty shocking. Second of all there is a consistency to it
that is pretty dramatic. There is a trend line here that is
positive for us and ought to be troubling for them.''
</P>
<P>
   At Gore headquarters in Nashville, there were no outward signs
of concern. Communications Director Kathleen Begala scoffed at
anyone who would read too much into springtime polls for a fall
election. Begala said polling data shows her guy prevails on the
issues likely to move votes this year _ education, health care and
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at those issues. Al Gore is right and George W.
Bush is wrong,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She also noted that many of the horse-race polls show a
statistical dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   The most important caveat about horse-race polls is the fact
that the presidential race is only tangentially about popular
votes. It's electoral votes that count.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign is now working off a map, based on the most
recent state-by-state polls, that shows their candidate winning 280
electoral votes, 10 more than needed for victory. Gore leads in
states with 190 electoral votes, with toss-up states accounting for
68 more.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush advisers are not banking on the polls as irrefutable
evidence of pending victory, they are using the numbers to craft
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key point is that clearly Gore wants us to be involved in
a daily tit for tat that clearly deteriorates in quality and
increases in quantity. They want us to be in a mudbath where we're
tossing stuff at each other each day . . . that is making us look
like Gore and we're just another politician who won't bring about a
total change in Washington D.C.,'' said a top Bush adviser.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
