<SLUG> BC-PERU-PRESSURE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. PUT PRESSURE ON PERU TO ANNOUNCE RUNOFF 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN OTIS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ Huge anti-government protests at home and stinging
criticism from abroad may have played a key role in last week's
dramatic announcement by Peru's government that President Alberto
Fujimori will stand in a runoff election, according to analysts and
election monitors.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials denied charges from opposition politicians
that they had discussed tampering with the returns cast during the
April 9 vote.
</P>
<P>
   But during the four days it took to count the ballots,
Fujimori's official vote total teetered on the verge of topping 50
percent _ the amount required to win without having to stand in a
runoff.
</P>
<P>
   Many observers believe that the slow vote count was intentional
and that it gave Fujimori time to test the political winds. If the
outcry was muted, they said, the president would have claimed to
have won in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   However, a handful of independent exit polls and ballot surveys
all indicated that Fujimori won just 48 percent of the vote _ short
of the 50 percent needed to declare outright victory over a field
of eight opponents.
</P>
<P>
   That information _ plus growing evidence of election-day
irregularities _ prompted U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, the Organization of American States and European
diplomats to warn Fujimori in public that they expected a runoff.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Congress went so far as to pass a resolution raising
the possibility of an aid cutoff if Fujimori cooked the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they wanted to doctor the data, all they would have needed
was a small push,'' said a senior electoral observer who asked not
to be named. But, he added, ``there was such a formidable network
of pressure (on the Fujimori government) that it, in effect,
prevented something like that from happening.''
</P>
<P>
   After the polls closed, anti-government demonstrations mounted
with thousands of Toledo supporters eventually taking to the
streets in Lima and several other Peruvian cities to demand a fair
vote count.
</P>
<P>
   According to Daniel Mora, a former Peruvian army general and now
an opposition politician, electoral officials were artificially
inflating Fujimori's vote count, little by little, in order to test
the reaction of Peruvians.
</P>
<P>
   ``But more than one million people mobilized,'' Mora said. ``For
any government, that's a lot of pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, election authorities announced that Fujimori's final
tally stood at 49.84 percent and declared that he would face a
second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that they announced a second round was a political
decision rather than a decision based on the actual vote count,''
said Joanna Drzewieniecki, a U.S.-born political scientist based in
Lima.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
