<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7913 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-BOMBING-MEMORIAL-HNS &LR;      04-15 1402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMBING-MEMORIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMORIAL MAY GIVE OKLAHOMA CITY A NEW IMAGE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KIM COBB 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ The deadly April 1995 bombing of the Alfred P.
Murrah Building followed by last year's devastating tornadoes have
left an image of Oklahoma City as a smoking ruin inhabited by a
doomed population.
</P>
<P>
   It is an image many in the city are itching to shed.
</P>
<P>
   ```We hope to be known someday for something other than
suffering,'' says Mayor Kirk Humphreys.
</P>
<P>
   That day may not be far off.
</P>
<P>
   In the years since terrorism put Oklahoma City in the public
eye, a massive infusion of federal recovery funds has turned a
section of downtown that was dying, even before the bombing, into a
neighborhood on the mend. The bomb, packed into a rental truck and
parked outside the federal building, killed 168 people, including
19 children, and mortified the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Even as they were grieving, bombing survivors and family members
of the dead began planning a memorial at the site of the blast. The
project that some local business leaders feared would turn the area
into a tomb is, instead, a peaceful village green with water
running through it.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the fifth anniversary of the bombing, families,
survivors, rescue workers and the rest of the city will dedicate
the Symbolic Memorial. An international conference on mitigating
terrorism will be held Monday in advance of the dedication. An
explanatory museum is scheduled to open adjacent to the memorial in
November. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Only a few blocks away from the memorial, which was built by a
private foundation, city tax dollars have funded a minor-league
baseball park and, of all things, a canal with paddleboats in a
thriving entertainment zone called ``Bricktown.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't view the memorial as a negative,'' Humphries said.
``It changes our traffic patterns (the memorial spans a section of
what was Fifth Street.) But how could you take that strip of land
where the truck sat and use it as a street?
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we view it as a negative to be known as the place where so
many people suffered? I don't think so,'' Humphries said. ``We
didn't choose it, we certainly wouldn't want it if we had a choice,
but it is who we are.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure it changed us, but it did reveal us,'' Humphries
said.
</P>
<P>
   When the bomb blew the front face off the federal building, it
also devastated block after block of surrounding businesses to the
north.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wound up with three-quarters of a square mile that was just
a wasteland,'' Humphries said. ``I mean everyone moved out. We lost
the federal building, we lost the Journal Record Building, a pretty
large building, we lost the YMCA.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what you lost was everything that supports that _ the dry
cleaners where they dropped their laundry off, the day-care
centers, the restaurants. We lost the whole fabric of life,''
Humphries said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then the question comes, who will move in and take a chance?
Well, nobody.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell Claus, an outspoken Australian, took over as project
manager for the Murrah Revitalization Area in December 1996,
managing the distribution of federal reconstruction funds and
attempting to rekindle business in a neighborhood that was
struggling before the blast. Being an outsider helped him cut
through the emotion that local residents couldn't help but bring to
the table, he said.
</P>
<P>
   To date, $52.5 million in federal funds has been spent
rebuilding the area damaged by the blast.
</P>
<P>
   Many businesses destroyed by the blast were marginal, he said,
and many of those couldn't rebuild even with federal aid. People
are still significantly disturbed by the blast and the place where
it happened, Claus said, and redevelopment still suffers for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past five years, the country has been going
gangbusters, but this area has lost those five years because we
couldn't do anything until the memorial was completed,'' Claus
said. Some businesses were hesitant to try the area because they
weren't sure of the tone the memorial would set, others were
worried about the street closure.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor notes that the location of a new federal campus to
regroup the agencies forced to relocate after the Murrah Building
blast is still a missing piece of the redevelopment puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some concern on the part of many of those agencies
about moving back downtown,'' Humphries said. ``Some people (say)
hey, we're happy where we are now. Some people don't want to come
back because it will bring back bad memories.''
</P>
<P>
   The agencies once housed in the Murrah Building, including the
credit union and Social Security offices where so many of the
victims died, moved into whatever space they could find at the time
_ many finding offices in suburban strip centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's important to the city that we have this new federal
campus that will be about two blocks north of where the Murrah
Building was,'' Humphries said.
</P>
<P>
   The General Services Administration has the authority to force
the agencies to move into the new campus, ``but that's not our
goal,'' said regional GSA spokesman George Hozendorf. The GSA finds
itself caught between the reluctance of the federal workers, and
the determination of Congress and President Clinton to create a
symbol of resilience in the face of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the memorial is nearing completion, Claus thinks
potential private investors will be pleasantly surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole process is a difficult balancing act,'' Claus said,
``because at the one time you want to retain the sense of respect
that relates to the site, and at the same time there's the
pragmatic reality that they're expecting to draw between 300,000
and 500,000 people a year. We can look at this as people who go
just to that site and leave, as they have so far, or we can say ...
you've come to this site, here's other things in Oklahoma City you
may be interested in looking at.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we would be remiss if we didn't use that
opportunity,'' Claus said.
</P>
<P>
   He doubts if the memorial foundation, which gets kid-glove
treatment from the rest of the city, will have any objections if
the private sector elects to build, for example, restaurants around
the memorial to serve its visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're more concerned with blatant disrespect _ selling
trinkets, and the like,'' Claus said. ``I don't believe that will
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't design it for tourism, but we certainly designed it
for people to come,'' said foundation director Kari Ferguson
Watkins. ``We don't use the word tourism, because we don't have to.
It's a historic site.''
</P>
<P>
   The local convention and visitor's bureau has a link to
information on the memorial on it's Web site, www.okccvb.org.
</P>
<P>
   It's clearly an attraction, but spokeswoman Sandy Pantlik makes
it clear she's treading cautiously. ``You're exactly right. It's a
fine line,'' Pantlik said. ``We're very sensitive to the victims
and the survivors.'' The best solution they've found is to provide
information about the memorial when it's requested, Pantlik said,
and there are no shortage of requests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing they'll find is it's no longer a hole. There's
a beautiful, symbolic memorial there,'' Pantlik said. And the
dedication of the memorial comes as Pantlik's agency is
aggressively trying to promote Oklahoma City as a whole new town,
promoting instead the new ballpark and overt tourist attractions in
Bricktown.
</P>
<P>
   The attempt to redevelop downtown actually began before the
bombing, with a locally funded project known as ``MAPS'' that was
approved by voters in 1993. The mayor attributes the resurgence of
downtown to that effort and not the federal funding and national
attention that followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't talk about benefits,'' Humphries said, shaking his
head vigorously. ``People want to ask me the question, `Well, in
the long run will this be good for you?' You just can't go there.''
</P>
<P>
   As many as 350,000 people a year have been coming to see the
site of the bombing for the past five years, Humphries said. People
who don't know he is the mayor routinely stop him in the street to
ask where it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our challenge is, how do they find it? How do they find
restaurants if they want it?'' Humphries asked, rhetorically.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't view it as crass commercialism if we give them what
they're looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-15-00 1503EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
