<DOCNO> NYT20000415.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7920 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-LA-WRITERS-TAXES-NYT     04-15 0502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-WRITERS-TAXES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG FEUD OVER LOS ANGELES TAX IS SETTLED
</HEADLINE>
 
 refiling c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After years of heated conflict, the union that
represents screenwriters and the city of Los Angeles have reached a
truce over imposing local taxes on writers, artists and other
self-employed people who work at home.
</P>
<P>
   The union, The Writers Guild of America, has dropped opposition
to state legislation, sought by Los Angeles, that would allow
cities to examine state tax records to find people who file as a
business entity but do not pay local business license taxes.
Although the legislation stops short of an outright exemption for
writers and artists, it contains language taking ``artistic or
literary capacity'' into consideration in deciding whether to
impose the local tax. The guild, which represents about 5,000 film
and television writers who live in Los Angeles, succeeded in having
a previous version of the bill killed in the state Senate last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The guild, which sought its own bill seeking an exemption, has
agreed to add a 20-point test to determine whether a person should
be subjected to the tax. The City Council voted this week to
withdraw its opposition to the legislation sought by the guild.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're confident that, in most circumstances, our members will
easily meet these tests, as will other artists and authors,'' said
Cheryl Rhoden, a spokeswoman for the guild.
</P>
<P>
   City leaders have long said they were losing tax revenue _
perhaps $60 million a year _ from businesses that do not pay local
business license taxes, and they pursued legislation they believed
would enable them to catch scofflaws. But that plan immediately
became anathema to much of Los Angeles' creative community in the
mid-1990s when the city said it would include home-based
screenwriters.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the city imposed a requirement that writers and
artists working at home pay $25 for a city permit. The rule was
quickly rescinded in the face of fierce opposition and an opinion
from the city attorney that it might be unconstitutional. But until
now, the battle has continued over whether creative employment
should be subject to the same local business license taxes as more
commercial pursuits.
</P>
<P>
   The guild, comparing the permit plan to systems used in
Communist countries to monitor writers, opposed the idea as an
infringement on the First Amendment, though some elected leaders
dismissed that issue as a false premise. The guild filed suit to
block the plan, but an appeals court rejected the suit after
finding that the guild had not assembled the proper plaintiffs to
bring a case.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Feuer, a city councilman involved in brokering the
compromise, said the agreement alleviated ``enormous distrust and
suspicion'' that had built up between the city and the guild in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The city's legislation, sponsored by Assemblyman Gil Cedillo,
cleared the tax committee this week and is expected to be voted on
by the full Assembly next month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-15-00 1510EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
