<DOCNO> NYT20000415.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7921 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-EARNHARDT0416-COX     04-15 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-EARNHARDT0416-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Winston Cup's Intimidator is back
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The life of a Winston Cup crew chief is a hectic one.
Even those who appear calm are churning inside. Kevin Hamlin,
laid-back as they come, takes a little yellow pill to keep his
ulcers under control.
</P>
<P>
   But he was looking for something stronger two summers ago when
his boss, Richard Childress, told him that there would be a switch
in their garage.
</P>
<P>
   Hamlin would be leaving the newcomer, Mike Skinner, to team with
Dale Earnhardt. Intimidated by The Intimidator? You bet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't anything I even cared about doing,'' Hamlin said.
``I said, `Whoa, whoa, whoa. That's not me, Richard. That's not
what I want. I don't want to be involved in that limelight. I just
need to start out with a driver like Skinner, try to build a strong
team and win my first race with him.'''
</P>
<P>
   That was 62 races and many stomach pains ago. As Earnhardt
prepares to tackle the field in Sunday's DieHard 500 at Talladega
Superspeedway, life has taken some happy twists for the men around
the No. 3 Chevrolet.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Earnhardt's a contender with a competitive ride. He
has won one race and is fourth in the point standings. As an owner,
he suddenly has an identity crisis. When his son won for the first
time two weeks ago, he joked, ``When did I become Dale Sr.? I'm not
Dale Sr.''
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to make Hamlin forget about the frustrating road the
No. 3 has traveled back to respectability.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wish I was in this situation quite a long time ago,
to tell you the truth,'' Hamlin said. ``I really do like working
with Dale Earnhardt. I feel like every time we come to the race
track we have a legitimate chance to win. That's a good feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   If he has been burned by Earnhardt's competitive fire, Hamlin
hides his scars well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter if he's playing race cars or playing
checkers or if he's playing tiddlywinks, Dale wants to win,''
Hamlin said. ``If you're walking from here to that yellow line, he
wants to be there before you do.
</P>
<P>
   If you're going to go through that door, he wants to go through
there in front of you or two-wide. That's just Dale Earnhardt.
That's a good thing to have, especially in a race-car driver.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamlin doesn't have the nerve to challenge Earnhardt, even in
checkers. ``I don't want to compete against him; I want to compete
with him,'' he said. ``I've found that it's better to be on his
team than against his team.''
</P>
<P>
   It was during the turbulent 1998 season, when Hamlin and Larry
McReynolds traded uniforms within Childress' shop, that many people
began to question Earnhardt's skills. It was suggested that perhaps
his best years were behind him.
</P>
<P>
   The seven-time champion had gone winless in 1997 and except for
the season-opening victory at the Daytona 500 in 1998, that season
was a disappointing period of adjustment to a new crew chief.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt will be 49 Saturday. Already in 2000, he can celebrate
a victory at Atlanta, three top fives and four top-10 finishes. It
appears he'll be a factor in the championship. Did someone say
``too old''?
</P>
<P>
   ``All the guys laying the numbers on the board right now are in
their 40s, and it's pretty inspiring to see Earnhardt up there at
49 years old, kicking butt again this year and winning three races
last year,'' said Rusty Wallace, another ``geezer'' who is winning
in his 40s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our sport is a lot different than stick and ball, man,''
Wallace said. ``Stick and ball is how muscular you are and how fast
you are with your feet and arms and all that, but our sport it's
how much you know about the sport. It's how much you know about the
track and how much you know the setup is going to change or what
did you run here in the past. I think it's a neat deal to watch and
see what he's done.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace said Earnhardt still has to be taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know _ he's been eatin' his Wheaties or something,''
Wallace said. ``I talked to him the other day and I asked him what
he was doin' different, and he said, `I'm just concentrating and
trying to get better.' He really thinks the new Monte Carlo has
given him a big edge over last year, and it looks like it has. I
don't think he ever thought he'd be this strong, but he is and
that's good.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, both Childress and Hamlin concede that the previous
problems were Earnhardt's cars, not the driver. As the new
Chevrolet Monte Carlo body continues its shakedown, Hamlin thinks
that putting his driver on a level playing field aerodynamically
with the Fords and Pontiacs will make a big difference this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to be equal with them,'' Hamlin said. ``Look at
IROC. That's as equal as you can get things. You put Dale Earnhardt
in an IROC car and he shines. Just give him something to work with,
and he'll drive the wheels off of it. If we were racing the same
bodies every week, he'd beat their butts.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt's revival has several explanations in addition to the
car. He's feeling better after offseason back surgery. And there's
the pride factor: He's working hard not to get beat by Dale Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I was racing pretty much with a lot of pain and
stuff,'' Earnhardt said, ``but not as far as getting to the point
where I couldn't feel my hand. After I'd get out of the car, it was
that way. That aggravated me a lot. I would go to the chiropractor,
until I got smart and went to a doctor. We got through that.''
</P>
<P>
   He concedes that having his son in Cup races has invigorated
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I'm a little competitive with him, but we've always been
that way from the time he was a kid,'' Earnhardt said. ``I sort of
do that in raising him, I think, let him win sometimes. I just
haven't let him win on the race track yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season the Chevy teams were out of sorts from anticipating
a new Monte Carlo that wasn't rolled out on schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we didn't build any new stuff to start with; we
were still running on old stuff from the year before, because we
were anticipating building new cars from May on with the new
Chevrolets,'' Hamlin said. ``But they never got introduced. So we
got behind at the beginning of last year and stayed that way. This
year, we've got the new stuff built up the way we want, and so far
it's been working all right.''
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, Earnhardt is back on a superspeedway, where he's
considered the master at drafting. The team owner is still
impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were sitting in the truck a couple of weeks ago watching an
IROC race he had won, and he told me what he was looking for and
how he was looking and what the guys racing around him were
doing,'' Childress said. ``He just has a natural knack, the ability
to know what's going on around him and watching the moves everybody
else is making.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it goes with the experience he's got in
restrictor-plate racing. I was one of the first persons who said,
`I think he can see air.' I've watched the moves and things. He was
one of the first guys I can ever remember see doing the side draft.
That goes back into the '80s.''
</P>
<P>
   And, so it seems, does this season of rebirth for The
Intimidator.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
