u p BC-BUSH-DILEMMA-2TAKES(T     04-15 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-DILEMMA-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH TRIES TO HOLD THE FAR RIGHT WHILE COURTING THE MIDDLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)   By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ When George W. Bush emerged from his meeting last week
with a group of gay Republicans, what mattered was style, not
substance. By appearing with a group shunned by many conservatives,
Bush signaled a measure of independence. He even reminded
conservative Republicans to judge gays by their heart and soul.
</P>
<P>
   Flashback to 1994: The candidate for governor, George W. Bush,
found himself in a ticklish spot. Ultraconservatives in his Texas
Republican Party had adopted a contentious platform that included a
plank for teaching creationism in schools. Bush could not afford to
alienate social conservatives but he needed Democratic crossover
votes to win. The platform? When asked, he said he had not read it.
</P>
<P>
   Two elections, same candidate, seemingly the same dilemma: Hold
on to right-wing conservatives but keep enough of a public distance
from them to court the political middle. In his two governor's race
victories, Bush performed this balancing act. In Texas, he has
cultivated a bipartisan, above-the-fray image that has earned him
many Democratic friends even as he has held on to the religious
right and other conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would have lost his effectiveness had he been a
religious-right champion,'' said state Rep. Arlene Wohlgemuth, a
conservative, ardently anti-abortion Republican who supports Bush.
``I think he has been very wise politically.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are perils. In Texas, Bush has had a complicated and
occasionally contentious relationship with conservative leaders.
Some consider him a true believer; others are among his loudest
critics. His courtship of conservative groups has often been quiet
and behind the scenes. He has feuded with some leaders and wooed
others, particularly religious conservatives like the outspoken
Fort Worth televangelist, James Robison. But he has infuriated some
Republican hard-liners by refusing to campaign against Democratic
allies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's comfortable in the middle, but they've gone out
of their way to woo certain religious leaders on the right,'' said
Tom Pauken, the former chairman of the Texas Republican Party who
has feuded with Bush. ``It's worked to a degree, in that there
isn't strong opposition on the right to Bush. But there isn't
strong enthusiasm on the right for Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   To some degree, Bush has enjoyed a charmed life in Texas in
winning over conservatives. Before the 1994 election, he was
untested in statewide races and his appeal to conservatives was
uncertain. But after Bush announced his candidacy, his two likely
primary opponents withdrew. He essentially then inherited a
conservative vote without a fight and focused on the Democratic
incumbent, Gov. Ann Richards, whose sassy social liberalism
incensed the Texas right.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to do anything we could to get rid of her,'' said
Cathie Adams, president of the Texas Eagle Forum, the state chapter
of the group founded by Phyllis Schlafly.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's victory was surprisingly emphatic, but his honeymoon with
some Republican conservatives was surprisingly short. Before his
election the state party had undergone a revolution at its 1994
convention. The longtime party chairman, Fred Meyer, a Bush family
friend, resigned under pressure from social conservatives. The
grass-roots activists who dominated the convention elected Pauken,
who became an irritant to Bush and his chief political strategist,
Karl Rove.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer and other Bush supporters describe Pauken as a polarizing
figure. ``Pauken has very, very few friends,'' Meyer said.
</P>
<P>
   The tension meant that the new Republican governor and the new
chairman of the Republican Party barely spoke. During his four
years as party chairman, Pauken said the governor refused to meet
with him or to allow the party to place a liaison in the governor's
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's personal with him,'' Pauken said. ``Once you're an enemy,
you stay an enemy. Same with Karl.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Bartlett, a Bush campaign spokesman, said the governor did
initially hold a couple of meetings with Pauken. But he
characterized the relationship between the men as ``distant,'' and
the meetings quickly ended.
</P>
<P>
   Other conservatives also were becoming disenchanted with Bush.
Adams of the Eagle Forum said that she and others felt ignored and
taken for granted. She described Bush's relationship with
grass-roots conservatives in Texas as ``very tepid'' and ``arm's
length.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The real reaching out, and the real, `I want to work with
you,' has been for Democrats,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The strained relations surfaced publicly at the 1996 party
convention in San Antonio. Religious conservatives again adopted a
very conservative state platform. But the larger controversy arose
over the voting on delegates to the national convention in San
Diego. Delegates proposed by the campaign of the Republican
presidential nominee, Bob Dole, were repeatedly voted down as
ultraconservatives supported other candidates.
</P>
<P>
   And in a symbolic slap at Bush, delegates voted for Pauken as
chairman of the Texas delegation to the national convention, a post
traditionally held by the party's highest elected official. To the
surprise of some, Pauken did not turn down the job. A year later,
when Bush sought to overhaul the state's outdated tax code, Pauken
and other conservatives called his plan a thinly disguised income
tax, which is prohibited under Texas' constitution, and lobbied
successfully to defeat it.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bush found himself prevailing in a fight with conservatives on
the state Board of Education. Six Christian conservatives had won
seats on the obscure 15-member board and waged a high-profile
effort to change textbooks and loosen federal and state control.
They criticized Bush's state education standards and accountability
system as too soft and urged the dismissal of the state education
commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Ballard, a member of the board from Houston until she
moved to West Texas, became so disenchanted with Bush that she
campaigned for Steve Forbes in the early presidential primaries.
She said the governor expanded, rather than reduced, the role of
federal programs in local schools, and she contended that
grass-roots conservatives, not Bush, were responsible for
toughening education standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The facts are that he has not been a friend to conservatives
in the state of Texas,'' said Ballard, a minister's wife.
</P>
<P>
   But Bruce Buchanan, a University of Texas political scientist,
said that even in a conservative state like Texas, many of Bush's
critics are regarded as extremists. Buchanan said that Bush
succeeded in positioning himself as a moderating force toward
hard-liners and staking out positions in keeping with broader
public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have no leverage over him because the rest of the state
is more moderate than them, in part, and because they have not
gotten elected,'' Buchanan said. In 1998, Pauken, who had resigned
as party chairman, lost his bid to be state attorney general to a
Republican, John Cornyn, reportedly recruited by Rove. Ballard and
Bob Offutt, another Bush critic on the education board, were
defeated this year.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Lambert, one of Texas' three members on the Republican
National Committee, said that Bush had been adept at appealing to
more moderate voters, but he said he considered the governor a true
conservative. Lambert said he considered Bush's aggressive
courtship of religious conservatives in the South Carolina primary
as a true indication of his political compass.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say he moved to the right,'' Lambert said. ``I don't
think he moved to the right. I think he articulated positions he
always had.''
</P>
<P>
   Above any conservative group in Texas, Bush has most openly
curried favor with religious conservatives, particularly groups
like the Christian Coalition. ``They have to like him a lot because
this is a religious guy,'' Meyer said. ``They'd be crazy not to
like George W. Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Anderson, executive director of Texas Christian Coalition,
which represents about 200,000 people, said that Bush delivered on
the organization's three most important concerns during the 1999
legislative session: a parental notification law for minors seeking
abortions, passage of the Religious Freedom Restoration Act, and
tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Anderson also praised Bush's earlier appointment of Dr. William
R. Archer III, an opponent of abortion, as state health
commissioner. Archer has sought to curtail school-based health
clinics, which many conservatives believe provide abortion
counseling.
</P>
<P>
   ``On most every issue,'' Anderson said of the governor, ``we've
had pretty much the same goals.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Reed, former executive director of the Christian Coalition
and now a Bush adviser, said the governor had appealed to religious
conservatives with the openness with which he talks about his own
faith. In return, many Texas ministers have rallied behind him,
even if his position on abortion is more tepid than they might
like. Last November, The Dallas Morning News reported that a
network of Texas religious leaders was contacting conservatives in
crucial political states to assure them that Bush shared their
convictions and beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also has an influential ally in Robison, the televangelist
and host of the nationally syndicated program ``Life Today.'' When
the influential televangelist, James Dobson, criticized Bush and
talked of renouncing the Republican Party, Robison rallied support
for the governor. In February 1999, on Presidents' Day, Bush even
appeared on Robison's program, startling some in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would a Methodist governor wander into the televangelist's
domain, where stern sermons are spliced between money requests and
crackpot Y2K warnings,'' Bud Kennedy, a Fort Worth Star-Telegram
columnist, wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Robison said he had often prayed or spoken with
Bush, including on the day the governor decided to run for
president. ``He said when he called me that I was the sixth person
he had told,'' Robison recalled. ``He said, `I've heard the call. I
believe God wants me to run for president.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
