u p BC-GORE-REFORM-NYT &LR;      04-15 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-REFORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRACING GORE'S ROOTS AS SUPPORTER OF CAMPAIGN FINANCE OVERHAUL
</HEADLINE>
  By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Vice President Al Gore declared in late March
that he would devote himself to remaking the system of political
finance, he conceded that he was an ``imperfect messenger'' for
campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   Gore knows that his 1996 fund-raising exploits, including
cadging cash at a Buddhist temple and dunning contributors from his
White House office, make his new campaign finance reform mantra
subject to skepticism and a few snickers. Also, all the while he is
proclaiming the need for a campaign finance overhaul, including a
ban on soft money, the vice president is busily raising these
unrestricted donations to keep up with George W. Bush and the
Republicans. This very weekend he is helping the Democratic
National Committee sweep up more than $4 million from rich donors
in Silicon Valley and Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Since his March 27 speech proposing radical changes in the way
politicians finance their campaigns, Gore's aides have taken pains
to show that he is not a late and cynical convert to a crusade
popularized in the presidential primaries by Republican Sen. John
McCain of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, they say, has supported campaign reform legislation since
his earliest days in Congress. He has sponsored or co-sponsored
bills to limit contributions from political action committees, to
restrain spending in House and Senate campaigns, to provide for
public financing of congressional elections and to grant free
television time to candidates.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, supporters and critics of Gore agree that he has been,
since first elected to Congress in 1976, a steady if largely
invisible supporter of measures to change the political finance
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be fair to say he certainly was a supporter but an
exaggeration to say he was an activist or a crusader,'' said former
Sen. David L. Boren, D-Okla., a longtime sponsor of legislation to
clean up campaigns. ``I don't say that as a criticism, because
every vote and every co-sponsor we got was crucial.''
</P>
<P>
   Boren, now president of the University of Oklahoma, said that he
could count on Gore's signature on campaign bills and on his vote,
but that Gore was not an ally who would make sacrifices for the
cause.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Gore, like McCain, had become a committed proponent
of campaign reform because of the criticism he had endured for
zealously exploiting the system's flaws. Gore said in his speech in
March that he and President Clinton (with their Republican
opponents) had ``pushed the system to the breaking point'' and
fueled public cynicism about politics and politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Other congressional advocates of campaign revisions speak
similarly of Gore during his eight years in the House and eight
years in the Senate: he was a reliable vote and co-signer, but his
heart was elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Quinn, Gore's communications director, said that it was
difficult to discern his motives or the depth of his feelings after
so much time. But she conceded that as a member of Congress, hehad
devoted far more effort to arms control, the environment and
technology policy than to election law. She added that there was
considerable evidence that Gore early on recognized the value of
campaign finance as both a substantive and a symbolic issue.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1978 newspaper column, Gore, then a representative, wrote
that changing the campaign finance system was ``one of the most
important steps we can take to return government to the people.''
</P>
<P>
   The next year, he co-sponsored legislation introduced by Rep.
Abner J. Mikva, D-Ill., to impose limits on spending in House
campaigns in exchange for partial public financing.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also co-signed a bill in 1979, sponsored by Rep. David R.
Obey, D-Wis., to limit the amount of money that a political action
committee could give to a candidate and the total amount of PAC
money a candidate could receive.
</P>
<P>
   The Mikva and Obey bills went nowhere. But Gore can now
justifiably claim he was an early proponent of reform.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Gore, by then a senator, sponsored a bill to provide
public financing for Senate campaigns. In 1988, he introduced
legislation to give presidential candidates free television time,
to cut the cost of campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commitment was early and consistent, and he is clearly
convinced from his own experience that this is essential to his
success as president and is desperately needed now to steady the
course of the country,'' Quinn said.
</P>
<P>
   Mikva, who since leaving Congress in 1979 has been a federal
judge and White House counsel under Clinton, said that he had
little recollection of Gore's support for his political fight to
finance congressional campaigns with public money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not at the top of his agenda,'' Mikva said.
</P>
<P>
   Mikva's 1979 legislation was a precursor of the centerpiece of
Gore's proposal this year. It would have created a fund to pay for
general election campaigns of candidates who agreed to limit their
spending. Gore's more ambitious proposal, which he calls the
Democracy Endowment, would create a $7 billion fund to pay for
campaigns of candidates who agree not to take any outside money.
Both measures aimed to break the link between those who write the
checks and those who write the laws.
</P>
<P>
   Mikva agreed with Gore's acknowledgment that he was an
``imperfect messenger'' for campaign reform, having exploited every
available loophole in his campaigns for Congress and the vice
presidency and fashioned a few new ones.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that Gore was wise to adopt the cause of reform now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pleased when he made a big issue of campaign finance
reform,'' Mikva said. ``The consequences of 1996 are going to
plague him anyway. If he's going to try to pretend it didn't happen
and say nothing, he's worse off.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's proposal would provide public financing of campaigns from
a $7 billion fund to be filled with tax-deductible contributions
from many of the same interests and individuals who now fuel
campaigns _ but without the direct contributions to candidates. It
would also outlaw so-called soft money, the unlimited contributions
from corporations, unions, interest groups and wealthy donors,
require greater disclosure of independent expenditures and provide
free television time for candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But until such laws are enacted, Gore intends to aggressively
employ the current system to finance his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gore told contributors at a $500,000 soft-money luncheon in
Washington on Wednesday that he had no intention of taking a
high-minded vow of poverty in his combat with Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will fight fire with fire,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
