u a BC-TEXAS-SHRIMP-SHORTAGE     04-15 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-SHRIMP-SHORTAGE-ART-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEIGHING NEW RULES AS SHRIMP STOCKS FALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROSS E. MILLOY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FULTON, Texas _ Along the harbor docks of this windswept village
of 1,000 on the Texas coast where several dozen shrimp boats rock
on their moorings in a steady southeasterly breeze, shrimpers are
facing two unwelcome changes _ declining shrimp stocks and the
likelihood of tougher government regulations.
</P>
<P>
   But faced with the shortage of shrimp in the Gulf of Mexico, the
Texas Parks and Wildlife Department is considering stringent new
measures for an industry already reeling from decades of government
intervention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not going to preside over the death of a fishery,'' said
Hal Osburn, director of the department's coastal fisheries program,
noting that an 18-month study shows that shrimp have dwindled to 30
percent of their historical levels and may soon reach a point that
makes it impossible for the remaining shrimp to reproduce fast
enough to replenish the stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When that happens, the entire fishery collapses and everyone
loses, the shrimpers, the sports fishermen and the public,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the measures being contemplated by the agency are
increased regulation of net mesh sizes, reduced catch limits, and
seasonal and area closures of some fishing grounds, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But for many shrimpers, more regulations of the industry only
mean more problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too much laws already,'' Haun Nguyen, a 32-year old Vietnamese
shrimper lamented. Working aboard his battered 42-foot wooden
vessel, the Saint John, Nguyen said: ``Somebody in Austin need a
job, so they make up rules. They make it too hard to make a
living.''
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen, a father of three who works 12 hours a day seven days a
week fishing alone in the waters of Aransas Bay, says that there
are plenty of shrimp in the bay if only the government would allow
shrimpers to harvest them.
</P>
<P>
   Any perceived shortages, he says, are the result of
environmental pollution from pesticides off farmlands draining into
the bay, or more likely, he says, an increase in trout and redfish
resulting from restocking programs managed by area fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   But Osburn said two major changes over the last 20 years have
made increased regulatory efforts necessary: an influx of primarily
Asian refugees like Nguyen seeking a livelihood from the shrimping
industry, and the invention of ``peeler technology,'' which created
a market for extremely small shrimp that would otherwise be
unprofitable to harvest.
</P>
<P>
   Texas bay and Gulf shrimpers harvest about 70 million pounds of
fish annually, worth nearly $160 million, with a total $500 million
impact on the state's economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throughout most of a shrimp's life, there is a fleet of
commercial vessels out there in active pursuit,'' Osburn said.
</P>
<P>
   He said 1,400 bait shrimp vessels target the small shrimp in the
back bays. As shrimp grow and move into the primary bays, a bay
shrimping fleet of another 1,400 vessels seeks them. Finally, as
the shrimp reach maturity and move out to the Gulf, they are hunted
by a fleet of 2,300 licensed Gulf shrimping vessels, plus many
out-of-state boats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shrimping industry obviously doesn't like increased
regulation, but you can't keep doing that forever,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Kenneth Jackson, 68, said he retired after 41 years of
shrimping in the bays and out in the Gulf of Mexico because ``I
just couldn't make a living at it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jackson said shrimpers face a bewildering tangle of state and
federal regulations and licensing requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some times of the year you can only fish from sunrise until 2
in afternoon, sometimes you can't fish at night, sometimes you can
only catch certain sizes and only so much of that,'' he said. ``In
the Gulf, if you catch the wrong size at the wrong time of year,
you have to throw them back even though they're already dead. It's
a mess.''
</P>
<P>
   Osburn says another program, buying back licenses from fishermen
while limiting new entries to the industry, offers the best hope
for future regulation. Despite the possible new rules, Nguyen has
no intention of quitting the shrimping industry, though he says he
would never let his children enter the business. ``It's too hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Regulations are only part of the many difficulties feeding
Nguyen's frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen, who says he makes about $10,000 a year shrimping, says
rising fuel costs have soared to $100 of his average daily earnings
of $150. And without warning, the owner of the docks at Fulton
Harbor notified him on April 1 that slip rentals would double from
$50 to $100 a month.
</P>
<P>
   And on Friday, a key pulley that hoists his nets from the water
broke. As he climbed up among the nets to replace it, he pointed to
the shiny new pulley he had just bought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty bucks I pay for this. No money for me today. No milk for
my kids. Tell somebody in Austin about that,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
