<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7959 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0416-COX     04-15 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0416-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHOWDOWN ON HOLD AS BOTH SIDES AWAIT COURT'S RULING ON ELIAN
 &HT;    For Sunday, April 16
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ With the showdown over Elian Gonzalez on hold pending a
court ruling, hundreds of Cuban-Americans still turned out Saturday
at the Little Havana home of the boy's Miami relatives, praying,
singing and showing their determination to keep the 6-year-old in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my first time here,'' said Adolfo Jimenez(cq), 36, a
soft-spoken attorney who brought his young daughter in a stroller
and stood for several hours in a broiling South Florida sun to
protest government plans to turn Elian over to his father. ``I've
never seen the Cuban community unified like this.''
</P>
<P>
   After a week of tension and drama, both sides in the controversy
were awaiting a ruling by the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals in
Atlanta, which last week issued a temporary ban on removing Elian
from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The court is considering whether to leave the ban in place until
it hears arguments at a May 11 hearing on a lawsuit stemming from
the case. Its ruling could come at any time.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's Miami relatives are asking the court to overturn a
decision in March by a Miami federal judge who sided with a
decision by federal officials to send the boy back to his father.
Government officials have asked the court to order the boy reunited
with his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, until the court case is
resolved.
</P>
<P>
   The standoff reached a crisis last week after Attorney General
Janet Reno came to South Florida and met with Elian and his Miami
relatives in an 11th-hour bid to resolve the dispute. But her
efforts failed, and Reno issued an order telling the family they
must turn Elian over.
</P>
<P>
   The family refused, angrily vowing to hold the boy as long as
possible. Elian's great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, said he would stand
aside if federal agents came to his home, but would not take the
boy elsewhere to be turned over.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Cuban exiles surrounded his home Thursday as Reno's
2 p.m. deadline approached, but no agents came for the boy. The
situation went back into a holding pattern a short time later when
the Atlanta court issued its temporary ban on removing Elian from
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Miami relatives opened another legal front,
asking a Washington, D.C. federal court to block Elian's removal to
Cuba until the government certifies that his human rights won't be
violated there. A judge set a hearing on the matter for Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday, the Justice Department sent a letter to Lazaro
Gonzalez officially revoking Elian's immigration status and telling
Gonzalez that he is in violation of the law for continuing to
``exercise control over Elian.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno apparently still hopes the family might resolve the crisis
on its own, and has offered to provide a secure retreat where the
two sides can live separately for a week or two, sharing time with
Elian while they negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   But the Miami relatives will agree to such a deal only if they
aren't required to turn the boy over permanently to his father,
while Juan Miguel Gonzalez has insisted he get custody of his son
at any reunion. Gonzalez has promised to remain in the United
States pending the outcome of the case in the Atlanta court, but
that apparently has not been enough for the Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   It was unknown if any further negotiations were taking place
over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Reno has made it clear that she wants the boy reunited with his
father, and federal officials have been working on a plan to
extract Elian from the Little Havana house if the family continues
its refusal to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   Protestors have vowed to block any removal, saying they will
form a human chain around the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will sit in the street,'' said Eliseo Rodriguez(cq) , who
said serving time in an American jail would be easy compared to the
9 years he spent in Cuban prisons in the 1960s for opposing Fidel
Castro. ``I will put out my hands and let them arrest me, but
others won't. There will be trouble if they try it.''
</P>
<P>
   Relations between the two sides of the Gonzalez family have
turned bitter, with both sides trading angry rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's father reportedly is deeply hurt and angry over the
Miami family's actions, which have included parading the boy before
television cameras and the cheering crowd. The family also made a
videotape of Elian in which he addresses his father directly and
says he does not want to go back to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday, the Miami relatives released an affidavit by a
Cuban man who said he is a friend of Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Rodriguez _ who survived the boat crossing that left
Elian's mother and 10 others dead _ claims Gonzalez beat his wife
and inflicted his ``violent nature'' on Elian.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Miguel Gonzalez's Washington attorney, Gregory Craig,
blasted the allegations Saturday, saying they showed the Miami
family's desperation.
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Williams can be reached by e-mail at:
mikew(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
