<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7962 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-KAZAKHSTAN-U.S.-MAP-N     04-15 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KAZAKHSTAN-U.S.-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KAZAKH LEADER SAYS ALBRIGHT IS MEDDLING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By STEVE LEVINE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASTANA, Kazakhstan _ At the start of a five-day visit to Central
Asia, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on Saturday renewed
American criticism of Kazakhstan for its sale of some 40 MiG
fighter jets to North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   But President Nursultan A. Nazarbayev reproached Albright, too _
for, in essence, not minding her own business.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange of remarks, at a news conference after a meeting at
the presidential palace, stemmed from the recent appointments of
two senior government officials whose dismissal last year helped
persuade Albright not to impose sanctions on Kazakhstan over the
MiG sale last June.
</P>
<P>
   Albright is on a visit to three former Soviet republics in the
Caspian Sea region, where the United States has sought to increase
its influence in recent years because of the region's enormous
reserves of oil and natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   The trip also coincides with a time of rising Western concern
about the flow of weapons and narcotics through the area. For
example, Uzbekistan authorities seized a shipment from Kazakhstan
this month that they said contained radioactive material.
Kazakhstan has denied the assertion.
</P>
<P>
   Kazakhstan's sale of the 1960s-era MiG jets, which experts say
are effective in the Korean region despite their comparative
technological backwardness, severely strained relations with the
United States last year.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has tried to discourage weapons sales to
several countries that it considers dangerous, like Iraq, Libya and
North Korea. Countries that carry out such sales are subject to a
range of sanctions, including a possible cutoff of American foreign
assistance. Kazakhstan has received $550 million in American aid
since the Soviet Union came apart in 1991, according to
Kazakhstan's figures.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the sanctions threat, Nazarbayev dismissed his
closest aide, Chief of Security Nurtay Abykaev, and his defense
minister, Mukhtar Altynbaev, last fall. In recent weeks, however,
Abykaev was named deputy foreign minister, and Altynbaev was
appointed chief of the air force.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Kazakhstan courts have acquitted one Kazakhstani
who was charged in the case, and awarded an amnesty to the only
remaining defendant.
</P>
<P>
   In her remarks, Albright praised Nazarbayev for tightening
controls on the flow of conventional weapons abroad since the sale.
The Kazakh leader, too, thanked the United States for its advice on
how to prevent illegal transfers of conventional arms.
</P>
<P>
   But the two officials dispensed with niceties regarding the
recent appointments. ``I expressed our disappointment and
surprise,'' Albright said, sitting next to Nazarbayev.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department official said that U.S. officials were
particularly angry over Abykaev's return to government this month.
``Coming so close to Albright's visit, we look at it as in our
face,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Nazarbayev said that Abykaev and Altynbaev had been ``punished
enough,'' arguing that their new jobs were ``three levels junior to
what they previously held.'' Nazarbayev blamed the sale of the MiGs
on private citizens, who he said doctored government documents so
the planes could be diverted to North Korea. He said two suspects
were being pursued abroad.
</P>
<P>
   He proceeded to reprove Albright, saying it was ``not the place
of the secretary of state to decide'' the fate of Kazakhstan
ministers.
</P>
<P>
   Albright is also to visit Kyrgyzstan and Uzbekistan.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary of state has had to approach the republics
delicately. While the United States considers Kazakhstan and, to a
lesser extent, Uzbekistan strategically important, the entire
region has essentially jettisoned earlier democratic pretensions in
the last two years and conducted blatantly rigged elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-15-00 1558EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000415.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7963 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-PROTESTS-0416-COX     04-15 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROTESTS-0416-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLICE MAKE PRE-EMPTIVE RAID AS NATION'S CAPITAL BRACES FOR
SUNDAY PROTESTS
 &HT;    By BOB DART and ALEC SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Police seized materials that they said could be
used to make firebombs and closed the training center for
protesters Saturday as the nation's capital braced for mass
demonstrations against the World Bank and International Monetary
Fund.
</P>
<P>
   But thousands of activists, bearing backpacks and bravado,
gathered in the rain and vowed not to be deterred from shutting
down the meetings of the world trade organizations on Sunday and
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, they've made us more passionate,'' said Katie, a
friendly Wittenberg University student from Springfield, Ohio, who
had a phone number written prominently on her arm in indelible ink.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's for the legal team _ in case I get thrown in jail,'' she
explained, adding she didn't want to give her last name.
</P>
<P>
   The drizzly day began with police and fire officials entering
the protesters' ``convergence center'' _ a brick warehouse across
town from the World Bank, which is located several blocks from the
White House and has been blocked off by crowd-control barricades
for days.
</P>
<P>
   The fire department had been warned of possible code violations
in the building, said Capt. Brian Lee. They closed the warehouse as
being ``immediately dangerous to life and health'' after finding
propane stoves and other hazards, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant chief Terry Gainer said police also found rags,
bottles and jars and flammable liquids that he said could be used
in making ``Molotov cocktails.''
</P>
<P>
   Protesters scoffed at the notion that they were making bombs.
What the police seized was paint remover and other materials to
make banners and placards, said Patrick Reinsborough, a spokesman
for the Mobilization for Global Justice, the umbrella organization
for scores of groups including, labor unions to environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``They even took our puppets,'' he said. ``It was clearly an
effort to silence us.''
</P>
<P>
   The protesters promptly moved their ``action prep'' and other
activities to a community center and sidewalks several blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a decentralized movement without leaders. This was just
one physical space, so closing it isn't going to change what is
happening,'' said Reinsborough. ``It just makes us stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Police have made at least 20 arrests since demonstrators began
arriving in the past week _ several for allegedly possessing
ammunition and plastic pipes and chains used to link protesters
together into human barricades. Police Chief Charles Ramsey said he
expected 10,000 or more protesters to be here for the annual
meeting of financial ministers and world bankers.
</P>
<P>
   The great variety of protesters are united in their accusations
that international financiers are destroying the environment
through improper development in Third World countries and imposing
monetary policies that hurt poor people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned about the growing gap between rich and poor in
the world,'' said Art Gish, who has been a social activist for 40
years. ``World trade organizations help cause it. I'm part of a
global movement that is determined to stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gish is an organic farmer who looked the part with his white
beard and broad-brimmed straw hat. He grows vegetables near Athens,
Ohio, and came to the protest with a group of students from Ohio
University.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters came in all ages and attire. Some had florescent
hair and pierced nostrils, lips and tongues. Others appeared to be
outfitted by L.L. Bean. They sipped bottled water and ate bread and
bean sprouts and dispersed for activities ranging from a ``Cinema
of Resistance Filmfest'' to a ``Save the Redwoods'' teach-in to a
protest outside a Gap store.
</P>
<P>
   Starlene Rankin, a gray-haired Green Party activist from Ames,
Iowa, talked earnestly with the row of stern men and women wearing
bright orange raincoats and white helmets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been telling those officers that they don't have to do
this. They can take off those uniforms and not be robots for the
police state,'' she explained. ``I'm trying to appeal to their
humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   She was undeterred by her failure to find converts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be in the streets tomorrow with or without
puppets,'' she vowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just a loser high school dropout who doesn't like the way
this country is going and wants to change it,'' said Chris, 21, who
came with a New Jersey group called ``Food Not Bombs'' and didn't
want to give his last name. ``The more people who protest to show
that we're unhappy with the way the system is, the harder it is to
ignore us.''
</P>
<P>
   Many were still stirred by the spirit of Seattle, where
sometimes violent protests disrupted world trade talks last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Direct action is the tactic that we have to use,'' said David
Hill, a labor organizer who graduated last spring from the
University of Texas at Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason we're getting so much attention here _ the
only reason that you're talking to me now _ is because of what
happened in Seattle,'' said Hill, who works for a union in New
York. ``Labor is a big part of the movement, but the union didn't
order me to come here. I'm doing this on my own. We're going to try
to shut down the city.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the protesters have promised non-violent
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been saying all the time that it will be peaceful, I
just hope they honor that. We don't want trouble here. We hope the
demonstrators don't resort to that type of activity,'' Chief Ramsey
told reporters. He said police had confiscated large plastic pipe
sections used to connect ``sleeping dragons'' _ human chains _ as
well as gas masks, chains, chicken wire, duct tape and rope.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, police raided a house and found small-caliber
ammunition and firebomb instructions, Gainer said.
</P>
<P>
   He said two people were arrested on Saturday morning for
refusing to obey police orders to leave the ``convergence center.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, about 20 protesters staged a dawn protest outside the
home of World Bank President James Wolfensohn. On his way to work,
Wolfensohn listened to the reading of a protest letter and saw
signs saying ``Wake Up World Bank'' before leaving.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Dart can be reached by e-mail at: bobdart(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   (Alec Schultz can be reached by e-mail at: alecs(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Mobilization for Global Justice: www.a16.org
</P>
<P>
   Ruckus Society: www.ruckus.org
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
