<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7968 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-DEMS-HOLLYWOOD0416-CO     04-15 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-HOLLYWOOD0416-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eds: This version excludes Sat. night fundraiser due to time
element.
 &HT;    Hollywood gives generously to Democrats
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hollywood and the entertainment industry have
become one of the biggest and most reliable sources of political
money for the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Individually, Gore and First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, who is
running for a New York Senate seat, are reaping the biggest
dividends from Hollywood. The Democratic Party as a whole is
benefiting even more, taking in millions in unregulated ``soft
money'' donations from film moguls like the DreamWorks SKG
triumverate comprised of David Geffen, Steven Spielberg and Jeffrey
Katzenberg, among other Hollywood celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the DreamWorks trio, whose film credits include the
Academy award-winning ``American Beauty,'' threw a fund-raiser for
the Democratic Party, raising about $2 million, much of it in soft
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parties all have their soft money troughs,'' said Don
Simon, a consultant for Common Cause. ``The Democrats have
Hollywood and the trial lawyers and the Republicans have a lot of
other business groups.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``From now until the election, we are going to see a
spectacle of extraordinary proportions in terms of the presidential
candidates going around the country sucking up soft money. It's
really going to dwarf what happened in 1996, which in itself was a
depressing spectacle.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal laws restrict the amount individuals can give to
candidates. But their are no restrictions on soft money donations
to the parties, which can use the funds to finance expensive
television advertising in support of the party ticket.
</P>
<P>
   The soft money chase puts Gore in an awkward position
politically. Gore has vowed to make campaign finance reform,
including a ban on soft money, the first piece of domestic
legislation he submits to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a problem to talk about ending the soft money system at
the same time you are participating in the soft money system.,''
Simon said. ``He has to demonstrate his credibility on this
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The liberal streak that runs through Hollywood and the
entertainment industry has long translated into an affinity for the
Democratic Party and Democratic candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But the relationship blossomed under the Clinton administration.
State dinners at the White House routinely include well-known
actors and actresses, some of whom have been overnight guests at
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   When the White House planned ``America's Millennium Gala,'' the
light and music extravaganza on the Mall to ring in the New Year,
Clinton turned to Spielberg to produce an 18-minute movie for the
event.
</P>
<P>
   Quincy Jones and George Stevens Jr. were tapped to produce the
gala. Jones himself has contributed $10,000 in soft money to
Democrats this election cycle, and Stevens has contributed to Mrs.
Clinton's Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Spahn, a spokesman for DreamWorks who formerly worked on
Gary Hart's presidential campaign, said Hollywood feels both a
generational and intellectual affinity for the Clinton-Gore
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very creative, passionate community and this is a
very brilliant, compassionate president,'' Spahn said. ``There were
a lot of very real relationships established.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Mrs. Clinton are now benefiting the most from the
strength of those ties. Walt Disney Co. employees are the largest
group of contributors to Mrs. Clinton's Senate campaign, according
to the Center for Responsive Politics. Mrs. Clinton has raised more
than $321,000 from television, music and entertainment
personalities, according to the center, and that does not include
contributions to a separate New York Senate fund that has been
established to help her campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gore outraised Gov. George W. Bush among entertainment industry
people by more than two to one, according to the Campaign Study
Group in Virginia, which analzyed figures for the Los Angeles
Times. Gore raised almost $500,000 and Bush raised just over
$200,000.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's celebrity contributors include Nicolas Cage, Chevy Chase,
Kevin Costner, Robert DeNiro, Michael Douglas, Harrison Ford, Jerry
Seinfeld, Candice Bergen, Muriel Hemingway and Lily Tomlin.
</P>
<P>
   Among Bush's backers, only actor Chuck Norris, who lists an
address in Texas, stands out. Bush has also received some money
from Terry Semel, the former chairman of Warner Bros., and producer
Jon Peters.
</P>
<P>
   Author David Horowitz, who lives in Los Angeles and is an active
Republican, said Republicans in Hollywood are fearful that their
political views will hurt their careers in a culture that is
dominantly liberal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a kind of political McCarthyism that reigns in
Hollywood,'' Horowitz said. ``There are Republicans in Hollywood,
but the reason you don't see numbers there is because the (Federal
Election Commission) will disclose any contribution you make and
you'll get punished....It's like giving money to Nazis because
that's the way they think of Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   But Horowitz also said that Republican presidential candidates
and GOP leaders in Washington have hurt their image in Hollywood by
blaming the industry for violence among young people.
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle and Republican nominee Bob Dole
both attacked Hollywood in well-publicized remarks about what they
perceived as the negative moral content of Hollywood movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans have helped this along,'' said Horowitz, who has
joined with liberals to fight government intrusion in the movie
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Columbine massacre last year, both Clinton and Gore
have adopted tougher rhetoric on Hollywood, calling on studio
executives to exercise more restraint in producing movies with
sexual and violent content.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Clinton ordered the Federal Trade Commission to
conduct an inquiry into how the entertainment industry markets
sexual or violent material to young people. Hollywood executives
were not happy about the inquiry, set to be concluded this summer,
but are voluntarily cooperating with the FTC, said FTC spokesman
Mitch Katz.
</P>
<P>
   Spahn, the DreamWorks spokesman, counted the FTC inquiry among
the few ``differences'' Hollywood had with the Clinton-Gore
administration. But he said that issue paled in comparison to gun
control, abortion rights, the environment and other issues that
Hollywood cares about and that Clinton and Gore support.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
