<HEADER>
A7969 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     04-15 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DOES NO. 1 PICK FIND HIS WAY TO CANTON? NOT
USUALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At noon on Saturday, Commissioner Paul Tagliabue opened the
National Football League's annual draft of college talent by
announcing that the Cleveland Browns were ``now on the clock'' with
the No. 1 choice. Within 15 minutes, the Browns had to select what
they projected to be an impact player.
</P>
<P>
   Behind a partition adorned with photos of past No. 1 choices in
the Theater at Madison Square Garden, Courtney Brown, a massive
defensive end from Penn State, soon heard Tagliabue announce his
name. Brown is touted as ``the next Bruce Smith,'' the longtime
Buffalo Bills pass rusher now with the Washington Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   But will Brown provide enough impact to sculpt a bronze bust in
the Pro Football Hall of Fame?
</P>
<P>
   According to the impact rate of the overall No. 1 choices since
1936, it's possible but unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   For all the hype each year that surrounds the very first choice
in the draft as if he were some sort of superman in shoulder pads,
only nine No. 1 selections are enshrined in Canton, Ohio: Earl
Campbell, Lee Roy Selmon, Terry Bradshaw, O.J. Simpson, Buck
Buchanan, Paul Hornung, Chuck Bednarik, Charley Trippi and Bill
Dudley.
</P>
<P>
   Three loom as Hall of Famers when they are eligible for
election: John Elway, Bruce Smith and Troy Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   Four others have already displayed enough Hall of Fame potential
in their early NFL seasons to be projected as possible inductees at
Canton barring an injury that would diminish their career: Drew
Bledsoe, Orlando Pace, Keyshawn Johnson and Peyton Manning.
</P>
<P>
   At best, that adds up to only 16 out of the previous 70 overall
No. 1 choices, counting the six years from 1961 through 1966 during
the NFL's war with the American Football League when each league
had a No. 1 choice before the merger agreement created a common
draft in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Only 16 out of 70 is a .229 average, little more than one out of
five, not very good considering that the team selecting No. 1 each
year has the pick of the litter.
</P>
<P>
   The percentage is better lately. In the 17 drafts that began
with Elway's selection in 1983, seven No. 1 choices are either sure
or projected Hall of Famers, more than one out of three. That's
much better than the nine from the first 44 years that are already
enshrined.
</P>
<P>
   Of those nine, five were running backs _ Campbell, Simpson,
Hornung, Trippi and Dudley _ and only one was a quarterback,
Bradshaw. Selmon was a defensive end, Buchanan a defensive tackle,
Bednarik both a center and linebacker who was the NFL's last
two-way player.
</P>
<P>
   And of the 49 players chosen for the NFL's 75th anniversary team
in 1994, only one was an overall No. 1 choice _ Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   So the moral is that most of the NFL's best players were not
overall No. 1 choices; sometimes nowhere close to being the No. 1
choice.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Montana, the best quarterback of the last two decades, was a
third-round pick of the San Francisco 49ers in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Bart Starr, the quarterback on Vince Lombardi's five NFL
championship teams in Green Bay, was the Packers' 17th-round choice
in 1956. Both are in the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely, but occasionally, the No. 1 choice turned into his
team's worst nightmare, a bust who never made any impact at all.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest bust was Aundray Bruce, an all-American
linebacker at Auburn who was chosen by Atlanta with the very first
pick in 1986. After four seasons with the Falcons, only the first
two as a starter, he played for the Raiders as a backup and
special-teams player through the 1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce was what pro football people call a ``tweener,'' lacking
either a linebacker's speed or a pass-rushing defensive end's size.
But more than anything else, he was a wasted No. 1 choice.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the unluckiest choice was Ki-Jana Carter, the Penn State
running back hounded by injuries, especially a damaged knee in his
first exhibition game after being chosen by the Cincinnati Bengals
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Not that most No. 1 choices didn't turn out to be established
players, if not deserving of All-Pro or Pro Bowl honors, like the
Heisman Trophy running backs Bo Jackson, George Rogers and Billy
Sims, as well as such feared pass-rushers as Ed (Too Tall) Jones,
John Matuszak and Bubba Smith.
</P>
<P>
   But as history shows, just because a team has the No. 1 overall
choice doesn't mean that its pick will have enough impact to be
elected eventually into the Pro Football Hall of Fame.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-15-00 1641EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
