<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7975 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ELIAN-CUBANS0416-COX     04-15 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-CUBANS0416-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Miami's Cuban community strengthens its position
 &HT;    By Bill Douthat
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Joe Carollo was furious. The Miami mayor heard that
Geraldo Rivera had just blurted out on network television that a
``mob'' was outside the home of Elian Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday night, Carollo rushed back to the round-the-clock
TV network encampment outside Elian's home to refute the latest
slap at the city's Cuban-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Miami is a peaceful community, Carollo said for the hundredth
time. The crowds are nonviolent and legally assembled, he insisted.
</P>
<P>
   While relatively adept on live television, the mayor and other
political leaders may find damage control in a post-Elian Miami to
be a bigger problem.
</P>
<P>
   National polls show a huge majority of Americans favor returning
the boy to Cuba. And, perhaps more seriously, the uproar over Elian
has deepened the already gaping divisions between racial and ethnic
groups in Miami-Dade County itself. None of Miami's other major
ethnic groups seems able to even remotely see the Elian saga as
Cuban-Americans see it. In fact, they often seem to resent the
Cuban community's attachment to the young boy.
</P>
<P>
   University of Miami professor Juan Carlos Espinosa likens it to
the gulf between white and non-white reactions following the
not-guilty verdict in the 1995 O.J. Simpson trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``People seem to be living on different planets,'' said
Espinosa, assistant director of UM's Institute for Cuban and
Cuban-American Studies. ``For a lot of people, this became another
excuse for Cuban bashing.''
</P>
<P>
   Local polls show the rift. A survey conducted by The Miami
Herald and NBC-Channel Six a week ago showed non-Hispanics in Miami
were less sympathetic to Elian's plight than non-Hispanics in other
parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Espinosa says the poll may have simply offered non-Hispanics an
opportunity to vent their frustration after years of watching
economic and political power shift to an immigrant population that
often prefers Spanish over English.
</P>
<P>
   ``This city has changed demographically, and there are people
who have great resentment,'' Espinosa said.
</P>
<P>
   The non-Hispanics saw Cuban-Americans using Elian for purely
political reasons while ignoring the father's rights to claim his
own child.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every single argument about why Elian should stay begins and
ends with Fidel Castro,'' said Joe Oglesby, an associate editor of
The Herald. ``There is no sympathy and not much empathy for that
position.''
</P>
<P>
   The least sympathetic was Miami's black community, whose own
long-standing civil rights issues don't command equal attention
from Cuban-American political leaders. American and Haitian-born
blacks can only dream of the political clout and media-drawing
powers of the Cuban-Americans, who number about 800,000 in the
county.
</P>
<P>
   So sure is the Cuban community of the righteousness of its
cause, so sure is it of its own might, that it has been able to
stare down the full might of the federal government for months,
including Miami-born Attorney General Janet Reno, who has a
reputation as one public official who cannot be pushed around.
</P>
<P>
   But many Cubans and non-Cubans alike were astounded when 22
mayors stood in front of the federal courthouse on March 29 and
said they would not help federal authorities carry out an order to
pick up Elian from his Little Havana home. Miami-Dade County Mayor
Alex Penelas said he would blame Reno and President Clinton for any
outbreak of rioting. An editorial in The Herald the next day called
Penelas' remarks ``incendiary.''
</P>
<P>
   A Cuban-American businesswoman, Maria Elena Torano, said she was
disappointed by such shrill threats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reminded me of Havana in 1959 and 1960 when 'Yankee go
home' was heard all over,'' said Torano. ``We left Cuba because we
didn't want to listen to those kinds of refrains.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Cuban-American leadership fails to understand is that
they are the majority political power behaving as a minority, said
H.T. Smith, a Miami attorney and activist in the black community.
</P>
<P>
   ``People didn't feel that our mayor was speaking for our
community,'' Smith said. ``He was speaking for his
'confederation.'''
</P>
<P>
   Smith sees Miami broken into a half-dozen major ethnic
``confederations'' that seldom interact. The Elian controversy has
further hardened the boundaries, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to have to fix that or move to a real big
confrontation in the future,'' he warned.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is no newcomer to Miami's ethnic battles. He led a boycott
of hotels when a half-dozen local mayors in 1990 denounced a visit
to Miami Beach by South African leader Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela's crime? He said some nice things about Fidel Castro,
one of the voices around the world against South African apartheid.
The 3-year boycott cost the county about $30 million in lost
conventions and, many say, increased old enmity between the blacks
and Cuban-Americans here.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some Cuban leaders have an idealized view of their
brothers-in-arms links to the black community. Some protest leaders
justify their own acts of civil disobedience by quoting Martin
Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban exiles don't apologize for their successes. In fact, they
are quite publicly proud.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been around here for 41 years and have learned how the
system works,'' said Jorge Escala, 57, one of the thousands who
have demonstrated outside the Little Havana home where Elian is
staying. ``Other groups can do the same thing we have done.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian touched the Cuban community like nothing before. Earlier
ideological battles _ the downing of Cuban-American light plane
pilots who had entered Cuban airspace in 1996 and last year's
protests over an orchestra from Cuba playing in downtown Miami _
saw divisions from within the Cuban community.
</P>
<P>
   Not Elian. Most Cubans see themselves in his innocent face. He
represents the struggle thousands have endured to escape Castro's
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult for Americans to understand the position of the
Cuban community, unless you have experienced the cruelty of the
Castro regime,'' said Rafael Penalver, a Miami attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Carollo, for his part, says he doesn't see any urgent need to
mend fences with the city's other racial and ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``God will be protecting Elian, and Miami will survive,''
Carollo said, wrapping up his final interview at Camp Elian, the
name given to the row of news media tents in front of Elian's
house.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all, we haven't been hit by a nuclear bomb.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
