<HEADER>
A7980 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-DRAFT-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      04-15 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR TOP PICKS IN NFL DRAFT, THEIR BIGGEST DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also FBN-DRAFT, FBN-NOTEBOOK, FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Each year the National Football League invites a
handful of projected top picks to its draft. The players are
whisked through Manhattan streets from news conferences to
luncheons. They shake more hands than they have probably caught
footballs. At every destination, cameras await and questions from
reporters are inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   It is the predraft drill.
</P>
<P>
   In a matter of hours, their lives are shaped. Their new cities.
Their new teams.
</P>
<P>
   It was all unfolded for them Saturday in the Theater at Madison
Square Garden, where the draft was conducted.
</P>
<P>
   Courtney Brown, LaVar Arrington, Chris Samuels, Peter Warrick
and Thomas Jones were among the top picks. On Friday, none of them
knew his destiny. But together they epitomized all of the hope and
anxiety, anticipation and emotion that the draft brings.
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND
</P>
<P>
   Courtney Brown
</P>
<P>
   Defensive End, Penn State
</P>
<P>
   After his senior season at Penn State, Brown was considered a
definite first-round pick, easily among the top 10. But then scouts
viewed his private workout on March 16 and left mesmerized. The
word was out. Brown was a can't-miss at defensive end, one of the
most difficult and important positions to fill.
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Browns made him the top pick of the draft.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Brown said: ``To be the first player picked would be
a real honor, a blessing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've looked at Bruce Smith and Reggie White and tried to learn
from them at my position,'' he said. ``But I don't compare myself
with any of them. Right now, that is not possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown is humble. He is a complete package in character and in
talent. Scouts say he will be a dominant NFL edge rusher. They love
his instincts. He is a natural.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   LaVar Arrington
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker, Penn State
</P>
<P>
   Arrington is an imposing player in size (6 feet 3 inches, 250
pounds) and in attitude. He talks intensely. He exudes confidence.
He is a pure football player, one who can roam from sideline to
sideline and leap over blockers to make Herculean plays.
</P>
<P>
   He has often been compared to Lawrence Taylor, the Hall of Fame
linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   Arrington and Brown, his Penn State teammate, jostled for the
No. 1 spot in the draft. Cleveland chose Brown but was enamored of
Arrington, who went to Washington as the second overall pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just proud to be in the situation I'm in,'' Arrington
said. ``I'm a student of the game. My athleticism and leaping in
the air sometimes to make plays has never been an issue. I can make
the big play or the routine play, and it doesn't matter how you get
there as long as you can get there.''
</P>
<P>
   He was asked whom his former coach, Joe Paterno of Penn State,
would choose if he were forced to choose between him or Brown as
the draft's top choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach has a lot of respect for both of us, and I know he is
proud of us,'' Arrington said. ``But he would probably take
Courtney because Courtney plays defensive end. And the way Joe
plays football, that's the way he would see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean Brown is the better player?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that question will be answered,'' Arrington said.
``Under the right circumstances, I can make a huge impact right
away. But anywhere I go, I'm going to be able to fit.''
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   Chris Samuels
</P>
<P>
   Offensive Tackle, Alabama
</P>
<P>
   While Arrington was drafted by Washington with the No. 2 pick,
Samuels went to Washington, too, at No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins absolutely adore Samuels at offensive tackle. He is
6-5 and 325 pounds. He explodes at the snap of the ball; his
opponent rarely gains the first step. He is excellent in motion,
sweeping left or right, to block defenders. His agility and his
foot quickness are exceptional.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very athletic for a big man, I run well, I'm a smart
player and I'm a good person,'' Samuels said, smiling. ``On and off
the field I handle business, and I won't do anything to hurt the
program.''
</P>
<P>
   His favorite NFL player is Jerry Rice. An offensive tackle who
patterns himself after a receiver? ``He is a class guy,'' Samuels
said.
</P>
<P>
   Samuels said that he should often be eligible to catch passes
for his new team. He said he would find the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Samuels certainly knows how to create a path for others to get
there.
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI
</P>
<P>
   Peter Warrick
</P>
<P>
   Receiver, Florida State
</P>
<P>
   Whenever Warrick steps into a room, eyes quickly follow him.
Warrick can feel everyone looking him over.
</P>
<P>
   Here is the guy who blew the Heisman, some are thinking. Who ran
into trouble at Florida State. Who returned and finished his senior
season in a blaze in the national championship game. Who slipped in
the draft from the top spot to the fourth, where he was chosen by
Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of negativity around me sometimes,'' Warrick
said. ``People are very quick to judge me by something that
happened in college that I did wrong. But I know I can't please
everybody. I can only be what I am _ God's gift.''
</P>
<P>
   With flair. With drama.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick was by far the best receiver in the draft, and many
believed he was the top player in the draft. Elusive. Exciting.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick said his game is like that of the former Detroit Lion
Barry Sanders, though Sanders was a running back. Warrick can stop
and start, juke and spin, do all of the things with a football that
make him a special player.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dream was to be in the NFL, not the top pick,'' Warrick
said.
</P>
<P>
   And how about revenge against the teams that passed him over?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got that in me,'' he said Friday. ``I want to make it to
take care of my mom, and I've got a 3-year-old girl. I want them to
have the best things in life. A lot of people say that if I'm
picked in the No. 4 position and wind up in Cincinnati that I won't
like it there. Right now, I'm nowhere. I can't complain. I'm going
from nothing to something.''
</P>
<P>
   Straight to stardom.
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Jones
</P>
<P>
   Running Back, Virginia
</P>
<P>
   Jones was selected out of Virginia by Arizona at No. 7. In a
draft with backs with bigger, more well-known names (Wisconsin's
Ron Dayne, Tennessee's Jamal Lewis), he surfaced as the scouts'
favorite as the best back.
</P>
<P>
   Jones graduated as a junior but stayed at Virginia to play his
senior year. He was a three-time class president. And he knows
plenty about commitment. He flew to New York for Friday's predraft
activities, returned to Virginia on Friday night to speak to a
group of incoming freshmen _ not football players _ and headed back
to New York for the draft.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-15-00 1732EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
