<DOCNO> NYT20000415.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7983 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NY-HOTELS-REAL-1035(3     04-15 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOTELS-REAL-1035(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: IN NEW YORK, A SCATTERING OF NEW HOTELS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN HOLUSHA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The last few years have been good for New York City
hotels. Occupancy rates have been consistently near or over 80
percent, compared with 63 percent to 65 percent for the rest of the
country. Room rates have been rising, with the cost of a night in
the city last year averaging $213 before taxes, according to Ernst
&AMP; Young, the accounting and consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the strong business, developers have found lenders
willing to finance new hotels. As a result, from 3,200 to 4,000 new
hotel rooms are set to open in Manhattan this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the largest number of new hotel rooms to open in the
city as long as I have been keeping a list, which is back to
1985,'' said John A. Fox, a senior vice president of PKF
Consulting, a hospitality specialist.
</P>
<P>
   The projects _ some new construction, some the renovation of
existing buildings _ are spread across Manhattan, from the southern
tip of the island to the Upper West Side, rather than concentrated
in the traditional midtown and downtown business districts. Some
real estate executives said this is a reflection of how Internet
start-ups and related companies have rejected the high rents and
perceived stuffiness of traditional business centers for places
like the Flatiron District and Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   With a base of about 60,000 rooms already available, the influx
of new rooms is expected to trim occupancy rates only slightly. And
the new rooms may provide some good news for travelers by limiting
the rise in room rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The effect will be to probably reduce the occupancy rate by
one half to a full percentage point and limit room-rate increases
to $10 to $15 a night in calendar 2000,'' Fox said. Nevertheless,
New York will remain a pricey location compared with the rest of
the nation, where the average daily rate is estimated at $81 a
night.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts argue that additional hotel rooms cannot be added
fast enough. ``The New York hotel market is not one of the largest
in the nation,'' said Sean Hennessey, manager of the New York
hospitality practice for PricewaterhouseCoopers, the accounting and
consulting firm. ``Las Vegas and Orlando have about 120,000 rooms.
It could be that we are underserved rather than on the brink of a
glut.''
</P>
<P>
   The new offerings include both the luxurious and the
budget-minded: the return of the Ritz-Carlton brand to Manhattan
after an absence of two years, the advent of the Regent brand _
with a basic room rate of $545 a night _ and the arrival of a Red
Roof Inn, with rates starting at $89 a night.
</P>
<P>
   The single biggest hotel developer this year is Bruce C. Ratner,
the president of Forest City Ratner Companies, which plans to open
more than 900 rooms in hotels attached to entertainment and retail
complexes in Battery Park City and Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   The Embassy Suites Hotel in Battery Park City will have 463
rooms in a 383,000-square-foot complex facing North End Avenue that
will also include a 16-screen, 4,000-seat Regal Cinema, a
20,000-square-foot sports club and several restaurants and stores,
including a 6,500-square-foot Kinko's.
</P>
<P>
   The 444-room Hilton hotel on 42nd Street has been built atop a
335,000-square-foot development that is to include a 25-screen AMC
Entertainment motion picture theater, Madame Tussaud's Wax Museum,
an HMV music store and assorted restaurants and stores. Both Ratner
hotels are expected to open this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Ratner said the addition of the entertainment, food and other
retail uses to the two projects improved the economics of the
hotels to the point where he could obtain financing.
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel Stern, the president of Hartz Mountain Industries, which
operates the SoHo Grand hotel and is due to open the 203-room
TriBeCa Grand, at Avenue of the Americas and Walker Street, next
month, said that finding financing for hotel projects is difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hotels are the last asset class the lenders warm up to and the
first one they go cold on,'' Stern said. ``You can get hotel
financing for about 18 to 24 months in any 10-year period.''
</P>
<P>
   Ratner said that when he took over the Battery Park City project
three years ago, the hotel business was rebounding from a sluggish
time in the early '90s and financiers were still skittish. ``This
is a good example of mixed-use development,'' he said. ``Another
developer had this site and could not make it work. When we took it
over we doubled the amount of retail to absorb more of the cost of
the land and taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Since retailers typically pay a far higher rent per square foot
than do other tenants, devoting the lower floors of the two
projects to stores, restaurants and movies made the projects
bankable, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, putting entertainment and retail stores in
the same building as the hotel improves the quality of a visit to
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people come to New York they don't want to just stay at a
hotel,'' Ratner said. ``Putting the retail and the entertainment in
direct proximity to the hotel benefits both.'' Most of the rooms in
the Embassy Suites open to a central atrium, eliminating the long,
gloomy corridors common in large hotels. One wall of the atrium is
decorated by what the company said is New York's largest painting,
an 80-foot-high by 130-foot-wide work by Sol LeWitt titled ``Loopy
Doopy (Blue and Purple).''
</P>
<P>
   At the 42nd and 41st Street entrances for the Hilton, which is
between Seventh and Eighth avenues, there will be sculptures by Tom
Otterness of figures trying to topple clocks from the marquees.
Original art, sculpture and historic photographs will be in the
public spaces and guest rooms of both hotels. The value of the art
commissioned and purchased for the two hotels is put at $4 million
by the Public Art Fund, Forest City Ratner and Hilton Hotels, which
were partners in the art program.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the new hotels opening are much smaller than the Embassy
Suites, the Hilton and the Sofitel _ the other big, newly
constructed hotel, which is to open in June on West 44th Street,
between Fifth Avenue and Avenue of the Americas, with 398 rooms.
Some emphasize a theme to differentiate them from hotels that
simply offer a room for the night.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Few will be more highly themed than the Library, which is due to
open with 60 rooms by the end of May. It is being developed by
Henry Kallan, who recently opened a similar theme hotel, Giraffe,
at Park Avenue and 26th Street. He also owns the Casablanca Hotel
on 43rd Street just off Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   The Giraffe incorporates balconies in many of its guest rooms to
emphasize a European style. The Library, at Madison Avenue and 41st
Street, is named for its proximity to the New York Public Library
at Fifth Avenue and 42nd Street.
</P>
<P>
   The Library will have a restaurant on the first floor and a
library on the second. The library theme will be carried throughout
the renovated office building, with room numbers using the Dewey
decimal system and a ``library card'' instead of a room key.
</P>
<P>
   Kallan said that each floor would have a different subject, such
as social science, geography or Slavic languages. The rooms
themselves will be stocked with books on the theme subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are interested in a subject, you can book a room and
read up on it,'' said Kallan, who added that he expects to attract
guests from the publishing, fashion and cosmetics industries. He
said he was exploring the possibility of staging special events
with literary trappings, including one with a book-of-the-month
theme.
</P>
<P>
   Kallan said he would try to capitalize on the hotel's location a
block from Grand Central Terminal by developing the 14th floor as a
kind of clubhouse. Suburban spouses who wanted to come into the
city early to shop before meeting a working spouse for dinner or a
show would have a place to rest and store packages and would be
entitled to the corporate rate if they decided to stay the night.
</P>
<P>
   Rates at the Library are to range from $245 to $325 a night,
with the corporate discount lowering that to $195 to $225, Kallan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Across 41st Street, Morris Moinian is preparing to open the
Dylan Hotel in late June or early July. Housed in a building that
was once home to the Chemists Club, the 108-room hotel is the
product of a complete renovation that added four stories to the
existing 10-story structure.
</P>
<P>
   Moinian, who owns Jordan, a woman's fashion company, and the
300-room Wyndham Sugar Bay Hotel in St. Thomas, Virgin Islands,
said he was convinced that there is a place for boutique hotels
that can attract people who prefer not to stay at mass-market
properties, such as the big hotels operated by Hilton and Marriott.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be attractive to creative people from the
fashion and advertising industries who want a small hotel but one
that is business-friendly as well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moinian said he had spent $30 million to renovate the 1903
building, whose exterior is designed in the beaux-arts style. Of
that, more than $1 million was devoted to restoring the facade,
ornate plasterwork and other architectural details. The former
ballroom, with its six-foot stone fireplace and 20-foot ceilings,
is being converted to a restaurant that is being called, in
deference to the building's origins, Rx.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of mahogany and stained glass, and we
preserved as much as we could,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this sensitivity to the past, the guest rooms are fully
wired for high-speed Internet access, with fax capability and two
or three telephones in each room. There are two conference rooms on
the third floor that can be combined to seat up to 75 people, and a
two-bedroom grand suite with a 2,000-square-foot balcony. Room
rates at Dylan will range from $295 to $395, with suites priced
higher.
</P>
<P>
   Moinian said he believed there were still opportunities to
develop boutique hotels in Manhattan neighborhoods that were
largely neglected manufacturing areas but that have been
rejuvenated as the shortage of office space in traditional
locations has brought an influx of new tenants from Internet and
related businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, he said, he is looking in Chelsea for a suitable
property. ``Chelsea appears to be a continuation of SoHo,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Stern of Hartz Mountain said the key to putting a hotel in a
nontraditional area was that the area have a vibrant business
community in addition to attractive living and trendy retail
spaces. ``Nontraditional businesses are spreading into areas like
SoHo and TriBeCa,'' he said, ``and they will generate demand for
hotel rooms.''
</P>
<P>
   The downtown business district is also attracting hotel
development. In addition to the Embassy Suites project, a high-tech
Holiday Inn Wall Street opened last year at 15 Gold St., and a
Ritz-Carlton is being built on Battery Place near the southern tip
of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The 311-room hotel at Battery Place is part of a mixed-use
project being developed by Millennium Partners, which is also
renovating the old St. Moritz Hotel, at Central Park South and
Avenue of the Americas. When complete late next year, the former
St. Moritz will also be branded a Ritz-Carlton and be managed by
the company, which is a subsidiary of Marriott International.
Twelve condominium units, each a full floor of the building, will
also be sold.
</P>
<P>
   The Battery Park project will also include 120 condominium units
in addition to the hotel rooms. Matthew Hall, an executive with
Millennium, said that the sale of the condominiums would improve
the economics of the $175 million project. ``Revenues from
condominium sales will help cover infrastructure costs,'' he said.
``It helps spread the risk and provides a different source of
income.''
</P>
<P>
   The Regent Hotel, in the column-encrusted building at 55 Wall
St., has gradually been opening since last December, and executives
expect it to be fully ready for business by May 1. (Hotel
developers say that these so-called soft openings, in which only a
few floors are ready to receive guests, are a way of getting some
cash flowing early and are a means of training staff.)
</P>
<P>
   The 156-year-old building, which has been home to a stock
exchange and a customs house and had been the headquarters of
National City Bank, has undergone an $80 million renovation and has
144 guest rooms plus a restaurant and lounge. Aimed at affluent
business travelers _ presumably visiting their investment bankers _
the rooms have the typical array of technology features, such as
Internet connections and multiple telephone lines for voice mail
and fax.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the hotel said that no decision had been made
about what to do with the dozen jail cells that are a legacy of the
building's use as a federal building during the draft riots of the
Civil War. They are being used as storerooms, the spokeswoman said,
but some thought is being given to converting them to wine cellars
or a cigar bar.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Suites at the Regent can cost as much as $1,600 a night, but
there are places to stay in Manhattan that do not require a bank
loan.
</P>
<P>
   Apple Core Hotels is converting an office building at 6 West
32nd St. to a 172-room Red Roof Inn, that brand's first entry into
Manhattan. It is expected to open in early May, with room rates
ranging from $89 to $199 a night.
</P>
<P>
   Vijay Dandapani, Apple Core's chief operating officer, said the
Red Roof Inn project, like the company's other four hotels in
Manhattan _ the brands include Best Western and Quality Inn _ is
focusing on hotel basics rather then themes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most customers want a nice lodging experience,'' he said.
``They want a comfortable bed and a quiet room.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that the 17-story former office building had a
50-by-80-foot footprint that made it ``ideal for conversion.'' And
Apple Core knew something about the location. It operates a Best
Western across the street, at 17 West 32nd.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel is aimed at travelers on a budget, but guests will
find amenities not always available at lower-priced hotels. The Red
Roof will have an exercise room, a meeting room and a business
center with computing, copying and fax facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Another facility aimed at budget travelers has been announced by
Ian Schrager, a hotel developer associated with upscale, trendy
projects, who has said he plans to convert the 960-room Henry
Hudson Hotel on West 57th Street to a hotel with rates starting at
$75 a night.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, another group is taking aim at the budget traveler by
converting once-dowdy single-room-occupancy hotels in good
locations to transient lodgings with room rates as low as $75 a
night.
</P>
<P>
   The Citylife Hotel Group has converted the old Allerton House at
57th Street and Lexington Avenue into Habitat, which has been
marketed mostly to European tourists. The hotel is on a popular
shopping street, and the first floor is to house a Kenneth Cole
fashion store, with the hotel's lobby on the second floor.
</P>
<P>
   The old Broadway American hotel at 77th Street and Broadway in
the heart of the Upper West Side has been transformed by Citylife
into On The Ave (for ``avenue,'' although Broadway is not an
avenue). And by this summer the former Martha Washington Hotel at
30 East 30th St. is to be be relaunched by Citylife as Thirty
Thirty.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a total of about 1,100 rooms in the three hotels,
but not all will be available for transient rental, because some
permanent residents remain. In each case all the rooms have been
renovated and equipped with new furnishings and linens. Amenities
include alarm clocks, color television sets, Internet access and
free continental breakfast in the lobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our concept was to be the low-cost provider,'' said Kevin
Maloney, a partner in Citylife. Maloney said that each property is
distinctive and intended to appeal to different segments of the
budget market.
</P>
<P>
   At On The Ave, where the basic rate is $155 a night, the stress
is proximity to the West Side's cultural institutions, such as the
American Museum of Natural History, the Rose Center for Earth and
Space and Lincoln Center, as well as the area's restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   At Habitat the emphasis is on midtown, including Rockefeller
Center, St. Patrick's Cathedral and the Disney Store. There is one
other detail at Habitat _ to get the $75 rate you have to accept a
room with the toilet and shower down the hall and in separate
rooms. For a room with an attached bath, the rate is $105 for a
single and $125 for a double.
</P>
<P>
   Maloney said the baths down the hall had been an obstacle to
European tour groups, particularly those from Scandinavia. He said
he hoped to encourage repeat business by showing that budget
lodgings can be acceptable. ``The idea is if they come and stay in
the city and feel they have not been ripped off, they will come
back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Budget travelers may be tight with a dollar, but that does not
mean they are technically unsophisticated.
</P>
<P>
   Maloney said Citylife had been focusing most of its marketing
efforts on the Internet over the last few months, and that it seems
to be paying off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty to 25 percent of our bookings are coming directly
through the Internet,'' he said. ``People in the budget range shop
the Internet. We are getting over 200,000 hits on our site a
month.''
</P>
</TEXT>
