<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: VOTING FOR BOARDS IN A CO-OP 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAY ROMANO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Elections for board members in a co-op can be as
combative and controversial as those for public officials. And
co-op elections, with complex rules that often allow such things as
proxies and cumulative voting, can also be confusing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many issues to address when running a co-op
election that if I don't do everything exactly right, there's a
good chance I'll end up in court,'' said Maralin Falik, executive
director of the Honest Ballot Association, a not-for-profit
organization in Queens, that conducts elections for trade groups,
special-interest organizations, unions and, with increasing
frequency, housing corporations. ``More and more elections are
being run by organizations like ours, because the rules are so
confusing.''
</P>
<P>
   One potentially perplexing issue in a co-op's annual election,
Falik said, is proxy voting. People taking part in elections of
public officials generally must cast their own vote, either in
person or by absentee ballot. That is not the case in co-op
elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most votes in co-op elections are proxy votes,'' she said.
``And proxy votes can drive you crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   A proxy vote is cast by someone other than the individual or
individuals entitled to vote. In most co-op elections, Falik said,
a shareholder who does not intend to attend the annual meeting is
allowed to give permission to a third party to cast votes on that
shareholder's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   And while that may sound simple, she said, proxy voting can get
complicated and even contentious.
</P>
<P>
   There are two basic types of proxies: directed proxies and
discretionary proxies. With a directed proxy, the shareholder tells
the proxy holder to vote for specific candidates. With a
discretionary proxy, the proxy holder can vote for whomever he
chooses.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we run an election we use directed proxies,'' Falik said.
She said that the proxy forms her organization mails to
shareholders contain the names of all the candidates. Shareholders
who vote by proxy indicate on the form the candidate or candidates
of their choice and then name the Honest Ballot Association as the
proxy holder.
</P>
<P>
   ``That way, the shareholders get to vote directly for the
candidates of their choice with the assurance that no one can
change their vote and no one will know whom they voted for,'' Falik
said.
</P>
<P>
   No such assurances, she said, apply with discretionary proxies.
With such proxies, she said, the proxy holder can vote for whomever
he wishes, even if there was an understanding between the
shareholder and the proxy holder that the shareholder's votes would
be cast in a certain way.
</P>
<P>
   ``A discretionary proxy basically disenfranchises the
shareholder,'' Falik said.
</P>
<P>
   New York state's Business Corporation Law permits shareholders
to use whichever form of proxy they wish, she said, and it is not
uncommon to see large numbers of discretionary proxies used in
co-ops. That, she said, is because most shareholders who vote by
proxy give the proxy to people they believe will vote in a manner
consistent with the shareholder's best interest.
</P>
<P>
   One problem with proxies, she said, is that there is nothing to
prevent a shareholder who has given a proxy to one individual from
giving a subsequent proxy to another. ``It sounds crazy, but
shareholders can give out as many proxies as they want,'' she said.
``My all-time record was 15. We had a guy in one building who was
giving out proxies to everyone in sight.'' By law, she said, the
proxy dated closest to the date of the election is the only one
that counts.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, she said, to ensure the legitimacy of an election,
it must be clearly established that the person who has given the
proxy is legally entitled to do so. ``We've had court-ordered
elections where half the proxies in the previous election were not
signed by the real owners,'' Falik said, adding that she has seen
many instances in which the shareholder's signature on the proxy
clearly does not match the signature on the proprietary lease.
</P>
<P>
   Errol A. Brett, a Manhattan co-op lawyer, said that such
incidents are not always accidental or even innocent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are there proxies that are forged?'' he said. ``Absolutely.
Some of these buildings don't even check signatures, even though
all the signatures are on file.''
</P>
<P>
   Falik said that occasionally, the spouse of a shareholder tries
to give a proxy even though that spouse is not listed as an owner
of the apartment. And there are even cases, she said, in which two
people are owners of record of one apartment and each gives a proxy
to a different proxy holder. In such cases, she said, the proxy
dated closest to the election is the one that counts.
</P>
<P>
   Brett said that if proxy voting seems confusing, cumulative
voting is even more vexing. ``Cumulative voting is hugely important
in buildings where sponsors still own a lot of apartments,'' Brett
said. ``And many shareholders have no idea what cumulative voting
is or how to use it to their advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Generally speaking, he said, a co-op's bylaws determine whether
board members are elected by direct voting or cumulative voting.
With direct voting, Brett said, each shareholder is permitted to
vote his total number of shares for each open seat on the board. A
shareholder with 1,000 shares in the co-op would be able to cast
1,000 shares for each open position.
</P>
<P>
   With cumulative voting, each shareholder starts with his total
number of shares multiplied by the number of board seats available
and can cast them any way he desires. If a shareholder owns 1,000
shares, and there are five board seats available, the shareholder
has a total of 5,000 votes to cast. He can vote all 5,000 for one
candidate, or divide the shares among two or more candidates any
way he wishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you play your cards right, that means that even a minority
group of shareholders can elect at least one board member using
cumulative voting,'' Brett said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The results of co-op elections, lawyers say, can be difficult to
predict and even more difficult to control. ``Election strategies
can be devious and they can be sneaky,'' said James G. Samson, a
Manhattan co-op lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   It would not be at all unusual, Samson said, for a board
candidate to ask a shareholder who has already submitted a proxy
vote for another candidate to submit a superseding proxy to a
different proxy holder. Indeed, he said, it would not be unusual
for the shareholder to agree to such a request to avoid hurting
anyone's feelings. Such tactics, however, can result in fierce
displays of partisanship at the annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been to meetings where there have been chairs thrown
across the room,'' Samson said. ``When people are fighting over
their homes, they can do some really weird things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
