<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: AT INDIANA U., TRUSTEES CAN'T HANDLE COACH KNIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They won't dare.
</P>
<P>
   They've got the tape, but they won't dare.
</P>
<P>
   They've got the evidence that Bobby Knight puts his hands _ or
even one hand _ on the throat of a player during practice.
</P>
<P>
   They have the evidence that Bobby Knight uses vile tactics to
``motivate'' _ that is, bully, threaten, intimidate _ his players.
</P>
<P>
   They have more than two decades of behavior so crude, so
grotesque, that it would get anybody else fired. But they won't
dare.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing against Frederick Eichhorn and John Walda, the two
Indiana University trustees in charge of the Bobby Knight
investigation, but they will not dare recommend dismissal because a
generation's worth of compliant administrators has created the
800-pound gorilla, too big, too mean, too entrenched. The safe path
in Indiana will be to find some middle ground, deliver a slap on
the wrist, slip a letter of warning into Knight's dossier, to keep
him in charge of the Indiana basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   This a man who thinks it is acceptable to wave soiled toilet
paper at his players to make them play better, presumably out of
disgust rather than pride. Coach Charmin.
</P>
<P>
   The hostages identify with the captor. This is well known from
airline hijackings. After a while, the people cower in a corner and
decide their captor isn't such a bad guy after all because he
hasn't killed them, and he actually smiled once or twice. That's
what goes on in the state of Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   It must be embarrassing to Eichhorn and Walda, who were
confronted with a CNN/SI documentary in which one former Indiana
player who later transferred, Neil Reed, claimed Knight had choked
Reed in practice.
</P>
<P>
   Like all the previous Indiana officials during Knight's rule,
the trustees seemed perfectly prepared to label this as outside
agitation designed to hurt the state and its basketball program _
and besides, look at the graduation rate, look at the three
national championships.
</P>
<P>
   Knight himself set the tone with a public filibuster. Right
after the charges were broadcast on CNN/SI in mid-March, Knight
appeared at the mandatory news conference at the regional
tournament, delivering a seething, rambling discourse on his
graduation rates and how he had raised $5 million for the
university library.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not teaching kids to play canasta,'' Knight said. ``This
is a game where kids get bloody noses and get hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   He never addressed the specifics. He talked and talked, and
basically dared anybody to stop him.
</P>
<P>
   If this were a movie, it would have been the scene where the
demagogue finally goes too far, starts babbling in public, until
finally everybody realizes just how far along he is. However, this
was Indiana basketball, so Knight just glared out at the world. The
next night, his players reacted like automatons who had long lost
the will to play.
</P>
<P>
   Then along came more evidence from CNN/SI _ a videotape of a
1997 practice, showing the great man putting his hand on Reed's
throat. If it was not the two-handed Sprewell throttle, with
assistants pulling Knight away, as Reed had claimed, it was surely
the act of a man far out of control.
</P>
<P>
   Now the trustees are stuck with it. The tape is public.
</P>
<P>
   There is also testimony from other former players that Knight
behaved in such an odious manner that they either transferred or
wished they had. You don't get these testimonies from the former
players of John Wooden or Mike Krzyzewski or Dean Smith or John
Chaney or Lou Carnesecca. Coach Charmin is one of a kind.
</P>
<P>
   Most former Indiana players, well placed in the adult world,
speak highly of Knight. But there are also more than a few former
Indiana players who have regrets about their association with
Knight, and this seems to be as important as the graduation rate or
the three championships.
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, in the state of Indiana, a huge segment of
residents _ perhaps still a majority _
adore/respect/admire/support/accept Coach Knight. Or they look the
other way. It's their state and their team and they are entitled to
their loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   But from outside the state, it looks bad, real bad. The face of
Indiana is a man on a dais, talking and glowering, his eyes darting
around the room, as if to say: ``Come and get me. See if you can.''
</P>
<P>
   It is too late to do it peacefully. One university president
after another has passed on Bobby Knight. So he behaved like a
buffoon during the 1979 Pan American Games in Puerto Rico. So he
stuffed a heckler into a garbage can. So he head-butted a player.
So he kicked a player. So he tossed a chair. So he flung a
telephone and intimidated a referee and got himself a victory over
Louisiana State to get to the 1987 Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   It is getting worse. Apparently, after the Ohio State game on
Feb. 19, Knight had an incident with the Indiana athletic director,
Clarence Droninger, that was so tempestuous that Droninger reported
it to a school vice president. The sad fact is that Knight has been
bullying people for decades. Tony Soprano's analyst has a better
chance of locating the source of his anger than anybody in Indiana
has with Coach Knight.
</P>
<P>
   These two trustees live in Indiana. They work in Indiana. They
report back to the state of Indiana. They're going to want to get
along. Indiana has not been embarrassed yet, apparently. By June,
they will write a report saying Knight needs to change a few of his
ways in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Take him off the job? They won't dare.
</P>
<P>
   It will take something worse than one hand on the throat of a
player to end the career of Coach Charmin. Maybe it will be like
Woody Hayes, the blustery football coach at Ohio State, finally
losing it and trying to tackle a foe near the sideline. Or maybe it
will be even worse. And that's scary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
