<SLUG> BC-SEATTLE-REAL-825&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: IN WEST SEATTLE, CONSTRUCTING ROOMS WITH A VIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   By HARRIET KING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The economic boom is visible in the new housing seen
in many older neighborhoods here, among them West Seattle, the
birthplace of the city, where high-density housing is rising along
the Puget Sound in the area where the first settlers landed in
1851.
</P>
<P>
   On Alki Beach across Elliott Bay from downtown, a 10-minute
drive away, developers have constructed 21 buildings in the last
decade or so, with a total of about 440 condominiums. About half of
them have been built in the latest development spurt in the last
five years.
</P>
<P>
   Now, two developers are framing two luxury buildings, with 15
more luxury condos. The apartments have sweeping views of the water
or the downtown skyline and are replacing ramshackle
turn-of-the-century cabins that were summer homes for city
dwellers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like this area because there is not a lot of beachfront
around the downtown,'' said Mark Pryde, a vice president of Pryde
Corp., which sold the last of its 20 apartments at Point Nautica
last year. Pryde has built six buildings in the last six years at
Alki Beach, with a total of 140 apartments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The condominiums have water views that will never be blocked,
and Alki Beach has a resort-town feel, with restaurants and pastry
shops,'' he said. ``We're seeing the rebirth of older cities all
across the country, and this is happening in West Seattle now.''
</P>
<P>
   With 96,000 residents, a mix of blue-collar and professional,
West Seattle was annexed by the city of Seattle in 1907.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1900s, West Seattle was a thriving community when
the Luna Park amusement park was built on the tide flats.
Initially, it drew crowds that arrived by train or ferry from
downtown Seattle to ride the roller-coaster, but its popularity
dwindled, and under pressure from prohibitionists, the park closed
in 1913.
</P>
<P>
   Its remains burned down in 1931, and Alki Beach became neglected
and blighted. Many people considered West Seattle the boondocks,
because the Duwamish River, its eastern boundary, cuts it off from
the rest of the city.
</P>
<P>
   West Seattle's fortunes began to change in 1983 when a high-rise
bridge was built over the river, connecting with Interstate 5. At
Alki (pronounced with a long i, like bike) Beach, the city invested
in a four-mile-long promenade, boathouse and fishing pier. By the
late 1990s, new condominiums and single-family homes were going up,
and restaurants and a bakery were thriving. In December, Starbucks
opened a branch.
</P>
<P>
   Now housing prices are heating up. In 1999, the average price
for 154 condominiums sold was $272,288, compared with $229,730 for
the 227 sold in 1998 and $191,999 in 1997. In 1999, 1,403 homes
sold at an average price of $237,779, compared with $209,115 for
the 1,323 homes sold in 1998 and $184,248 in 1997. West Seattle is
still more affordable than Seattle as a whole, where the average
sale price in 1999 was about $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   As land becomes scarcer in the Alki Beach area, prices for the
new condos are rising. At Point Nautica, the latest Pryde
development, prices ranged from $450,000 to $1.8 million for
apartments with 1,500 square feet to 4,000 square feet. At Pryde's
first building in 1994, prices ranged from $250,000 to $400,000 for
the same amount space.
</P>
<P>
   The company sold about half of its condos before construction
even began at Point Nautica. But the high prices make the
developers nervous. ``Higher land costs create a thinner market,''
Pryde said, ``as more people can afford $250,000 units than
$500,000.''
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks away, on the eastern side of Alki Beach, Sabey
Corp. is completing the shell of a five-story building, called
Duwamish Head. Each condo will occupy a single floor, with 4,000
square feet plus 700 square feet of patio or terrace.
</P>
<P>
   Sabey has sold the top three floors at about $2 million each,
and buyers will hire their own designers to install the kitchens
and to complete the decorating. Joe Wang, the development manager,
said the first- and second-floor units are unsold, priced at $1.4
million for the shell and $1.8 million if Sabey completes the
interiors.
</P>
<P>
   Down the street, construction crews for Seagulf Group are
framing the third floor of a six-story building containing 10
condominiums with 1,681 to 1,880 square feet priced at $599,900 to
$786,000. Two 3,750-square-foot penthouses will be priced at $2
million each. Gerald Potter, the sales agent for the project, said
the smallest unit is sold _ to the banker that financed the
project. ``The lower units have a 35-foot span of windows,'' he
said, ``and the penthouses 70 feet, to capture views.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Roth, a Prudential Northwest Realty salesman, said:
``Construction on Alki will continue for some time as a number of
sites are still left. A lot of units will soon go into areas by the
beach that do not have views. People want to be by the salt water
and where things are booming.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The rising prices at Alki Beach are causing Matt Vaughn to delay
construction until he sees how the market evolves. He has another
reason to delay development of his site, which includes three
quaint 1920s houses. ``It's hard to tear down the homes, especially
since I live in one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   About three miles inland from Alki Beach, the 30-year-old
Westwood Village shopping mall is in the middle of a $10 million
expansion, adding 50,000 square feet to its 350,000 square feet.
Tom Sroufe, the senior vice president of Wesbild Inc., the mall's
owner, said that plans include a new 12-screen movie theater with
2,200 seats.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks from the mall, the nonprofit Delridge Neighborhood
Development Association has just begun selling 17 two-bedroom town
houses. The 1,000-square-foot units, priced at $150,000, are part
of the Brandon Court mixed-use project that also houses the
association's headquarters, a Gai's Bakery and city offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked hard to keep the town houses affordable as part of
our goal to create a thriving neighborhood,'' says Paul Fischburg,
Delridge's director. The group's next project will be a
6,500-square-foot building with a Seattle Public Library branch on
the first floor and 19 low-income apartments above. A few blocks
away, Jefferson Properties will develop 15 acres, a former sand and
gravel pit, into 141 homes priced from $180,000 to $230,000 for
1,200 square feet to 1,800 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the largest vacant residential land parcel left for
development in Seattle because it has environmental problems from
contaminated soil that was dumped long ago,'' said Ray Stevenson,
the developer. He plans to clean up the site this summer and start
construction next year. ``Unfortunately, these are the types of
sites for homes that are left in the city.''
</P>
<P>
   But Stevenson added, ``West Seattle is a great area and appeals
to people who are so tired of the traffic bottlenecks on the
freeways and no longer want long commutes to the suburbs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
