<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7990 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-KNICKS-CAMBY-ART-2TAK     04-15 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KNICKS-CAMBY-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 IT'S A BEAUTIFUL DAY IN CAMBY'S NEW NEIGHBORHOOD  (ART ADV: Photo
NYT7 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The doorbell rang deep in a pristine enclave of Westchester
County, N.Y., and a petite lady with a heavy accent peeled back the
foyer curtain to take a peek at her visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, her eyes grew to the size of poker chips as they took
in 6-foot-11-inch Marcus Camby and his muscular buddy. She finally
cracked the door, listened to their pleas and quickly shooed them
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure she was like, `I'm not opening the door to these
guys,''' Camby said, smiling, one afternoon last week. ``I was
like: `Ma'am, we don't want no trouble. I play for the Knicks.
Really. We're looking for a FedEx letter.' I told her: `It was
delivered here by mistake? You signed for it?' She said, `Uh, uh,
check the trash.' She closed the door. I mean, like, bam.''
</P>
<P>
   That was how, last summer, the county's newest homeowner found
himself staring over a neighbor's garbage can like a wishing well.
He paused, took a deep breath and plunged right into the milk
cartons, soup cans and sticky bottles in search of a letter
delivered to the wrong suburban cul de sac.
</P>
<P>
   He found it. Inside the envelope _ which had not been opened _
Camby found his $100,000 endorsement check. Panic attack over.
</P>
<P>
   These are the kind of dramas that unfold in Camby's life now.
And he could not be more pleased. There are junk fliers in his
mailbox, a neighbor's casserole dish in the fridge and peace in his
life. He has a girlfriend who teaches kindergarten, who can whip up
a delicious lamb chop and who has made sure the furniture in his
new home is not out of a bachelor's shop of horrors. Not a
wagon-wheel coffee table in sight.
</P>
<P>
   `'It's really a good time for me,'' said Camby, whose voice
echoed through the grand parlor in his new home. ``It's like
finally, after everything that has happened, all the stuff in the
past, I can stop holding my breath and exhale.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Camby was living in a rambling old estate as a
renter. He lost a security deposit of sorts the day general manager
Ernie Grunfeld was abruptly sacrificed by the Madison Square Garden
president, Dave Checketts. A year ago this week, Grunfeld _ who
made a move unpopular with coach Jeff Van Gundy when he traded a
rugged folk hero like Charles Oakley for Camby _ was cast aside
when the dysfunctional Knicks were on the verge of missing the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first got here, Ernie was about the only guy who talked
to me,'' Camby said. ``I talked to Ernie more than I talked to
Jeff. He was like the only guy who extended out a hand and seemed
like he wanted me here.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the only guy you think you have in your corner is not
there anymore, it's like: `Oh, boy. Am I gone next?' No one knew
what was going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   That is when the most unlikely finish unfolded. With injuries to
Larry Johnson and Patrick Ewing, Van Gundy had no choice but to
trust Camby. When given the chance, Camby rose out of anonymity as
swiftly and gracefully as a dolphin breaks the ocean's surface. He
was free to make a splash.
</P>
<P>
   Instantly, he was adored. On the June night the Knicks patched
together their makeshift roster and advanced to the NBA finals,
Camby felt the full force of the public's affection. As he exited
the ramp leading from the Garden garage, fans began shaking his
Range Rover like a bottle of champagne.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, I was like, `Whoa, are we getting `jacked?''' Camby
said. ``They were just so excited. So I was like, `Please, Marcus,
don't hit anyone.' It was pretty wild. Never forget it. That's what
you love about New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Camby has reveled in the acceptance. And he has been genuinely
moved by it. After he missed 17 games this season with a knee
injury, he walked to the sideline to check into the Houston game on
March 14 and saw the Garden fans come to their feet. In response,
he swiped his fist through the air.
</P>
<P>
   Camby is going a step further. While some athletes detach
themselves from the public by tinting their windows and building
bigger fences, Camby decided to spend about $10,000 to give a free
party on Sunday for the first 600 fans to show up from 3:30 to 6
p.m. at the Park Avenue Country Club in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just an appreciation party,'' Camby said. ``I just wanted
to say, thank you. That's all.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two seasons, if there are a few traits that have
become clear in Camby's development, it is his desire for positive
reinforcement.
</P>
<P>
   In his first months as a Knick, he did not respond well to Van
Gundy's tough love approach. Even now, as they begin to enter their
second playoff run together, there is still an uneasiness to their
relationship. For Camby, it is more about the lingering sting from
his embarrassing 19-second debut in last year's season opener than
the contract negotiations last March that were based on his limited
playing time.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have said that Jeff cost me like $30
million,'' said Camby, who signed a six-year, $40 million extension
when the maximum was $79 million. ``And I won't lie to you. I was
kind of frustrated at the time. But I knew the consequences of
signing and have security for my family. I'm fine about that.
Everything with Jeff went deeper than money. We're cool now. We'll
never be best friends, but we have a working relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``But sometimes I reflect back and wonder: What if Patrick
didn't get hurt? What if I'd remained the ninth or 10th man?
Thankfully, I got an opportunity.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   This season, his minutes are steadier but there are still games
when his playing time is inconsistent. He averages 26 minutes a
night, puts up an average of 10.1 points, 7.8 rebounds and 2
blocked shots a game, but he can disappear under foul trouble or
get lost on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two things you have to have to be a great player:
consistency and durability,'' Van Gundy said. ``Those are two of
the keys to stepping up to the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   Does Van Gundy mean Camby is fragile or has fallen short of
expectations this season? Probably not. And in some sense, the only
thing that matters is how Camby takes Van Gundy's criticisms. The
feeling-out process between the two continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``You find out over time how certain guys react,'' Van Gundy
said. ``Some guys need to have a foot in their pants all the time.
And it depends on how you do it, too. I think Marcus is on the more
sensitive side of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think with Marcus, he needs to feel good about what he's
doing. And the more upbeat you can keep him, the better off he
responds.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Camby is nothing but upbeat these days. A year ago, before the
playoff run, he would exit the Garden for silent rides home with
his girlfriend, Eva Piper, and his friend Percell Oliver. Now,
Camby's sixth-man role is secure. His days end with his pulling up
in his own driveway and settling into the overstuffed sofa in the
back room of his own house. And then talking all night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me and Eva talk a lot,'' Camby said. ``We met two years ago
and were really just friends for a long time. It's like, you spill
your guts, she spills her guts and you just really learn about
someone else. It's cool. We really connect. I don't meet many new
people, but it's been cool getting to know her.''
</P>
<P>
   He keeps his circle of friends very tight. Once the trade for
Camby was made in the summer of 1998, there were concerns that he
would allow some of his questionable associations from his nearby
hometown to distract him in New York. There were plenty of fast
friends who knew him from the Bellevue Square Housing projects in
Hartford, Conn., enough faces from the past to cause trouble if
Camby let them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mainly had to cut people out of my life,'' Camby said. ``I
used to wonder why Rick Mahorn and guys like that who made it out
of Hartford didn't go back home. Now, being in the NBA, you see why
people don't go back. There's a lot of hatred and jealousy back
home.''
</P>
<P>
   He cannot turn away from the children there, though. He has
started reading programs and helped pay for classes at schools in
Hartford for the same kind of kids that often ended up in his
mother's tidy apartment when Camby was in school.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom was a family advocate,'' Camby said. ``She'd bring kids
home when their parents didn't pick them up. We didn't have a lot.
But then you'd see kids that were a lot worse off. Just to see how
kids were dressing _ some of them had holes in their shoes and
holes in their socks and their clothes were ragged _ I never...it's
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses, gathers his emotions and continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing was,'' he added, ``they always had a smile on their
face. Kids are like that, very resilient.''
</P>
<P>
   Camby has had to do some bouncing back, as well. From the agent
scandal at the University of Massachusetts, from his troubled years
in Toronto, from his invisible start to his Knick career. After all
that, he has found comfort in the very normal rhythm of the suburbs
and acceptance from the fans in the big city.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny,'' Camby said. ``When I first moved in, I guess the
neighbors felt like we didn't ever go to the grocery store. All the
neighbors came over with dishes. We had six dishes in our fridge.
And everyone would say: `Oh, don't worry about it. You can keep the
dish.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And when I was injured, I was getting all kinds of things.
Kids would come by and ring the doorbell, have cookies in their
hands for me. They'd want to see my cars and see how tall I was and
stuff. A few times I was here to answer the door. And some of the
kids would be in shock. They'd say, `Whoa, I didn't really expect
you to be here.' But there I was, answering the door, like, `What's
up, neighbor?'''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-15-00 1758EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
