<DOCNO> NYT20000415.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7992 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-15 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TAKING A LITTLE REST (WHEN TESTOSTERONE LEVELS ARE
HIGH)
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Please note that the word AT within parentheses has been
used in the third graf instead of the symbol, which is
non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(Eds.: Unusual usages in first and next to last graf cq'd) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTEx   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a week when the Jets unaccountably jettisoned Keyshawn
Johnson (was the new owner, a Johnson, afraid he might be confused
with his wide receiver?) and the Rangers flirted with the
possibility of fulfilling my wildest dreams and bringing back Mark
Messier (but without his evil twin, Coach Mike Keenan, they will
never make the pay-offs), a cybersports fan called Marcojcaputo
questioned the decision of Mets Manager Bobby Valentine to ``rest''
Mike Piazza and Rey Ordonez during the first week of a season when
it costs a family of four nearly $175 to attend a major league
game. The first week? How had they exhausted themselves? Would they
come out of the dugout in their robes and give the family its money
back?
</P>
<P>
   ``All the more reason,'' declared Marcojcaputo, ``that moms and
dads should be the heros, and not the players. When was Cal Ripken
rested? I can understand injuries. I remember Johnny Bench being
rested, at either third base (or left field?) and Yogi was rested
in the outfield as well. Valentine lost that game. Fitting?''
</P>
<P>
   I love this e-mail. It feels like wandering outside the glass
booth of the press zoo and sitting in the sun of the grandstand.
The first week of TheLipsite(AT)aol.com there was little response,
many readers apparently thinking it was yet another lame joke from
this corner. Who could blame you? But by the second week, the
response was overwhelming. Keep writing, please, but don't be put
off if some weeks I take the column back. It's mine.
</P>
<P>
   Among the main threads of response have been to a magazine
writer's suggestion that testosterone is the reason men usually
beat women in most sports and to the manifesto from the academics
of the Drake Group calling for an end to the ``student-athlete''
sham. Personally, I think the two threads may cross somewhere;
college presidents drive the semipro sports show, and it takes as
much he-hormone to hustle big bucks as it does to buck the line.
</P>
<P>
   Fiona Bayly of New York, who describes herself as a competitive
runner and a sponsored triathlete, writes: ``Many women can run
faster/lift more weight/throw farther/aim better/use more skillful
stick-work/balance longer and defend more tenaciously than many
men. How come, when they have LESS testosterone?
</P>
<P>
   ``How come?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you how come: through hard work, through education,
through desire, through experience, through talent, and through
self-application towards fulfilling goals, that's how. Lots of
sweat involved; lots of brain, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Karin Winegar, a member of the Frances Willard Society, a group
named in honor of the author of ``How I Learned to Ride the
Bicycle: Reflections of an Influential 19th Century Woman,''
writes: ``I'd like to point out that there are two sports where
women compete equally with men: sailing (where men dominate,
largely, because of economics), and riding (where women dominate,
largely, because of passion for the sport). When we have horses or
boats, the testosterone discrepancy is irrelevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Only money is considered more powerful than testosterone these
days, and money is what college sports seem to be about. ``Just
license them!'' cries Robert Britton of Richardson, Texas. ``If
colleges and universities license their names, logos and the like
to apparel and other manufacturers, it's not a great leap to extend
the concept to the teams. Let some corporation acquire rights to
the Duke Blue Devils or whatever, and let the schools focus on what
they're supposed to be doing _ educating people.''
</P>
<P>
   The idealism of the likes of Britton astounds me. Who says
schools are supposed to educate people? If that were the case, why
would Bob Knight, Jerry Tarkanian, John Thompson (add your own
favorite student-coach) have been hired in the first place? In
fact, toss in Coach K and JoePa, those saints of the sidelines (if
you don't know who they are, write me privately).
</P>
<P>
   Greg Kannerstein, associate dean of Haverford College and
director of athletics, has few illusions along with a certain
Division III arrogance. He writes: ``There's nothing wrong with the
term `student-athlete,' except the way it's been used as a cosmetic
device in some Division I circles to cover up the presence of some
athletes who are anything but students. The experience of a student
who plays intercollegiate sports at any college is qualitatively
different than that of a nonathlete and there's no reason to deny
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than blaming the victims _ in this case, the alleged
student-athletes, the Drake Group ought to go after the real
culprit, the desire of many colleges to use athletic recognition
for institutional prestige instead of focusing on its faculty,
students and academic programs. Athletics is a convenient target
but `reform' will never succeed unless the mind-set which
identifies Duke or Georgetown as teams, not colleges, and which
seeks to evoke financial support for the institution through
athletics no longer dominates.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the problem is not with the athlete but with students
such as ARIZJOE, who overwrites: ``We are on the precipice of the
Internet acting as a superego or a filter which will identify
competitive sports as a fetish born of androgen and an antiquated
vicarious pastime. This foofaraw was the etiologic agent in my
matriculation to Ohio State University. In the dorm, I heard of the
suppression of evidence in the case of a footballer who had
committed a felony. When I questioned this aloud, an all-Big Ten
defensive end lectured me, in his own way, that I had no standing.
He bid defiantly, `Athletes are better people than you.' His manner
was unmistakenly truculent and threatening. He told me to shut up.
At that moment I felt like I did when I learned there was no Santa
Claus. Then the mantra of `God is Dead' hit me. An epiphany of
gridiron existentialism demeaned my soul.''
</P>
<P>
   As well it should.
</P>
<P>
