</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-HUDSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOORS: HUDSON PROJECT SOLVES LONG-RUNNING MYSTERY 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT H. BOYLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Trout fishermen ``read'' a stream to locate their
quarry, and largemouth bass fishermen seek ``structure'' in a lake
to find theirs. But the tidal Hudson River, which reaches from the
Battery in New York City to the Troy dam, has forever been an
entrancing mystery to anglers and anyone else who ever wondered
what the bottom actually looks like.
</P>
<P>
   This 154-mile length of the Hudson is not really a river, but an
estuary, a super protein factory, where fresh water meets salt
water and the tides help trap nutrients that would otherwise
quickly flow to the ocean. In a sense, the Hudson is a shoestring
version of Chesapeake Bay, historically the most productive estuary
in the world.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the wide, shallow Chesapeake has been troubled.
Its flushing rate is not as dynamic as that of the relatively
narrow and deep Hudson, which has the distinction of being the only
major East Coast estuary _ and one of only a handful in the entire
North Atlantic basin _ that retains all of its original fish
species.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, navigation charts of the Hudson note the depth (as
much as 200 feet) and kind of bottom (soft, hard or rocky), but the
ceaseless tidal action and the sediment loads that the estuary
receives render it perpetually murky and generally limit visibility
to 6 feet at best. It has been easier for NASA to send back
detailed pictures of the Martian surface than for New Yorkers to
see what lies at the bottom of the Tappan Zee.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, thanks to the Hudson River Action Plan, a project
underwritten by the New York State Department of Environmental
Conservation, it is at last possible to look at images of the
Hudson's bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Using advanced remote sensing instruments, a team of scientists
from the Lamont-Doherty Earth Observatory of Columbia University,
the Marine Sciences Research Center of State University of New
York-Stony Brook, and Queens College, have so far probed four
reaches of the estuary, totaling 40 miles.
</P>
<P>
   One of the key instruments, a Chirp sonar profiler, evolved from
the prototype devised by Dr. William Ryan, a senior scientist at
Lamont-Doherty, who is putting together the project database. In
1980, Ryan used the prototype to take the first sonar pictures of
the wreck of the Titanic, 12,000 feet down in the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   The project coordinator, Dr. Robin E. Bell, a geophysicist at
Lamont-Doherty who has made five trips to Antarctica, said that the
goal is to depict the different types of Hudson habitats that serve
as home for benthic (bottom-dwelling) invertebrates, such as worms,
crustaceans and insects, and are thus likely to attract fish.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s and '80s, researchers from the Boyce Thompson
Institute and the Department of Environmental Conservation examined
sediment samples hauled from the bottom and found the richest
fauna, up to several thousand invertebrates per square meter, in a
mixture of silt, clay and sand.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic sturgeon appear to favor such an area, while another
bottom feeder, the endangered shortnose sturgeon, occurs over
different types of bottom. Knowledgeable anglers have long known
that striped bass like rocky areas, which accounts for their other
common name, rockfish.
</P>
<P>
   And what have the project scientists found? Just north of the
Tappan Zee Bridge toward the Tarrytown shore, Bell said, they
discovered a 100-foot-long barge on the bottom and the wreck of a
150-foot schooner off Hook Mountain. Wrecks like these, along with
other objects that stand out from the bottom, generally attract
fish.
</P>
<P>
   Between the bridge and Ossining are belts of oyster reefs,
alternately buried and exposed, that extend across the river. Bell
guessed the reefs to be 2,000 to 6,000 years old, but well into the
19th century the waters around New York City remained celebrated
for oysters, so much so that Napoleon III of France dispatched a
naval lieutenant named DeBroca here to take back some for
cultivation. DeBroca returned home with the choicest of all. They
were from the East River.
</P>
<P>
   Just above the Bear Mountain Bridge and hard by the western
shore are three railroad freight cars that tumbled into the river
sometime in the past, while the wrecks of so many small vessels
litter the bottom of Newburgh Bay that the scientists stopped
counting them. Interestingly, the footings of the Newburgh-Beacon
Bridge, a favorite fishing ground for stripers, have also made
their mark on the bottom; sediment ridges a mile and a half long
are behind the downriver side of each footing.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five feet down off Bannerman's Island, the scientists
discovered four chevaux-de-frise, relics from the Revolutionary
War. Each cheval-de-frise originally consisted of sharpened wooden
poles pointing toward the surface and affixed in a rectangular rock
base. American troops sank them to stop British warships from
moving upriver. Although never realized, the British grand strategy
was to seize the Hudson River Valley, divide the colonies in two
and subdue them one by one.
</P>
<P>
   Below Bannerman's Island is what Bell described as ``a strange
structure that looks like a pair of stone walls, 50 feet apart and
200 feet long, in 20 feet of water.'' Its purpose is unknown, and
Bell called it ``the biggest historical mystery we've
encountered.''
</P>
<P>
   Off New Hamburg, Diamond Reef looms up from the bottom.
Traditionally one of the best fishing spots for striped bass, white
perch and snapper bluefish, the image reveals how the reef was
named. It is, Bell said, ``shaped like a diamond, with the rock
trending northeast-southwest.''
</P>
<P>
   Between Kingston and Saugerties, the bottom resembles the Sahara
Desert, with rank upon rank of 10-foot-high dunes of sand and silt.
They are formed by the current that is gradually moving sediments
downriver, but in a few places, Bell said, the incoming tides may
be moving dunes upriver.
</P>
<P>
   Between the cities of Hudson and New Baltimore lie glacial lake
sediments, bricks from abandoned brickyards and coal from long-gone
steamboats. This reach of the Hudson may be the least exciting to
anglers, but to Bell: ``The river is as exciting as anything in
Antarctica, and compared to Antarctica it has wonderful
ramifications in more directly recording human activities.
Understanding your own back yard can be just as important as
understanding the remote corners of the earth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
