<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-ROBINSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBINSON'S DEVILS HAVING FUN 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It didn't work out the way it was supposed to for Larry
Robinson, but now he has this second chance, like a rebound in the
slot with the goalie sprawled out of position. Will he bury this
one in the net or misfire on his next and possibly best shot?
</P>
<P>
   When Robinson left the New Jersey Devils after their Stanley Cup
of 1995, he was a highly regarded assistant coach on the way up.
With his Montreal pedigree as a player and his apprenticeship under
Jacques Lemaire in New Jersey, Robinson went to the Los Angeles
Kings as a can't-miss candidate.
</P>
<P>
   And he missed. The Kings made the playoffs only once in
Robinson's four seasons and were swept in four games. Robinson
developed a stress condition that caused patches of skin to fall
off his arms and hands. He became known as a nice guy and a good
teacher whose players took advantage of his good nature.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils were aware of it when he returned to New Jersey this
season as an assistant to Robbie Ftorek. ``He had a young team in
L.A. and maybe the message didn't come across as good as it's
coming toward us right now,'' the veteran goalie Martin Brodeur
said. ``Hopefully we'll be able to keep that respect towards him.
He's got a lot to teach us.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson became their headmaster late in the season when Ftorek
was fired. Although he maintains friendly relations with the
players, Robinson put them through unusually long and strenuous
practices before the current playoffs opened against Florida.
</P>
<P>
   That paid off as the Devils defeated the Panthers by 4-3 in the
opener on Thursday night. Since then, Robinson seems to have a
jaunty bounce in his step. His chipper mood has spread through a
roster that often seemed grim under Ftorek. The series resumes
Sunday night at Continental Arena, and Robinson is eager.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I look forward to, I love the playoffs,''
Robinson said. ``This is what it's all about. You know who you're
going to be facing, the same team for at least a week. Everybody
seems to be more focused. The guys are more intense. This is like
the start of a long journey. It's very exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Stevens, the captain, said Robinson is ``very positive,
very confident, very approachable'' and ``very much a players'
coach.'' They all know he is in the Hall of Fame as a star
defenseman whose 20 years in postseason play are tied with Gordie
Howe for the National Hockey League record.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tells us to play with confidence and have fun,'' Stevens
said.
</P>
<P>
   That word ``fun'' is uncommon around the Devils. ``You don't
really associate fun with the playoffs,'' Stevens said, ``because
it's usually a dog fight and a long, hard road. But it does make
sense. You've got to enjoy the game. Work hard and have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Robinson senses that the Devils' early exits in recent
seasons happened in part because the players were mentally
exhausted by the rules and pressure from General Manager Lou
Lamoriello and his coaches. When two Florida goals late in the
first period Thursday cut a Devils lead from 3-0 to 3-2, some
Devils expected anger from Robinson. He maintained his composure,
and this impressed Scott Gomez, the rookie star, who went out and
scored the winning goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was upbeat and he lit a fire under everybody in a positive
way,'' Gomez said. ``Nothing negative was said.''
</P>
<P>
   In general, Gomez added: ``With Larry, it's fun coming to the
rink. I'm not saying anything against Robbie, but every coach
brings something different. Larry's always positive. He's always
joking around. If you do your job, he's going to let you know you
did a good job. If you're not doing what you're supposed to, he's
going to tell you in a positive way.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson played on six championship teams in Montreal. His
teammates from that dynasty have flourished. Ken Dryden is the
president of the Toronto Maple Leafs, a vastly improved team under
his regime. Bob Gainey is the general manager of the Dallas Stars,
the defending champions. Lemaire is a consultant with the
Canadiens. They were not only the best as players but also among
the brightest, a group of hockey sophisticates whose influence now
guides the league.
</P>
<P>
   Their coach in that 1970s era, Scotty Bowman, is with Detroit,
seeking his third Red Wings championship in four seasons. Like many
players from that group, Robinson carefully chooses his words when
asked about the old coach who sometimes motivated players with
psychological ploys that mixed fear with humiliation. What did
Robinson learn from Bowman?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember that far,'' Robinson said, dodging the
subject the way a player might dodge a body check. ``Short-term
memory.'' Perhaps this spring, in his short-term assignment,
Robinson will fashion something memorable for the long term.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
