<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HINDSIGHT SHOWS THAT NFL DRAFT IS NEVER A SURE THING 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also FBN-DRAFT, FBN-DRAFT-ASSESS, FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN)  
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To demonstrate just how much a game of chance the
National Football League draft is, these were the top 10 players
picked in 1992: Steve Emtman, Quentin Coryatt, Sean Gilbert,
Desmond Howard, Terrell Buckley, David Klingler, Troy Vincent, Bob
Whitfield, Tommy Vardell and Ray Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   Busts, busts and more busts. Thus the following phrases,
overused by various draft geeks, should be banned from the English
language: ``destined to be great'' and ``future NFL star.''
Because, in fact, no one knows. For goodness' sake, Emtman was the
first pick in the draft and played only two years.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to this draft and the talk centering on two Penn
State players, defensive lineman Courtney Brown and linebacker
LaVar Arrington. Many analysts believe they are guaranteed to be
stars in the NFL, but as history has proved, there is a fine line
between success and failure, and only time will tell how good both
players become.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, draft debates have centered on two players, as
when personnel officials argued whether Rick Mirer or Drew Bledsoe
was the better quarterback, the same way there are now heated
discussions about whether Brown or Arrington was the better
selection.
</P>
<P>
   Twice in the past three years, the Indianapolis Colts have been
in the middle of these kinds of arguments. Two years ago, they had
to decide between quarterbacks Peyton Manning and Ryan Leaf. Then
last year, the debate was which running back was better, Edgerrin
James or Ricky Williams?
</P>
<P>
   No one would question the Colts' selections now, though at the
time many did, especially in the case of James and Williams, with
many league executives believing that Williams was by far the
better player. But teams and the news media forgot the lesson
learned from 1992: that the draft is as much about luck as it is
about thorough preparation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are intangibles you cannot account for,'' Denver coach
Mike Shanahan said.
</P>
<P>
   What happened with the Colts shows how one pick can change the
fortunes of a franchise, either taking it to the next level or
hurting it.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the NFL believed that Leaf, out of Washington State, was
the best quarterback in 1998, and maybe the best player in the NFL
draft. Some were saying Leaf would be a quarterback for 10 years,
break passing records and win Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts weren't buying it. General manager Bill Polian thought
Manning's maturity gave him an edge. The inner strength, or
maturity, of a player is something that no test can measure, and
thus Polian went by his gut. Indianapolis had the first pick in the
draft in 1998 and chose Tennessee's Manning.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego had wanted to pick Leaf all along and ended up dead
wrong. Manning is a Pro Bowler and Leaf has been a tremendous
disappointment. Leaf has been through two shoulder operations, and
just last month he was called fat and ``out of shape'' by a
teammate, Fred McCrary.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego's quarterback situation is so messy that the team
worked out the free agent Todd Marinovich, who spent three months
in jail in 1998 after pleading guilty to charges that he grew
marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Colts were faced with another tough decision.
Many NFL scouts as well as members of the news media had Williams
rated ahead of James, mainly because Williams had both bulk and
speed.
</P>
<P>
   But again the Colts followed their instincts. They thought that
James was a better pass receiver and that he was more mentally
prepared to make an immediate impact. They turned out to be right.
</P>
<P>
   James is a hard worker who is respected in the locker room,
while Williams, selected by New Orleans, has proved to be immature
and injury prone and is disliked by many of his teammates who
believe he is lazy and a complainer.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts leave very little to chance while preparing for the
draft. Months before, they make contact with every football school
in the country, asking for thoughts on their players. The Colts
usually view more than 100 players either on tape or in person, and
each must submit to personal interviews and psychological tests.
Indianapolis' examinations are similar to those of other teams, but
Polian adds his personal touch, his brilliant instincts.
</P>
<P>
   But the line is thin. One pick can ruin a franchise for years.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Ditka traded the entire Saints draft last year for
Williams. Ditka was fired and ended up leaving the organization in
disarray. The Chargers' decision to select Leaf may end up being
one of the more disastrous ones in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   Arrington and Brown may both be great players, but there was a
time when the Chargers thought the same thing about Leaf. That is
the most intriguing _ and frustrating _ part of this inexact
science known as the draft.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
