<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8003 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-DRAFT-JETS-NYT &LR;      04-15 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS GET TWO ON DEFENSE, THEN A QUARTERBACK 
</HEADLINE>
   By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Jets, coming off one of the most controversial and
shocking trades in franchise history, indicated that while they
insist they want to make an immediate run at a title, they are also
building for the future. They failed to trade up in the early part
of Saturday's National Football League Draft to grab a top-rated
receiver and instead used two of their first-round picks to fill a
desperate need for a pass rush _ defensive end Shaun Ellis and
linebacker John Abraham.
</P>
<P>
   But coach Al Groh talked before the draft about extending the
Jets' ``cycle of success,'' and he is apparently looking for a
long-term cycle. With the third selection of the first round, the
18th overall, the Jets again passed on a receiver in a
receiver-rich draft.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps harkening back to the dismal days after quarterback
Vinny Testaverde went down in the season opener last season, the
Jets chose a bit of a project, plucking quarterback Chad Pennington
of Marshall, who had fallen from a top-10 pick into the Jets' laps.
</P>
<P>
   When Testaverde, 36, was injured last season, it became obvious
the Jets did not have a quarterback prepared to step in. But Ray
Lucas emerged as a suitable backup during the second half of the
season, and the acquisition of Pennington calls Lucas' future with
the team into question.
</P>
<P>
   Groh said he was surprised that Pennington, who passed for 4,006
yards as a senior, had dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at ourselves for the long range and we'll have
two very good quarterbacks in place,'' Groh said. ``Ray has proven
he can win for our team. When Vinny chooses not to play anymore,
we'll still have a 1-2 circumstance, however those two work it out.
He keeps us from getting into a position where everything else is
in place and we don't have a quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis was the second-rated defensive end in the draft, and he
and Abraham, a former defensive end who shifted to linebacker in
his senior year, provide the pass-rush for the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation in the wake of the Jets' trade on Thursday with San
Francisco to move up to the 12th pick centered on the Jets wanting
to get Ellis before Green Bay could. And their commitment to Ellis
became obvious when the Jets let just 2:10 go off the clock before
making their pick.
</P>
<P>
   The selection of Abraham was a surprise not so much because he
was not projected as a first-round pick but because the Jets'
offensive needs _ they also were looking for a tight end _ seemed
so pressing.
</P>
<P>
   In Ellis (6-4, 285 pounds), the Jets get a likely immediate
starter who combines size and speed. Last season, only Cleveland
had fewer sacks than the Jets had last season and the defensive
ends had just four sacks. Ellis had eight and a half sacks, 14
quarterback pressures and 11 tackles for lost yardage after
recovering from a 1998 car accident in which he fractured a hip _
and nearly ended his career _ after falling asleep at the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham (6-3, 251) was projected by some scouts as a defensive
end but is a pure pass rusher. He had six sacks and 12 quarterback
pressures last season and five stops for losses of 18 yards. But in
10 games, he showed his versatility, with 60 tackles and five
fumbles caused.
</P>
<P>
   ''With our first two players we were looking for players with
power and speed,'' Groh said. ``Both should develop into three down
players.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering the draft, the Jets' needs were obvious: a receiver to
replace Keyshawn Johnson, a pass-rushing linebacker or defensive
lineman, and a tight end. In the days leading up to the draft, it
was thought that the Jets had focused on trying to acquire Plaxico
Burress, the Johnson-like receiver from Michigan State.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the trade speculation surrounding the Jets had centered
on how far they would have to move up to take Burress. And when the
Jets made the deal with San Francisco to move up to the 12th
overall selection, it was inferred that they were hoping to get
Shaun Ellis, the Tennessee defensive end, before Green Bay could
grab him.
</P>
<P>
   But on Saturday, the early part of the draft unfolded,
surprisingly, according to order. The Jets could not pull off a
trade with Baltimore, with the fifth pick or with any of the other
teams between fifth and eighth. And when Pittsburgh was on the
clock with the eighth pick, the Jets had their last chance to move
up to secure Burress.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh was believed to be choosing between Burress and
quarterback Chad Pennington of Marshall. When the Steelers pulled
off a mild surprise and went with Burress, and Baltimore completed
their ideal first round by selecting Travis Taylor of Florida with
the 10th pick, the Jets had lost out on the three best receivers in
the draft and had lost the chance to make a high-profile pick to
replace Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets came the hard way by the unprecedented bounty of picks
that they started the day with. The 18th pick is theirs because
they finished a disappointing 8-8 last season. The 12th pick was
received in a trade with San Francisco for the Jets' 16th pick
(packaged with a second-round pick), which they acquired as
compensation when they lost their second head coach in two days,
Bill Belichick. And the 13th and 27th picks are, of course, Tampa
Bay's parting gift for Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Al Groh spoke in the week before the draft _ and in the
days before the Johnson trade _ about his hope to extend the Jets'
``cycle of success.'' By that he meant that he did not want to see
the Jets subjected to the same fate as San Francisco and, to a
lesser extent, Dallas: the dramatic dropoff in results when age and
salary-cap restrictions limit the team's ability to restock with
young talent.
</P>
<P>
   That was a veiled reference that suggested the Jets would not
gut the rest of the team to restructure Johnson's deal. Later, Groh
added that he thought Johnson could be replaced, likening the
situation to how Indianapolis successfully replaced the departed
Marshall Faulk with Edgerrin James.
</P>
<P>
   After Johnson's trade was completed Wednesday, and after he had
finished dumping the blame for his departure squarely in Groh's
lap, the Jets did their best to boost their long-distance carrier's
profits.
</P>
<P>
   They worked the phones furiously, talking to almost everyone
ahead of them _ and several teams behind them _ in the draft
pecking order about a trade. They let their ears perk up, albeit
briefly, at the mention of Carl Pickens, the disgruntled Bengals
receiver. They inquired about the Browns' first overall pick, the
Bengals' fourth pick, the Ravens' fifth overall pick, the Steelers'
eighth pick.
</P>
<P>
   If this is, as expected, the final draft of Bill Parcells'
career, he earned the rest this week. But, as teams maneuvered
throughout the league for what was expected to be a chaotic round
of draft-day deals, the Jets made just one move before the draft
began: the trade with San Francisco that gave them the 12th pick
Saturday, which they acquired, some league executives felt, because
they were concerned Green Bay would take defensive end Shaun Ellis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-15-00 1842EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
