<DOCNO> NYT20000415.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8005 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-ROYALS-NYT &LR;      04-15 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ROYALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY-SEASON CLEMENS HAS ENOUGH TO GET BY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roger Clemens keeps teasing the New York Yankees, pitching the
way they hope that he will in some spurts and then disappointing
them in others. They always want to believe that Clemens can
dominate, and sometimes he does. But there are other puzzling
starts in which Clemens is ordinary and the Yankees become
exasperated. On Friday night, Clemens was barely ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   A botched pop fly helped the Yankees score two important runs
and defeat the Kansas City Royals, 7-5, as Clemens lasted six
innings to win. The Yankees can preach about how Clemens battled on
a chilly night when his fastball was inconsistent and when he
needed to rebound after slogging through the first two innings. The
Yankees can dig for positives with Clemens because it is only
April.
</P>
<P>
   But Clemens did not offer an artistic effort in becoming the
first Yankee starter other than Orlando Hernandez to win a game
this season. He gave up five runs and seven hits in six innings,
walking four, hitting one and throwing one wild pitch that scored a
run. So what were the positives? Well, Clemens never lost a lead,
although the leads felt perilous, and he won despite unleashing 116
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I pitched well,'' Clemens said. ``I was in bad counts.
I've got to stay away from bad counts.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens said that he had good velocity on his fastball and that
his split-finger fastball was jumping. He forgot about the slider
that did not break and he overlooked the inconsistency that he
displayed too often. Clemens kept saying that the only problem he
had was falling behind batters, but those bad counts were caused by
his wayward pitches, so the pitches that led to the counts, not the
counts, were the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're throwing far too many pitches,'' Manager Joe Torre said.
``A lot of 3-2, 2-1, 3-0. You can't pitch like that.''
</P>
<P>
   It was another ugly game for the Yankees, another game in which
they did not play too crisply and still won. The Royals rumbled
into Yankee Stadium as the most dramatic team in the major leagues
after winning four straight games in their last at-bat. The streak
died Friday night and Mariano Rivera bagged the final four outs to
erase Kansas City's chance for more drama and mercifully end a
three-hour-48-minute affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was long and ugly,'' Torre said. ``It's just nice to be
able to get away with games like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees moved their games to 7:05 p.m. from 7:35, but that
early start was forgotten as some players left the Stadium close to
midnight. ``Maybe we're going to have to start them at 6 now,''
Jeff Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens began the second by drilling Mike Sweeney in the right
forearm with a fastball, a pitch that he said flew out of his hand.
One out later, Clemens walked Mark Quinn. A groundout pushed
runners to second and third with two out.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens fired two quick strikes past the No. 9 batter, Rey
Sanchez, setting up an enviable situation where he could pump a
fastball past Sanchez or get him to bite on a splitter. But
Clemens' splitter never dived and Sanchez lashed it to center for a
two-run single.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Posada's two-run homer into the right upper deck in the
second and Ricky Ledee's run-scoring double in the third put the
Yankees ahead, 3-2. The Yankees received two breaks in the fourth.
Derek Jeter's tapper to second went for an infield single to
prolong an inning when replays indicated that he was out. Bernie
Williams hit a pop-up to shallow left field with the bases loaded
that inexplicably dropped in for a two-run double and a 5-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clemens bounced a splitter to bring in Kansas City's
third run and, after Jeter's two-run single made it 7-3, Clemens
gave up a bullet of a two-run homer to Gregg Zaun to keep the
Royals close. Two batters later, Clemens trudged to the dugout
after finishing the sixth and finishing his night. Clemens got the
victory. He just left some unanswered questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now,'' Torre said, ``he's not in a groove.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-15-00 1849EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
