<DOCNO> NYT20000415.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8011 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-N     04-15 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTEBOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The scenario is ripe for a recurring nightmare. Darryl Kile
escapes from Colorado after being trapped there for two grueling,
punishing, agonizing years. Just when he begins to flourish in his
new home, he finds himself back in Colorado and again spends a
grueling, punishing, agonizing night.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Kile, it was not just a nightmare. After
winning his first two starts for St. Louis, he pitched against the
Rockies on Thursday night and did not survive the second inning.
The team with which he struggled the past two years pummeled him
for 11 runs (8 earned), including 10 in the second. He gave up two
consecutive home runs, hit three batters and threw two wild
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he went into that game with some apprehension,'' said
Dave Duncan, the Cardinals' pitching coach. ``Even in the first
inning it looked like he was trying too hard. I think he was
affected by being back in Colorado. You can't get distracted like
that. Being in that ballpark and trying to do so good, he lost his
concentration. I talked to him after the game. He was pretty
frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Kile is one of Duncan's two pet projects this season. Pat
Hentgen is the other. How successful the Ph.D. of Pitching is could
determine how far the Cardinals go in the National League Central
race.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan's goal is to return Kile and Hentgen to their better
days, when Hentgen won the American League Cy Young award (1996)
with Toronto and Kile won 19 games (1997) with Houston. With the
lusty hitting the Cardinals have unleashed on the league, they
could win the division title if their pitchers do their part.
</P>
<P>
   Until the Rocky Mountain nightmare, the Duncan developments
seemed promising. Although Kile and Hentgen did not pitch shutouts,
each won his first two starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kile had been throwing the ball real good, and I think he'll
continue to throw the ball real good,'' Duncan said.
</P>
<P>
   Hentgen, he said, has improved steadily. ``He still hasn't
picked up that velocity that I think he has a chance of
regaining,'' the coach said, ``but he's been getting himself into a
better position to throw the ball, a more powerful position. In two
or three more starts I think he'll be really good.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan said Hentgen had steadily altered his delivery to the
point that it affected the speed of his pitches. A study of
videotapes from better years showed that Hentgen, a right-hander,
was leaning toward first base and not moving directly toward home
plate when he prepared to throw his pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to bring that delivery back into balance,''
Duncan said. ``If we can do that, I think what we'll see is Pat
pick up some velocity. There's no reason he should have dropped off
in velocity. He's as physically strong as he's ever been. But his
delivery was not enabling him to take advantage of his strength,
putting him in a position where he can have his maximum arm speed.
If we can get him back into balance, then everything else is going
to fall into place.''
</P>
<P>
   Kile had a different problem, Duncan said. It is the free-agent
syndrome. A player moves to a new team with a lucrative contract
and thinks he has to justify the contract by doing more than he had
done to warrant the money. Instead, he winds up performing poorly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darryl may have varied off the path of success simply because
he tried to do more than he had done before when he pitched good,''
Duncan said. ``He tried to add to his game and it probably took him
away from the things that he had done consistently before. The
whole thing is to get him back on a more narrow path doing things
that he has a lot of confidence in and he knows he can execute. I
didn't do anything major other than talking to him about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kile has two poor seasons to overcome, two seasons in which he
compiled a 10-12 record with a 6.76 earned run average at Coors
Field. A trade to the Cardinals freed him from that nightmarish
park, but the schedule and the Cardinals' pitching order brought
him right back to it.
</P>
<P>
   Home Run Ho-Hum
</P>
<P>
   The National League's Home Run Central has not taken off the way
it was expected to. Mark McGwire has a bad back, and Sammy Sosa and
Ken Griffey Jr. have started slowly, although Griffey hit his first
three home runs in three consecutive games last week.
</P>
<P>
   The big hitter in the Central Division has been Jim Edmonds.
Rumors in the winter and spring had him heading from Anaheim to the
Yankees or Seattle or any number of other places, but he wound up
in St. Louis. In the team's first 11 games he amassed 16 hits in 35
at-bats, slugged five home runs, walked 13 times and compiled a
1.000 slugging percentage (same number of total bases as at-bats)
and .612 on-base percentage to go with his .457 batting average.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Starts Fast
</P>
<P>
   Frank Thomas was probably the most maligned player of the
spring, receiving critical comments from former teammates and
undergoing unusually close scrutiny in news media reports. It did
not help that his performance the past two years did not live up to
his production in his first seven full seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Determined to get back to those All-Star seasons and silence his
critics, Thomas is off to a dazzling start for the Chicago White
Sox. In the team's first 11 games (through Friday night), he had 22
hits in 46 at-bats for a .478 average, three home runs and 10 runs
batted in.
</P>
<P>
   Slow Starts
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Mike Hampton, pitching for Houston, lost only four
games and Rey Ordonez, the Mets' shortstop, committed only four
errors. In the same game last week, Hampton, now a Mets pitcher,
lost his third game of this season and Ordonez made his third
error.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Morgan holds the unenviable record of having lost games for
more teams (11) than any other pitcher in major league history. But
Morgan, a 40-year-old right-hander pitching for his 12th team, has
found a new career. Filling in for Matt Mantei, the Diamondbacks'
injured closer, Morgan relieved three times and earned three saves
in a span of six Arizona victories. In the first 18 years of his
career, Morgan gained three saves in his 71 relief appearances. He
has not added the Diamondbacks to the lengthy list of teams with
which he has lost games.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Double Duty
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza needed extra innings, but he kept this season's most
intriguing streak alive Friday night by hitting his second home run
of the Mets' game in Pittsburgh in the 12th inning. Each day since
the season really began (that is, excluding the two games in
Japan), at least one player entering Saturday's schedule had hit
two home runs in a game.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza was the 31st player to perform the double (Kevin Elster
is the only one of the group who hit three in a game). In the
corresponding period last season, 16 players had done it.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza was the 17th in the National League, which had 11 a year
ago. The huge leap has been in the American League, 14 as against
five a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ball of Fire
</P>
<P>
   With home runs flying out of parks more frequently than ever,
commissioner Bud Selig has directed that the baseballs be tested
again. They have been tested the past couple of seasons, officials
have said, and found to be no different from their predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   Selig does not expect the results of the new tests to show
anything new but wants to be in position to answer the charges that
the ball is more potent. He is not necessarily looking to defuse
the bombs that are falling on the poor pitchers. Fans like home
runs and high-scoring games.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing wrong with pleasing your customers,'' Selig
said.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the Houston Astros and the San Francisco Giants
seemed to have had in mind when they built their new parks. Fans
like home runs? Okay, keep the fences close. The distance down one
foul line in each park is shorter than the minimum 325 feet the
rules call for. But both clubs say they had other reasons for the
abbreviated distance.
</P>
<P>
   The right-field line at the Giants' Pacific Bell Park is 309
feet. ``It wasn't a matter of wanting to do it that way,'' said Bob
Rose, the team's vice president for communications. ``It was a
matter of what's behind it, which is water. Literally they couldn't
go any farther.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros said their 315-foot distance down the left-field line
at Enron Field stemmed from an economic decision. They said a
greater distance would have required the span across the
retractable roof to be longer and therefore cost significantly
more.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams had approval of the commissioner's office for the
shorter lines. The Astros nevertheless defended their left-field
line by saying the rule book provides only a guideline on
distances. The wording, however, is stronger than a guideline. Rule
1.04 states that any park built after June 1, 1958, ``shall provide
a minimum distance of 325 feet from home base to the nearest fence,
stand or other obstruction on the right and left field foul
lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming Events
</P>
<P>
   John Rocker is eligible to return from his two-week suspension
Tuesday night when the Atlanta Braves play at home against
Philadelphia. The Braves hope he will concentrate on his pitching,
believing that his fastball is so much more eloquent than his
mouth.
</P>
<P>
   The owners will meet in Houston Monday and Tuesday but will not
vote on realignment. That step is expected to come at their June
meeting. However, John Harrington of Boston and David Montgomery of
Philadelphia will make a presentation on realignment. Barring an
unforeseen development, Arizona will move to the American League
West, Tampa Bay to the National League Southeast and Texas to what
will become a six-team AL Central.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
