<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-WOOD-MEMORIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED BULLET AIMS TO BREAK A 118-YEAR STREAK IN KENTUCKY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   He is a Philadelphia native who has borrowed European training
techniques and endorses a practice most horsemen consider
blasphemous: Sundays are a day of rest for both him and his stock.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Joe Orseno wants to upend another bedrock of horse racing:
he is hoping to win the Kentucky Derby with a colt who did not race
as a 2-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   The last time that was done America was barely a century old and
the Derby, now the nation's oldest continuously held sports event,
was in only its eighth running: it was done in 1882 by Apollo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game has changed,'' Orseno said. ``This is the year 2000.
Things are done differently. My colt doesn't know he didn't run as
a 2-year-old. He doesn't know how many races he has run.''
</P>
<P>
   The colt is Red Bullet, a son of Unbridled. His competitors in
the Wood Memorial Saturday knew he had looked formidable in winning
all three of his previous races, especially last month's Gotham
Stakes with Alex Solis aboard. Even Neil Drysdale, the trainer of
Fusaichi Pegasus, the odds-on favorite, tried to deflect attention
away from his $4 million colt at Thursday's post-position draw by
pointing out what many have marveled about. ``Let's see,'' Drysdale
mused, ``we have an undefeated horse in here and my horse has been
beaten. Maybe I shouldn't be the favorite.''
</P>
<P>
   Orseno, 44, wasn't always sure his way was the right way. He
saddled his first winner in 1977 and notched training titles in the
1980s in the big time's satellite circuits of Atlantic City, the
Meadowlands, Garden State Park and Delaware Park. But in 1993, when
he showed up at the Meadowlands with 10 very ordinary horses,
Orseno realized he was on the verge of becoming a free-thinking
former trainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on my way out,'' he said. ``I was working hard, but no
one was coming to me with horses.''
</P>
<P>
   Some powerful owners had been watching him, it turned out.
First, Leonard Green offered him the trainer's job for DJ Stable,
which brought him to the attention of another free-thinker who
wanted to make a larger impact on horse racing: Frank Stronach.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Stronach, a Canadian businessman, sent six of his
second-string horses to Orseno at Monmouth Park. The next year
Stronach doubled that number, and in 1998 he signed Orseno to a
five-year contract to handle 35 to 40 of his top horses. Last year,
Orseno was the third-leading trainer in New York and Stronach
Stables topped the owners list with 58 victories and $2.29 million
in purses.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Orseno has received an education in how experimentation
and expansion breeds success. Stronach recently purchased several
tracks, including Gulfstream and Santa Anita, increased his racing
and breeding operation and won the 1999 Eclipse Award as America's
leading owner. ``He has a vision of things and it includes getting
people in place and trusts his people,'' Orseno said. ``He lets
them do what works.''
</P>
<P>
   What works for Red Bullet and the rest of Orseno's stock is a
fitness method borrowed from Europe but tailored to American
horses. Instead of relying on fast workouts of four to seven
furlongs, Orseno gets his horses fit in what he calls ``controlled
gallops.'' In Europe, trainers sometimes gallop their horses on
trails through the countryside, but Orseno keeps them on the track
and varies their pace and distance from day to day. One day, he'll
ask Red Bullet for a mile in 2 minutes 20 seconds, another in 2:15
and some days as low as 2:00.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was claiming horses, I noticed that they'd come out of
a race that they just won but barely could get around the track in
an easy gallop,'' Orseno said. ``What I'm trying to do is give them
stamina and fitness every day without hurting them. When I ask them
to go fast, I know they're ready to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   So far Red Bullet has demonstrated not only sturdy fitness but
also a racing savvy that belies the fact that he had only three
races before the Wood. In his brief career, the colt has been
bumped and blocked and has stumbled out of the starting gate.
</P>
<P>
   Red Bullet and Orseno will rest Sunday because the trainer
believes both humans and horses need their rest. Monday? Red Bullet
is scheduled to fly to Louisville for the Kentucky Derby. His
trainer has yet to attend one even as a spectator.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
