<DOCNO> NYT20000415.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8015 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FREAKNOT0416-COX     04-15 1395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREAKNOT0416-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Freaknik is now Freaknot
 &HT;    By Jack Warner and Sandra Eckstein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Leaden skies and cold winds gave way to sunshine in
downtown Atlanta Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   It was a good day for a funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Freaknik, which grew from a little picnic in 1982 to what many
saw as a planned disaster in the mid-'90s, did not survive the
millennium. The question was whether it was slain by city officials
or committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, ``It's time to go ahead and just call the
eulogy for Freaknik,'' said George Hawthorne, an event planner who
advised city officials on ways to control it. ``It is definitely
dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorne is certainly not the first to announce the death of
Freaknik. Every year, visitors upset by the increasing police
presence said ``it's dead'' and vowed never to return. This year,
they kept their word.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta police, put on the usual 12-hour shifts for Freaknik
weekend, reported no trace of anyone getting their freak on.
Barricades hauled out in case streets needed to be blocked off sat
unused on street corners. What is now officially known as Black
College Spring Break was reported alive and well this weekend on
the beaches of Texas, a resort area better prepared to deal with
it.
</P>
<P>
   The sole remnant of the celebration was its most positive; more
than 50,000 people came to the World Congress Center looking for
work at the National Job Fair.
</P>
<P>
   An offshoot of Freaknik, the job fair attracted 239 companies
looking for everything from security guards to high level
executives. Kenneth Wimberly of KW Productions, the organizer of
the job fair, said he hopes to get jobs for at least 10,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where the happening is this weekend,'' said Wimberly,
referring to the demise of Freaknik.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Huey, who moved to Atlanta about two months ago from
Charlotte, NC, was taken aback when asked about Freaknik.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freaknik? We are all here looking for jobs,'' she said
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's leaders blew hot and cold over the years on Freaknik.
Attempts to provide some organization for the event, including
scheduled events at different venues, proved fruitless. As violence
became more and more a part of the party, the city began to get
tough.
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorne was chairman of the mayor's 1998 committee to look
into ways to control the event. The committee advised the city not
to issue permits or offer support for any Freaknik-related events.
It recommended asking black colleges to discourage their students
from attending. And it endorsed strict policing, including shutting
down roads, towing cars and making arrests.
</P>
<P>
   The city followed the committee's advice. Actually, crowds had
dwindled steadily from the estimated 200,000 who brought Atlanta to
a standstill in 1994, but as the crowds went down, arrests went up.
Freaknik recorded only one fatality _ a visitor from Ohio killed by
local thugs in a 1996 robbery attempt _ but violence, especially
against women, got worse until last year, when few black college
women showed up.
</P>
<P>
   That may have been the real death knell for Freaknik. A Spelman
freshman reported last year that ``There were 10 to 20 guys to
every girl, and they were really rude and disrespectful.'' That was
an improvement from the previous year, however, when at least two
women were raped and others had their clothes ripped off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the women there is no event,'' Hawthorne said. He
contended that Freaknik ``stopped being a college event years
ago.'' Indeed, police usually reported that many if not most of
those arrested were not students, and many were local residents.
</P>
<P>
   Freaknik is a prime example of a nice little idea that got out
of hand with an unexpected, even unintended, boost from the media.
</P>
<P>
   It began in 1982, when Morehouse and Spelman students from the
Washington, D.C. area _ members of a little group called the D.C.
Metro Club _ decided it would be a nice idea to have a picnic just
before final exams. Soon they added a pajama party on Friday that
tended to overshadow the picnic on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Growing slowly, it was usually a few hundred students in John
White Park having a cookout, playing touch football and listening
to D.C.-style music. ``It was very wholesome,'' recalls 1989
Morehouse grad Jim Shelton.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, however, the media plug came along and the celebration
``blew up,'' Shelton said. It was on ``A Different World,'' the NBC
sitcom on black college life, that ``somebody actually mentioned
that they were going to Freaknik. All of a sudden it went from
three or four thousand to 20,000 people.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of Atlanta was still unaware of Freaknik and city
officials, wanting to keep it that way, stopped granting permits to
the D.C. Metro Club. But Freaknik took on a life of its own.
</P>
<P>
   Freaknik finally hit the headlines and the airwaves of Atlanta's
major news outlets in 1992, when 80,000 people showed up and
started the annual traffic snarl.
</P>
<P>
   It began getting out of hand in a big way in 1993, when police
severely underestimated the crowd, 120,000 or more. City officials
agreed that authorities needed to get control of it, but their
attitudes were divided along racial lines, which was usually the
case with Freaknik.
</P>
<P>
   Councilwoman Mary Davis, saying her constituents in Midtown
complained loudly of traffic jams, lewd displays and partiers
relieving themselves in residents' yards, demanded Freaknik be
outlawed. ``We are not a resort city,'' she said. ``We are a
convention city, but this was not a convention.''
</P>
<P>
   Then-Councilman Bill Campbell, however, described the partiers
he encountered as ``innocent as those in 'Beach Blanket Bingo'
movies.''
</P>
<P>
   Next year, Campbell was mayor, and Freaknik reached its
watershed. Despite events planned at various venues, police
blockades around midtown and a tougher attitude, the city was
overwhelmed by more than 200,000 visitors. It was hard, sometimes
impossible, for workers, wedding parties, doctors and even
ambulances to get from here to there. Police arrested 143 people
and towed 706 cars. Businessmen, who never seemed to lose hope that
they could make money off the event, began to complain that it was
costing them money.
</P>
<P>
   Numbers were down by half in 1995, but the ugliness grew. Police
managed to protect the Midtown area, but other area roads were
gridlocked tight, and white motorists stranded in the traffic said
they were terrified by threats and overt gestures from blacks in
nearby cars. Looting broke out downtown, forcing shopkeepers to
close their doors, and crowds surged out to a local mall, where to
the dismay of black residents in the area, a major department store
was trashed and looted.
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested 509 people and confiscated 53 weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The city was gearing up for the Olympics in 1996, and Freaknik,
according to Mayor Bill Campbell, was ``the best ever. We made
great strides in eliminating the tension and divisiveness. We have
come a long way from last year to this year. It is a tremendous
victory for us. There is a degree of harmony we did not have last
year.'' The harmony may have been aided by the fact that only about
60,000 people showed up, and 683 of them were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the crowd estimate was up to 75,000, and arrests down
to about 300, and officials declared it an even nicer party than
1996. Police Chief Beverly Harvard, however, complained about the
continuing ``lewd and inappropriate behavior,'' and businessmen
groused that they still weren't making any money off Freaknik.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, it seemed that 1998 spelled the beginning of the
end. Florida and Texas beaches began drawing partiers; Atlanta
crowds were down to 50,000, 64 weapons were confiscated and arrests
soared to nearly 500. The lewdness turned to violence. Two
18-year-old women reported they were raped. Others were groped and
some were partially stripped by anonymous hands reached through
open car windows and ripping their clothes off. In one incident,
four men intervened to rescue a woman being manhandled by a crowd
of men.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was under 50,000 last year, and the vast majority were
men, prowling disconsolately in search of agreeable women. Police
enforced tough regulations, and this time, the vows never to come
back were kept.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
