<DOCNO> NYT20000415.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8017 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BRAVES0416-COX     04-15 0479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES0416-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves fall back into losing ways
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ Temperatures fell back into the 40s, wind off Lake
Michigan picked up, and the Braves started back into their
week-long freeze Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   After snapping a three-game losing streak Friday night, the
Braves had the tables turned on them by the Brewers in a 6-3 loss.
A three-run eighth inning off John Burkett spoiled a two-run
Quilvio Veras game-tying home run in the top of that inning,
handing the Braves their fourth loss in five games on this trip.
</P>
<P>
   And this was supposed to be the easy part of the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   They'll try to get themselves turned back in the right direction
today with struggling fourth starter Terry Mulholland facing the
Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get a win here (Sunday) and get back home,'' Bobby
Cox said. ``It hasn't been a good trip so far.''
</P>
<P>
   Veras had just tied the game at 3 with his first home run with
the Braves when they loaded the bases with one out for Javy Lopez.
But he bounced into a double-play, continuing the team's pattern of
missed scoring chances on this trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a sinking fastball,'' Lopez said. ``I hit it well, just
bad luck. Unfortunately, I hit it on the ground rather than a fly
ball. (David Weathers) made a good pitch on me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves take solace in knowing they have only one more game
until they return home to warmer Turner Field, where John Rocker
will rejoin them Tuesday, Brian Jordan will return on Wednesday and
Rudy Seanez won't be far behind. Burkett will work into the
rotation, where it looked Saturday afternoon like he'd be a better
fit than in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I neve think that,'' Burkett said of not being comfortable as
a reliever. ``I try to do the best job at whatever job I have.
Pitching is pitching. You either you do your job or you don't, and
I didn't get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Burkett had leadoff hitter Mark Loretta 1-2 before giving up a
double on a fastball inside for Loretta's third hit of the game.
Andres Galarraga then let a Jeromy Burnitz grounder scoot under his
glove, allowing a run to score, and Geoff Jenkins launched a
monster homer off the scoreboard in right-center field.
</P>
<P>
   With that, the Braves bullpen fell to 1-4 with a 5.00 ERA to go
with two blown saves.
</P>
<P>
   A lineup without Jordan and Chipper Jones (sore elbow), didn't
offer much of a fight for LaGrange native Jimmy Haynes, who retired
13 in a row in one stretch. Before this no-decision, he had won his
first two starts after coming over from Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody in here is worried,'' said Kevin
Millwood, who has yet to get a decision in three starts. ``With the
team we've got in here, we'll be able to bounce back and play some
good baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
