<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday, 04/15/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) WASHINGTON -- April 15, 2000 -- TRADE-PROTEST-3 -- A
wave of protesters united in their accusations that international
financiers are destroying the environment through improper
development in Third World countries and imposing monetary policies
that hurt poor people, have gathered in Washington to demonstrate
against the World Bank, the International Monetary Fund and the
World Trade Organization. Protesters outside of a Gap store,
Saturday. Police have made at least 20 arrests since demonstrators
began arriving. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) WASHINGTON -- April 15, 2000 -- TRADE-PROTEST-2 -- As
thousands of protesters determined to stop the World Bank meeting
poured into Washington on Saturday, police shut down the
demonstration's headquarters in a sudden pre-emptive strike,
fearing a repeat of the chaotic Seattle protests against the World
Trade Organization in December. Freelance photographer Les Stone is
arrested by Washington police during a student anti-sweatshop
protest outside a Gap clothing store, Saturday. Police officials
say that Stone would not move from the sidewalk when asked to do
so. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- April 15, 2000 -- FBN-DRAFT-2 -- The
Washington Redskins, already loaded with talent, should be favored
to represent the National Football Conference in the Super Bowl
this year, especially after drafting Alabama's Chris Samuels, left,
with the third pick of the draft, and Penn State linebacker LaVar
Arrington with the second. Samuels and Arrington along with NFL
Commissioner Pete Tagliabue at Madison Square Garden during the NFL
draft, Saturday. (Chang W. Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- April 15, 2000 -- FBN-DRAFT-1 -- The
Cleveland Browns have spent weeks scrutinizing, analyzing and
agonizing over two players from Penn State, linebacker LaVar
Arrington and defensive lineman Courtney Brown. Back and forth the
Browns went, sometimes in heated discussions. Arrington possesses
explosive athletic ability, but Brown is the kind of player who can
dominate a game. Brown, secon from left, flanked by family and
friends, after he was drafted No. 1 by Cleveland, Saturday. (Chang
W. Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- April 15, 2000 -- BKN-KNICKS-CAMBY -- In his
first months as a New York Knick in 1999, Marcus Camby did not
respond well to coach Jeff Van Gundy's tough love approach to the
game. Now, as they begin to enter their second playoff run
together, things are looking up for Camby, a player who is nothing
but upbeat these days. In response to his tremendous work effort on
and off the court Camby, in his new home in Westchester County, has
reveled in the acceptance of New York fans. (Keith Meyers/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- April 15, 2000 -- TRADE-PROTEST -- Under an
umbrella organization called Mobilization for Global Justice,
adherents of a number of causes plan two days of demonstrations in
Washington against the annual spring meeting of the World Bank and
International Monetary Fund, beginning on Sunday. Alex Loftus, a
geography major from Kingston, Ontario, seeks shelter from the rain
inside his van at a campground outside Washington, where thousands
have gathered to protest economic globalization. (Stephen
Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) FAIRFIELD, Conn. -- April 15, 20000 --
2D-GENERATION-NIMBY -- NIMBY, the overcooked acronym for ``not in
my backyard,'' once referred to disputes about garbage dumps and
hazardous waste sites. In the 1980s, it came to symbolize a
backlash against affordable (read: lower income) housing and social
service sites like halfway houses and homeless shelters _ virtually
anything seen as a potential threat to property values. In many
cases, it still refers to all of these. Today, in wealthy
communities across the New York region, the pitched battles are now
over ball fields and libraries, school buildings, churches and
housing, projects once seen as pillars of an upright community.
(Michael Kolomatsky/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) RALEIGH, N.C. -- April 15, 2000 -- GIULIANI-DONORS -- For
many of the people who have been showering New York Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's senate campaign with donations from far-flung ZIP codes,
just one fact matters, his opponent is Hillary Rodham Clinton. And
she must be stopped. Fenton Hord of Raleigh, N.C., who displays his
sentiments on his computer, gave to Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani's
Senate campaign. (Karen Tam/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) YOUNGSTOWN, Ohio -- April 15, 2000 -- OHIO-MOB -- The
Citizens' League of Greater Youngstown is trying to rouse outrage
against organized crime and is fighting to help the Ohio city shed
its image as ``Crimetown USA.'' James B. Callan, 54, the director
of Ohio Legal Services and founder of The Citizens' League of
Greater Youngstown, is concerned that the city takes corruption for
granted. ``Government officials can put a thousand people in jail,
but unless we change the culture in the community, the way we do
business, it doesn't matter,'' says Callan. (Barney Taxel/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) WASHINGTON -- April 15, 2000 -- TRADE-INSTITUTIONS-2 --
As thousands of protesters determined to stop the World Bank
meeting poured into Washington on Saturday morning, police
officials prepared for a repeat of the chaotic Seattle protests
against the World Trade Organization in December. While many of the
protesters have vowed to block finance ministers and other
delegates from around the world from attending the meetings, some
voiced their concerns about economic globalization in stores
throughout Washington. Protesters who made their way into a Nike
store are peacefully escorted out of the building by police,
Saturday. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) WASHINGTON -- April 15, 2000 -- TRADE-INSTITUTIONS-1 --
Under an umbrella organization called Mobilization for Global
Justice, adherents of a number of causes plan two days of
demonstrations in Washington against the annual spring meeting of
the World Bank and International Monetary Fund, beginning on
Sunday. Protesters contend that globalization and the financial
institutions' development policies are destroying the environment
and hurting poor people in the third world. Demonstrators intent on
halting a World Bank meeting protested the closing of their
headquarters by police, Saturday. The space was the nerve center
for demonstrations planned as a repeat of the Seattle protests
against the WTO in December. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
