<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8024 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-DRAFT-FALCONS-041     04-15 0433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-FALCONS-0416-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons select Claridge with top pick
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Travis Claridge is not about to dazzle anyone with
footwork, and he wasn't the fastest or most agile offensive lineman
available in this year's NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   But the two-time All-Pac-10 selection from Southern Cal has the
mean streak Falcons coach Dan Reeves likes in his blockers. And the
Falcons have lost three offensive linemen since last season, so
Saturday they selected Claridge in the second round, 37th overall.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons didn't have a first-round pick, and it took more
than six hours for the 6-foot-5, 305-pound Claridge to become the
fourth offensive linemen drafted. He won't have to wait long to get
in the mix.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive line coach Art Shell believes Claridge would be good
at guard, but Reeves said Claridge's first shot with the Falcons
will come at right tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt like he was the best choice for us to come in and
compete at the right tackle position with (starter) Ephraim
(Salaam),'' Reeves said. ``He's got to prove that he can't play
tackle.''
</P>
<P>
   Claridge started every game in his college career, the first
three years at right guard, then at right tackle as a senior. He
was chosen the Pac-10's outstanding offensive lineman of the year
last fall.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons, who will have one selection today in each of rounds
three through seven, drafted for need on the first day.
</P>
<P>
   Salaam, who in 1998 became just the fourth player in NFL history
to start every game of his rookie season, including a Super Bowl,
regressed in '99.
</P>
<P>
   At the urging of coaches, Salaam _ a seventh-round choice in '97
_ gained weight in the hope he would become a more prototypical,
power-blocking right tackle. Instead, his footwork suffered, and
his confidence took a beating as he didn't play as well as in '98.
</P>
<P>
   Claridge, a high school All-American from Vancouver, Wash., was
first team All-Pac-10 his past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   His best time in the 40-yard dash was 5.16 seconds, which for
his weight is average. But he's strong, bench-pressing 225 pounds
29 times, and can push defensive linemen around.
</P>
<P>
   His pass protection skills trail his run-blocking skills,
however, and Claridge had arthroscopic surgery after the '97 and
'98 seasons to clean debris out of his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``My shoulders are fine,'' Claridge said. ``I can play heavier
if they want me to, and ... play whatever position they want me to.
I feel ecstatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
