<HEADER>
A8027 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-HAAKENSON-COLUMN-     04-15 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-HAAKENSON-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO FAR, STONEMAN LOOKING LIKE A GENIUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO -- The outfield fence at Edison Field this season has a
mural honoring the members of the Angels' all-time team. There are
the usual suspects, like Reggie Jackson, Bobby Grich and Doug
DeCinces.
</P>
<P>
   And there are others who left Anaheim in a huff. Rod Carew was
bitter after being let go as a player in 1985, and a bit perturbed
when it happened to him again as a coach after last season. Brian
Downing vowed never to return to the ballpark after the Angels cut
him loose following the 1990 season. He finally showed up on
opening night this year.
</P>
<P>
   Even Nolan Ryan was allowed to leave via free agency after going
16-14 in 1979. Then-Angels GM Buzzie Bavasi reasoned that he'd just
go out and sign two 8-7 pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   That brings us to present day. There are three players still
playing today that grace the wall, but only one -- Troy Percival --
is with the team. Jim Edmonds and Chuck Finley are up there, a
testament to their popularity with the fans, who voted for the
team.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the irony of it all is that Edmonds and Finley aren't
with the team anymore, Edmonds having been traded to St. Louis, and
Finley signing as a free agent with Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Behind those moves -- or lack thereof -- was new general manager
Bill Stoneman.
</P>
<P>
   Stoneman took on what many might consider an impossible job --
turning around the fortunes of a club that hit rock-bottom last
season. And having to do so under the watchful eyes of that big
mouse in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Being the guy that oversaw the departure of two of the
franchise's most popular players is not the legacy Stoneman would
like to have. And early in his tenure with the club, the criticism
was endless.
</P>
<P>
   It came from everywhere. Of course, the radio talk-shows joined
the fray when Stoneman-bashing became trendy. But it started with
Finley, who was not offered a contract after 14 years with the
club. It continued with talk that agents and general managers
around the league were annoyed with Stoneman, because he wouldn't
budge on his demands for Edmonds in a trade.
</P>
<P>
   But Stoneman is still standing, and the Angels are off to a
relatively good start, considering expectations for the team. With
Finley, Stoneman explains, the parting of the two sides was of
Finley's doing.
</P>
<P>
   Stoneman was told by Finley's agent, Tim Shannon, that Finley
was seeking a three-year deal worth at least $25 million. That
didn't fit under Stoneman's budget, but he still wanted to speak
with Finley face-to-face and get a ``feeling'' for what Finley
really wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Would Finley take less to stay with the Angels or not?
</P>
<P>
   ``I recall one phone conversation,'' Stoneman said. ``I had left
messages and he did finally get back to me. I asked if we could get
together that week and he said he couldn't do it, that he'd
definitely call next week and we'd definitely get together. That
call never came.''
</P>
<P>
   With Edmonds, there were the constant rumors. When nothing
happened, Stoneman was criticized. But when he finally did make a
trade, he filled two needs the club had -- starting pitching (Kent
Bottenfield) and second base (Adam Kennedy).
</P>
<P>
   ``All that stuff, whether it was all the media pressure over the
winter in terms of trades, or people not having a good outlook for
the team ... I've seen that before,'' said Stoneman, who spent 17
years in the Expos organization. ``It wasn't anything that
surprised me or caused me to change anything. It really isn't a
surprise the team has come together like it has.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been on clubs that were very disappointing. You can
correct things very quickly. The important thing is don't change
your plan. If you have a good plan and you believe in your plan and
the people around you believe in it, it's going to work. The
important thing is to have discipline to stay with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did trade Jim Edmonds, but we had opportunities early. Had
we followed through on one of those, it wouldn't have worked out
nearly as well as it did. Sometimes you've just got to be patient
until the right thing does come along. One thing I've learned over
the years, if you exercise patience and good judgement, you'll be
rewarded.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels fans have waited 40 years. Is that long enough?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
