<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8030 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-DRAFT-LEDE0416-CO     04-15 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-LEDE0416-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Browns think Brown
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The first round of the NFL draft stayed pretty much
true to form Saturday _ until the Ravens and Raiders pulled some
surprises.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the Browns drafted Penn State defensive end
Courtney Brown with the No. 1 pick. Brown, from Alvin, S.C., beat
out Nittany Lions teammate LaVar Arrington for that distinction.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, 6 feet 4 and 270 pounds, is the first defensive end
drafted No. 1 since Bruce Smith was taken first by Buffalo in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Arrington, an All-America linebacker, was drafted second by the
Redskins, making it the first time since 1984 that teammates went
1-2. Irving Fryar and Dean Steinkuhler of Nebraska were the top two
choices that year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a long, healthy discussion about both players,'' Browns
coach Chris Palmer said. ``Basically, what it came down to is that
defensive ends are involved in rushing the quarterback. They're
both outstanding players. We couldn't have gone wrong selecting
either one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins became only the fifth team in 30 years to make two
picks in the top five. After selecting Arrington, Washington
drafted Alabama offensive tackle Chris Samuels with the third
choice.
</P>
<P>
   Washington obtained the No. 2 pick from New Orleans in last
year's Ricky Williams trade, and the Redskins got No. 3 from San
Francisco in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really hard to please the whole war room,'' Redskins
coach Norv Turner said. ``But once we got Arrington for the
defense, and Samuels for the offense, everybody was happy. We're
facing lofty expectations now, but I think we're going to be a
really good football team.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Bengals drafted Florida State receiver Peter Warrick
with the fourth pick, the Ravens surprised a lot of people by
drafting Tennessee running back Jamal Lewis at No. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis struggled last season after missing most of the '98
campaign with a serious knee injury. But he seemed to temper
concerns during his offseason workouts for NFL scouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no concerns about repercussions from the previous
injuries,'' Ravens coach Brian Billick said. ``Anytime you draft a
player, you're concerned about injuries. Jamal was the key to our
draft, whether we got him at No. 5 or No. 10.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who vaulted himself into the top 10 after running the
40-yard dash in only 4.34 seconds at a workout last month, said he
didn't know what to expect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything was going to be a surprise to me,'' Lewis said. ``I
talked with the Ravens and kind of felt like they wanted to take a
running back. I didn't know if it was going to be me, (Virginia's)
Thomas Jones or (Alabama's) Shaun Alexander.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, 6 feet and 240 pounds, said Ravens general manager Ozzie
Newsome called him only minutes before NFL commissioner Paul
Tagliabue announced the selection on ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to run well and prove to everybody that the knee
is fine and I'm healthy,'' Lewis said. ``That's what I wanted to do
going into the draft. I think that's what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ravens acquired the fifth pick from the Falcons last year.
Atlanta received Baltimore's second-round pick in the `99 draft and
selected tight end Reggie Kelly of Mississippi State.
</P>
<P>
   The draft's biggest surprise came from the Raiders, who selected
Florida State kicker Sebastian Janikowski at No. 17. It was the
first time a kicker went in the first round since New Orleans
selected Russell Erxleben of Texas with the 11th pick in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Janikowski, a native of Poland, has one of the strongest legs to
ever enter the draft. But he also faces a bribery charge for
allegedly offering a police officer in Tallahassee, Fla., $300 to
release his roommate from custody.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like this pick will help our entire football team,''
Raiders coach Jon Gruden said. ``He'll help our defense and he'll
put points on the board for our offense. ... We did a lot of
research on this young man. We feel we have an environment with our
veteran players and our coaching staff for this young man to
flourish.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
