<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0416-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Clinton and Gore together again
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore and President Clinton were to appear
together at a fundraiser in Beverly Hills, Calif., late Saturday _
the first time the two have been seen in public together since last
year. The Democratic National Committee event was expected to bring
$2.5 million and attract a variety of Hollywood actors, directors
and producers.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the duo appeared together in public was Dec. 9 for
a firefighters' memorial in Massachusetts and a DNC fund-raiser in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Gore headlined a DNC fundraiser near San Jose,
Calif., that raised $2.6 million _ shattering the DNC's previous
Silicon Valley record of $1.5 million. At the same event, Gore
renewed his call for a ban on unlimited ``soft money'' _ the very
kind of money he was raising Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH WAR CHEST TOPS $80 MILLION
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush has broken the $80 million mark in his Republican
presidential campaign, adding to his own fund-raising record while
replenishing his war chest after an expensive primary effort. The
campaign raised about $7 million between March 1 and April 6,
spokesman Scott McClellan said Friday. That is three-quarters of
the $10 million goal Bush is trying to raise by the end of this
month. The campaign expects to raise an additional $550,000 next
week with events in North Carolina and Michigan. Bush's camp also
is increasing its push for online contributors, and has raised $1.6
million via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is trying to rebuild his war chest after spending a record
$63.3 million earlier in the year in his bid to defeat former
Republican presidential opponent Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   GORE AND TIPPER DONATED $15,000
</P>
<P>
   Democratic presidential contender Al Gore and his wife Tipper
contributed about $15,000 to charities in 1999 _ the same as in the
previous year _ two years after Gore earned the sobriquet of ``Vice
President Scrooge'' for his meager giving of $353.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Gores declined to disclose the charities publicly,
the White House said in releasing their 1999 tax returns that the
contributions went to religious organizations, educational
institutions, public service entities and groups set up to combat
diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The returns showed that the Gores had an adjustable gross income
of $240,930 in 1999, including $175,400 from his salary as vice
president, and paid $62,051, or almost 26 percent, in federal
income taxes. By comparison, they earned $504,109 in 1998 and paid
$89,951 in taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who aides say will seek an extension
for filing his income tax return, on Monday is expected to make a
payment to cover any money he might owe the government. He also
said that on Monday he will release how much money he gave to
charities in 1999, Bush spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said. He said he
needs the extension because he still has not received information
from a blind trust that manages his assets.
</P>
<P>
   TIT FOR TAT BETWEEN GORE AND BUSH
</P>
<P>
   The Bush and Gore presidential campaigns are crunching some
serious numbers as each scolds the other for ducking separate
issues: Democrat Al Gore, the media, and George W. Bush, a debate
with his Republican rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore today cancelled a scheduled news conference, which
would have been the first in 54 days,'' the Bush camp said Thursday
in a news release.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, Gore aides released their own statement
showing off some math as well: ``George W. Bush has managed to bob
and weave away from debating Gore for 30 days in a row,'' the
release said, referring to an e-mail challenge sent last month to
the Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   The campaigns failed to mention the most important number: 205.
</P>
<P>
   That's how many days until Nov. 7 _ Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
