<HEADLINE>
THE TRUE HEROES OF NBA SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Our regularly scheduled, season-ending Valentine
of NBA achievement will not be seen in order to save the Shaquille
O'Neal-related MVP metaphor and simile for everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, you will receive (at no extra charge) a list of
citizens who ``done good'' in categories the league has refused to
sanction.
</P>
<P>
   -- The first award is presented to one of the few players who
could stare down an allowance-packin' third-grader at a candy
store. For remaining loyal to his plan of losing games rather than
weight, Cleveland's Shawn Kemp is the recipient of our first M&AMP;MVP
Award.
</P>
<P>
   -- While Elton Brand and Steve Francis stimulate debate over
first-year superiority, publicists for Minnesota's Wally Szczerbiak
have deployed his merciless mug shot just frequently enough to
secure the Rookie of the Yearbook Award.
</P>
<P>
   -- For disguising himself as a victim, our award for Best
Costume Design goes to Boston Celtic emperor Rick Pitino.
</P>
<P>
   -- Atlanta hired him as its go-to guy, but our next honoree
parlayed that presumption into the role of go-to-hell guy. For such
versatility, J.R. Rider receives the league's Citizenshipwreck
Award.
</P>
<P>
   -- To secure our Sixth Man-iac Award, Seattle super-sub Vernon
Maxwell tossed a 10-pound weight at Gary Payton's head. He is
alleged to have missed.
</P>
<P>
   -- For hiring more assistant coaches than Jerry Jones,
dispatching limos to drive players to games when the streets of
Dallas are icy and not being run out of the country by Janet Reno,
our Best New Rich Rascal Award will be e-mailed to Mavericks owner
Mark Cuban.
</P>
<P>
   -- For having the chutzpah to think he can balance a budget in
Washington, our Michael Jordan Award will be given to ... Michael
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   -- The award for Best Sound Effects goes to Tyrone Nesby, who
was rescued from the CBA by the Clippers but now whines about how
they ruined his career by matching San Antonio's three-year
contract offer sheet.
</P>
<P>
   -- He isn't employed by the Magic, but does get paid for
disappearing, and that makes Sherman Douglas of the Nets (we think)
the first winner of the Ike Austin Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   -- Steve Javie was a unanimous choice for our Most Defensive
Referee Award after assessing technical fouls for the crime of
exhaling.
</P>
<P>
   -- Another landslide was tallied by Dennis Rodman, who
campaigned hard for his Comeback (To Earth) Player of the Year
Award.
</P>
<P>
   -- Our Lifetime Achievement Award goes to the late Wilt
Chamberlain, who according to rumor just finger-rolled over Elvis.
</P>
<P>
   Minor adjustment
</P>
<P>
   The recent NBA Board of Governors meeting supplied league owners
with the semi-official and expected news of Commish David Stern's
proposed minor league.
</P>
<P>
   An age limit for players was proposed to eliminate participation
by high school refugees and create public perception that the NBA
respects the sovereign turf of college basketball. And, ahem,
higher education. But several league sources believe that without
providing sanctuary and a controlled environment for players who
insist upon bypassing college, the ``NBA-minus'' has little merit.
</P>
<P>
   Many personnel bosses would prefer Stern in partnership with CBA
owner Isiah Thomas, whose growing stable of game-ready franchises
eventually could provide a farm team for each NBA club.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of ego would have to be reeled in - from both sides -
for that to happen,'' one source said, ``but I still don't think
you should shut the door on Isiah. And without a legit farm system
or a place for players who truly aren't ready, they might as well
keep the CBA system the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Shot-clock violations
</P>
<P>
   According to a witness at Staples Center, the recovery time for
injured University of Cincinnati star and No. 1 draft-pick threat
Kenyon Martin may have been cut in half. Martin, who broke his leg
in the Conference USA tournament opener last month, reportedly ran
screaming from the arena Tuesday night after watching the Clippers
lose to Phoenix. ... A source close to the LSU coaching staff
reports that reality may be biting Stromile Swift. After learning
he could be a top three NBA pick this June, the Tigers' remarkably
springy sophomore forward is having second thoughts about his
commitment to stay in school. ... Iowa State junior Marcus Fizer,
who's not expected to last beyond the first two picks, said he
would keep open his option of returning to school, but reportedly
has hired agent Henry Thomas. ... The early star of this weekend's
pre-draft camp at Phoenix is Oklahoma State's Desmond ``40-Inch
Vertical'' Mason. The 6-foot-6 Mason's potential - known in
roundball's patois as ``up side'' is vast enough to have attracted
a representation approach from the mighty David Falk. ... Reviews
of last week's pre-draft festival at Portsmouth, Va. have been
mixed, ranging from ``weak'' to ``pretty terrible.'' The official
MVP was 6-8 stringbean Mike Smith of Louisiana-Monroe, who provided
frequent glimpses of keen 3-point marksmanship (65 percent) and the
bottoms of his sneakers. Other prospects who demonstrated signs of
becoming live second-round bait were Samford small forward Reed
Rawlings and Colorado point guard Jaquay Walls. ... Don't panic,
Grizzlies fans. The Dickie V and B. Knight from Indiana reportedly
heading your way are coach Dick Versace and Pacers vice president
Billy Knight. ... Clippers center Michael Olowokandi recently
purchased a computer company in England. When the Clips visit
Dallas next season, the Kandi Man probably will know how to get
re-booted.
</P>
</TEXT>
