<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-WAR-REENACT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AROUND LEXINGTON, BATTLE CALL SOUNDED YET AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROLINE LOUISE COLE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEXINGTON, Mass. _ Just as they did 225 years ago, British
Regulars, 200 strong, marched into Lexington at dawn Saturday on a
``secret'' mission to find hidden munitions. Instead, they
encountered a rag-tag band of 77 musket-toting Colonials ready to
fight.
</P>
<P>
   And just as they did 225 years ago, the British ordered their
fellow countrymen to lay down their arms as the sun rose over
Lexington Green. But instead, a single shot rang out, that
mysterious shot heard 'round the world.
</P>
<P>
   The British, imposing in their red coats and tight lines of
battle, charged the poorly clad and poorly organized Patriots, some
of whom returned fire before they fled into the woods.
</P>
<P>
   When the smoke cleared, eight civilians lay dead and nine were
wounded. But on this day, the casualties rose to their feet again
at the end of the event. And the crowd of about 10,000 on-lookers,
many them also wearing Colonial costumes, made it clear that
Saturday's battle was not a matter of life and death.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it was a celebration of liberty. This year's
anniversary of the opening clashes of the Revolutionary War on
April 19, 1775, is a four-day affair, which began Friday and runs
through Monday. It's expected to draw up to 100,000 spectators and
several thousand reenactors, including 600 from England and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow, this was awesome,'' said Jeffrey Kiggins, 10, as he
watched the recreation of the Battle of Lexington get under way on
a crisp spring morning. Kiggins, a fourth-grader from South
Hampton, N.H., had dragged his mother out of bed at 2:30 a.m. to
ensure their front-row seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait until I can join up, even if it means I have to
start out as a fife or drummer,'' Kiggins said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Colonials would later claim the day and
eventually wrest independence from Britain, but not until these
British Regulars regrouped and pushed onto Concord and then
retreated back to Boston. History records the day's casualties as
73 dead and 174 wounded for the British, 49 dead and 40 wounded for
the Colonials.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Robert Allegretto of Woburn drew sneers in the
garb of His Majesty's 23d Royal Welsh Fusiliers when he heckled the
Colonial militia making fun of their dress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won here but we do encourage you to fight back,'' he told
the crowd following the 15-minute reenactment.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to watching the replays of several key battles along
the 2.5 mile stretch of highway now known as Battle Road,
spectators could tour a Colonial encampment and visit with
interpreters displaying Colonial crafts and gear.
</P>
<P>
   Among the early morning crowd in Lexington were Dorothy
McCormack and Janet Rigazio and their class of fifth-graders from
Andover, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``What better way to learn history than to see it in action
right in our own backyard?'' McCormack said.
</P>
<P>
   Also there was Jim Brown, a retired federal worker, who drove up
from Jacksonville, Fla., for the reenactment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard this year was going to be special and I haven't been
disappointed,'' he said as he straightened his tricorn hat,
purchased for the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Following the Battle Green show, he and his son Nick hoped to
catch the action at Merriam's Corner.
</P>
<P>
   Bursting with satisfaction was Bob Marrigan of Bedford, who
hatched the idea of celebrating American liberty with live players
back in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to see this kind of interest because when I first
suggested replaying the Lexington battle 30 years ago, it was a
pretty unpopular idea, Vietman being on everyone's minds,'' said
Marrigan, dressed in a blue wool coat and linen breeches for his
adopted role of Colonial Lieutenant William Tidd.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Lexington Minute Men, sponsors of the event,
beefed up the initial engagement in Lexington by staging the
capture of messenger Paul Revere at midnight. And, to Kiggins's
delight, Revere showed up in Lexington, after escaping from the
Regulars, just in time to save John Hancock's precious trunk of
papers before the British arrived.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
