<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ENGELMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDMUND ENGELMAN, 92, DIES; TOOK FREUD PHOTOS 
</HEADLINE>
   By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Edmund Engelman, the clandestine photographer who let
the world glimpse the famous couch of Dr. Sigmund Freud (without a
consultation fee), died on April 11 at Lenox Hill Hospital in
Manhattan. He was 92 and had homes in Manhattan and East Hampton,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Engelman, a native of Vienna and an engineer by training, was
asked by a friend of Freud's to make a pictorial record of the
birthplace of psychoanalysis. He succeeded in doing so in 1938,
days before the Freud family left Vienna for London after the Nazi
takeover of Austria.
</P>
<P>
   Freud had lived in a nondescript four-story apartment house at
Berggasse 19 since 1891. Engelman surreptitiously took a series of
about 150 pictures of his offices and living quarters, using only
natural light for fear of alerting the Gestapo, which kept Freud
under constant watch.
</P>
<P>
   Engelman himself escaped Vienna months later. He reached the
United States in 1939 by a circuitous route but without the
negatives, which he retrieved from Freud's daughter Anna in London
after World War II. They became the material for a book,
``Berggasse 19'' (Basic Books, 1976).
</P>
<P>
   The historian Peter Gay, who wrote an introduction, said the
pictures ``let us walk through Freud's rooms, sit at his desk, and
contemplate, almost through his eyes, the objects he collected and
cherished.'' Engelman also took portraits of Freud, his wife,
Martha, and his daughter. The pictures are on view at the Freud
museums in Vienna and London. The Austrian government awarded
Engelman its Cross of Honor for Science and Art, first-class, in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Engelman received his engineering degree at the Technical
University in Vienna in 1932 and founded a center for
experimentation in photography and cinematography. He was a
consultant to the Anatomical Institute at the University of Vienna
on the use of film in medical education.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States he worked during the war as an engineer for
International Telephone and Telegraph, helping to develop
electronic gear for combat aircraft. He owned a camera center in
New York from 1946 to 1958, after which he became a consulting
engineer for photographic technology.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Irene Lipnofska Engelman; two sons,
Ralph, of Brooklyn, and Thomas, of Newton, Mass.; and three
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-15-00 2019EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000415.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8044 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-MARKET-REACT-1STLD-WR     04-15 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-REACT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE STOCK MARKET, A SENSE THAT THE GAME HAS CHANGED 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to insert new 11th and 12th grafs about Joseph Chung in 2nd
take.)  
 By ALEX BERENSON and PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a sweltering second-floor office of a midtown
Manhattan branch of Quick &AMP; Reilly, a discount brokerage, Sean M.
Mullin, a 23-year-old broker, tugged at his tie as he explained how
he had spent much of Friday afternoon. As the market plummeted,
Mullin was making ``margin calls'' on investors who had bought
losing stocks with borrowed money. Those investors now had to put
up more cash as collateral or sell their shares to pay off their
loans.
</P>
<P>
   Mullin said he disliked making margin calls, although he had no
choice. ``You get people on the phone, and they're just upset,'' he
said. ``They'll call you and say, `How much do I owe?'''
</P>
<P>
   As for his own portfolio, ``I'm holding tough,'' Mullin said.
``It's painful.''
</P>
<P>
   Pain was everywhere Friday as the technology-heavy Nasdaq
composite index fell almost 10 percent, capping its worst week
ever, and the Dow Jones industrial average was off more than 5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In other market declines over the past decade, investors have
been quick to follow experts' exhortations to buy on dips. That
buying has driven U.S. stocks, especially technology stocks, to
unprecedented levels.
</P>
<P>
   It may happen again when the market opens on Monday. But as
investors reviewed the damage wrought last week, their uncertainty
about the market's near-term prospects was palpable. And few of
them sounded eager to step up and buy.
</P>
<P>
   There was a sense of shock among many investors on Friday, a
suggestion that the game had run its course, at least for a little
while.
</P>
<P>
   The selling, the crescendo of a week when the Nasdaq fell 25
percent and U.S. stocks lost $2 trillion in value, did not reflect
panic. It was worse, a steady and relentless decline that showed
few signs of letting up as the 4:00 p.m. bell finally rang to end
the action, closing a one-sided bout that finished several rounds
too late.
</P>
<P>
   Among individual investors, panicked sellers were hard to find,
except for people who had to pay taxes or who faced margin calls.
Figures from Birinyi Associates, a stock market research firm in
Connecticut, confirmed the anecdotal evidence, showing that big
institutions, not individuals, accounted for most of Friday's
selling.
</P>
<P>
   But no one seemed to be bargain hunting either. The aggressive
buyers who drove technology stocks up to all-time highs last month
seem to be out of fresh cash, and more conservative investors still
think the highfliers are too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   The dynamic was clear Friday afternoon at Quick &AMP; Reilly. There,
clusters of investors were talking to brokers, making trades and
checking the stock prices displayed on computer monitors. Above
them, a muted television played CNBC, the business news cable
channel, as a series of pundits talked and the Dow skidded south.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting at a desk at the front of the branch, Dmitri Jones, a
Quick &AMP; Reilly consultant, said he did not expect the sell-off to
end soon. Despite sharp declines, technology stocks are still
overvalued, and many conservative investors will not be interested
in buying them until they fall much lower, he said. ``A lot of
people are waiting on the sidelines,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Others are too badly bruised to step up right now, he said.
``You look at people's accounts,'' he said. ``It's straight
carnage.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he had bought 200 shares of Microsoft on Tuesday. ``I
thought I was getting a bargain,'' he said ruefully. Since then,
shares in the software company have plunged, costing Jones more
than $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's more than I make,'' he said. ``I'm just looking at my
future getting smaller and smaller.''
</P>
<P>
   Vinod Malhotra, another investor, said, ``It's very bad,'' as he
worriedly checked the ever-changing prices displayed on the
computer screens near the branch's front entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Malhotra said he owned shares in several of the Internet and
technology highfliers that have been hardest hit in the last month,
including Internet Capital Group, down from $147 on March 6 to
$52.0625 at Friday's close, and Exodus Communications, which has
fallen from $179.625 on March 23 to $85.5625 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, it has been a very expensive couple of weeks,
Malhotra said. He has accounts at several brokerage firms, and he
said his largest portfolio, at Prudential, had fallen from $1.8
million to under $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Malhotra has no plans to sell. ``I have no choice,'' he
said. ``I have to hold on until they come back.''
</P>
<P>
   A few investors started unloading stocks before last week.
Norman Nouskajian, a San Diego lawyer, said the irrational behavior
of other investors drove him to sell most of his stocks six weeks
ago. ``When I saw some of my clients who were in businesses having
nothing to do with finance divert their time and money into the
market, to me that pointed to a type of excess,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of keeping half of his assets in the stock market, as he
usually does, Nouskajian said he cut back to 20 percent. His
remaining stocks have lost half their value, erasing about 10
percent of his net worth.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is in no particular hurry to get back into the market.
``Next week, I might nibble a little,'' he said. ``I feel sorry for
people who have taken a lot of money and thrown it at the
overpriced tech stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Donald F. Zele, a retired auditor who lives in Farmington,
Conn., told a similar story. Zele said he had called his
stepdaughter on Tuesday and told her to sell her mutual funds, and
had then sold all of his own stocks and funds. ``Today's debacle
proved me right,'' he said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Now Zele wants to get back in. But not yet. ``People are
panicking and getting out at all costs,'' he said. ``This thing
could get a lot uglier. I can't wait to get back in, but right now
I am not going to touch it.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The nervousness is hardly confined to individual investors.
</P>
<P>
   Kim S. Fennebresque, president and chief executive officer of SG
Cowen, an investment bank that specializes in underwriting stock
issues for the health care and technology companies that have been
hardest hit over the last month, held a conference call Friday to
reassure his employees that Cowen's future remained bright. But
afterward, Fennebresque confessed that he was less sanguine about
the overall stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Investors who buy too soon may ``catch a falling knife,''
Fennebresque said. ``One cannot help but be a little sober about
the playing field in which we find ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Fennebresque said he worried about a ``poverty effect'' as
investors who have lost money cut back on purchases. It is probably
too early for that, especially since both the Dow and Nasdaq are
still higher than they were even six months ago. Several real
estate brokers and travel agents who cater to wealthy clients said
that as of Friday, they had not lost any business.
</P>
<P>
   But the plunge seems to have hurt sales of at least one luxury
item. At the Wall Street Humidor, a cigar shop in lower Manhattan
that caters to wealthy traders and investment bankers, the owner,
Richard Hu, said business had been terrible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an absolute disaster,'' Hu said. ``The last thing they
want is a cigar. A cigar will kill them too slowly.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, longtime bears like Seymour Rosen, 65, a cabinetmaker
from Monroe Township, N.J., remain wary.
</P>
<P>
   Rosen said he had been warning for more than a year that the
runup in technology stocks was ``smoke and mirrors.'' He got really
worried when a waitress at the Prestige Diner in East Windsor,
N.J., boasted about her purchase of shares in ViroPharma, a
drugmaker that has lost more than 85 percent of its value in the
last month. ``I said you haven't made a nickel until you sell it,''
he recounted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wanted to jump in and make a million dollars,'' Rosen
said. Now all he wants to do is jump out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it does bounce back, I want to get out,'' he said, adding
that he would settle now for bonds that guarantee him a return of 6
percent a year. If the market continues to decline, he said, he
might sell anyway. ``It's better to lose some than to lose it
all.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone was displeased with Friday's action. Even some
investors with big losses expressed a certain relief. ``We've
certainly seen a lot of paper wealth disappear,'' said Joseph
Chung, chairman of the Art Technology Group, an Internet software
company that went public in July. Art Technology shares fell 46
percent last week, and Chung's net worth fell by more than $200
million. ``But I think it's healthy,'' he said from his San
Francisco office. ``I honestly do.''
</P>
<P>
   Chung had been worried that investors and entrepreneurs had
become more focused on quick financial returns than on actual
business development. Now that the tar's been knocked out of the
market a bit, people may get back to some of the reasons why we're
actually here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Short-sellers, who make money when stocks decline, said the
sell-off confirmed their warnings that many technology companies
were badly overvalued.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, by most measures, technology stocks have been in a
bubble for years, with many priced at 100, 200 or even 300 times
their annual earnings. In less heady times, most stocks sport
price-earnings ratios of 30 or less, although technology bulls note
that many technology companies are growing at very fast rates.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's plunge was needed to wring excesses out of stock
prices, said Marc Cohodes, general partner of Rocker Partners,
which manages $600 million. Cohodes is a short-seller, a bearish
investor who borrows what he believes are overpriced shares and
then sells them, betting that their prices will decline and he will
be able to buy them back later for a lower price. ``Today was a day
I would like to see repeated a few more times,'' Cohodes said. ``I
think what this is, it's the start of a change that's going to
happen in the markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohodes said that change would be healthy for both Wall Street
and the economy as a whole, by keeping capital out of the hands of
money-losing dot-com businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who burn cash and have no business model _ that game is
over,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
