<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ALSOP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN ALSOP, 84, GOP FIGURE IN CONNECTICUT 
</HEADLINE>
   By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John deKoven Alsop, a veteran of Connecticut
Republican politics, a gubernatorial candidate and a retired
insurance company president, died on April 6 at a health care
center in Old Saybrook, Conn. He was 84 and lived in Old Lyme,
where he had moved from Avon, his birthplace, in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Alsop, who served two terms in the state legislature in the late
1940s, was allied with the liberal wing of his party. He came to
wider attention as an early backer of Dwight D. Eisenhower for
president, and was a state vice chairman for Eisenhower's campaign
in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   He first sought the Republican nomination for governor in 1958,
but lost in a primary. He won the nomination in 1962 in a bruising
contest and lost the November election to the incumbent, Gov. John
Dempsey.
</P>
<P>
   Alsop, a colorful figure, remained influential in party circles
for years. He represented Connecticut on the Republican National
Committee and held leading positions in various councils on the
state level.
</P>
<P>
   He retired in 1980 as president of the Covenant Group of
insurance companies in Hartford. The business was originally formed
by his father in the 1920s, and he had led it as chief executive
for 27 years.
</P>
<P>
   John Alsop was born into a well-connected family. He was a
descendant of President James Monroe and was related to the Oyster
Bay, N.Y., branch of the Roosevelt family as a grandnephew of
President Theodore Roosevelt. His parents, Joseph W. and Corinne
Alsop, were both elected to the General Assembly, and his
grandfather, a Democrat, was lieutenant governor.
</P>
<P>
   He was the younger brother of the Washington political
columnists Joseph and Stewart Alsop. Joseph died in 1989 and
Stewart in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   John Alsop graduated from the Groton School in 1933 and from
Yale University in 1937, when he went to work at Smith, Barney &AMP;
Co. in New York. He enlisted in the Army in 1942 and served with
the Office of Strategic Services in Britain, France and China,
receiving a Bronze Star with cluster and rising to captain.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife of 52 years, Augusta Robinson Alsop;
a son, John deK., of Cornville, Maine; two daughters, Mary Culver
of Guilford, Conn., and Augusta Alsop of Solon, Maine; and nine
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
