<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8050 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-PROTESTS-0416-1STLD-C     04-15 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROTESTS-0416-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLICE ARREST HUNDREDS AS CAPITAL BRACES FOR MASS DEMONSTRATIONS
 &HT;    EDS: New top, with minor revisions throughout.
 &HT;    By BOB DART and ALEC SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After closing a training center for protestors
earlier in the day, police in riot gear arrested hundreds of
peaceful demonstrators late Saturday as the nation's capital braced
for mass rallies against the World Bank and International Monetary
Fund.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators were handcuffed and loaded onto yellow school
buses after a tense standoff with police near the World Bank and
IMF headquarters buildings, located just blocks from the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time we're finished I expect to have 500 arrests,''
said Police Chief Charles Ramsey. He said they would be charged
with ``parading without a permit and refusal to disperse, among
other things.''
</P>
<P>
   The arrests came on the eve of planned mass demonstrations aimed
at shutting down the meetings of the world trade organizations on
Sunday and Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's downtown area was quiet after the arrests, but a
heavy police presence remained. All told, nearly 50 blocks around
the World Bank and IMF buildings were off limits to demonstrators.
The area was cordoned off by metal crowd-control barriers that
prevented all but authorized people from passing.
</P>
<P>
   As those arrested were led away, others shouted to police to let
them go.
</P>
<P>
   In the earlier raid on the training center, police seized
materials that they said could be used to make firebombs.
</P>
<P>
   But thousands of activists, bearing backpacks and bravado,
gathered in the rain and vowed throughout the day to press ahead
with their planned Sunday and Monday protests.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, they've made us more passionate,'' said Katie, a
friendly Wittenberg University student from Springfield, Ohio, who
had a phone number written prominently on her arm in indelible ink.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's for the legal team _ in case I get thrown in jail,'' she
explained, adding she didn't want to give her last name.
</P>
<P>
   The drizzly day began with police and fire officials entering
the protesters' ``convergence center'' _ a brick warehouse across
town from the World Bank and IMF buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The fire department had been warned of possible code violations
in the building, said Capt. Brian Lee. They closed the warehouse as
being ``immediately dangerous to life and health'' after finding
propane stoves and other hazards, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant chief Terry Gainer said police also found rags,
bottles and jars and flammable liquids that he said could be used
in making ``Molotov cocktails.''
</P>
<P>
   Protesters scoffed at the notion that they were making bombs.
What the police seized was paint remover and other materials to
make banners and placards, said Patrick Reinsborough, a spokesman
for the Mobilization for Global Justice, the umbrella organization
for scores of groups including, labor unions to environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``They even took our puppets,'' he said. ``It was clearly an
effort to silence us.''
</P>
<P>
   The protesters promptly moved their ``action prep'' and other
activities to a community center and sidewalks several blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a decentralized movement without leaders. This was just
one physical space, so closing it isn't going to change what is
happening,'' said Reinsborough. ``It just makes us stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   In the days before last night's mass arrests, police had made at
least 20 arrests _ several for allegedly possessing ammunition and
plastic pipes and chains used to link protesters together into
human barricades. Chief Ramsey said he expected 10,000 or more
protesters to be here for the annual meeting of financial ministers
and world bankers.
</P>
<P>
   The great variety of protesters are united in their accusations
that international financiers are destroying the environment
through improper development in Third World countries and imposing
monetary policies that hurt poor people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned about the growing gap between rich and poor in
the world,'' said Art Gish, who has been a social activist for 40
years. ``World trade organizations help cause it. I'm part of a
global movement that is determined to stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gish is an organic farmer who looked the part with his white
beard and broad-brimmed straw hat. He grows vegetables near Athens,
Ohio, and came to the protest with a group of students from Ohio
University.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters came in all ages and attire. Some had florescent
hair and pierced nostrils, lips and tongues. Others appeared to be
outfitted by L.L. Bean. They sipped bottled water and ate bread and
bean sprouts and dispersed for activities ranging from a ``Cinema
of Resistance Filmfest'' to a ``Save the Redwoods'' teach-in to a
protest outside a Gap store.
</P>
<P>
   Starlene Rankin, a gray-haired Green Party activist from Ames,
Iowa, talked earnestly with the row of stern men and women wearing
bright orange raincoats and white helmets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been telling those officers that they don't have to do
this. They can take off those uniforms and not be robots for the
police state,'' she explained. ``I'm trying to appeal to their
humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   She was undeterred by her failure to find converts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be in the streets tomorrow with or without
puppets,'' she vowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just a loser high school dropout who doesn't like the way
this country is going and wants to change it,'' said Chris, 21, who
came with a New Jersey group called ``Food Not Bombs'' and didn't
want to give his last name. ``The more people who protest to show
that we're unhappy with the way the system is, the harder it is to
ignore us.''
</P>
<P>
   Many were still stirred by the spirit of Seattle, where
sometimes violent protests disrupted world trade talks last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Direct action is the tactic that we have to use,'' said David
Hill, a labor organizer who graduated last spring from the
University of Texas at Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason we're getting so much attention here _ the
only reason that you're talking to me now _ is because of what
happened in Seattle,'' said Hill, who works for a union in New
York. ``Labor is a big part of the movement, but the union didn't
order me to come here. I'm doing this on my own. We're going to try
to shut down the city.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the protesters have promised non-violent
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been saying all the time that it will be peaceful, I
just hope they honor that. We don't want trouble here. We hope the
demonstrators don't resort to that type of activity,'' Chief Ramsey
told reporters. He said police had confiscated large plastic pipe
sections used to connect ``sleeping dragons'' _ human chains _ as
well as gas masks, chains, chicken wire, duct tape and rope.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, police raided a house and found small-caliber
ammunition and firebomb instructions, Gainer said.
</P>
<P>
   He said two people were arrested on Saturday morning for
refusing to obey police orders to leave the ``convergence center.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, about 20 protesters staged a dawn protest outside the
home of World Bank President James Wolfensohn. On his way to work,
Wolfensohn listened to the reading of a protest letter and saw
signs saying ``Wake Up World Bank'' before leaving.
</P>
<P>
   (The Associated Press contributed to this story).
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Dart can be reached by e-mail at: bobdart(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   (Alec Schultz can be reached by e-mail at: alecs(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Mobilization for Global Justice: www.a16.org
</P>
<P>
   Ruckus Society: www.ruckus.org
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
