<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PIRATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSCH'S FIRST START IS A LOSS: PIRATES BEAT METS, 2-0  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ The Mets played a very quiet game Saturday, losing
to the Pirates, 2-0, in 1 hour 57 minutes. Glendon Rusch pitched a
complete game in his first start as a Met, but when he made a
mistake _ a changeup to Kevin Young that caught too much of the
plate and turned into a two-run homer _ he paid for it.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Valentine was quiet as well, saying he has decided to stop
talking about the speech he gave this past week at the Wharton
School of Business in Philadelphia that ended with Valentine's
criticizing several players and front-office decisions to students.
Unlike Rusch, the Mets' manager will not be paying for his mistake.
</P>
<P>
   General Manager Steve Phillips and the co-owner Fred Wilpon said
Saturday that ``the Wharton situation,'' as Valentine called it, is
a closed issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everything's been addressed satisfactorily and we will
move forward today with putting this whole mess behind us,'' said
Phillips, who met with Valentine for an hour after Friday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby's version is the version that I will take at face value.
I don't know what sort of credence to lend to some sort of posting
on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   But Phillips lent significance to the issue when he flew here
Friday, unscheduled, to meet with Valentine. Valentine said he
never believed his job was in serious jeopardy because of his
comments at Wharton, but according to a person familiar with the
club's operations, the idea of firing Valentine was discussed among
Mets executives. But without knowing what effect the controversy
might have on the players, it was decided that firing Valentine
would be rash.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine's contract expires at the end of this year. If he were
to be fired, that decision would be made by Phillips, Wilpon said,
though Wilpon would expect to be consulted.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is someone in the organization that wanted him fired,
that's someone I didn't talk to,'' said Wilpon, who added that he
has spoken only to Phillips about the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the topic of firing Valentine arose in his
conversations with Phillips, Wilpon said: ``That was not the thrust
of the conversation that we had. The thrust of the conversation was
how do we go forward, how do you get the facts so that we know from
Bobby, and not from some anonymous person.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Wilpon nor Phillips said they wanted to investigate the
issue further, despite the possible existence of a videotape of
Valentine's speech. Phillips said he hoped that if there is a tape,
it has been destroyed, and added that he would not watch it if it
existed; to do so, he said, would imply that he did not trust
Valentine's explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine would not comment Saturday on a published report that
suggested he may have asked that a tape of his talk be destroyed.
Wilpon said neither he nor Phillips had first-hand knowledge of
that, though Phillips said it was his understanding that it may, in
fact, have happened.
</P>
<P>
   For now, it seems, Valentine's only crime is telling the 100 or
so students at the speech to keep his comments confidential. One
student posted the comments on the Mets' official Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't be naive to think that the words can be private,''
Wilpon said. ``We have to be realistic to know that whatever we
say, we're in the public arena and a public sport and people want
to know. It can't be private.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilpon reiterated that he has told Valentine _ just as he tells
everyone he works with, he said _ that a person must be responsible
for his or her actions and statements. Wilpon said he would talk
with Valentine the next time he sees him, but for now, he is going
through Phillips, leaving two very different people to sort through
an uneasy relationship.
</P>
<P>
   If Valentine remains as manager, controversies over comments he
makes will probably be recurring issues. Phillips said the core
group of Mets learned last year to deal with such distractions.
Valentine said he pulled aside each of the Mets individually _
except for Rusch, because he was Saturday's starting pitcher _ to
talk with them about the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine said he wanted ``to alleviate confusion and to let
them know that if there ever is confusion, that I am here to
alleviate it, not to create it.''
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were held to five hits by Pirates left-hander Jimmy
Anderson, who had pitched only a third of an inning against them in
his career. Several Mets sounded satisfied that Anderson would not
repeat such success the next time he faces them. ``Sometimes you
can deal with it,'' said second baseman Edgardo Alfonzo of his
0-for-3 day at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Mets catcher Todd Pratt called Rusch's performance
``Glavine-esque,'' referring to two-time Cy Young winner Tom
Glavine of the Atlanta Braves. Rusch said he has always admired
Glavine and tries to emulate the way he works the outside part of
the plate and uses his change-up so effectively. ``I'm ecstatic,''
Bobby Valentine said of Rusch's outing, in which he allowed four
hits and one walk. Rusch, the Mets' fifth starter, was pitching for
the first time in 11 days, since he worked in an exhibition game at
Class AAA Norfolk on April 4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
