<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS GO DOWN SWINGING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT -- The Kings crashed the net and nearly crashed the
party.
</P>
<P>
   They came at the Detroit Red Wings with goals and fists and a
high octane passion that might one day make them the hunted ones.
But not Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings are still the Red Wings, and always stayed on top
no matter how hard the Kings tried to pierce the frenzy of a sold
out Joe Louis Arena during an 8-5 loss in Game 2 of this
best-of-seven series .
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to be down two games, but there is no time for
frustration,'' said Ziggy Palffy, who scored twice. ``That was a
great game out there tonight. We took it to them. Now we go back to
L.A and we'll get a win.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the button down 2-0 opener Thursday, this one was wide
open from the opening whistle.When they weren't scoring, both teams
were ringing shots off the cross bar. And unlike Game 1 when they
were the stars of the night, goaltenders Chris Osgood and Stephane
Fiset were punished for standing in the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are showing them that we are not going to just fade
away,'' said a stern Kings coach Andy Murray, who pulled Fiset
after the Wings' fifth goal. ``Most people don't even know what we
are doing here, but we do. We are down 2-0, but we are not going to
slide away. Not with the energy we showed tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings and Red Wings, who continue the series Monday night at
Staples Center, combined for the fastest six goals (6:56) to open a
game since the NHL started keeping records during the 1943-44
season.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Palffy, Luc Robitaille, Craig Johnson and Sean
O'Donnell had goals for the Kings, who outshot Detroit 44-43.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly wasn't a perfect game, not when turnovers by
defenseman Garry Galley and Jere Karalahti led to two Red Wings
goals in the first 93 seconds of the game. And the Kings were
annoyed with the ruthless play of Detroit strongman Darren McCarty,
who helped bottle them up after Palffy cut the lead to 6-5 with
1:11 gone in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   But they also never had an answer for Martin Lapointe, who
scored three times, including the eventual game winner midway
through the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, Detroit's top guns Steve Yzerman and Sergei
Fedorov never joined the fun. Yzerman, back after missing the
opener with the flu and a tender knee, had two assists. Fedorov,
who played harassing defense and scored an empty netter in Game 1,
assisted on Lapointe's second goal. It came at the 6:56 mark of the
second period and gave Detroit a 4-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Kris Draper scored twice and Niklas Lidstrom added two goals in
the final 11 minutes of the third period, including an empty netter
after Jamie Storr was pulled for an extra attacker.
</P>
<P>
   It was Draper's first goal, after a sprint up the right boards
and a blast near the Kings blue line, that got Fiset pulled.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I wasn't mad at him,'' Murray said. ``His teammates let
him down.''
</P>
<P>
   Fiset certainly wasn't to blame for the first two. On the first,
Galley fumbled with the puck behind the Kings net. Slava Kozlov,
who scored the Wings first goal Thursday, took control and took a
shot. Brendan Shanahan got the rebound and scored on the second try
55 seconds into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Just 38 seconds later, Karalahti, who has been consistent since
joining the team in December, tried to send the puck off the
boards, but missed. Kirk Maltby picked it up and passed cross ice
to the slot where Lapointe was waiting.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, a lot of television probably blinked off. ABC's
national telecast was 1:33 old and the tattered Kings trailed 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Murray called time out.
</P>
<P>
   The tone of the game was looser than Thursday and he urged his
forwards to get involved.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty one seconds later, Robitaille scored the 46th playoff
goal of his career, on a rebound in front of Osgood. Robitaille did
not have a shot in the first two periods Thursday and just one
overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the timeout helped us regain our composure,'' Galley
said. ``We knew we could play with these guys, but the game was
quickly getting out of hand. After that it was pretty even. We just
came up a little short.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
