<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8055 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-DRAFT-1STLD-WRITE     04-15 1274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENN STATE'S DEFENSE PROVIDES THE 1-2 PUNCH: BROWN AND ARRINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to make changes in 2nd-to-last graf.)  
(See also FBN-DRAFT-ASSESS, FBN-NOTEBOOK, FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT 8, 9 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Cleveland Browns have spent weeks scrutinizing,
analyzing and agonizing over two players from Penn State,
linebacker LaVar Arrington and defensive lineman Courtney Brown.
Back and forth the Browns went, sometimes in heated discussions.
Arrington possesses explosive athletic ability, but Brown is the
kind of player who can dominate a game.
</P>
<P>
   The Browns ended up actually rating Arrington a small percentage
higher than Brown on their draft board, but then visions of last
season danced in the heads of the Cleveland brass. They remembered
opposing quarterbacks sitting comfortably in the pocket and picking
apart their defense, which had a league-low 25 sacks. Suddenly the
answer became crystal clear.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland chose Brown Saturday with the first overall pick of
the National Football League draft, and in doing so selected a
player who could be a defensive anchor on the Browns' line for
years to come. They picked him only a matter of minutes after
reaching agreement on a six-year contract with the 6-foot-5-inch,
265-pound player who has a chance to be the next Bruce Smith. In
fact, Brown is the first defensive end picked No. 1 overall since
Smith was selected first by Buffalo in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a long, healthy discussion about both players,''
Cleveland coach Chris Palmer said. ``Basically what it came down to
was that we really needed a pass rusher, and Courtney is just such
a great football player.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown did not have to wait long to see the destination of his
excitable teammate. The Washington Redskins, as expected, selected
Arrington with the second overall pick, making it the first time
that two players from the same university were drafted 1-2 since
1984.
</P>
<P>
   `For Courtney to go No. 1, there's no disappointment from me,''
Arrington said. ``I mean, I couldn't be picked after a better guy.
Courtney, I think he deserved it. I just feel like I was the
natural pick for the Redskins.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington used its third selection to pick Alabama offensive
tackle Chris Samuels. There is no question that the Redskins,
already loaded with talent, should be favored to represent the
National Football Conference in the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   With the 11th selection, the Giants boosted a weak running game
by picking Ron Dayne, the Heisman Trophy winner out of Wisconsin, a
power back whose brutal running style fits their desire to pound
the football.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets, who had four selections in the first round, met their
need for help on the defensive line by picking Tennessee defensive
end Shaun Ellis at No. 12 even though some teams had rated him
lower in the first round. With the 13th pick, the Jets selected
linebacker John Abraham from South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   After making the most trade noise of almost any team in the
draft, Cincinnati made Peter Warrick the fourth selection. The
Bengals had thought seriously of trading down. While they were on
the 15-minute deadline clock, the Bengals fielded calls from teams
including the Jets. In the end, Cincinnati decided Warrick's
play-making ability was too enticing to pass up.
</P>
<P>
   There was speculation that the Baltimore Ravens might trade the
fifth pick _ the Giants recently inquired about it _ but they
decided to take Tennessee running back Jamal Lewis. Most scouts
rated Lewis as the best running back in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   There were only a handful of surprises in the top 10.
Philadelphia took Florida State defensive tackle Corey Simon with
the sixth pick despite recent shoulder operations, Arizona selected
the speedy Virginia running back Thomas Jones with the seventh
pick, Pittsburgh took Michigan State wide receiver Plaxico Burress
with the eighth pick, and Chicago selected New Mexico linebacker
Brian Urlacher ninth. Urlacher has moved rapidly up some team's
draft boards because of his exceptional workouts in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore, with the 10th pick, again helped its offense by
picking Florida's Travis Taylor, known for his speed and work
ethic.
</P>
<P>
   There were some definite shocks in the first round. First,
several personnel men said they were stunned by the lack of trades.
But teams, on draft day, were reluctant to give up picks to make a
move.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Marshall quarterback Chad Pennington, a possible
franchise quarterback, went lower than expected, with the Jets
grabbing him at No. 18. And by far the most surprising selection of
the day _ and maybe of the last five drafts _ was the Oakland
Raiders' picking Florida State kicker/punter Sebastian Janikowski
at 17.
</P>
<P>
   Janikowski, who weighs 260 pounds, was rated a third-rounder by
some scouts. One of the reasons was his arrest in an attempt to
bribe a police officer. A native of Poland, Janikowski faces
deportation because of those charges, though the Raiders must be
convinced that his situation will be fine.
</P>
<P>
   The days before the draft were among the most hectic ever.
Several times the Browns considered trading the first pick and
acquiring multiple picks to address their numerous needs.
</P>
<P>
   In one instance last week, they talked with the Jets, which
Cleveland general manager Carmen Policy confirmed in a television
interview. The Jets offered three of their four No. 1 picks to the
Browns; the Browns, in turn, requested all four of the Jets'
first-round picks. The Jets said no.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Cleveland held on to the pick because it felt that
Brown was a rare commodity _ a dominant defensive lineman who could
be among the best for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   All of the teams in the top five seriously considered making
major trades. In fact, one league executive maintained that of the
31 teams, at least 20 explored trades in the first round alone. The
Eagles heard from at least three teams: the Jets, Green Bay and
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Another theme in this draft was character. The NFL has urged its
teams to draft as much for character as for talent. A number of
teams, including the Denver Broncos and the Giants, either removed
troubled players from their draft boards or dropped them
significantly in their rankings.
</P>
<P>
   One player who dropped on the boards of some teams, perhaps
unfairly, is Burress. He missed a scheduled appointment with
several teams, including the Philadelphia Eagles, because he wanted
to attend the college basketball Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles began to spread the word that Burress had a bad
attitude _ as well as other unsubstantiated information _ and his
stock began to drop. To some team scouts, the league's emphasis on
drafting players with good character had gone too far in this case.
The Steelers are not concerned about any off-field problems and
think Burress' 6-5 stature can overwhelm most cornerbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick might have been the first overall selection had it not
been for an arrest while at Florida State after he and a friend
paid $21.40 for $412.38 worth of clothing in a scam at a department
store. He also ran some lackluster times in the 40-yard dash.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are judging me by what I did,'' Warrick said. ``It was
something that happened. What I did was wrong, but I'm a better
person than that. Don't judge me by what I did. I can't please
everybody. I can't be what somebody else wants. I can only be
myself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
