<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FISHER PROMISES TO BE BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO - Derek Fisher's frustration was immediately evident
Saturday as he (almost) blew off a handful of reporters asking
about his sore ankle. It's a rare day that the talkative and
congenial Fisher gives a ``no comment,'' but it's rarer still that
an injury keeps the fourth-year guard from playing, so his
reluctance was understandable.
</P>
<P>
   An irritating bone spur has forced him to the injured list for
the first time in his career, and though Fisher is unhappy about
it, he's also adamant that he'll be back for the playoffs next
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not any question in my mind,'' he said. ``I've been
dealing with it for a while and just trying my best to be as
effective as I could. That was getting harder and harder. So
everybody decided that this (the injured list) would be the best
thing at this point. I still didn't want to do it. I mean, I wanted
to keep playing, but I was limited, to say the least ....
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have done this earlier if it wasn't for my personal
beliefs and things that I just don't like to do. And being injured,
I just don't like it, and never will.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the team didn't reveal the injury until last week, Fisher
clarified that the ankle actually has been bothering him for at
least a month. But he kept playing until Friday, and though he
preferred just a short rest, coach Phil Jackson decided to make the
roster move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really couldn't run,'' said Fisher. ``Every step, everything
hurt. And a lot of my game is speed and power and being able to
explode, not just on offense, but on the defensive end. And it
really limited me. I wasn't using it as an excuse and I'm not using
it now. Whenever you suit up and go out there, you have to perform.
Hopefully, this week (off) will do me good.''
</P>
<P>
   The condition may eventually require surgery, but for now Fisher
hopes that rest, therapy and medication will decrease the
inflammation - at least to begin the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing really has been able to knock it out for an extended
period of time,'' he said. ``It may feel great, but then a week
later, once we get through pounding and doing what we do on a daily
basis, it may come back.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fisher said he can play through the pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think so. I was doing it before,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   March on: The Lakers are 2-1 since clinching the NBA's best
record. But the starters continue to play into the fourth quarter,
and the intensity level has not noticeably waned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's been - I don't want to use the word admirable -
but I think it's been honest effort,'' Jackson said. ``And that's
the thing that's important for ballplayers to understand, is that
.... I think you have an obligation to your team and your fans and
to your principles of working hard and the right effort and all
that kind of stuff. And I hope that's a principle they've gotten.''
</P>
<P>
   LAKERS vs. MINNESOTA
</P>
<P>
   Tipoff: 2:30 p.m., Staples Center
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: KNBC-Channel 4; KLAC-AM (570)
</P>
<P>
   Lakers (66-13) update: They are 35-5 at Staples Center as they
head into their last home game of the regular season. A victory
would give the Lakers no worse than a tie with Indiana for the
NBA's best home record. But it will leave them short of the
franchise high for home wins (37). The Lakers have won 10 of the
last 11 meetings with Minnesota, including all three this season.
</P>
<P>
   Timberwolves (49-30) update: They've won five of their last six
games but needed two overtimes to beat lowly Vancouver on Friday.
Minnesota is currently seeded sixth in the West, which would pit
the Timberwolves against No. 3 Portland in the first round of the
playoffs. But the Wolves are within striking distance of the
teetering No. 4 seed, San Antonio, and have three games to try to
catch them.
</P>
<P>
   - Howard Beck
</P>
</TEXT>
