<HEADER>
A8253 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k BC-FISHER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      04-15 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE AMAZON ARMY' MARCHED TO SUPPORT STRIKING COAL MINERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIRARD, Kan. _ How many women marched on those freezing December
days in 1921 is unclear _ estimates ranged from 2,000 to 6,000,
almost all wearing ragged coats, run-down shoes, stocking caps and
dresses down to their ankles.
</P>
<P>
   The women _ wives and kin of striking miners _ tramped through
Crawford and Cherokee county coal camps: No. 23, Franklin, Camp 50,
Capaldo, Arma, Katy No. 2, Ringo, Chicopee and scores of others.
Their numbers grew each day.
</P>
<P>
   The only color amid the largely monochromatic mass came from the
American flags they carried.
</P>
<P>
   It was a time before strip mining became dominant; when coal
powered the nation and Kansas produced 2 million tons a year; when
most of the 517 mines in Crawford and Cherokee counties were
tunneled into the earth and miners usually worked lying on their
sides, hacking out the thin coal seams with laborious effort for
$1.25 a day. Living conditions were wretched, pay was arbitrarily
withheld, and more than 200 miners in southeast Kansas had been
injured or killed in 1921 alone.
</P>
<P>
   That winter most of the 8,000 miners here struck, and Alexander
Howat, the local union president, was jailed.
</P>
<P>
   Strikebreakers were brought in.
</P>
<P>
   The women marched.
</P>
<P>
   But they did more than march. They hounded those they called
``scabs,'' blocked entrances to mines and pursued company men
through the slag heaps, beating on them with their trusty brooms.
They sang songs of solidarity and gave as good as they got in
invective. In several languages, too.
</P>
<P>
   After a couple of days, the women had shut down the mines again.
At least for a while. But by the end of December, 49 of the women
had been arrested and jailed; shots had been fired at their feet in
an attempt to intimidate them; the panicked governor of Kansas set
up his command post at Pittsburg's Stilwell hotel; and the state
militia, including a machine gun company, had been activated.
</P>
<P>
   The nation had never seen anything like it. ``Near-anarchy,''
inveighed The New York Times, which gave the women the sobriquet by
which they would be known: ``The Amazon Army.''
</P>
<P>
   The press had raced here from all over the world. Breathless
dispatches spoke of the ``red sector of Kansas,'' ``Bolsheviks,''
``syndicalists,'' ``radicals'' and ``subversives.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the marchers were hungry, cold and angry.
</P>
<P>
   With the arrests, the local union leadership sent its miners
back to work; the ``scabs,'' many of them youths from Kansas
colleges, returned to their fraternity houses; the Kansas coal
industry started its long slide into oblivion; and The Amazon Army
was largely forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Until now. On April 30, a 10- by 12-foot mural of the women's
march and the miners' struggle will be unveiled at the John E.
Shireman Performing Arts Center at Girard High School.
</P>
<P>
   The painting, by Wayne Wildcat, a Lawrence artist, depicts the
miners, faces dirty and tired, and the marching women, erect,
determined, relentless.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as if we opened a Pandora's box,'' said Linda O'Nelio
Knoll, whose grandmother was one of the marchers. Knoll came across
the women's story while ruminating about a history project suitable
for the gifted junior high schoolers she teaches.
</P>
<P>
   Knoll had read the poems of the late Gene DeGruson, longtime
archivist at Pittsburg State University. He had dedicated one of
them, contained in a slim volume called Goats House, to his mother,
Clemence Merciez DeGruson, who had been a marcher. Part of that
poem:
</P>
<P>
   In '21, my mother still herself at seventeen marched for
Alexander Howat to bust the scabs who worked the mines in place of
the fathers and husbands of the women who marched with her carrying
their men's pit buckers filled with red pepper to throw in the eyes
of the poor scabs who cursed back in English to their Slovene,
German, French and Italian over the State Militia's rifle fire.
</P>
<P>
   Knoll's students dove into project, doing all sorts of research,
talking to old-timers, digging up bygone photographs and yellowing
news clippings. DeGruson's poem was the tip of an iceberg, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The students eventually wrote a 20-page play called ``The Army
of Amazons,'' which has been received with enthusiasm all over the
area. You can read it at www.digitalhistory.com by clicking on the
Pittsburg Middle School site. The play appeared about the same time
a grant sponsored by the PAACA//Pittsburg Arts Council, the Kansas
Arts Commission and the National Endowment for the Arts became
available.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Wildcat, 45, a half-blooded Yuchi Indian and a former
winner of the Governor's Art Award.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' Wildcat said, ``is one cool story.''
</P>
<P>
   Meaning, he added, it shows one of the first instances of
women's empowerment, something now taken for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has everything,'' he said. ``Those women, their husbands on
strike, broke, infants at home in a shack crying for milk. But they
didn't just sit. Instead they picked up their babies, brought their
young ones along, and went out and protested injustice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we think of protest as common. But it wasn't back then. It
was revolutionary.''
</P>
<P>
   Tolly Smith Wildcat, the artist's wife, did research for the
painting, discovering old photographs of the marchers that have
been incorporated into the mural.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got the grant,'' she said, ``I hardly knew Kansas had
coal. ... Once we got into it, everything opened up.''
</P>
<P>
   Disparate facts about the march: Mother Mary Harris Jones, ``The
Miners' Angel,'' came here to support the women; the marchers laid
American flags across mine openings, daring anyone to step on Old
Glory; and a leader of the march was Mary Skubitz, whose fluency in
five languages helped communication among the ranks. Skubitz also
was the mother of a young boy named Joe who became a U.S.
congressman from southeast Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Knoll said the play, mural and the other ancillary discoveries
had resulted in a new appreciation of the rich, tumultuous history
of this area.
</P>
<P>
   ``For instance, in the 1880s there was a mine disaster near
Frontenac,'' Knoll said. ``It killed 47 miners. They were buried in
a mass grave. No marker. No nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you know what? I'll bet in a couple of years we have a
marker. Now people down here want to remember.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
