<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMESCHOOL-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   {KANSAS CITY, Mo. :...``Wise Women.''}  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Hendrix took courses at Johnson County Community
College. Last semester, she carried a full load there at her
mother's urging but disliked the rigid schedule, sometimes skipping
morning classes.
</P>
<P>
   But she's sure she won't have trouble readjusting to classroom
life when she joins the other freshmen at the University of Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Hendrix scored well enough on the Preliminary Scholastic
Assessment Test to win a National Merit Scholarship. And she scored
a perfect 800 on the literature portion of the SAT II.
</P>
<P>
   Most U.S. colleges and universities accept homeschooled
students, and some even recruit them, said Christopher Klicka,
executive director of the National Center for Home Education. Many
colleges are attracted by the self-discipline and motivation of
their homeschooled applicants, Klicka said.
</P>
<P>
   His organization estimates there are about 200,000 homeschooled
students in college now, and that number will continue to rise as
the movement grows, Klicka said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The homeschool movement is growing up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many church-affiliated colleges and universities have accepted
homeschoolers for years, and most state schools do, too.
Homeschooled students are among the undergraduates at KU, Kansas
State University and the University of Missouri-Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Ashley Miller, though, will be heading east this fall to Earlham
College in Indiana to pursue a degree in music. And he'll pay for
his four years at the liberal arts college with the money he earned
in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   His parents, Kriss and Gary Miller, want their children's
education to be practical.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my kids can have a stock portfolio instead of an accounting
class, doesn't that make more sense?'' Kriss Miller asked.
</P>
<P>
   That philosophy is why Ashley and his sister, Abbi, practice
their math skills by having checking accounts. That's why Ashley
does the maintenance on his car. And that's why Gary and Ashley
Miller last year built a recording studio in the basement of their
brick ranch home outside Kearney.
</P>
<P>
   The 16-channel recording studio lets Ashley Miller record his
original compositions, mixing the parts independently. He also
practices there with his punk band, Annie on My Mind.
</P>
<P>
   Miller says homeschooling has allowed him to ``evolve himself,''
although he suspects his interests would be the same even if he'd
been formally schooled.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a little bit more of a personal route,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Kriss Miller strives for as she guides the education
of her children. Life isn't divided into separate subjects, she
said. And because her children learn by doing, Miller thinks they
will retain more of what they're exposed to.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they leave this house to function in the real world, I
feel like they're going to be well equipped,'' Miller said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
