<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-IRAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: IRAN'S DUBIOUS ESPIONAGE TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Sunday, April 16:
</P>
<P>
   Iran's justice system is run by conservative Islamic clerics,
not the reform-minded government of President Mohammad Khatami. But
clerical control does not absolve Iranian courts of their
responsibility to provide fair, impartial and transparent justice
in the trial of 13 Iranian Jews that opens May 1 in Shiraz.
</P>
<P>
   The 13 are accused of spying for Israel, charges that carry a
potential death penalty. Israel and all the defendants deny that
the alleged spying took place. Proceedings were set to start this
week, but they have now been delayed in honor of the Jewish holiday
of Passover. That could be an encouraging sign that intense
international concern is leading Iran to reconsider its offensive
handling of this case.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the first arrests a year and a half ago, elementary
considerations of due process have been overridden. Conservative
Iranian news media have been unrestrained in whipping up public
animosity, though neither the formal charges nor any incriminating
evidence has ever been made public. The defendants were only
recently allowed to choose their own lawyers, who have not yet been
given adequate time to prepare. Court proceedings are being held in
secret, and requests by the Iranian Jewish community and
international human rights organizations to send observers have
been denied. These abuses have brought protests from the
governments of France, Germany, Britain, the European Union, the
United States and Israel, as well as private organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Iran's Islamic Constitution grants legal tolerance to Jews. But
since the 1979 revolution the Jewish community has suffered
persecutions, prejudice and violence. Of the 80,000 Jews who lived
in Iran before the revolution, fewer than half remain.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants in this case should not be punished for their
religion or to score points in the ongoing battle between clerical
conservatives and reformers. They are entitled to a fair and open
trial, and to acquittal if the charges against them cannot be
convincingly proved.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-15-00 2254EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
