<DOCNO> NYT20000415.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8261 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-HOMESCHOOL-2TAKES-KAN     04-15 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMESCHOOL-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NONTRADITIONAL HOMESCHOOLERS CHERISH THE NONCONFORMITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE BEEM  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ For Amanda Hendrix, 10th grade looked
something like this: Language arts was a writing workshop at the
Coterie Theatre, social studies was a three-week trip to France,
and home economics was instruction on vegetarian cooking and
medicinal herbs.
</P>
<P>
   For Ashley Miller, one junior year math exercise consisted of
investing in the stock market. Miller studied his pick and invested
$10,000 last summer. By the end of the year, he'd made $80,000.
</P>
<P>
   Hendrix and Miller are products of homeschooling, but not the
traditional version, which is based on religious freedom. Theirs is
based on educational freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Homeschooling in all its forms has been gaining popularity the
past two decades. By some estimates, as many as 1.7 million U.S.
children forgo formal schooling to learn from their parents at
home.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Virginia-based National Center for Home
Education, Missouri has 30,000 to 35,000 homeschoolers and Kansas
15,000 to 17,500. The numbers are estimates only; although the
practice is legal in every state, most don't require homeschoolers
to register. And those that do, such as Kansas, don't enforce the
rule.
</P>
<P>
   Hendrix and Miller, both 17, are the first members of a local
secular homeschooling group, LEARN, to finish their home studies
and head for higher education.
</P>
<P>
   LEARN, which stands for Let Education Always Remain Natural,
began in late 1995. Homeschooling parents Kelly Wilson of Kansas
City and Kriss Miller, Ashley's mother, felt like a minority within
their homeschooling support group, which was geared toward people
who homeschooled for religious reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson and Miller wanted a support group of another kind. Both
had decided to teach their children at home because they believe
formal schooling breeds conformity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schooling can get in the way of trying to learn things,''
Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   LEARN now has 68 member families across the Kansas City area.
All recognize, as LEARN's mission statement spells out, that
members' beliefs aren't necessarily the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't care where you go to church,'' said Wilson, a mother
of two. ``It's just not an issue for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Some LEARN members have traditional classrooms set up in their
homes, and children learn from formal curricula and textbooks.
Others, such as Miller and Wilson, favor ``unschooling,'' in which
children's interests guide their learning and school isn't an
activity separate from other family endeavors.
</P>
<P>
   The group meets the last Monday of each month at All Souls
Unitarian Universalist Church in Kansas City, and throughout the
year members plan field trips, play days and family activities. On
March 31, six families left for the Grand Canyon. In May, LEARN
families will hold their annual prom.
</P>
<P>
   Miller thinks that having a group of people that understands
where you're coming from is paramount to homeschooling success.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to find people that homeschool, because we need to
feel supported,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When they start out, homeschoolers often encounter pressure and
misunderstanding from family and neighbors. One of the most common
criticisms is that homeschooled students are isolated socially.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a downside, what people say is kids that are
homeschooled don't have the same opportunities for interaction that
kids have in a school setting,'' said Judy Seltz of the American
Association of School Administrators.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson counters that LEARN families come from a variety of
backgrounds and the group's field trips expose children to all
sorts of experiences. Members plan outings to parks all over the
area, for example. Many students volunteer, too.
</P>
<P>
   Social isolation is not an aspect of homeschooling that worries
Gene Neely, president of the Kansas National Education Association.
Children whose parents are well educated and conscientious will
turn out much as they would have in school, Neely suggested: well
rounded and socialized.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's too early in the homeschooling movement to judge how
well children perform as adults, Neely said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as I may think parents make the wrong choice, it's
really difficult to criticize the folks who do it and do it well,''
Neely said. ``What we don't hear about are the kids who don't do
well.''
</P>
<P>
   For Susan Myers, Hendrix's mother, LEARN was validation that she
wasn't making a mistake when she let her daughter quit high school.
</P>
<P>
   During her freshman year at Shawnee Mission East High School,
Hendrix picked up a copy of The Teen-Age Liberation Handbook by
Grace Llewellyn. Among other things, the book advocates teen-agers'
taking control of their education through homeschooling.
</P>
<P>
   Hendrix found answers to what had been bugging her about school
since the third grade: She felt forced to learn things she wasn't
interested in, and she never had time to pursue in depth the things
that really mattered to her, such as writing and performing. And
she was stressed by the pressure she felt to maintain good grades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't free to do what I chose to,'' Hendrix said.
``Whatever it was, it was all directed by the school. You had to go
to it all day, but you weren't even done when you got home.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she knew school was disturbing for her younger
daughter, it took some persuading for Myers to allow Hendrix to
leave East. She kept fretting over whether Hendrix was taking
enough classes to get into college.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was anxious and worried a lot that Amanda would miss out,''
Myers said.
</P>
<P>
   Hendrix grinned and patted her upswept hair, stiff with hair
spray from a stint earlier in the day as a saloon girl in a Lyric
Opera production. ``That's backwards thinking,'' she said. ``I was
missing out in school.''
</P>
<P>
   So she left East after her freshman year. She spent the next
three years ``unschooling,'' reading books and exploring subjects
that caught her fancy. Although Myers continued to work, she kept
tabs on her daughter's activities and compiled transcripts at the
end of each semester as the two looked back over what Hendrix had
accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   Hendrix took French and Italian at a private school. She took
voice lessons. She performed in plays and musicals, such as the
Civic Opera of Kansas City's December production of ``Wise Women.''
(MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
