<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BLUEGRASS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH YIELD'S BLUE GRASS SHOWS HE'S READY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DURSO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEXINGTON, Ky. _ In his final dress rehearsal for the Kentucky
Derby three weeks from now, High Yield defeated More Than Ready by
a head Saturday to win the Blue Grass Stakes and position himself
among the leaders on the road to Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   High Yield, a son of Storm Cat who won the Fountain of Youth in
Florida last month and the Hopeful at Saratoga last September,
carried D. Wayne Lukas one step closer to another Derby as the most
successful trainer in modern racing. But before he did, he had to
put away an early challenge from the storybook horse, Hal's Hope,
who faded and finished last, and a late challenge from More Than
Ready, who brushed High Yield several times as they dueled down the
homestretch at Keeneland.
</P>
<P>
   High Yield lived up to his notices as a well-traveled warrior
who has raced from California to Florida to Kentucky, winning 4 of
his 12 starts and running in the money 11 times. He is now aimed
directly at the Derby on May 6 at Churchill Downs, where he will
tangle with Fusaichi Pegasus, who won the Wood Memorial at Aqueduct
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't be happier with a horse,'' said Lukas, who has won
the Kentucky Derby four times. ``He's got pedigree and speed, and
he fights back. There are so many good 3-year-olds this year that
the Derby will be a handicapper's nightmare. But we'll be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the eight colts who ran in the Blue Grass suffered
unhappy trips with unhappy results. Mighty, who won the Louisiana
Derby last month for Claiborne Farm, brushed the side of the gate
at the start and eventually faded to seventh place. The only horse
he beat was Hal's Hope, who wrote a fairy tale saga in Florida by
racing into prominence for his 88-year-old breeder, trainer and
owner, Harold Rose.
</P>
<P>
   But this was a day when speed outran sentiment, and the early
speed was flashed predictably by High Yield, More Than Ready and
Hal's Hope. After half a mile, High Yield led by a head over Hal's
Hope while More Than Ready stalked them from third place. After
three-quarters of a mile, they were still locked in a speed match
separated by a few feet. As they turned for home, Hal's Hope
suddenly surrendered his place to More Than Ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``High Yield took control going into the turn,'' said Pat Day,
who rode the colt for the third straight time, ``and I was able to
secure room down inside. He was very relaxed at this point. Then,
turning for home, he fought back very gamely. It was a heroic
effort in the stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   The fractions probably told the story on Hal's Hope, winner of
the Holy Bull and the Florida Derby. He captured the public's fancy
with his owners, Rose and his 85-year-old wife, Elsie, and their
42-year-old jockey, Roger Velez, a recovering alcoholic who, like
Rose, had suffered a stroke in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The horse stayed the first quarter-mile in 23 1/5 seconds, the
half-mile in 46 seconds and three-quarters of a mile in 1:09 4/5.
When they hit the stretch with its final 1,174 feet, they had raced
one mile in 1:35 2/5, and the tiring Hal's Hope was no longer being
pushed by his jockey.
</P>
<P>
   But High Yield had to shake off the bruising drive of John
Velazquez and More Than Ready, who won his first five races last
year and chased Mighty home in the Louisiana Derby.
</P>
<P>
   As they crossed the line, Wheelaway, winner of the Tampa Bay
Derby last month, was third, three lengths behind More Than Ready.
He was followed by Deputy Warlock, Bare Outline and Settlement,
three long-shots, and by Mighty and Hal's Hope.
</P>
<P>
   The final time, before a Keeneland record crowd of 29,687, was
1:48 3/5. High Yield paid $5.80 for a $2 bet to win and headed for
Churchill Downs with $465,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not crying about this by any means,'' said Todd Pletcher,
the trainer of More Than Ready. ``My horse ran as good as anyone
could run against the grain of this track. The inside speed has won
almost every race in the last two days.''
</P>
<P>
   John Kimmel, who trains Wheelaway for his father, Caesar Kimmel,
agreed that the Keeneland track paid off on inside speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wheelaway ran a huge race,'' he said, ``especially when you
consider that the track was really playing to all the speed. I
think my horse ran his way into contention for the Kentucky
Derby.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
