<HEADER>
A8270 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-INTERNET-MYTHS-2TAKES     04-15 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-MYTHS-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE'RE SUCKERS FOR URBAN LEGENDS THAT THRIVE ON THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The banana will not eat your flesh.
</P>
<P>
   Hydrogen peroxide will not cure your cancer.
</P>
<P>
   There's no serious plan to tax your e-mail, to sell your census
specifics to strangers, or to ban Jesus from public television.
</P>
<P>
   And never-kidnapped Kelsey Brooke Jones, whose disappearance
story and digitized picture continue to circulate around the globe,
is home safely in the bosom of Faribault, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   Arm us with unfathomable calculating power and fingertip access
to the world's great libraries and periodicals. We still, it seems,
make P.T. Barnum proud. Born every minute, we are suckered into one
urban legend or dubious conspiracy theory or not-quite-so yarn
after the next.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have always bought into fanciful things,'' said Joe
Nickell of the Committee for the Scientific Investigation of Claims
of the Paranormal. ``The subjects always tap into people's basic
hopes and fears.''
</P>
<P>
   So fears of demons in the Middle Ages evolved to ghost sightings
in Victorian times and into alien abductions in the jet age, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, as Americans hunch over their keyboards for longer
periods, fears grow of about the vulnerability to the gargantuan
computer network known as the Internet. A recent virus hoax warns
of e-mail with ``Jesus'' in the subject line _ supposedly crafted
by a rabidly atheist professor _ that will devour your hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who are new to the Internet have been reading horror
stories in the media for years about these viruses that will
destroy everything,'' said Rob Rosenberger, who runs an anti-virus
hoax Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then they get an e-mail warning from a friend who's been
duped, and in two seconds they hit the `send to all' button. It's
passed on to everybody in their (e-mail) address book...
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could come up with a virus, it would delete that `send to
all' button.''
</P>
<P>
   While there's no way to measure how often we're fooled by
fantastic tales, people who chart the urban legends we pass on, and
on, say the fiction moves faster today on the Internet's
speed-of-light transom. The stories also reflect our times: fears
of the incredible technology we rely on, hope for solutions or
excitements yet to visit our easy lives, suspicion of those in
power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the legends we tell are a reflection of current
societal concerns or a search for excitement,'' said Barbara
Mikkelson, who runs a Web site in Agoura, Calif., debunking urban
legends.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have always been worried about their health. So today
you hear lots of things about needles in (play area) ball pits and
on movie theater seats. Today we worry about HIV and AIDS.''
</P>
<P>
   Add to that, say Mikkelson and others who track the modern myth,
is a distrust of government. They say a post-Vietnam,
post-Watergate, post-Lewinsky America is conditioned to expect lies
from the highest authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of distrust in government,'' she said. ``It's a
standard feeling that if someone has power over your life, you
distrust them.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether bred of anxiety about government, technology or an
increasingly impersonal society, the stories grow. Some recent
examples:
</P>
<P>
   - ``Bananas from Costa Rica have been infected with ...
flesh-eating bacteria,'' reads a well-traveled e-mail. ``The
disease has been able to graft itself to the skin of fruit (and),
until this finding, scientists were not sure how the infection was
being transmitted.''
</P>
<P>
   Relax, implores the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention, the rare disease strikes fewer than one in 15,000
Americans a year. It is most often passed person to person, and
consumption of fruit would be ``an unlikely cause for necrotizing
fasciitis. ... The bacteria cannot survive long on the surface of a
banana.''
</P>
<P>
   - Last month Kansas City radio talk show host Chris Baker told
listeners that for $40 anyone could read the census forms the
government was ordering them to fill out. Producer Scott Voorhees
quickly had Baker qualify the statement to say the records were
open to anyone ``authorized by the government.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, federal law makes individual census returns
confidential for 72 years. The rule is backed by penalties of a
$5,000 fine and a five-year prison term for sharing the forms with
the wrong people.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out people ``authorized by the government'' are limited
to the parents of minor children, guardians of the mentally
incompetent and the relatives of a dead person. That exception is
made when a birth certificate isn't available.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize we're making a stretch here,'' Voorhees said. ``But
it seems like a lot of the time the government can't be trusted.''
</P>
<P>
   - ``I have a five-year-old daughter named Kelsey Brooke Jones.
We are from southern Minnesota. She has been missing since pm Oct.
11, 1999. ... If anyone anywhere knows anything, sees anything,
pleeeeaaaase contact me.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelsey was missing when her mother, Amy Wolkenhauer, wrote the
message. But she had only wandered off to play with a friend, and
was back in less than two hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was true when she wrote the e-mail,'' said Taylor Wilcox, a
case manager for Missing Children Minnesota. ``But the plea for
help has lived on much longer than the case.''
</P>
<P>
   - ``I just heard recently,'' a Blue Springs woman wrote to The
Kansas City Star, ``that the Federal Communications Commission has
voted 3-2 to remove Christian broadcasting from all noncommercial
TV stations.''
</P>
<P>
   This is where fact gets slightly fictionalized. In ruling on the
licensing of a public television station to a Christian
broadcasting firm in Pittsburgh, the FCC said the firm could air
religious shows. But, in a controversial vote, the commission ruled
that the company could not count ``religious exhortation,
proselytizing or statements of personally held religious views and
beliefs'' toward its requirement to fill more than half its time
with educational programming.
</P>
<P>
   - Pity The Washingtonian. One version of a recent rumor passed
on an editorial supposedly penned by its staff extolling a tax on
e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never,'' the monthly magazine responded, ``wrote such an
article. ... The congressman quoted does not exist, the bill number
does not exist, the law firm which supposedly wrote this e-mail
does not exist. ... It is not true.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be so easy to pick on the Internet, said Jamie Love,
director of the Consumer Project on Technology, as the bogeyman who
dupes us. But people have always fallen for tall tales. Cyberspace
only allows them to travel more quickly.  &QL; 
(MORE)
</P>
<P>
   (KANSAS CITY, Mo.: more quickly.)
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, there's so much crap floating around on the
Internet it just makes you more skeptical,'' Love said. ``My
experience is that when you put something wrong out on the
Internet, you're almost immediately bombarded by people trying to
point out your mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail rumor probably grew, he said, from people's love of
e-mail and their fear of having to pay by the message.
</P>
<P>
   Other times the engine behind a fantasy is profit. Indiana State
University chemistry professor John Allen wrote a recent article
for Skeptical Inquirer magazine debunking so-called oxygen therapy,
which often includes the drinking of hydrogen peroxide, as a way to
fight diseases such as cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has just enough science to fool people. But it's fraud and
charlatanism and snake oil sales at its worst,'' Allen said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   It's promoted by people preying on the desperate, he said, and
believed by people who can't find hope elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think the (U.S. Food and Drug Administration) are in
collusion with the drug companies to keep this quiet to make more
money,'' Allen said. ``People gravitate to conspiracy theories
because they reinforce a dislike for big institutions. ... Besides,
those explanations are so much more exciting than real life.''
</P>
<P>
   The solution, he said, is to understand the source of
information and the source's motives. Then, he said, favor the more
plausible over the fantastic.
</P>
<P>
   ``If something sounds outrageous,'' Allen said, ``it probably is
outrageous.''  &QL; 
(OPTIONAL INFORMATION FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   According to the urban legend-debunking site www.snopes.com,
maintained by amateur sleuths Barbara and David Mikkelson, these
are a few fresh phonies:
</P>
<P>
   Rumor: The glue on deposit envelopes at automated teller
machines is laced with cyanide.
</P>
<P>
   Reality: Lick away. This started in Canada, where someone
thought they heard it on radio.
</P>
<P>
   Rumor: Amazon.com gave a thumbs-up review to the anti-Semitic
tome The Protocol of the Elders of Zion.
</P>
<P>
   Reality: No attaboy to the author from the online bookseller,
although it does let cybersurfers post their reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Rumor: Forwarding a particular e-mail will get you a free
cellular phone (or computer company stock, or free cases of soda,
or ...).
</P>
<P>
   Reality: Wishful thinking only.
</P>
<P>
   Rumor: The U.S. Postal Service is discontinuing its ``Black
Heritage'' stamp series.
</P>
<P>
   Reality: The stamps have been a popular issue for 20 years, and
the post office is still selling them.
</P>
<P>
   Rumor: Kentucky Fried Chicken became KFC because the government
says genetically modified poultry no longer counts as chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Reality: It was the ``fried,'' not the ``chicken.'' It still
fries chicken; it just doesn't want to emphasize its deep-fat
cooking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
