<HEADLINE>
HUNDREDS ARE ARRESTED ON EVE OF BIG D.C . RALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Police corralled, handcuffed, and led away hundreds
of people protesting the World Bank and International Monetary Fund
Saturday night, as the capital braced for protests Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The arrests of as many as 600 peaceful demonstrators was a
display of force. Officials have said all along they would not
tolerate the lawlessness that tore apart meetings of the World
Trade Organization in Seattle last year.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, police here have been training since January, and
have spent more than $1 million on security preparations.
</P>
<P>
   The clearest show of muscle came Saturday night, as police in
riot gear herded hundreds of activists, along with one tourist and
a news photographer, behind barricades, then arrested them for
demonstrating without a permit.
</P>
<P>
   Police then transported the demonstrators away on school buses.
Demonstrators shouted ``shame, shame'' as police made the arrests.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Washington police closed a warehouse being
used by anti-IMF organizers. They also tightened security
throughout the capital, as thousands of demonstrators poured into
town.
</P>
<P>
   Police said that the warehouse violated safety codes, and that
they had found a device that resembled a homemade explosive. One
demonstrator, however, said police had ``been looking for any
excuse to shut us down,'' and other protesters said the aggressive
police moves had been intended to intimidate people from joining
Sunday's rallies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the guise of fire violations, they have violated our
constitutional rights,'' said a protest spokesman, Adam Eidinger.
He said the device found was a plastic bottle, not a Molotov
cocktail.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgetown, about 150 demonstrators, including one almost
naked man, blocked the entrance to the Gap store, saying it
exploited underpaid laborers to make its clothes. A protester was
arrested for nudity after he dashed across the street wearing only
a grass skirt. Nearby, demonstrators carried a sign that read,
``We'd Rather Wear Nothing than Wear Gap.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the mass detentions, there had been 21
demonstration-related arrests since the protests began last
weekend. At least one of those arrests included seizure of
ammunition, police said.
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of as many as 10,000 protesters Sunday, police
have prepared extra jail space.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters insisted that their goal was passive resistance _ not
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been saying all the time that it will be peaceful,''
Police Chief Charles Ramsey said. ``I just hope they honor that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
