<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-15 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8285 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-CAVALIERS-     04-15 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-CAVALIERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS PICK A BAD TIME TO PLAY THEIR WORST
</HEADLINE>
  By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Although the dazed Allan Houston has spent the last
week groping for inspiration, he is only a symptom of the
unsettling mental slide the Knicks have found themselves in as they
prepare for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   For the meaningful minutes of the game, Houston was in another
world again Saturday night, right along with his cloud-covered
teammates, as the Knicks were embarrassed for the second time in 24
hours. This time, it wasn't the playoff-bound Raptors, but the
struggling Cavaliers who tucked them away with disturbing ease,
106-96, at Gund Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, down by 19 points in the third quarter, pulled to 10
at the start of the fourth only to have their sloppy perimeter
defense eaten alive by the Cavs' 3-point shooting during a 16-6
run. Cleveland built a 20-point lead with 5 minutes 21 seconds left
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   For the second night in a row, Houston (5 for 15, 21 points) was
not into the game on offense or defense. And his partners, Latrell
Sprewell (15 points) and Patrick Ewing (10 points), were absent in
spirit as well. The Cavs looked more like playoff contenders, with
six players scoring in double figures. They hit 9 for 19 on their
3-point shots and shot 47 percent. Somehow, the Knicks' sense of
urgency has been dulled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's totally unlike last year when we getting more intense and
more urgent and more desperate,'' Coach Jeff Van Gundy said before
the game. ``We're less of everything because we're in the playoffs
this year. Instead of heading toward playing our best, you can make
the case that in our last few games, we have been at our worst.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been an untimely lapse for the Knicks. Their chances of
catching the sliding Heat _ who have lost three in a row _ are
fading. The Knicks are one-and-a-half games behind the
second-seeded Heat. To catch them, the Knicks would have to win
their last two games, while the Heat would have to lose their three
remaining games.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last week, the Knicks have collapsed in the fourth
quarter against Miami, received a fortunate no-call on a goaltend
by Patrick Ewing to edge Indiana, played their worst ball of the
year in an overtime victory against the depleted Nets and were
embarrassed against the Raptors.
</P>
<P>
   It has infuriated their coach. But perhaps the Knicks are numb
to Van Gundy's rants of urgency. After coming undone in Toronto
against a team they may well meet in the first round of the
playoffs, there was an odd giddiness in their locker room before
the game.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be a prelude to their carefree attitude once
the game began. In one telling snapshot, the Knicks allowed Bob
Sura to sprint free on a fast break for an uncontested layup to
close the first quarter with the Knicks down, 31-22.
</P>
<P>
   On defense, Sprewell stared vacantly as Lamond Murray took him
off the dribble for 8 first-quarter points. On offense, Houston was
smartly driving to the basket, but he was going in blindly and
taking ill-advised circus shots. He ended the half shooting 1 for
9.
</P>
<P>
   If not for Marcus Camby, who scored 13 first-half points and
grabbed 7 rebounds off the bench, the Knicks would have had no
chance at all. As it was, they trailed by 59-45 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   With a couple of putbacks for dunks and trips to the free-throw
line, Camby brought them back to within 9 points with 1 minute left
in the first half. But quickly, the Knicks lost their composure.
When Ewing picked up his third foul, Childs barked at the officials
and drew a technical. Instead of closing in on the Cavaliers, the
Knicks let them end the second quarter on a 5-0 run.
</P>
<P>
   The Cavs were moving the ball and playing unselfishly with 21
assists, while the Knicks (10 assists) were holding the ball too
long and taking jumpers at the shot-clock buzzer. Cavs point guard
Andre Miller was breaking down Charlie Ward and getting the ball to
the open man, while the Knicks were tripping over each other and
shooting 34.3 percent in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear the Knicks were far from inspired. Playing on the
second night of a back-to-back game, the 37-year-old Ewing was
dragging, and Houston and Sprewell closed the first half a combined
3 for 13 from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Shawn Kemp in foul trouble, the Knicks couldn't
capitalize. In the third quarter, Kemp picked up his fourth foul
and went to the bench. After the Knicks closed to 67-57, they
failed to score on their next four possessions and let the Cavs
take a 74-57 lead with 4:51 left in the third.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks' weariness was magnified after Houston made just his
second basket of the game with 2:50 left in the period. The Cavs
pushed the ball up the floor and caught Ewing on his heels as
Andrew DeClercq streaked in for a fast-break dunk. Ewing was 20
feet behind. After they fell back by 19 points, the Knicks closed
the third down by 85-70.
</P>
<P>
   It was misery for Van Gundy to witness. All the progress the
Knicks made on their West Coast trip two weeks ago was slipping
away.
</P>
</TEXT>
