<HEADLINE>
DE FERRAN WANTS NO SUSPENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH _ Gil de Ferran cares about all you folks who are
putting out good money to secure a seat for today's 26th running of
the Toyota Grand Prix of Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   He knows, and readily admits, that the size of the crowd helps
turn the Long Beach race into one of the most popular stops for the
drivers on the CART FedEx Championship Series. And he would love
for the fans to see an exciting event. Just not today.
</P>
<P>
   De Ferran, a 32-year-old Brazilian born in Paris, hopes that the
most excitement of the weekend came on Saturday when he wrested the
pole position away from Target/Chip Ganassi Racing teammates Jimmy
Vasser and Juan Montoya in the closing minutes of a final and
frantic 30-minute qualifying session on the 11-turn, 1.968-mile
street circuit.
</P>
<P>
   De Ferran was the fifth and final leader in the final five
minutes of the session, which included the quickest drivers from
Friday's provisional qualifying. His best-lap time of 67.494
seconds at 104.969 miles per hour was just enough to hold off
Vasser (67.703 at 104.645 mph), Montoya (67.984 at 104.213 mph),
provisional pole sitter Adrian Fernandez (68.007 at 104.178),
Walker racing sub Bryan Herta (68.012 at 104.170) and
Miami-Homestead winner Max Papis (68.086 at 104.057).
</P>
<P>
   Today's 82-lap, 161.376-mile race begins at 1 p.m. This will be
the first time a Marlboro Team Penske driver starts on the pole
since Paul Tracy did it in 1997 at the oval in Milwaukee and the
first street-course pole for Penske since Al Unser Jr. was there in
1994 at Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully I'm going to disappear into the lead and make this
the most boring race in the history of Long Beach,'' de Ferran
said.
</P>
<P>
   Vasser, sitting on de Ferran's right, had his own hopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, just like in '96 when you disappeared in my (rear-view)
mirror,'' Vasser said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   De Ferran countered with a smile, albeit one with a twinge of
sadness, at the memory of a not-so-fond Long Beach memory when he
started on the pole and led 90 laps of the 104-lap race until a
disconnected turbocharger ended his day four laps shy of victory.
When de Ferran encountered his trouble, Vasser sped by en route to
the first of four consecutive Long Beach victories for Team Target.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't remind me,'' de Ferran told Vasser, ``it took me two
years to forget about that.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been more than two years since Marlboro Team Penske, once
the most feared on the circuit, has won a race. Since the final
race of 1999 season, Roger Penske made changes in personnel,
including bringing in de Ferran and Helio Castro-Neves to drive,
and switched from Mercedes-powered Penske cars with Goodyear tires
to the Honda- powered Reynards with Firestone rubber.
</P>
<P>
   The team, which is stuck on 99 Champ Car victories, has been
excellent in qualifying thus far. De Ferran was also on the pole in
the season-opener and Miami and Castro-Neves was slated to start
third in the snow-postponed Nazareth race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we did our homework and everything, but it's really
nice to get it confirmed,'' de Ferran said.
</P>
<P>
   Team Target, which has won four consecutive points
championships, has also adapted quickly to its changes during the
off-season. The biggest change, of course, was the switch from the
proven Honda/Reynard package to a Toyota/Lola setup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a great group of people on the race team,'' Vasser
said. ``That gives us a lot of confidence. But you've got to give
Chip Ganassi credit because he made some pretty bold decisions on
the chassis and engine that don't seem so ludicrous right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Montoya, the defending series and Long Beach champion, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how (Ganassi) does it, but he does,'' Montoya
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez improved on his provisional pole effort, but it wasn't
good enough to hold the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (car) was better today than yesterday, but for some reason
we couldn't get the most out of (it),'' Fernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the happiest driver in the first three rows, aside from
de Ferran, is Herta, who was hired early this week to replace
injured Shinji Nakano at Walker Racing for two races.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made the car better every session and we're all still
getting to know one another,'' Herta said. ``Gil's time was pretty
good, but I think we were just one or two runs away from being
right there with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the top 10 were Team Rahal's Kenny Brack, who was
on the pole after the first session on Saturday, Roberto Moreno,
Helio Castro-Neves and Player's Forsythe Racing sub Memo Gidley.
</P>
<P>
   Brack, making his first street-course start in three years, made
the biggest move of the day, improving from 21st to seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Dario Franchitti, last year's runnerup, will start in 19th after
another tough qualifying effort. He broke the right front tire of
his car on Turn 4 just four minutes into his session.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went out there and was trying a bit too hard on my first
lap,'' Franchitti said. ``I'll be (mad) for a while, but you've got
to get on with it. You need to start thinking about our strategy
for passing in the race.''
</P>
</TEXT>
