<HEADLINE>
SHORT NEWS ITEMS ABOUT BASKETBALL 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reggie Miller and Mark Jackson asked for contract extensions
earlier this season, requests that went nowhere. Donnie Walsh was
candid and honest with the two proud Indiana veterans, but Miller
and Jackson viewed the wait-and-see approach of Walsh, the Pacers'
president, as genuine disrespect for their longevity and loyalty to
the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have great respect for the guys who brought us to this
level,'' Walsh said last week in an interview at Madison Square
Garden. ``I like every one of them. I don't like this year because
I feel estranged.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're angry at me; I'm not angry at them. It's never been
like this before.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Eastern Conference getting younger and more athletic
each off-season, Walsh, like many executives, wondered if an aging
team like the Pacers could keep up with the nouveau Knicks, the
Philadelphia 76ers and the Toronto Raptors. With six of his top
eight players eligible for free agency, the notion of detonating
the roster in the off-season was a distinct possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to sign up a bunch of guys and then the team
goes down and you're stuck,'' Walsh acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Pacers decide to rebuild will ultimately be decided
over the next few weeks as they try to parlay another impressive
regular season into their first appearance in the National
Basketball Association finals. Yet by essentially sewing up
home-court advantage in the East with a huge victory in Miami on
Friday night, the Pacers moved closer to buying themselves another
season together.
</P>
<P>
   While the Heat wilted amid turmoil _ Pat Riley blasted his team
for back-to-back losses, saying the Heat quit on Wednesday night,
and Alonzo Mourning overslept and showed up late for Friday's
shoot-around and did not start that night's game _ the Pacers were
poised and purposeful.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh has firmly committed to re-signing only Jalen Rose,
saying, ``I only know one thing: we want him.'' In shaping the team
next season, Walsh added, ``How we play makes a big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   But the acrimony between the organization and Miller and Jackson
may cease soon.
</P>
<P>
   Like Patrick Ewing, they appear to have a lot of game left.
Miller dropped in 26 points in the victory over the Heat, making 9
of 12 shots and all three 3-pointers he took. Jackson played
maestro as well as ever, keeping the Pacers in the game early with
a first-quarter offensive binge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to show them the way I felt about them the last
time,'' Walsh said of the multiyear deals he gave Miller and
Jackson. ``I've had, without a doubt, the best guys in the league
over the last five years.''
</P>
<P>
   They will most likely not be around another five years. But like
the Knicks of the mid-1990s, the Pacers appear to have at least
another run left.
</P>
<P>
   Taking Sides on Knight
</P>
<P>
   The league's coaching fraternity is one of those tight-knit
societies that usually airs its grievances privately, if at all.
Sure, the coaches occasionally covet and secretly campaign for one
another's jobs. But for the most part, they commiserate with their
less-fortunate peers like Jim Todd, the Clippers' interim coach,
saying, ``He's in a tough situation'' or ``I hope they turn it
around for his sake.''
</P>
<P>
   Codes and lines were not only crossed last week; they were
obliterated. Blame it on Bobby Knight, the embattled Indiana
University coach.
</P>
<P>
   In an excerpt from his new book, Butch Carter, who played for
Knight at Indiana and now coaches the Toronto Raptors, contends
that Knight used a racial slur during an angry tirade against a
black player.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Knight deny the claim, but two more of his former
players, Cleveland Coach Randy Wittman and the Cavaliers assistant
Mike Woodson, took umbrage with Carter's charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little shocked that it's in a book because I never heard
Knight use that word,'' Woodson said. ``This is a low blow.''
</P>
<P>
   Wittman, who is white and played with Carter for two years, said
he never heard Knight use a racial slur. ``That never took place in
the five years I was there,'' Wittman said. ``Obviously, you would
remember something like that. I'm sure he is using all this to try
and make a buck. The timing of it _ no question.''
</P>
<P>
   Excerpts from Carter's book were published Friday in The
National Post of Toronto. The book is co-written by Carter's
brother Cris, a wide receiver for the Minnesota Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's allegations come at a time when Knight faces a
university investigation over allegations that he assaulted a
former player, Neil Reed, who said the coach choked him during a
1997 practice.
</P>
<P>
   Isiah Thomas, the former Raptors owner and general manager, who
led the Hoosiers to the 1981 national title, also came to Knight's
defense. ``I never heard coach ever use that word,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Carter barely responded to the criticism from his peers on
Friday night, letting his published work speak for him. But he did
say that as long as people are taking sides on the Knight issue,
``the private will all become public.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Carter wasn't speaking about long-held resentments
between people in his own profession, you wonder if this little
break in the dike will widen.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley's Last Stand
</P>
<P>
   No playoff seeding is at stake. No national cable-television
audience is scheduled to view the game. By most accounts, the
Rockets-Grizzlies game on Wednesday night in Houston appears to be
a drab affair between two lottery-bound teams.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you factor in the return of Charles Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Chucky is back _ in all his verbose splendor. And this time
when he says he is done, he means it. Honest. He promises.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley, who ruptured a tendon in his left leg in December, said
he planned to play against Vancouver. He announced that he would
retire at the end of this season when he was hurt in a Dec. 8 game
against Philadelphia. Yet within weeks, he decided he wanted
desperately to end his career by walking off the floor at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to playing a couple of minutes and leaving
the court under my own terms,'' he said last week.
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, Barkley appears to miss the attention that came
with a brilliant and bombastic All-Star career, one in which he won
the most valuable player award in 1993 and carved out a niche
during the league's meteoric rise in popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Playing a few minutes against Vancouver almost seems
self-congratulatory, a staged event that is beneath one of the
NBA's top 50 players ever.
</P>
<P>
   But then you remember Barkley's career, and you realize he was
all about playing to the crowd, entertaining the masses and taking
everyone along for the ride. Once a young knucklehead, he became a
blueprint for what happens when a player grows up and realizes what
is important in his career.
</P>
<P>
   In that vein, here's hoping he treasures his last night in a
uniform, that Sir Charles is afforded royal treatment for all the
human majesty he displayed the past 16 years. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
